WEBVTT

00:00:12.880 --> 00:00:18.500
Read and recorded by Betsy Bush, Marquette, Michigan, December 2005.

00:00:19.300 --> 00:00:22.700
Anne of Green Gables, by Lucy Mond Montgomery.

00:00:26.780 --> 00:00:28.940
Mrs. Rachel Lind is surprised.

00:00:30.480 --> 00:00:36.280
Mrs. Rachel Lind lived just where the Avonlea Main Road dipped down into a little hollow,

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:41.560
fringed with alders and ladies' ear drops, and traversed by a brook that had its source

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:44.480
way back in the woods of the old Cuthbert place.

00:00:45.100 --> 00:00:49.440
It was reputed to be an intricate headlong brook in its earlier course through those

00:00:49.440 --> 00:00:52.400
woods with dark secrets of pool and cascade.

00:00:53.240 --> 00:00:57.920
But by the time it reached Lind's hollow, it was a quiet, well-conducted little stream,

00:00:58.340 --> 00:01:04.040
for not even a brook could run past Mrs. Lind's door without due regard for decency and decorum.

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:08.960
It probably was conscious that Mrs. Rachel was sitting at her window keeping a sharp

00:01:08.960 --> 00:01:14.640
eye on everything that passed, from brooks and children up, and that if she noticed anything

00:01:14.640 --> 00:01:20.800
odd or out of place, she would never rest until she had ferreted out the whys and wherefores

00:01:20.800 --> 00:01:21.420
thereof.

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:28.020
There are plenty of people in Avonlea and out of it who can attend closely to their

00:01:28.020 --> 00:01:30.680
neighbor's business by dint of neglecting their own.

00:01:31.020 --> 00:01:36.340
But Mrs. Rachel Lind was one of those capable creatures who can manage their own concerns

00:01:36.340 --> 00:01:38.920
and those of other folks into the bargain.

00:01:40.100 --> 00:01:41.520
She was a notable housewife.

00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:43.740
Her work was always done and well done.

00:01:44.180 --> 00:01:49.180
She ran the sewing circle and helped run the Sunday school, and was the strongest prop

00:01:49.180 --> 00:01:52.660
of the Church Aid Society and Foreign Missions Auxiliary.

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:59.120
Yet with all this, Mrs. Rachel found abundant time to sit for hours at her kitchen window

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:01.260
knitting cotton-warp quilts.

00:02:01.260 --> 00:02:06.580
She had knitted sixteen of them, as Avonlea housekeepers were wont to tell in odd voices,

00:02:07.200 --> 00:02:12.180
and keeping a sharp eye on the main road that crossed the hollow and wound up the steep

00:02:12.180 --> 00:02:13.160
red hill beyond.

00:02:14.060 --> 00:02:18.780
Since Avonlea occupied a little triangular peninsula jutting out into the Gulf of St.

00:02:18.920 --> 00:02:24.780
Lawrence with water on two sides of it, anybody who went out of it or into it had to pass

00:02:24.780 --> 00:02:30.700
over that hill road and sew run the unseen gauntlet of Mrs. Rachel's all-seeing eye.

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:34.760
She was sitting there one afternoon in early June.

00:02:35.180 --> 00:02:37.500
The sun was coming in at the window warm and bright.

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:43.380
The orchard on the slope below the house was in a bridal flush of pinky-white bloom, hummed

00:02:43.380 --> 00:02:45.020
over by a myriad of bees.

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:52.160
Thomas Lind, a meek little man whom Avonlea people called Rachel Lind's husband, was sewing

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:58.680
his late turnip seed on the hill-field beyond the barn, and Matthew Cuthbert ought to have

00:02:58.680 --> 00:03:03.400
been sewing his on the big red brook-field away over by Green Gables.

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:08.920
Mrs. Rachel knew that he ought because she had heard him tell Peter Morrison the evening

00:03:08.920 --> 00:03:14.820
before in William J. Blair's store over at Carmody that he meant to sew his turnip seed

00:03:14.820 --> 00:03:15.700
the next afternoon.

00:03:16.560 --> 00:03:22.240
Peter had asked him, of course, for Matthew Cuthbert had never been known to volunteer

00:03:22.240 --> 00:03:24.840
information about anything in his whole life.

00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:32.300
And yet here was Matthew Cuthbert at half-past three on the afternoon of a busy day placidly

00:03:32.300 --> 00:03:34.460
driving over the hollow and up the hill.

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:41.660
Moreover, he wore a white collar and his best suit of clothes, which was plain proof that

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:47.200
he was going out of Avonlea, and he had the buggy and the sorrel mare, which betokened

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:49.180
that he was going a considerable distance.

00:03:49.740 --> 00:03:53.900
Now where was Matthew Cuthbert going, and why was he going there?

00:03:54.800 --> 00:03:59.840
Had it been any other man in Avonlea, Mrs. Rachel deftly putting this and that together

00:03:59.840 --> 00:04:03.260
might have given a pretty good guess as to both questions.

00:04:03.760 --> 00:04:09.060
But Matthew so rarely went from home that it must be something pressing and unusual

00:04:09.060 --> 00:04:10.300
which was taking him.

00:04:10.300 --> 00:04:16.240
He was the shyest man alive and hated to go among strangers or to any place where he might

00:04:16.240 --> 00:04:17.080
have to talk.

00:04:18.180 --> 00:04:22.480
Matthew dressed up with a white collar and driving in a buggy was something that didn't

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:23.380
happen often.

00:04:24.400 --> 00:04:28.980
Mrs. Rachel, ponder as she might, could make nothing of it and her afternoon's enjoyment

00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:29.780
was spoiled.

00:04:31.100 --> 00:04:35.400
I'll just step over to Green Gables after tea and find out from Marilla where he's gone

00:04:35.400 --> 00:04:38.140
and why, the worthy woman finally concluded.

00:04:38.140 --> 00:04:42.920
He doesn't generally go to town this time of year and he never visits.

00:04:43.580 --> 00:04:48.120
If he'd run out of turnip seed he wouldn't dress up and take the buggy to go for more.

00:04:48.580 --> 00:04:51.980
He wasn't driving fast enough to be going for a doctor.

00:04:52.720 --> 00:04:56.480
Yet something must have happened since last night to start him off.

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:03.020
I'm clean puzzled, that's what, and I won't know a minute's peace of mind or conscience

00:05:03.020 --> 00:05:06.720
until I know what has taken Matthew Cuthbert out of Avonlea today.

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:10.980
Accordingly, after tea, Mrs. Rachel set out.

00:05:11.300 --> 00:05:12.740
She had not far to go.

00:05:13.100 --> 00:05:18.080
The big rambling orchard in Bowerd House where the Cuthberts lived was a scant quarter of

00:05:18.080 --> 00:05:20.180
a mile up the road from Lynn's Hollow.

00:05:21.020 --> 00:05:24.680
To be sure, the long lane made it a good deal further.

00:05:26.040 --> 00:05:31.580
Matthew Cuthbert's father, as shy and silent as his son after him, had got as far away

00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:36.700
as he possibly could from his fellow men without actually retreating into the woods when he

00:05:36.700 --> 00:05:38.000
found his homestead.

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:43.120
Green Gables was built at the furthest edge of his cleared land, and there it was to this

00:05:43.120 --> 00:05:48.340
day, barely visible from the main road along which all the other Avonlea houses were so

00:05:48.340 --> 00:05:49.440
sociably situated.

00:05:50.580 --> 00:05:55.260
Mrs. Rachel Lynde did not call living in such a place living at all.

00:05:55.820 --> 00:06:00.980
It's just staying, that's what she said as she stepped along the deep-rutted grassy lane

00:06:00.980 --> 00:06:02.740
bordered with wild rose bushes.

00:06:03.420 --> 00:06:08.660
It's no wonder Matthew and Marilla are both a little odd, living away back here by themselves.

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:13.980
Trees aren't much company, though dear knows if they were, there'd be enough of them.

00:06:14.380 --> 00:06:15.860
I'd rather look at people.

00:06:16.240 --> 00:06:21.480
To be sure, they seem contented enough, but then I suppose they're used to it.

00:06:21.920 --> 00:06:26.280
A body can get used to anything, even to being hanged, as the Irishman said.

00:06:26.980 --> 00:06:31.800
With this Mrs. Rachel stepped out of the lane into the back yard of Green Gables.

00:06:32.820 --> 00:06:38.660
Very green and neat and precise was that yard, set about on one side with great patriarchal

00:06:38.660 --> 00:06:40.720
willows and the other with prim lombardies.

00:06:41.480 --> 00:06:46.140
Not a stray stick nor stone was to be seen, for Mrs. Rachel would have seen it if there

00:06:46.140 --> 00:06:46.700
had been.

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:52.980
Privately, she was of the opinion that Marilla Cuthbert swept that yard over as often as

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:54.060
she swept her house.

00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:58.880
One could have eaten a meal off the ground without over-brimming the proverbial peck

00:06:58.880 --> 00:06:59.500
of dirt.

00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:05.080
Mrs. Rachel rapped smartly at the kitchen door and stepped in when bidden to do so.

00:07:05.780 --> 00:07:10.280
The kitchen at Green Gables was a cheerful apartment, or would have been cheerful if

00:07:10.280 --> 00:07:14.620
it had not been so painfully clean as to give it something of the appearance of an unused

00:07:14.620 --> 00:07:15.260
parlor.

00:07:16.460 --> 00:07:18.260
Its windows looked east and west.

00:07:18.720 --> 00:07:23.180
Through the west one, looking out on the back yard, came a flood of mellow June sunlight.

00:07:23.660 --> 00:07:29.280
But the east one, once you got a glimpse of the bloom-white cherry trees in the left orchard

00:07:29.280 --> 00:07:34.180
and nodding slender birches down in the hollow by the brook, was greened over by a tangle

00:07:34.180 --> 00:07:34.940
of vines.

00:07:35.860 --> 00:07:41.260
Here sat Marilla Cuthbert, when she sat at all, always slightly distrustful of sunshine,

00:07:41.520 --> 00:07:46.360
which seemed to her too dancing and irresponsible a thing for a world which was meant to be

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:47.240
taken seriously.

00:07:47.240 --> 00:07:52.400
And here she sat now, knitting, and the table behind her laid for supper.

00:07:53.620 --> 00:07:58.240
Mrs. Rachel, before she had fairly closed the door, had taken a mental note of everything

00:07:58.240 --> 00:07:59.280
that was on that table.

00:07:59.860 --> 00:08:04.520
There were three plates laid, so that Marilla must be expecting someone home with Matthew

00:08:04.520 --> 00:08:05.100
to tea.

00:08:05.560 --> 00:08:10.600
But the dishes were every-day dishes, and there was only crab-apple preserve and one

00:08:10.600 --> 00:08:15.580
kind of cake, so that the expected company could not be any particular company.

00:08:16.280 --> 00:08:19.700
Yet what of Matthew's white collar and the sorrowful mare?

00:08:20.600 --> 00:08:25.820
Mrs. Rachel was getting fairly dizzy with this unusual mystery about quiet, unmisterious

00:08:25.820 --> 00:08:26.540
green gables.

00:08:27.700 --> 00:08:30.380
"'Good evening, Rachel,' Marilla said briskly.

00:08:30.380 --> 00:08:32.920
"'This is a real fine evening, isn't it?

00:08:33.220 --> 00:08:34.260
Won't you sit down?

00:08:34.520 --> 00:08:36.400
How are all your folks?'

00:08:36.880 --> 00:08:41.260
Something that, for a lack of any other name, might be called friendship existed, and always

00:08:41.260 --> 00:08:46.700
had existed, between Marilla Cuthbert and Mrs. Rachel, in spite of, or perhaps because

00:08:46.700 --> 00:08:48.280
of, their dissimilarity.

00:08:49.540 --> 00:08:53.140
Marilla was a tall, thin woman, with angles and without curves.

00:08:53.640 --> 00:08:58.620
Her dark hair showed some gray streaks, and was always twisted up in a hard little knot

00:08:58.620 --> 00:09:02.700
behind, with two wire hairpins stuck aggressively through it.

00:09:03.180 --> 00:09:07.820
She looked like a woman of narrow experience and rigid conscience, which she was.

00:09:08.210 --> 00:09:12.660
But there was a saving something about her mouth which, if it had been ever so slightly

00:09:12.660 --> 00:09:15.860
developed, might have been considered indicative of a sense of humor.

00:09:16.500 --> 00:09:19.000
"'We're all pretty well,' said Mrs. Rachel.

00:09:19.400 --> 00:09:21.460
"'I was kind of afraid you weren't, though.

00:09:21.460 --> 00:09:27.280
When I saw Matthew starting off to-day, I thought maybe he was going to the doctor's.'

00:09:27.280 --> 00:09:29.880
Marilla's lips twitched understandingly.

00:09:30.180 --> 00:09:32.280
She had expected Mrs. Rachel up.

00:09:32.680 --> 00:09:37.920
She had known that the sight of Matthew jaunting off so unaccountably would be too much for

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:39.140
her neighbor's curiosity.

00:09:40.060 --> 00:09:44.880
"'Oh, no, I'm quite well, although I had a bad headache yesterday,' she said.

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:46.940
Matthew went to Bright River.

00:09:47.500 --> 00:09:51.860
We're getting a little boy from an orphan asylum in Nova Scotia, and he's coming on

00:09:51.860 --> 00:09:52.760
the train to-night.'

00:09:53.720 --> 00:09:58.440
If Marilla had said that Matthew had gone to Bright River to meet a kangaroo from Australia,

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:01.380
Mrs. Rachel could not have been more astonished.

00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:04.440
She was actually stricken dumb for five seconds.

00:10:05.200 --> 00:10:09.940
It was unsupposable that Marilla was making fun of her, but Mrs. Rachel was almost forced

00:10:09.940 --> 00:10:11.140
to suppose it.

00:10:11.580 --> 00:10:16.380
"'Are you in earnest, Marilla?' she demanded when voice returned to her.

00:10:17.260 --> 00:10:22.420
"'Yes, of course,' said Marilla, as if getting boys from orphan asylums in Nova Scotia were

00:10:22.420 --> 00:10:28.580
part of the usual spring work on any well-regulated Avonlea farm, instead of being an unheard-of

00:10:28.580 --> 00:10:29.160
innovation.

00:10:30.260 --> 00:10:33.560
Mrs. Rachel felt that she had received a severe mental jolt.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:39.680
She thought, in exclamation points, a boy—Marilla and Matthew Cuthbert of all people adopting

00:10:39.680 --> 00:10:41.840
a boy—from an orphan asylum.

00:10:42.120 --> 00:10:45.040
Well, the world was certainly turning upside down.

00:10:45.220 --> 00:10:47.840
She would be surprised at nothing after this—nothing.'

00:10:48.920 --> 00:10:53.600
"'What on earth put such a notion into your head?' she demanded disapprovingly.

00:10:54.200 --> 00:10:59.040
This had been done without her advice being asked, and must, reforese, be disapproved.'

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:05.980
"'Well, we've been thinking about it for some time—all winter, in fact,' returned Marilla.

00:11:06.560 --> 00:11:11.540
Mrs. Alexander Spencer was up here one day before Christmas, and she said she was going

00:11:11.540 --> 00:11:14.900
to get a little girl from the asylum over in Hopeton in the spring.

00:11:15.640 --> 00:11:20.240
Her cousin lives there, and Mrs. Spencer has visited here and knows all about it.

00:11:20.360 --> 00:11:23.260
So Matthew and I have talked it over off and on ever since.

00:11:23.260 --> 00:11:24.600
We thought we'd get a boy.

00:11:25.300 --> 00:11:30.980
Matthew is getting up in years, you know—he's sixty—and he isn't so spry as he once was.

00:11:31.460 --> 00:11:33.300
His heart troubles him a great deal.

00:11:34.060 --> 00:11:37.200
And you know how desperate hard it's got to be to get hired help.

00:11:37.500 --> 00:11:41.540
There's never anybody to be had by those stupid half-grown little French boys.

00:11:41.900 --> 00:11:46.180
And as soon as you do get one broke into your ways and taught something, he's up and off

00:11:46.180 --> 00:11:49.000
to the lobster canneries or the States.'

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:53.660
At first Matthew suggested getting a homeboy, but I said no, flat to that.

00:11:54.200 --> 00:11:56.820
They might be all right, I'm not saying they're not.

00:11:57.280 --> 00:11:59.740
But no London Street Arabs for me, I said.

00:12:00.260 --> 00:12:01.820
Give me a native born, at least.

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:04.200
There'll be a risk, no matter who we get.

00:12:04.460 --> 00:12:09.640
But I'll feel easier in my mind and sleep sounder at nights if we get a born Canadian.'

00:12:09.640 --> 00:12:14.120
So in the end we decided to ask Mrs. Spencer to pick us out one when she went over to get

00:12:14.120 --> 00:12:14.840
her little girl.

00:12:15.360 --> 00:12:20.520
We heard last week she was going, so we sent her word by Richard Spencer's folks at Carmody

00:12:20.520 --> 00:12:23.300
to bring us a smart, likely boy of about ten or eleven.

00:12:23.680 --> 00:12:28.460
We decided that would be the best age, old enough to be of some use in doing chores right

00:12:28.460 --> 00:12:30.620
off and young enough to be trained up proper.

00:12:30.940 --> 00:12:32.820
We mean to give him a good home and schooling.

00:12:33.620 --> 00:12:36.260
We had a telegram from Mrs. Alexander Spencer today.

00:12:36.700 --> 00:12:40.960
The mailman brought it from the station, saying they were coming on the 5.30 train tonight.

00:12:41.440 --> 00:12:43.320
So Matthew went to Bright River to meet him.

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:45.460
Mrs. Spencer will drop him off there.

00:12:45.620 --> 00:12:48.280
Of course, she goes on to White Sand Station herself.

00:12:49.980 --> 00:12:52.760
Mrs. Rachel prided herself on always speaking her mind.

00:12:53.360 --> 00:12:58.040
She proceeded to speak it now, having adjusted her mental attitude to this amazing piece

00:12:58.040 --> 00:12:58.560
of news.

00:12:59.720 --> 00:13:04.580
Well, Marilla, I'll just tell you plain that I think you're doing a mighty foolish thing.

00:13:04.820 --> 00:13:06.260
A risky thing, that's what.

00:13:06.660 --> 00:13:08.200
You don't know what you're getting.

00:13:08.680 --> 00:13:13.120
You're bringing a strange child into your house and home, and you don't know a single

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:18.320
thing about him, nor what his disposition is like, nor what sort of parents he had,

00:13:18.540 --> 00:13:20.320
nor how he's likely to turn out.

00:13:21.040 --> 00:13:26.040
Why, it was only last week I read in the paper how a man and his wife out west of the island

00:13:26.040 --> 00:13:31.600
took a boy out of an orphan asylum, and he set fire to the house at night, set it on

00:13:31.600 --> 00:13:35.320
purpose, Marilla, and nearly burnt them to a crisp in their beds.

00:13:36.160 --> 00:13:39.980
And I know another case where an adopted boy used to suck the eggs.

00:13:40.140 --> 00:13:41.780
They couldn't break him of it.

00:13:41.780 --> 00:13:47.060
If you had asked my advice in the matter, which you didn't do, Marilla, I'd have said

00:13:47.060 --> 00:13:50.060
for mercy's sake not to think of such a thing, that's what.

00:13:51.460 --> 00:13:55.620
This job's comforting seemed neither to offend nor to alarm Marilla.

00:13:55.720 --> 00:13:57.120
She knitted on steadily.

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:01.660
I don't deny there's something in what you say, Rachel.

00:14:02.060 --> 00:14:06.540
I've had some qualms myself, but Matthew has terrible set on it.

00:14:06.640 --> 00:14:08.860
I could see that, so I gave in.

00:14:08.860 --> 00:14:14.780
It's so seldom Matthew sets his mind on anything that when he does, I always feel it's my duty

00:14:14.780 --> 00:14:15.700
to give in.

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:20.680
And as for the risk, there's risk in pretty near everything a body does in this world.

00:14:21.200 --> 00:14:24.540
There's risks in people having children of their own if it comes to that.

00:14:25.060 --> 00:14:26.720
They don't always turn out well.

00:14:27.480 --> 00:14:29.680
And then Nova Scotia is right close to the island.

00:14:30.080 --> 00:14:32.680
It isn't as if we were getting him from England or the States.

00:14:33.120 --> 00:14:35.020
He can't be much different from ourselves.

00:14:35.920 --> 00:14:41.980
Well, I hope it will turn out all right, said Mrs. Rachel, in a tone that plainly indicated

00:14:41.980 --> 00:14:43.020
her painful doubts.

00:14:43.920 --> 00:14:48.680
Only don't say I didn't warn you if he burns green gables down or puts strychnine in the

00:14:48.680 --> 00:14:48.880
well.

00:14:49.520 --> 00:14:54.260
I heard of a case over in New Brunswick where an orphan asylum child did that, and the whole

00:14:54.260 --> 00:14:58.320
family died in fearful agonies, only it was a girl in that instance.

00:14:59.560 --> 00:15:04.700
Well, we're not getting a girl, said Marilla, as if poisoning wells were a purely feminine

00:15:04.700 --> 00:15:07.740
accomplishment, and not to be dreaded in the case of a boy.

00:15:08.400 --> 00:15:10.960
I'd never dream of taking a girl to bring up.

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:14.100
I wonder at Mrs. Alexander Spencer for doing it.

00:15:14.420 --> 00:15:19.140
But there she wouldn't shrink from adopting a whole orphan asylum if she took it into

00:15:19.140 --> 00:15:19.680
her head.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:25.120
Mrs. Rachel would have liked to stay until Matthew came home with his imported orphan,

00:15:25.620 --> 00:15:30.160
but reflecting that it would be a good two hours at least before his arrival, she concluded

00:15:30.160 --> 00:15:32.980
to go up the road to Robert Bell's and tell the news.

00:15:32.980 --> 00:15:37.920
It would certainly make a sensation second to none, and Mrs. Rachel dearly loved to make

00:15:37.920 --> 00:15:38.580
a sensation.

00:15:39.320 --> 00:15:44.480
So she took herself away, somewhat to Marilla's relief, for the latter felt her doubts and

00:15:44.480 --> 00:15:47.620
fears reviving under the influence of Mrs. Rachel's pessimism.

00:15:48.660 --> 00:15:54.020
Well, of all things that ever were or will be, ejaculated Mrs. Rachel when she was safely

00:15:54.020 --> 00:15:54.900
out in the lane.

00:15:55.280 --> 00:15:57.580
It really does seem as if I must be dreaming.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.280
Well, I'm sorry for that poor young one, and no mistake.

00:16:01.840 --> 00:16:06.680
Matthew and Marilla don't know anything about children, and they'll expect him to be wiser

00:16:06.680 --> 00:16:08.560
and steadier than his own grandfather.

00:16:09.060 --> 00:16:12.220
If so, bees, he's ever had a grandfather, which is doubtful.

00:16:12.700 --> 00:16:15.660
It seems uncanny to think of a child of Green Gables, somehow.

00:16:16.040 --> 00:16:20.340
There's never been one there, for Matthew and Marilla were grown up when the new house

00:16:20.340 --> 00:16:25.020
was built, if they were children, which is hard to believe when one looks at them.

00:16:25.540 --> 00:16:27.840
I wouldn't be in that orphan's shoes for anything.

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:29.580
My, but I pity him.

00:16:29.580 --> 00:16:30.500
That's what!

00:16:31.300 --> 00:16:35.040
So said Mrs. Rachel to the wild rose-bushes out of the fullness of her heart.

00:16:36.060 --> 00:16:40.020
But if she could have seen the child who was waiting patiently at the Bright River station

00:16:40.020 --> 00:16:44.220
at that very moment, her pity would have been still deeper and more profound.

00:17:10.640 --> 00:17:12.680
Matthew Cuthbert is surprised.

00:17:14.360 --> 00:17:19.280
Matthew Cuthbert and the sorrel mare jogged comfortably over the eight miles to Bright River.

00:17:19.860 --> 00:17:30.740
It was a pretty road, running along between snug farmsteads, with now and again a bit of balsam-y fir wood to drive through, or a hollow where wild plums hung out their filmy bloom.

00:17:31.580 --> 00:17:38.800
The air was sweet with the breath of many apple orchards, and the meadows sloped away in the distance to horizon mists of pearl and purple,

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:44.600
while the little birds sang as if it were the one day of summer in all the year.

00:17:45.520 --> 00:17:52.240
Matthew enjoyed the drive after his own fashion, except during the moments when he met women and had to nod to them,

00:17:52.620 --> 00:17:58.780
for in Prince Edward Island you are supposed to nod to all and sundry you meet on the road whether you know them or not.

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:02.820
Matthew dreaded all women except Marilla and Mrs. Rachel.

00:18:03.240 --> 00:18:07.640
He had an uncomfortable feeling that the mysterious creatures were secretly laughing at him.

00:18:07.640 --> 00:18:21.220
He may have been quite right in thinking so, for he was an odd-looking personage, with an ungainly figure and long iron-grey hair that touched his stooping shoulders and a full soft brown beard that he had worn ever since he was twenty.

00:18:21.820 --> 00:18:27.320
In fact, he looked at twenty very much as he looked at sixty, lacking a little of the grayness.

00:18:28.320 --> 00:18:31.480
When he reached Bright River there was no sign of any train.

00:18:31.480 --> 00:18:38.460
He thought he was too early, so he tied his horse in the yard of the small Bright River Hotel and went over to the station.

00:18:39.500 --> 00:18:47.120
The long platform was almost deserted, the only living creature in sight being a girl who was sitting on a pile of shingles at the extreme end.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:53.320
Matthew, barely noting that it was a girl, sidled past her as quickly as possible without looking at her.

00:18:53.840 --> 00:18:59.560
Had he looked, he could hardly have failed to notice the tense rigidity and expectation of her attitude and expression.

00:19:00.310 --> 00:19:09.100
She was sitting there waiting for something or somebody, and since sitting and waiting was the only thing to do just then, she sat and waited with all her might in mind.

00:19:10.560 --> 00:19:19.160
Matthew encountered the stationmaster locking up the ticket office preparatory to going home for supper, and asked him if the five-thirty train would soon be along.

00:19:19.940 --> 00:19:29.060
The five-thirty train has been in and gone half an hour ago, answered that brisk official, but there was a passenger dropped off for you, a little girl.

00:19:29.320 --> 00:19:30.880
She's sitting out there on the shingles.

00:19:31.400 --> 00:19:36.920
I asked her to go into the lady's waiting room, but she informed me gravely that she preferred to stay outside.

00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:40.220
There was more scope for imagination, she said.

00:19:40.880 --> 00:19:42.660
She's a case, I should say.

00:19:43.360 --> 00:19:46.700
I'm not expecting a girl, said Matthew blankly.

00:19:47.140 --> 00:19:48.560
It's a boy I've come for.

00:19:48.980 --> 00:19:54.420
He should be here. Mrs. Alexander Spencer was to bring him over from Nova Scotia for me.

00:19:55.340 --> 00:19:56.920
The stationmaster whistled.

00:19:57.760 --> 00:19:59.680
Guess there's some mistake, he said.

00:20:00.240 --> 00:20:04.040
Mrs. Spencer came off the train with that girl and gave her into my charge.

00:20:04.560 --> 00:20:09.660
Said you and your sister were adopting her from an orphan asylum, and that you would be along for her presently.

00:20:09.900 --> 00:20:11.540
That's all I know about it.

00:20:11.540 --> 00:20:14.400
And I haven't got any more orphans concealed hereabouts.

00:20:15.720 --> 00:20:21.560
I don't understand, said Matthew helplessly, wishing that Marilla was at hand to cope with the situation.

00:20:22.640 --> 00:20:26.020
Well, you'd better question the girl, said the stationmaster carelessly.

00:20:26.380 --> 00:20:30.860
I dare say she'll be able to explain. She's got a tongue of her own, that's certain.

00:20:31.540 --> 00:20:33.780
Maybe they were out of boys of the brand you wanted.

00:20:34.480 --> 00:20:42.740
He walked jauntily away being hungry, and the unfortunate Matthew was left to do that which was harder for him than bearding a lion in its den,

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:49.580
walk up to a girl, a strange girl, an orphan girl, and demand of her why she wasn't a boy.

00:20:50.760 --> 00:20:55.560
Matthew groaned in spirit as he turned about and shuffled gently down the platform towards her.

00:20:56.400 --> 00:21:00.720
She had been watching him ever since he had passed her, and she had her eyes on him now.

00:21:00.720 --> 00:21:05.700
Matthew was not looking at her and would not have seen what she was really like if he had been.

00:21:06.240 --> 00:21:09.180
But an ordinary observer would have seen this.

00:21:09.920 --> 00:21:16.180
A child of about eleven, garbed in a very short, very tight, very ugly dress of yellowish-grey wincey,

00:21:16.780 --> 00:21:24.620
she wore a faded brown sailor hat, and beneath the hat, extending down her back, were two braids of very thick, decidedly red hair.

00:21:25.260 --> 00:21:28.540
Her face was small, white and thin, also much freckled.

00:21:28.540 --> 00:21:34.520
Her mouth was large, and so were her eyes, which looked green in some lights and moods, and gray in others.

00:21:35.340 --> 00:21:37.000
So far the ordinary observer.

00:21:37.640 --> 00:21:42.140
An extraordinary observer might have seen that the chin was very pointed and pronounced,

00:21:42.320 --> 00:21:47.280
that the big eyes were full of spirit and vivacity, that the mouth was sweet-lipped and expressive,

00:21:47.620 --> 00:21:49.220
that the forehead was broad and full.

00:21:49.620 --> 00:21:57.580
In short, our discerning extraordinary observer might have concluded that no commonplace soul inhabited the body of that stray woman child

00:21:57.580 --> 00:22:01.100
of whom shy Matthew Cuthbert was so ludicrously afraid.

00:22:02.060 --> 00:22:05.040
Matthew, however, was spared the ordeal of speaking first.

00:22:05.660 --> 00:22:09.080
For as soon as she concluded that he was coming to her, she stood up,

00:22:09.340 --> 00:22:13.840
grasping with one thin, brown hand the handle of a shabby, old-fashioned carpet-bag.

00:22:14.260 --> 00:22:15.780
The other she held out to him.

00:22:16.740 --> 00:22:22.440
I suppose you are Mr. Matthew Cuthbert of Green Gables, she said in a particularly sweet, clear voice.

00:22:22.680 --> 00:22:24.320
I am very glad to see you.

00:22:24.320 --> 00:22:30.440
I was beginning to be afraid you weren't coming for me, and I was imagining all the things that might have happened to prevent you.

00:22:30.700 --> 00:22:33.180
I had made up my mind that if you didn't come for me tonight,

00:22:33.480 --> 00:22:38.680
I'd go down the track to that big wild cherry tree at the bend and climb up into it to stay all night.

00:22:39.340 --> 00:22:40.760
I wouldn't be a bit afraid.

00:22:41.060 --> 00:22:46.340
It would be lovely to sleep in a wild cherry tree all white with bloom in the moonshine, don't you think?

00:22:46.660 --> 00:22:49.980
You could imagine you were dwelling in marble halls, couldn't you?

00:22:50.200 --> 00:22:53.720
And I was quite sure you would come for me in the morning if you didn't come tonight.

00:22:54.840 --> 00:23:00.680
Matthew had taken the scrawny little and awkwardly in his, and then and there he decided what to do.

00:23:01.240 --> 00:23:04.960
He could not tell this child with the glowing eyes that there had been a mistake.

00:23:05.460 --> 00:23:07.660
He would take her home and let Marilla do that.

00:23:08.260 --> 00:23:12.320
She couldn't be left at Bright River anyhow, no matter what mistake had been made.

00:23:12.940 --> 00:23:17.780
So all questions and explanations might as well be deferred until he was safely back at Green Gables.

00:23:19.020 --> 00:23:21.760
I'm sorry I was late, he said shyly.

00:23:21.760 --> 00:23:24.440
Come along, the horse is over in the yard.

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:25.580
Give me your bag.

00:23:26.880 --> 00:23:29.600
Oh, I can carry it, the child responded cheerfully.

00:23:29.960 --> 00:23:30.720
It isn't heavy.

00:23:31.080 --> 00:23:34.400
I've got all my worldly belongings in it, but it isn't heavy.

00:23:35.100 --> 00:23:38.140
And if it isn't carried in just a certain way, the handle pulls out.

00:23:38.500 --> 00:23:41.440
So I'd better keep it, because I know the exact knack of it.

00:23:41.700 --> 00:23:43.260
It's an extremely old carpet bag.

00:23:44.620 --> 00:23:49.300
Oh, I'm very glad you've come, even if it would have been nice to sleep in a wild cherry tree.

00:23:49.300 --> 00:23:52.100
We've got to drive a long piece, haven't we?

00:23:52.340 --> 00:23:54.080
Mrs. Spencer said it was eight miles.

00:23:54.520 --> 00:23:56.380
I'm glad, because I love driving.

00:23:57.080 --> 00:24:00.720
Oh, it seems so wonderful that I'm going to live with you and belong to you.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:03.580
I've never belonged to anybody, not really.

00:24:04.160 --> 00:24:05.960
But the asylum was the worst.

00:24:06.460 --> 00:24:09.300
I've only been in it four months, but that was enough.

00:24:09.900 --> 00:24:14.900
I don't suppose you ever were an orphan in an asylum, so you can't possibly understand what it is like.

00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:17.240
It's worse than anything you could imagine.

00:24:17.240 --> 00:24:22.120
Mrs. Spencer said it was wicked of me to talk like that, but I didn't mean to be wicked.

00:24:22.760 --> 00:24:25.800
It's so easy to be wicked without knowing it, isn't it?

00:24:26.720 --> 00:24:29.000
They were good, you know, the asylum people.

00:24:29.340 --> 00:24:34.240
But there is so little scope for the imagination in an asylum, only just in the other orphans.

00:24:34.780 --> 00:24:37.180
It was pretty interesting to imagine things about them.

00:24:37.420 --> 00:24:41.900
To imagine that perhaps the girl who sat next to you was really the daughter of a belted earl

00:24:41.900 --> 00:24:47.940
who had been stolen away from her parents in her infancy by a cruel nurse who died before she could confess.

00:24:48.600 --> 00:24:54.140
I used to lie awake at nights and imagine things like that, because I didn't have the time in the day.

00:24:54.600 --> 00:24:56.180
I guess that's why I'm so thin.

00:24:56.580 --> 00:24:58.900
I am dreadfully thin, ain't I?

00:24:59.140 --> 00:25:00.820
There isn't a pick on my bones.

00:25:01.360 --> 00:25:04.800
I do love to imagine I'm nice and plump with dimples on my elbows.

00:25:05.900 --> 00:25:10.340
With this, Matthew's companion stopped talking, partly because she was out of breath

00:25:10.340 --> 00:25:12.860
and partly because they had reached the buggy.

00:25:13.060 --> 00:25:17.720
Not another word did she say until they had left the village and were driving down a steep little hill,

00:25:17.940 --> 00:25:21.300
the road part of which had been cut so deeply into the soft soil

00:25:21.300 --> 00:25:25.940
that the banks fringed with blooming wild cherry trees and slim white birches

00:25:25.940 --> 00:25:27.560
were several feet above their heads.

00:25:28.760 --> 00:25:33.500
The child put out her hand and broke off a branch of wild plum that brushed against the side of the buggy.

00:25:34.040 --> 00:25:35.340
Isn't that beautiful?

00:25:35.720 --> 00:25:39.380
What did that tree leaning out from the bank all white and lacy make you think of?

00:25:39.380 --> 00:25:40.180
She asked.

00:25:41.020 --> 00:25:44.160
Well, now, I don't know, said Matthew.

00:25:45.580 --> 00:25:50.120
Why, a bride, of course, a bride all in white with a lovely misty veil.

00:25:50.540 --> 00:25:53.680
I've never seen one, but I can imagine what she would look like.

00:25:54.140 --> 00:25:56.180
I don't ever expect to be a bride myself.

00:25:56.580 --> 00:26:01.180
I'm so homely nobody will ever want to marry me, unless it might be a foreign missionary.

00:26:01.720 --> 00:26:04.360
I suppose a foreign missionary mightn't be very particular.

00:26:05.160 --> 00:26:07.820
But I do hope that some day I shall have a white dress.

00:26:07.820 --> 00:26:10.460
That is my highest ideal of earthly bliss.

00:26:10.960 --> 00:26:12.320
I just love pretty clothes.

00:26:12.800 --> 00:26:15.540
And I've never had a pretty dress in my life that I can remember.

00:26:16.260 --> 00:26:18.960
But, of course, it's all the more to look forward to, isn't it?

00:26:19.140 --> 00:26:21.340
And then I can imagine that I'm dressed gorgeously.

00:26:22.500 --> 00:26:25.000
This morning when I left the asylum I felt so ashamed

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:27.640
because I had to wear this horrible old wincey dress.

00:26:28.180 --> 00:26:30.080
All the orphans had to wear them, you know.

00:26:30.460 --> 00:26:34.540
A merchant at Hopeton last winter donated 300 yards of wincey to the asylum.

00:26:35.100 --> 00:26:37.500
Some people said it was because he couldn't sell it.

00:26:37.500 --> 00:26:41.380
But I'd rather believe that it was out of the kindness of his heart, wouldn't you?

00:26:41.920 --> 00:26:46.320
When we got on the train I felt as if everybody must be looking at me and pitying me.

00:26:46.740 --> 00:26:51.080
But I just went to work and imagined that I had on the most beautiful pale blue silk dress.

00:26:51.460 --> 00:26:55.220
Because when you are imagining, you might as well imagine something worthwhile

00:26:55.220 --> 00:26:57.960
and a big hat, all flowers and knotting plumes,

00:26:58.460 --> 00:27:00.960
and a gold watch, and kid gloves and boots.

00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:03.260
I felt cheered up right away

00:27:03.260 --> 00:27:06.280
and I enjoyed my trip to the island with all my might.

00:27:07.400 --> 00:27:09.920
I wasn't a bit sick coming over in the boat.

00:27:10.460 --> 00:27:13.340
Neither was Mrs. Spencer, although she generally is.

00:27:13.980 --> 00:27:17.840
She said she hadn't time to get sick watching to see that I didn't fall overboard.

00:27:18.860 --> 00:27:21.380
She said she never saw the bead of me for prowling about.

00:27:21.960 --> 00:27:26.180
But if it kept her from being seasick, it's a mercy I did prowl, isn't it?

00:27:26.520 --> 00:27:29.540
And I wanted to see everything that was to be seen on that boat

00:27:29.540 --> 00:27:32.180
because I didn't know whether I'd ever have another opportunity.

00:27:32.820 --> 00:27:36.400
Oh, there are a lot more cherry trees all in bloom.

00:27:36.900 --> 00:27:38.940
This island is the bloomiest place.

00:27:39.480 --> 00:27:42.960
I just love it already and I'm so glad I'm going to live here.

00:27:43.500 --> 00:27:47.120
I've always heard that Prince Edward Island was the prettiest place in the world

00:27:47.120 --> 00:27:51.740
and I used to imagine I was living here, but I never really expected I would.

00:27:52.400 --> 00:27:55.760
It's delightful when your imaginations come true, isn't it?

00:27:56.280 --> 00:27:58.100
But those red roads are so funny.

00:27:58.100 --> 00:28:02.580
When we got into the train at Charlottetown and the red roads began to flash past,

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:06.940
I asked Mrs. Spencer what made them red and she said she didn't know

00:28:06.940 --> 00:28:09.660
and for pity's sake not to ask her any more questions.

00:28:10.560 --> 00:28:13.020
She said I must have asked her a thousand already.

00:28:13.860 --> 00:28:15.420
I suppose I had, too.

00:28:15.760 --> 00:28:18.760
But how are you going to find out about things if you don't ask questions?

00:28:19.580 --> 00:28:21.400
And what does make the roads red?

00:28:22.520 --> 00:28:25.760
Well, now, I don't know, said Matthew.

00:28:26.520 --> 00:28:29.180
Well, that is one of the things to find out sometime.

00:28:30.020 --> 00:28:33.080
Isn't it splendid to think of all the things there are to find out about?

00:28:33.420 --> 00:28:35.460
It just makes me feel glad to be alive.

00:28:36.040 --> 00:28:37.660
It's such an interesting world.

00:28:38.280 --> 00:28:41.720
It wouldn't be half so interesting if we knew all about everything, would it?

00:28:42.120 --> 00:28:44.460
There would be no scope for imagination then, would there?

00:28:45.420 --> 00:28:46.940
But am I talking too much?

00:28:47.300 --> 00:28:49.140
People are always telling me I do.

00:28:49.820 --> 00:28:51.240
Would you rather I didn't talk?

00:28:51.560 --> 00:28:53.060
If you say so, I'll stop.

00:28:53.060 --> 00:28:58.020
I can stop when I make up my mind to, although it's difficult.

00:28:59.300 --> 00:29:02.140
Matthew, much to his own surprise, was enjoying himself.

00:29:02.340 --> 00:29:07.120
Like most quiet folks, he liked talkative people when they were willing to do the talking themselves

00:29:07.120 --> 00:29:09.320
and did not expect him to keep up his end of it.

00:29:09.840 --> 00:29:12.900
But he had never expected to enjoy the society of a little girl.

00:29:13.600 --> 00:29:17.380
Women were bad enough in all conscience, but little girls were worse.

00:29:17.960 --> 00:29:22.580
He detested the way they had of sidling past him timidly with sideways glances

00:29:22.580 --> 00:29:27.100
as if they expected him to gobble them up at a mouthful if they ventured to say a word.

00:29:27.860 --> 00:29:30.600
That was the avidly type of well-bred little girls.

00:29:31.760 --> 00:29:36.060
But this freckled witch was very different, and although he found it rather difficult

00:29:36.060 --> 00:29:39.340
for his slower intelligence to keep up with her brisk mental processes,

00:29:39.920 --> 00:29:41.980
he thought that he kind of liked her chatter.

00:29:42.760 --> 00:29:44.520
So he said as shyly as usual,

00:29:45.540 --> 00:29:48.560
Oh, you can talk as much as you like. I don't mind.

00:29:49.580 --> 00:29:53.960
Oh, I'm so glad. I know you and I are going to get along together fine.

00:29:54.500 --> 00:29:56.920
It's such a relief to talk when one wants to,

00:29:56.980 --> 00:29:59.440
and not to be told that children should be seen and not heard.

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:02.920
I've had that said to me a million times if I had once.

00:30:03.580 --> 00:30:05.940
And people laugh at me because I use big words.

00:30:06.480 --> 00:30:10.780
But if you have big ideas, you have to use big words to express them, haven't you?

00:30:11.640 --> 00:30:14.920
Well, now, that seems reasonable, said Matthew.

00:30:15.860 --> 00:30:18.600
Mrs. Spencer said that my tongue must be hung in the middle.

00:30:19.120 --> 00:30:22.120
But it isn't. It's firmly fastened at one end.

00:30:22.980 --> 00:30:25.540
Mrs. Spencer said your place was named Green Gables.

00:30:26.040 --> 00:30:30.220
I asked her all about it, and she said there were trees all around it.

00:30:30.360 --> 00:30:33.060
I was gladder than ever. I just love trees.

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:35.900
And there weren't any at all about the asylum.

00:30:36.140 --> 00:30:39.180
Only a few poor weeny-teeny things out in front,

00:30:39.260 --> 00:30:41.380
with little white-washed cagey things about them.

00:30:41.380 --> 00:30:44.520
They just looked like orphans themselves, those trees did.

00:30:45.080 --> 00:30:47.380
It used to make me want to cry to look at them.

00:30:47.820 --> 00:30:48.920
I used to say to them,

00:30:49.380 --> 00:30:51.120
Oh, you poor little things!

00:30:51.640 --> 00:30:55.220
If you were out in a great big woods with other trees all about you,

00:30:55.340 --> 00:30:58.120
and little mosses and June bells growing over your roots,

00:30:58.280 --> 00:31:01.700
and a brook not far away, and birds singing in the branches,

00:31:02.060 --> 00:31:03.600
you could grow, couldn't you?

00:31:04.220 --> 00:31:05.860
But you can't where you are.

00:31:06.560 --> 00:31:08.700
I know just how you feel, little trees.

00:31:08.700 --> 00:31:12.000
I felt sorry to leave them behind this morning.

00:31:12.280 --> 00:31:15.560
You do get so attached to things like that, don't you?

00:31:16.800 --> 00:31:18.900
Is there a brook anywhere near Green Gables?

00:31:19.260 --> 00:31:21.240
I forgot to ask Mrs. Spencer that.

00:31:22.580 --> 00:31:26.160
Well, now, yes, there's one right below the house.

00:31:27.420 --> 00:31:31.020
Fancy! It's always been one of my dreams to live near a brook.

00:31:31.480 --> 00:31:33.420
I never expected I would, though.

00:31:34.220 --> 00:31:36.220
Dreams don't often come true, do they?

00:31:36.220 --> 00:31:38.340
Wouldn't it be nice if they did?

00:31:39.240 --> 00:31:42.200
But just now I feel pretty nearly perfectly happy.

00:31:42.680 --> 00:31:46.360
I can't feel exactly perfectly happy, because, well,

00:31:46.780 --> 00:31:48.360
what color would you call this?

00:31:49.080 --> 00:31:52.400
She twitched one of her long glossy braids over her thin shoulder

00:31:52.400 --> 00:31:54.420
and held it up before Matthew's eyes.

00:31:55.440 --> 00:31:58.480
Matthew was not used to deciding on the tints of ladies' tresses,

00:31:58.520 --> 00:32:01.220
but in this case there couldn't be much doubt.

00:32:01.960 --> 00:32:04.100
It's red, ain't it? he said.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:07.480
The girl let the braid drop with a sigh

00:32:07.480 --> 00:32:09.480
that seemed to come from her very toes

00:32:09.480 --> 00:32:12.400
and exhale forth all the sorrows of the ages.

00:32:13.940 --> 00:32:16.660
Yes, it's red, she said resignedly.

00:32:17.460 --> 00:32:20.060
Now you see why I can't be perfectly happy.

00:32:20.760 --> 00:32:22.560
Nobody could who has red hair.

00:32:23.740 --> 00:32:25.680
I don't mind the other things so much,

00:32:25.760 --> 00:32:28.380
the freckles and the green eyes and my skinniness.

00:32:28.740 --> 00:32:30.320
I can imagine them away.

00:32:30.320 --> 00:32:34.680
I can imagine that I have a beautiful rose leaf complexion

00:32:34.680 --> 00:32:37.220
and lovely starry violet eyes,

00:32:37.960 --> 00:32:40.400
but I cannot imagine that red hair away.

00:32:41.060 --> 00:32:42.220
I do my best.

00:32:42.940 --> 00:32:46.640
I think to myself, now my hair is a glorious black,

00:32:47.300 --> 00:32:48.940
black as the raven's wing,

00:32:49.320 --> 00:32:52.240
but all the time I know it is just plain red,

00:32:52.700 --> 00:32:54.300
and it breaks my heart.

00:32:54.820 --> 00:32:56.760
It will be my lifelong sorrow.

00:32:56.760 --> 00:33:00.540
I read of a girl once in a novel who had a lifelong sorrow,

00:33:00.820 --> 00:33:02.240
but it wasn't red hair.

00:33:03.020 --> 00:33:06.580
Her hair was pure gold rippling back from her alabaster brow.

00:33:07.380 --> 00:33:10.200
What is an alabaster brow? I never could find out.

00:33:10.400 --> 00:33:11.400
Can you tell me?

00:33:12.520 --> 00:33:15.780
Well, no, I'm afraid I can't, said Matthew,

00:33:16.100 --> 00:33:17.480
who was getting a little dizzy.

00:33:18.300 --> 00:33:21.120
He felt as he had once felt in his rash youth

00:33:21.120 --> 00:33:24.200
when another boy had enticed him on the merry-go-round at a picnic.

00:33:24.860 --> 00:33:28.120
Well, whatever it was, it must have been something nice

00:33:28.120 --> 00:33:30.020
because she was divinely beautiful.

00:33:30.680 --> 00:33:33.780
Have you ever imagined what it must feel like to be divinely beautiful?

00:33:35.220 --> 00:33:39.920
Well, now, no, I haven't, confessed Matthew ingenuously.

00:33:41.040 --> 00:33:42.080
I have often.

00:33:42.800 --> 00:33:44.860
Which would you rather be if you had the choice,

00:33:45.420 --> 00:33:49.500
divinely beautiful or dazzlingly clever or angelically good?

00:33:50.520 --> 00:33:54.840
Well, now, I don't know exactly.

00:33:56.180 --> 00:33:57.000
Neither do I.

00:33:57.220 --> 00:33:58.540
I can never decide.

00:33:59.040 --> 00:34:00.660
But it doesn't make much real difference,

00:34:00.700 --> 00:34:02.820
for it isn't likely I'll ever be either.

00:34:03.680 --> 00:34:06.020
It's certain I'll never be angelically good.

00:34:06.620 --> 00:34:07.720
Mrs. Spencer says,

00:34:08.800 --> 00:34:14.960
Oh, Mr. Cuthbert! Oh, Mr. Cuthbert! Oh, Mr. Cuthbert!

00:34:15.760 --> 00:34:18.360
That was not what Mrs. Spencer had said.

00:34:18.360 --> 00:34:20.600
Neither had the child tumbled out of the buggy,

00:34:20.920 --> 00:34:22.860
nor had Matthew done anything astonishing.

00:34:23.800 --> 00:34:28.260
They had simply rounded a curve in the road and found themselves in the Avenue.

00:34:29.500 --> 00:34:31.700
The Avenue, so called by the Newbridge people,

00:34:31.880 --> 00:34:34.460
was a stretch of road four or five hundred yards long,

00:34:34.880 --> 00:34:37.820
completely arched over with huge, wide-spreading apple trees,

00:34:38.220 --> 00:34:40.500
planted years ago by an eccentric old farmer.

00:34:41.620 --> 00:34:44.620
Overhead was one long canopy of snowy, fragrant bloom.

00:34:45.180 --> 00:34:48.480
Below the boughs the air was full of a purple twilight,

00:34:49.240 --> 00:34:52.060
and far ahead a glimpse of painted sunset sky

00:34:52.060 --> 00:34:56.080
shone like a great rose window at the end of a cathedral aisle.

00:34:57.060 --> 00:34:59.020
Its beauty seemed to strike the child dumb.

00:34:59.640 --> 00:35:03.600
She leaned back in the buggy, her thin hands clasped before her,

00:35:03.760 --> 00:35:06.600
her face lifted rapturously to the white splendor above.

00:35:07.460 --> 00:35:10.960
Even when they had passed out and were driving down the long slope to Newbridge,

00:35:11.520 --> 00:35:12.820
she never moved or spoke.

00:35:13.820 --> 00:35:17.660
Still, with rapt face, she gazed afar into the sunset west,

00:35:17.880 --> 00:35:21.920
with eyes that saw visions trooping splendidly across the glowing background.

00:35:23.040 --> 00:35:26.400
Through Newbridge, a bustling little village where dogs barked at them

00:35:26.400 --> 00:35:29.640
and small boys hooted and curious faces peered from the windows,

00:35:29.920 --> 00:35:31.660
they drove, still in silence.

00:35:32.380 --> 00:35:36.180
When three more miles had dropped away behind them, the child had not spoken.

00:35:36.920 --> 00:35:40.920
She could keep silence, it was evident, as energetically she could talk.

00:35:42.200 --> 00:35:47.000
I guess you're feeling pretty tired and hungry, Matthew ventured to say at last,

00:35:47.300 --> 00:35:51.360
accounting for her long visitation of dumbness with the only reason he could think of.

00:35:51.800 --> 00:35:55.260
But we haven't very far to go now, only another mile.

00:35:56.340 --> 00:35:58.640
She came out of her reverie with a deep sigh,

00:35:58.820 --> 00:36:03.720
and looked at him with the dreamy gaze of a soul that had been wandering afar star-led.

00:36:04.540 --> 00:36:10.340
Oh, Mr. Cuthbert, she whispered, that place we came through, that white place,

00:36:10.340 --> 00:36:12.100
what was it?

00:36:12.980 --> 00:36:18.360
Well now, you mean the avenue, said Matthew after a few moments' profound reflection.

00:36:18.880 --> 00:36:20.580
It is a kind of pretty place.

00:36:21.840 --> 00:36:27.760
Pretty? Oh, pretty doesn't seem the right word to use, nor beautiful either.

00:36:28.180 --> 00:36:29.720
They don't go far enough.

00:36:30.640 --> 00:36:32.180
Oh, it was wonderful.

00:36:32.780 --> 00:36:36.700
It's the first thing I ever saw that couldn't be improved upon by my imagination.

00:36:37.440 --> 00:36:39.340
It just satisfies me here.

00:36:39.340 --> 00:36:41.360
She put one hand on her breast.

00:36:41.780 --> 00:36:44.920
It made a queer funny ache, and yet it was a pleasant ache.

00:36:45.620 --> 00:36:47.940
Did you ever have an ache like that, Mr. Cuthbert?

00:36:49.100 --> 00:36:52.680
Well now, I just can't recollect that I ever had.

00:36:53.860 --> 00:36:57.880
I have it lots of times, whenever I see anything royally beautiful.

00:36:58.800 --> 00:37:01.020
But they shouldn't call that lovely place the avenue.

00:37:01.480 --> 00:37:03.460
There is no meaning in a name like that.

00:37:04.220 --> 00:37:07.080
They should call it, let me see,

00:37:07.080 --> 00:37:09.180
the White Way of Delight.

00:37:09.680 --> 00:37:11.640
Isn't that a nice imaginative name?

00:37:12.540 --> 00:37:16.540
When I don't like the name of a place or a person, I always imagine a new one,

00:37:16.800 --> 00:37:18.280
and always think of them so.

00:37:19.040 --> 00:37:22.140
There was a girl at the asylum whose name was Hepzibah Jenkins,

00:37:22.780 --> 00:37:25.340
but I always imagined her as Rosalia Devere.

00:37:26.560 --> 00:37:32.260
Other people may call that place the avenue, but I shall always call it the White Way of Delight.

00:37:33.100 --> 00:37:36.480
Have we really only another mile to go before we get home?

00:37:37.320 --> 00:37:39.020
I'm glad and I'm sorry.

00:37:39.640 --> 00:37:42.040
I'm sorry because this drive has been so pleasant,

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:44.840
and I'm always sorry when pleasant things end.

00:37:45.400 --> 00:37:49.320
Something still pleasanter may come after, but you can never be sure,

00:37:49.820 --> 00:37:52.080
and it's so often the case that it isn't pleasanter.

00:37:52.480 --> 00:37:54.400
That has been my experience anyhow.

00:37:55.120 --> 00:37:57.020
But I'm glad to think of getting home.

00:37:57.520 --> 00:38:00.500
You see, I've never had a real home since I can remember.

00:38:00.500 --> 00:38:06.780
It gives me that pleasant ache again just to think of coming to a really truly home.

00:38:07.940 --> 00:38:09.620
Oh, isn't that pretty?

00:38:10.640 --> 00:38:12.320
They had driven over the crest of a hill.

00:38:12.620 --> 00:38:17.280
Below them was a pond looking almost like a river, so long and winding was it.

00:38:18.080 --> 00:38:21.860
A bridge spanned it midway, and from there to its lower end,

00:38:22.020 --> 00:38:26.760
where an amber-hued belt of sand hills shut it in from the dark blue gulf beyond,

00:38:27.260 --> 00:38:29.680
the water was a glory of many shifting hues.

00:38:29.680 --> 00:38:34.200
The most spiritual shadings of crocus and rose and ethereal green,

00:38:34.760 --> 00:38:38.240
with other elusive tintings for which no name has ever been found.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:42.920
Above the bridge, the pond ran up into fringing groves of fir and maple,

00:38:43.420 --> 00:38:46.320
and lay all darkly translucent in their wavering shadows.

00:38:46.980 --> 00:38:52.600
Here and there a wild plum leaned out from the bank like a white-clad girl tiptoeing to her own reflection.

00:38:53.560 --> 00:38:57.880
From the marsh at the head of the pond came the clear mournfully sweet chorus of the frogs.

00:38:57.880 --> 00:39:02.980
There was a little gray house peering around a white apple orchard on a slope beyond,

00:39:03.360 --> 00:39:08.060
and although it was not yet quite dark, a light was shining from one of its windows.

00:39:09.180 --> 00:39:11.620
That's Barry's pond, said Matthew.

00:39:12.840 --> 00:39:14.760
Oh, I don't like that name either.

00:39:15.400 --> 00:39:20.740
I shall call it, let me see, the Lake of Shining Waters.

00:39:21.640 --> 00:39:23.840
Yes, that is the right name for it.

00:39:24.340 --> 00:39:25.920
I know because of the thrill.

00:39:25.920 --> 00:39:29.680
When I hit on a name that suits exactly, it gives me a thrill.

00:39:30.840 --> 00:39:32.240
Do things ever give you a thrill?

00:39:33.440 --> 00:39:34.400
Matthew ruminated.

00:39:35.560 --> 00:39:36.740
Well, now, yes.

00:39:37.300 --> 00:39:42.660
It always kind of gives me a thrill to see them ugly white grubs that spade up in the cucumber beds.

00:39:43.420 --> 00:39:44.780
I hate the look of them.

00:39:46.140 --> 00:39:49.640
Oh, I don't think that can be exactly the same kind of a thrill.

00:39:50.220 --> 00:39:51.220
Do you think it can?

00:39:51.740 --> 00:39:56.260
There doesn't seem to be much connection between grubs and Lakes of Shining Waters, does there?

00:39:57.160 --> 00:39:59.100
But why do other people call it Barry's pond?

00:40:00.220 --> 00:40:03.520
I reckon because Mr. Barry lives up there in that house.

00:40:04.100 --> 00:40:05.920
Orchard Slope's the name of his place.

00:40:06.660 --> 00:40:10.160
If it wasn't for that big bush behind it, you could see Green Gables from here.

00:40:10.460 --> 00:40:15.100
But we have to go over the bridge and round by the road, so it's near half a mile further.

00:40:16.320 --> 00:40:18.820
Has Mr. Barry any little girls?

00:40:18.820 --> 00:40:21.060
Well, not so very little either.

00:40:21.160 --> 00:40:22.420
About my size.

00:40:23.960 --> 00:40:25.480
He's got one about eleven.

00:40:25.800 --> 00:40:26.880
Her name is Diana.

00:40:28.300 --> 00:40:31.060
Oh, with a long in-drawing of breath.

00:40:31.720 --> 00:40:34.140
What a perfectly lovely name.

00:40:35.640 --> 00:40:37.560
Well, now, I don't know.

00:40:38.020 --> 00:40:41.360
There's something dreadfully heathen-ish about it, seems to me.

00:40:41.720 --> 00:40:45.900
I'd rather Jane or Mary, or some sensible name like that.

00:40:45.900 --> 00:40:53.200
But when Diana was born, there was a schoolmaster boarding there, and they gave him the naming of her, and he called her Diana.

00:40:54.340 --> 00:40:58.020
I wish there had been a schoolmaster like that around when I was born, then.

00:40:58.980 --> 00:41:00.340
Oh, here we are at the bridge.

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:02.620
I'm going to shut my eyes tight.

00:41:02.840 --> 00:41:04.680
I'm always afraid going over bridges.

00:41:05.240 --> 00:41:11.160
I can't help imagining that perhaps just as we get to the middle, they'll crumple up like a jackknife and nip us.

00:41:11.420 --> 00:41:12.780
So I shut my eyes.

00:41:12.780 --> 00:41:16.960
But I always have to open them for all when I think we're getting near the middle.

00:41:17.660 --> 00:41:21.760
Because, you see, if the bridge did crumple up, I'd want to see it crumple.

00:41:22.180 --> 00:41:23.800
What a jolly rumble it makes.

00:41:24.320 --> 00:41:26.040
I always like the rumble part of it.

00:41:26.300 --> 00:41:27.100
Isn't it splendid?

00:41:27.220 --> 00:41:29.240
There are so many things to like in this world.

00:41:30.120 --> 00:41:30.960
There, we're over.

00:41:31.120 --> 00:41:32.320
Now I'll look back.

00:41:33.100 --> 00:41:35.020
Good night, dear lake of shining waters.

00:41:35.640 --> 00:41:39.620
I always say good night to the things I love, just as I would to people.

00:41:39.800 --> 00:41:41.060
I think they like it.

00:41:41.600 --> 00:41:44.260
That water looks as if it was smiling at me.

00:41:45.580 --> 00:41:49.040
When they had driven up the further hill and around a corner, Matthew said,

00:41:49.580 --> 00:41:51.120
We're pretty near home now.

00:41:51.480 --> 00:41:52.800
There's Green Gables over.

00:41:53.220 --> 00:42:00.400
Oh, don't tell me, she interrupted breathlessly, catching at his partially raised arm and shutting her eyes that she might not see the gesture.

00:42:00.920 --> 00:42:01.620
Let me guess.

00:42:01.960 --> 00:42:03.320
I'm sure I'll guess right.

00:42:04.040 --> 00:42:06.220
She opened her eyes and looked about her.

00:42:06.560 --> 00:42:08.040
They were on the crust of a hill.

00:42:08.040 --> 00:42:13.340
The sun had set some time since, but the landscape was still clear in the mellow afterlight.

00:42:14.100 --> 00:42:18.060
In the west, a dark church spire rose up against a marigold sky.

00:42:18.780 --> 00:42:25.100
Below was a little valley, and beyond a long, gently rising slope with snug farmsteads scattered along it.

00:42:25.600 --> 00:42:28.640
From one to another, the child's eyes darted eager and wistful.

00:42:29.020 --> 00:42:37.140
At last, they lingered on one away to the left, far back from the road, dimly white with blossoming trees in the twilight of the surrounding woods.

00:42:37.760 --> 00:42:44.920
Over it, in the stainless southwest sky, a great crystal-white star was shining like a glamp of guidance and promise.

00:42:46.160 --> 00:42:48.220
That's it, isn't it? she said, pointing.

00:42:49.280 --> 00:42:51.920
Matthew slapped the rains and the sorrows back delightedly.

00:42:52.880 --> 00:42:57.640
Well, now you've guessed it, but I reckon Mrs. Spencer described it so as you could tell.

00:42:58.600 --> 00:43:03.960
No, she didn't. Really, she didn't. All she said might just as well have been about most of those other places.

00:43:03.960 --> 00:43:10.240
I hadn't any real idea what it looked like, but just as soon as I saw it, I felt it was home.

00:43:10.960 --> 00:43:13.360
Oh, it seems as if I must be in a dream.

00:43:14.120 --> 00:43:20.420
Do you know, my arm must be black and blue from the elbow up, for I've pinched myself so many times today.

00:43:21.380 --> 00:43:27.080
Every little while a horrible sickening feeling would come over me, and I'd be so afraid it was all a dream.

00:43:27.660 --> 00:43:29.880
Then I'd pinch myself to see if it was real.

00:43:29.880 --> 00:43:38.920
Until suddenly I remembered that even supposing it was only a dream, I'd better go on dreaming as long as I could, so I stopped pinching.

00:43:39.340 --> 00:43:41.960
But it is real, and we're nearly home.

00:43:43.080 --> 00:43:45.760
With a sigh of rapture she relapsed into silence.

00:43:46.840 --> 00:43:48.060
Matthew stirred uneasily.

00:43:48.500 --> 00:43:56.560
He felt glad that it would be Marilla and not he who would have to tell this waif of the world that the home she longed for was not to be hers after all.

00:43:56.560 --> 00:44:08.060
They drove over Lynn's Hollow where it was already quite dark, but not so dark that Mrs. Rachel could not see them from her window vantage, and up the hill and into the long lane of green gables.

00:44:09.380 --> 00:44:15.420
By the time they arrived at the house, Matthew was shrinking from the approaching revelation with an energy he did not understand.

00:44:16.020 --> 00:44:22.760
It was not of Marilla or himself he was thinking of the trouble this mistake was probably going to make for them, but of the child's disappointment.

00:44:22.760 --> 00:44:37.260
When he thought of that rapt light being quenched in her eyes, he had an uncomfortable feeling that he was going to assist at murdering something, much the same feeling that came over him when he had to kill a lamb or calf or any other innocent little creature.

00:44:38.840 --> 00:44:44.360
The yard was quite dark as they turned into it, and the poplar leaves were rustling silkily all round it.

00:44:45.200 --> 00:44:52.040
Listen to the trees talking in their sleep, she whispered, as he lifted her to the ground. What nice dreams they must have!

00:44:53.100 --> 00:44:59.080
Then, holding tightly to the carpet bag, which contained all her worldly goods, she followed him into the house.

00:45:19.660 --> 00:45:28.020
Reading by Annie Coleman in St. Louis, Missouri on December 13th, 2005.

00:45:29.380 --> 00:45:33.180
Anne of Green Gables by Lucy Maude Montgomery

00:45:33.700 --> 00:45:38.940
Marilla Cuthbert is surprised.

00:45:40.940 --> 00:45:45.160
Marilla came briskly forward as Matthew opened the door,

00:45:45.160 --> 00:45:57.300
but when her eyes fell on the odd little figure in the stiff ugly dress with the long braids of red hair and the eager luminous eyes, she stopped short in amazement.

00:45:58.020 --> 00:46:00.960
Matthew Cuthbert, who's that? she ejaculated.

00:46:01.360 --> 00:46:02.260
Where's the boy?

00:46:03.180 --> 00:46:06.200
There wasn't any boy, said Matthew wretchedly.

00:46:06.820 --> 00:46:08.320
There was only her.

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:13.820
He nodded at the child, remembering that he had never even asked her name.

00:46:14.580 --> 00:46:18.220
No boy, but there must have been a boy, insisted Marilla.

00:46:18.980 --> 00:46:21.440
We sent word to Mrs. Spencer to bring a boy.

00:46:22.400 --> 00:46:23.440
Well, she didn't.

00:46:23.520 --> 00:46:24.720
She brought her.

00:46:25.360 --> 00:46:28.780
I asked the station master and I had to bring her home.

00:46:29.140 --> 00:46:32.720
She couldn't be left there no matter where the mistake had come in.

00:46:33.640 --> 00:46:37.120
Well, this is a pretty piece of business, ejaculated Marilla.

00:46:38.300 --> 00:46:41.280
During this dialogue, the child had remained silent,

00:46:41.280 --> 00:46:47.820
her eyes roving from one to the other, all the animation fading out of her face.

00:46:48.220 --> 00:46:53.040
Suddenly, she seemed to grasp the full meaning of what had been said.

00:46:53.760 --> 00:46:58.860
Dropping her precious carpet bag, she sprang forward a step and clasped her hands.

00:46:59.480 --> 00:47:01.560
You don't want me, she cried.

00:47:02.060 --> 00:47:04.240
You don't want me because I'm not a boy.

00:47:04.820 --> 00:47:06.560
I might have expected it.

00:47:07.000 --> 00:47:08.560
Nobody ever did want me.

00:47:08.560 --> 00:47:11.720
I might have known it was all too beautiful to last.

00:47:12.240 --> 00:47:14.980
I might have known nobody really did want me.

00:47:15.460 --> 00:47:17.160
Oh, what shall I do?

00:47:17.580 --> 00:47:19.500
I'm going to burst into tears.

00:47:20.640 --> 00:47:22.500
Burst into tears, she did.

00:47:23.220 --> 00:47:27.860
Sitting down on a chair by the table, flinging her arms out upon it,

00:47:28.180 --> 00:47:32.920
and burying her face in them, she proceeded to cry stormily.

00:47:33.480 --> 00:47:38.620
Marilla and Matthew looked at each other deprecatingly across the stove.

00:47:39.160 --> 00:47:42.100
Neither of them knew what to say or do.

00:47:42.840 --> 00:47:46.180
Finally, Marilla stepped lamely into the breach.

00:47:47.500 --> 00:47:50.720
Well, well, there's no need to cry so about it.

00:47:51.240 --> 00:47:52.880
Yes, there is need.

00:47:53.340 --> 00:47:58.420
The child raised her head quickly, revealing a tear stained face and

00:47:58.420 --> 00:47:59.360
trembling lips.

00:47:59.900 --> 00:48:04.880
You would cry too if you were an orphan and had come to a place you thought was

00:48:04.880 --> 00:48:09.280
going to be home and found they didn't want you because you weren't a boy.

00:48:09.940 --> 00:48:14.500
This is the most tragical thing that ever happened to me.

00:48:15.300 --> 00:48:20.800
Something like a reluctant smile, rather rusty from long disuse,

00:48:21.180 --> 00:48:23.600
mellowed Marilla's grim expression.

00:48:24.460 --> 00:48:26.180
Well, don't cry anymore.

00:48:26.180 --> 00:48:29.160
We're not going to turn you out of doors tonight.

00:48:29.640 --> 00:48:32.620
You'll have to stay here until we investigate this affair.

00:48:33.540 --> 00:48:34.380
What's your name?

00:48:35.180 --> 00:48:37.440
The child hesitated for a moment.

00:48:38.360 --> 00:48:42.320
Will you please call me Cordelia, she said eagerly.

00:48:42.860 --> 00:48:44.180
Call you Cordelia?

00:48:44.660 --> 00:48:45.640
Is that your name?

00:48:46.960 --> 00:48:52.560
No, it's not exactly my name, but I would love to be called Cordelia.

00:48:53.200 --> 00:48:55.640
It's such a perfectly elegant name.

00:48:56.440 --> 00:48:57.880
I don't know what on earth you mean.

00:48:58.220 --> 00:49:01.200
If Cordelia isn't your name, what is?

00:49:02.560 --> 00:49:07.120
Anne Shirley, reluctantly faltered forth, the owner of that name.

00:49:07.760 --> 00:49:10.100
But please do call me Cordelia.

00:49:10.540 --> 00:49:14.700
It can't matter much to you what you call me if I'm only going to be here a little

00:49:14.700 --> 00:49:15.560
while, can it?

00:49:16.060 --> 00:49:18.700
And Anne is such an unromantic name.

00:49:20.520 --> 00:49:23.700
Unromantic fiddlesticks, said the unsympathetic Marilla.

00:49:24.340 --> 00:49:27.100
Anne is a real, good, plain, sensible name.

00:49:27.540 --> 00:49:29.260
You've no need to be ashamed of it.

00:49:30.020 --> 00:49:32.360
I'm not ashamed of it, explained Anne.

00:49:32.760 --> 00:49:34.600
Only I like Cordelia better.

00:49:35.060 --> 00:49:37.680
I've always imagined that my name was Cordelia.

00:49:38.180 --> 00:49:40.340
At least I always have of late years.

00:49:40.880 --> 00:49:43.620
When I was young, I used to imagine it was Geraldine.

00:49:44.040 --> 00:49:45.780
But I like Cordelia better now.

00:49:46.640 --> 00:49:51.100
But if you call me Anne, please call me Anne, spelled with an E.

00:49:52.260 --> 00:49:54.700
What difference does it make how it's spelled?

00:49:55.380 --> 00:49:59.300
Asked Marilla, with another rusty smile, as she picked up the teapot.

00:50:00.280 --> 00:50:02.140
Oh, it makes such a difference.

00:50:02.480 --> 00:50:04.200
It looks so much nicer.

00:50:04.800 --> 00:50:08.340
When you hear a name pronounced, can't you always see it in your mind,

00:50:08.740 --> 00:50:10.660
just as if it was printed out?

00:50:11.020 --> 00:50:14.960
I can, and A-N-N looks dreadful.

00:50:14.960 --> 00:50:18.960
But A-N-N-E looks so much more distinguished.

00:50:19.620 --> 00:50:22.660
If you'll only call me Anne, spelled with an E,

00:50:23.040 --> 00:50:26.780
I shall try to reconcile myself to not being called Cordelia.

00:50:28.460 --> 00:50:31.340
Very well then, Anne, spelled with N-E.

00:50:31.520 --> 00:50:34.280
Can you tell us how this mistake came to be made?

00:50:34.660 --> 00:50:37.340
We sent word to Mrs. Spencer to bring us a boy.

00:50:37.940 --> 00:50:39.640
Were there no boys at the asylum?

00:50:40.700 --> 00:50:42.960
Oh yes, there was an abundance of them.

00:50:42.960 --> 00:50:48.800
But Mrs. Spencer said distinctly that you wanted a girl about 11 years old.

00:50:49.300 --> 00:50:52.000
And the matron said she thought I would do.

00:50:52.460 --> 00:50:54.500
You don't know how delighted I was.

00:50:54.860 --> 00:50:57.040
I couldn't sleep all last night for joy.

00:50:57.560 --> 00:51:00.380
Oh, she added reproachfully, turning to Matthew,

00:51:00.740 --> 00:51:05.060
why didn't you tell me at the station that you didn't want me and leave me there?

00:51:05.560 --> 00:51:10.360
If I hadn't seen the white way of delight and the lake of shining waters,

00:51:10.700 --> 00:51:12.480
it wouldn't be so hard.

00:51:13.480 --> 00:51:17.040
What on earth does she mean, demanded Marilla, staring at Matthew.

00:51:18.380 --> 00:51:23.980
She's just referring to some conversation we had on the road, said Matthew hastily.

00:51:24.680 --> 00:51:26.820
I'm going out to put the mare in, Marilla.

00:51:27.100 --> 00:51:28.880
Have tea ready when I come back.

00:51:30.040 --> 00:51:33.160
Did Mrs. Spencer bring anybody over besides you,

00:51:33.460 --> 00:51:35.760
continued Marilla when Matthew had gone out.

00:51:36.380 --> 00:51:38.460
She brought Lily Jones for herself.

00:51:38.980 --> 00:51:41.740
Lily is only five years old and she is very beautiful.

00:51:42.200 --> 00:51:44.500
She has nut brown hair.

00:51:45.240 --> 00:51:49.540
If I was very beautiful and had nut brown hair, would you keep me?

00:51:50.260 --> 00:51:53.400
No, we want a boy to help Matthew on the farm.

00:51:53.940 --> 00:51:56.180
A girl would be of no use to us.

00:51:56.580 --> 00:51:57.520
Take off your hat.

00:51:58.120 --> 00:52:00.640
I'll lay it in your bag on the hall table.

00:52:02.420 --> 00:52:04.500
Anne took off her hat meekly.

00:52:04.860 --> 00:52:08.180
Matthew came back presently and they sat down to supper.

00:52:08.460 --> 00:52:10.280
But Anne could not eat.

00:52:10.980 --> 00:52:15.640
In vain, she nibbled at the bread and butter and packed at the crabapple preserve

00:52:15.640 --> 00:52:18.800
out of the little scalloped glass dish by her plate.

00:52:19.580 --> 00:52:22.080
She did not really make any headway at all.

00:52:22.600 --> 00:52:25.800
You're not eating anything, said Marilla sharply,

00:52:26.340 --> 00:52:29.580
eyeing her as if it were a serious shortcoming.

00:52:30.260 --> 00:52:31.980
Anne sighed.

00:52:32.180 --> 00:52:33.120
I can't.

00:52:33.220 --> 00:52:35.140
I'm in the depths of despair.

00:52:35.680 --> 00:52:38.600
Can you eat when you're in the depths of despair?

00:52:39.740 --> 00:52:44.900
I've never been in the depths of despair, so I can't say, responded Marilla.

00:52:45.400 --> 00:52:46.080
Weren't you?

00:52:46.460 --> 00:52:49.860
Well, did you ever try to imagine you were in the depths of despair?

00:52:50.800 --> 00:52:52.560
No, I didn't.

00:52:53.040 --> 00:52:55.760
Then I don't think you can understand what it's like.

00:52:56.160 --> 00:52:58.760
It's a very uncomfortable feeling indeed.

00:52:59.380 --> 00:53:04.780
When you try to eat, a lump comes right up in your throat and you can't swallow anything.

00:53:04.780 --> 00:53:07.740
Not even if it was a chocolate caramel.

00:53:08.600 --> 00:53:14.300
I had one chocolate caramel once two years ago, and it was simply delicious.

00:53:15.060 --> 00:53:18.820
I've often dreamed since then that I had a lot of chocolate caramels,

00:53:19.120 --> 00:53:21.880
but I always wake up just when I'm going to eat them.

00:53:22.820 --> 00:53:25.300
I do hope you won't be offended because I can't eat.

00:53:25.820 --> 00:53:29.620
Everything is extremely nice, but still, I cannot eat.

00:53:30.220 --> 00:53:35.460
I guess she's tired, said Matthew, who hadn't spoken since his return from the barn.

00:53:36.220 --> 00:53:37.860
Best put her to bed, Marilla.

00:53:39.260 --> 00:53:42.540
Marilla had been wondering where Anne should be put to bed.

00:53:43.040 --> 00:53:47.780
She had prepared a couch in the kitchen chamber for the desired and expected boy,

00:53:48.160 --> 00:53:53.820
but although it was neat and clean, it did not seem quite the thing to put a girl there somehow.

00:53:54.560 --> 00:53:58.940
But the spare room was out of the question for such a stray waif,

00:53:58.940 --> 00:54:02.040
so there remained only the east gable room.

00:54:02.940 --> 00:54:08.400
Marilla lighted a candle and told Anne to follow her, which Anne spiritlessly did,

00:54:08.920 --> 00:54:13.200
taking her hat and carpet bag from the hall table as she passed.

00:54:14.040 --> 00:54:16.200
The hall was fearsomely clean.

00:54:16.660 --> 00:54:22.540
The little gable chamber in which she presently found herself seemed still cleaner.

00:54:23.920 --> 00:54:30.320
Marilla set the candle on a three-legged, three-cornered table and turned down the bedclothes.

00:54:31.460 --> 00:54:35.720
I suppose you have a nightgown? she questioned. Anne nodded.

00:54:35.980 --> 00:54:40.380
Yes, I have two. The matron of the asylum made them for me.

00:54:40.880 --> 00:54:45.260
They're fearfully skimpy. There is never enough to go around in an asylum,

00:54:45.800 --> 00:54:49.720
so things are always skimpy, at least in a poor asylum like ours.

00:54:50.280 --> 00:54:55.180
I hate skimpy nightdresses, but one can dream just as well in them,

00:54:55.340 --> 00:55:00.260
as in lovely trailing ones with frills around the neck. That's one consolation.

00:55:01.020 --> 00:55:05.560
Well, undress as quick as you can and go to bed. I'll come back in a few minutes for the candle.

00:55:06.140 --> 00:55:10.960
I daren't trust you to put it out yourself. You'd likely set the place on fire.

00:55:11.960 --> 00:55:15.620
When Marilla had gone, Anne looked around her wistfully.

00:55:16.140 --> 00:55:21.540
The white washed walls were so painfully bare and staring that she thought they must

00:55:21.540 --> 00:55:28.440
ache over their own bareness. The floor was bare too, except for a round braided mat in the middle,

00:55:28.840 --> 00:55:34.560
such as Anne had never seen before. In one corner was the bed, a high,

00:55:34.620 --> 00:55:41.780
old-fashioned one, with four dark, low-turned posts. In the other corner was the aforesaid

00:55:41.780 --> 00:55:47.740
three-cornered table, adorned with a fat red velvet pin cushion, hard enough to turn the

00:55:47.740 --> 00:55:53.780
point of the most adventurous pin. Above it hung a little six-by-eight mirror.

00:55:54.540 --> 00:56:00.860
Midway between table and bed was the window, with an icy white muslin frill over it,

00:56:01.080 --> 00:56:07.980
and opposite it was the washstand. The whole apartment was of a rigidity not to be described

00:56:07.980 --> 00:56:15.640
in words, but which sent a shiver to the very marrow of Anne's bones. With a sob she hastily

00:56:15.640 --> 00:56:21.780
discarded her garments, put on the skimpy nightgown, and sprang into bed, where she

00:56:21.780 --> 00:56:26.580
burrowed face downward into the pillow and pulled the clothes over her head.

00:56:27.380 --> 00:56:33.120
When Marilla came up for the light, various skimpy articles of raiment scattered most

00:56:33.120 --> 00:56:39.920
tidily over the floor, and a certain tempestuous appearance of the bed were the only indications

00:56:39.920 --> 00:56:47.460
of any presence save her own. She deliberately picked up Anne's clothes, placed them neatly

00:56:47.460 --> 00:56:53.360
on a prim yellow chair, and then, taking up the candle, went over to the bed.

00:56:54.080 --> 00:57:03.000
Good night, she said, a little awkwardly, but not unkindly. Anne's white face and big eyes appeared

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:09.360
over the bed clothes with a startling suddenness. How can you call it a good night when you know it

00:57:09.360 --> 00:57:16.100
must be the very worst night I've ever had? she said reproachfully. Then she dived down into

00:57:16.100 --> 00:57:23.020
invisibility again. Marilla went slowly down to the kitchen and proceeded to wash the supper

00:57:23.020 --> 00:57:31.760
dishes. Matthew was smoking, a sure sign of perturbation of mind. He seldom smoked, for

00:57:31.760 --> 00:57:38.380
Marilla set her face against it as a filthy habit, but at certain times and seasons he felt driven

00:57:38.380 --> 00:57:45.220
to it, and then Marilla winked at the practice, realizing that a mere man must have some bent

00:57:45.220 --> 00:57:52.340
for his emotions. Well, this is a pretty kettle of fish, she said wrathfully. This is what comes

00:57:52.340 --> 00:57:58.020
of sending word instead of going ourselves. Robert Spencer's folks have twisted that message

00:57:58.020 --> 00:58:04.560
somehow. One of us will have to drive over and see Mrs. Spencer tomorrow. That's certain. This girl

00:58:04.560 --> 00:58:13.140
will have to be sent back to the asylum. Yes, I suppose so, said Matthew reluctantly. You suppose

00:58:13.140 --> 00:58:21.520
so? Don't you know it? Well now, she's a real nice little thing, Marilla. It's kind of a pity to send

00:58:21.520 --> 00:58:28.660
her back when she's so set on staying here. Matthew Cuthbert, you don't mean to say you think we

00:58:28.660 --> 00:58:35.400
ought to keep her. Marilla's astonishment could not have been greater if Matthew had expressed

00:58:35.400 --> 00:58:45.460
a predilection for standing on his head. Well now, no, I suppose not. Not exactly, stammered Matthew,

00:58:46.280 --> 00:58:52.020
uncomfortably driven into a corner for his precise meaning. I suppose we could hardly

00:58:52.020 --> 00:58:57.760
be expected to keep her. I should say not. What good would she be to us?

00:58:58.700 --> 00:59:06.420
We might be some good to her, said Matthew suddenly and unexpectedly. Matthew Cuthbert,

00:59:06.660 --> 00:59:12.620
I believe that child has bewitched you. I can see as plain as plain that you want to keep her.

00:59:13.180 --> 00:59:19.080
Well now, she's a real interesting little thing, persisted Matthew. You should have heard her talk

00:59:19.080 --> 00:59:26.300
coming from the station. Oh, she can talk fast enough. I saw that at once. It's nothing in her

00:59:26.300 --> 00:59:32.160
favor either. I don't like children who have so much to say. I don't want an orphan girl, and if

00:59:32.160 --> 00:59:39.300
I did, she isn't the style I'd pick out. There's something I don't understand about her. No, she's

00:59:39.300 --> 00:59:45.760
to be dispatched straightway back to where she came from. I could hire a French boy to help me,

00:59:45.860 --> 00:59:52.120
said Matthew, and she'd be company for you. I'm not suffering for company, said Marilla shortly,

00:59:52.540 --> 01:00:00.540
and I'm not going to keep her. Well now, it's just as you say, of course, Marilla, said Matthew,

01:00:00.960 --> 01:00:07.680
rising and putting his pipe away. I'm going to bed. To bed went Matthew,

01:00:08.240 --> 01:00:14.660
and to bed, when she had put her dishes away, went Marilla, frowning most resolutely,

01:00:15.740 --> 01:00:24.160
and upstairs, in the east gable, a lonely, heart-hungry, friendless child cried herself to sleep.

01:00:43.500 --> 01:00:50.840
Reading by Annie Coleman in St. Louis, Missouri, on December 14, 2005.

01:01:02.780 --> 01:01:09.460
It was broad daylight when Anne awoke and sat up in bed, staring confusedly at the window,

01:01:09.960 --> 01:01:16.240
through which a flood of cheery sunshine was pouring and outside of which something white

01:01:16.240 --> 01:01:19.780
and feathery waved across glimpses of blue sky.

01:01:20.740 --> 01:01:23.740
For a moment she could not remember where she was.

01:01:24.440 --> 01:01:30.760
First came a delightful thrill, as of something very pleasant, then a horrible remembrance.

01:01:31.480 --> 01:01:36.000
This was Green Gables, and they didn't want her because she wasn't a boy.

01:01:36.800 --> 01:01:42.720
But it was morning, and yes, it was a cherry tree in full bloom outside of her window.

01:01:43.400 --> 01:01:46.980
With a bound she was out of bed and across the floor.

01:01:47.740 --> 01:01:49.260
She pushed up the sash.

01:01:49.740 --> 01:01:55.760
It went up stiffly and creakily, as if it hadn't been opened for a long time, which

01:01:55.760 --> 01:02:01.200
was the case, and it stuck so tight that nothing was needed to hold it up.

01:02:02.320 --> 01:02:08.740
Anne dropped on her knees and gazed out into the June morning, her eyes glistening with

01:02:08.740 --> 01:02:09.180
delight.

01:02:09.940 --> 01:02:11.740
Oh, wasn't it beautiful?

01:02:12.220 --> 01:02:13.780
Wasn't it a lovely place?

01:02:14.600 --> 01:02:17.400
Suppose she wasn't really going to stay here.

01:02:17.800 --> 01:02:19.560
She would imagine she was.

01:02:20.140 --> 01:02:22.460
There was scope for the imagination here.

01:02:23.360 --> 01:02:29.440
A huge cherry tree grew outside, so close that its boughs tapped against the house,

01:02:29.840 --> 01:02:34.640
and it was so thick set with blossoms that hardly a leaf was to be seen.

01:02:35.300 --> 01:02:41.660
On both sides of the house was a big orchard, one of apple trees and one of cherry trees,

01:02:42.220 --> 01:02:47.880
also showered over with blossoms, and their grass was all sprinkled with dandelions.

01:02:48.480 --> 01:02:55.240
In the garden below were lilac trees, purple with flowers, and their dizzily sweet fragrance

01:02:55.240 --> 01:02:58.500
drifted up to the window on the morning wind.

01:02:59.520 --> 01:03:06.980
Below the garden a green field, lush with clover, sloped down to the hollow where the

01:03:06.980 --> 01:03:14.420
brook ran and where scores of white birches grew, upspringing airily out of an undergrowth

01:03:14.420 --> 01:03:21.440
suggestive of delightful possibilities in ferns and mosses and woodsy things generally.

01:03:22.360 --> 01:03:27.000
Beyond it was a hill, green and feathery with spruce and fir.

01:03:27.480 --> 01:03:32.720
There was a gap in it where the gray gable end of the little house she had seen from

01:03:32.720 --> 01:03:35.880
the other side of the lake of shining waters was visible.

01:03:37.100 --> 01:03:44.540
Off to the left were the big barns, and beyond them, away down over green, low sloping fields,

01:03:45.080 --> 01:03:47.940
was a sparkling blue glimpse of sea.

01:03:49.060 --> 01:03:54.980
Anne's beauty-loving eyes lingered on it all, taking everything greedily in.

01:03:55.400 --> 01:04:01.980
She had looked on so many unlovely places in her life, poor child, but this was as lovely

01:04:01.980 --> 01:04:04.060
as anything she had ever dreamed.

01:04:05.060 --> 01:04:11.040
She knelt there, lost to everything but the loveliness around her, until she was startled

01:04:11.040 --> 01:04:13.060
by a hand on her shoulder.

01:04:14.160 --> 01:04:17.560
Marilla had come in unheard by the small dreamer.

01:04:18.120 --> 01:04:21.140
"'It's time you were dressed,' she said curtly.

01:04:21.980 --> 01:04:27.380
Marilla really did not know how to talk to the child, and her uncomfortable ignorance

01:04:27.380 --> 01:04:30.760
made her crisp and curt when she did not mean to be.

01:04:31.700 --> 01:04:33.860
Anne stood up and drew a long breath.

01:04:34.840 --> 01:04:41.220
"'Oh, isn't it wonderful,' she said, waving her hand comprehensively at the good world

01:04:41.220 --> 01:04:41.860
outside.

01:04:42.520 --> 01:04:47.500
"'It's a big tree,' said Marilla, and it blooms great, but the fruit don't amount to much

01:04:47.500 --> 01:04:49.280
never, small and wormy.

01:04:50.040 --> 01:04:51.900
"'Oh, I don't mean just the tree.

01:04:52.340 --> 01:04:53.660
Of course it's lovely.

01:04:54.080 --> 01:04:56.120
Yes, it's radiantly lovely.

01:04:56.500 --> 01:04:58.680
It blooms as if it meant it.

01:04:59.020 --> 01:05:00.300
But I meant everything.

01:05:00.700 --> 01:05:03.980
The garden and the orchard and the brook and the woods.

01:05:04.380 --> 01:05:06.820
The whole big, dear world.

01:05:07.240 --> 01:05:11.140
Don't you feel as if you just loved the world on a morning like this?'

01:05:11.140 --> 01:05:14.580
And I can hear the brook laughing all the way up here.

01:05:14.820 --> 01:05:17.720
Have you ever noticed what cheerful things brooks are?

01:05:17.720 --> 01:05:19.320
They're always laughing.

01:05:19.740 --> 01:05:22.320
Even in wintertime I've heard them under the ice.

01:05:22.800 --> 01:05:25.400
I'm so glad there's a brook near Green Gables.

01:05:26.060 --> 01:05:30.620
Perhaps you think it doesn't make any difference to me when you're not going to keep me, but

01:05:30.620 --> 01:05:31.240
it does.

01:05:31.660 --> 01:05:36.820
I shall always like to remember that there is a brook at Green Gables, even if I never

01:05:36.820 --> 01:05:37.580
see it again.

01:05:38.100 --> 01:05:43.580
If there wasn't a brook, I'd be haunted by the uncomfortable feeling that there ought

01:05:43.580 --> 01:05:44.300
to be one.

01:05:44.910 --> 01:05:47.380
I'm not in depths of despair this morning.

01:05:47.840 --> 01:05:49.660
I never can be in the morning.

01:05:50.360 --> 01:05:52.560
Isn't it a splendid thing that there are mornings?

01:05:53.300 --> 01:05:54.720
But I feel very sad.

01:05:55.200 --> 01:06:00.140
I've just been imagining that it was really me you wanted after all, and that I was to

01:06:00.140 --> 01:06:01.640
stay here forever and ever.

01:06:02.160 --> 01:06:04.260
It was a great comfort while it lasted.

01:06:05.120 --> 01:06:09.980
But the worst of imagining things is that the time comes when you have to stop, and

01:06:09.980 --> 01:06:10.740
that hurts.

01:06:12.020 --> 01:06:16.880
You'd better get dressed and come downstairs and never mind your imaginings, said Marilla

01:06:16.880 --> 01:06:19.320
as soon as she could get a word in edgewise.

01:06:19.840 --> 01:06:20.800
Breakfast is waiting.

01:06:21.340 --> 01:06:22.960
Wash your face and comb your hair.

01:06:23.340 --> 01:06:27.120
Leave the window up and turn your bedclothes back over the foot of the bed.

01:06:27.660 --> 01:06:29.120
Be as smart as you can.

01:06:30.400 --> 01:06:35.620
Anne could evidently be smart to some purpose, for she was downstairs in ten minutes' time

01:06:35.620 --> 01:06:41.980
with her clothes neatly on, her hair brushed and braided, her face washed, and a comfortable

01:06:41.980 --> 01:06:47.320
consciousness pervading her soul that she had fulfilled all Marilla's requirements.

01:06:48.200 --> 01:06:52.260
As a matter of fact, however, she had forgotten to turn back the bedclothes.

01:06:52.960 --> 01:06:57.960
I'm pretty hungry this morning, she announced as she slipped into the chair Marilla placed

01:06:57.960 --> 01:06:58.680
for her.

01:06:59.100 --> 01:07:02.920
The world doesn't seem such a howling wilderness as it did last night.

01:07:03.440 --> 01:07:08.620
I'm so glad it's a sunshiny morning, but I like rainy mornings real well, too.

01:07:09.020 --> 01:07:11.440
All sorts of mornings are interesting, don't you think?

01:07:11.900 --> 01:07:16.900
You don't know what's going to happen through the day, and there's so much scope for imagination.

01:07:17.540 --> 01:07:22.500
But I'm glad it's not rainy today, because it's easier to be cheerful and bear up under

01:07:22.500 --> 01:07:24.420
affliction on a sunshiny day.

01:07:25.060 --> 01:07:27.560
I feel that I have a good deal to bear up under.

01:07:28.080 --> 01:07:33.360
It's all very well to read about sorrows and imagine yourself living through them heroically,

01:07:33.800 --> 01:07:37.060
but it's not so nice when you really come to have them, is it?

01:07:37.940 --> 01:07:40.500
For pity's sake, hold your tongue, said Marilla.

01:07:41.020 --> 01:07:43.420
You talk entirely too much for a little girl.

01:07:44.760 --> 01:07:50.060
Thereupon Anne held her tongue so obediently and thoroughly that her continued silence

01:07:50.060 --> 01:07:55.360
made Marilla rather nervous, as if in the presence of something not exactly natural.

01:07:56.160 --> 01:08:01.560
Matthew also held his tongue, but this at least was natural, so that the meal was a

01:08:01.560 --> 01:08:02.900
very silent one.

01:08:04.280 --> 01:08:10.440
As it progressed, Anne became more and more abstracted, eating mechanically, with her

01:08:10.440 --> 01:08:16.260
big eyes fixed unswervingly and unseeingly on the sky outside the window.

01:08:17.160 --> 01:08:19.420
This made Marilla more nervous than ever.

01:08:19.420 --> 01:08:25.300
She had an uncomfortable feeling that while this odd child's body might be there at the

01:08:25.300 --> 01:08:32.960
table, her spirit was far away in some remote, airy cloudland, borne aloft on the wings of

01:08:32.960 --> 01:08:33.540
imagination.

01:08:34.300 --> 01:08:36.740
Who would want such a child about the place?

01:08:37.700 --> 01:08:41.360
Yet Matthew wished to keep her of all unaccountable things.

01:08:42.120 --> 01:08:47.580
Marilla felt that he wanted it just as much this morning as he had the night before, and

01:08:47.580 --> 01:08:49.500
that he would go on wanting it.

01:08:49.940 --> 01:08:51.220
That was Matthew's way.

01:08:51.640 --> 01:08:57.680
Take a whim into his head and cling to it with the most amazing silent persistency,

01:08:58.300 --> 01:09:04.520
a persistency ten times more potent and effectual in its very silence than if he had talked

01:09:04.520 --> 01:09:05.220
it out.

01:09:06.640 --> 01:09:11.380
When the meal was ended, Anne came out of her reverie and offered to wash the dishes.

01:09:12.020 --> 01:09:13.840
Can you wash dishes right?

01:09:14.080 --> 01:09:16.040
asked Marilla distrustfully.

01:09:16.720 --> 01:09:17.720
Pretty well.

01:09:17.900 --> 01:09:19.940
I'm better at looking after children, though.

01:09:20.180 --> 01:09:22.240
I've had so much experience at that.

01:09:22.740 --> 01:09:25.580
It's such a pity you haven't any here for me to look after.

01:09:26.760 --> 01:09:30.780
I don't feel as if I wanted any more children to look after than I've got at present.

01:09:31.340 --> 01:09:33.380
You're a problem enough in all conscience.

01:09:33.880 --> 01:09:35.680
What's to be done with you, I don't know.

01:09:36.200 --> 01:09:37.940
Matthew is a most ridiculous man.

01:09:38.520 --> 01:09:41.700
I think he's lovely, said Anne reproachfully.

01:09:42.120 --> 01:09:43.700
He is so very sympathetic.

01:09:44.180 --> 01:09:46.040
He didn't mind how much I talked.

01:09:46.140 --> 01:09:47.400
He seemed to like it.

01:09:47.740 --> 01:09:51.460
I felt that he was a kindred spirit as soon as ever I saw him.

01:09:52.220 --> 01:09:56.500
You're both queer enough if that's what you mean by kindred spirits, said Marilla with

01:09:56.500 --> 01:09:57.040
a sniff.

01:09:58.420 --> 01:10:00.020
Yes, you may wash the dishes.

01:10:00.440 --> 01:10:03.040
Take plenty of hot water and be sure you dry them well.

01:10:03.480 --> 01:10:07.800
I have enough to attend to this morning, for I'll have to drive over to White Sands in

01:10:07.800 --> 01:10:09.440
the afternoon and see Mrs. Spencer.

01:10:10.160 --> 01:10:12.880
You'll come with me and we'll settle what's to be done with you.

01:10:12.880 --> 01:10:16.720
After you finish the dishes, go upstairs and make your bed.

01:10:18.240 --> 01:10:25.520
Anne washed the dishes deftly enough as Marilla, who kept a sharp eye on the process, discerned.

01:10:25.760 --> 01:10:31.240
Later on she made her bed less successfully, for she had never learned the art of wrestling

01:10:31.240 --> 01:10:32.640
with a feather tick.

01:10:33.260 --> 01:10:38.260
But it was done somehow and smoothed down, and then Marilla, to get rid of her, told

01:10:38.260 --> 01:10:41.540
her she might go out of doors and amuse herself until dinner time.

01:10:42.420 --> 01:10:46.300
Anne flew to the door, face alight, eyes glowing.

01:10:47.040 --> 01:10:53.560
On the very threshold she stopped short, wheeled about, came back, and sat down by the table,

01:10:54.240 --> 01:11:00.280
light and glow as effectually blotted out as if someone had clapped an extinguisher on

01:11:00.280 --> 01:11:00.680
her.

01:11:01.420 --> 01:11:02.960
What's the matter now?

01:11:03.240 --> 01:11:04.100
demanded Marilla.

01:11:04.860 --> 01:11:11.200
I don't dare go out, said Anne, in the tone of a martyr, relinquishing all earthly joys.

01:11:11.200 --> 01:11:16.100
If I can't stay here, there's no use in my loving Green Gables.

01:11:16.800 --> 01:11:22.360
If I go out there and get acquainted with all those trees and flowers and the orchard

01:11:22.360 --> 01:11:25.800
and the brook, I'll not be able to help loving it.

01:11:26.100 --> 01:11:28.720
It's hard enough now, so I won't make it any harder.

01:11:29.320 --> 01:11:33.120
I want to go out so much, everything seems to be calling to me.

01:11:33.660 --> 01:11:35.660
Anne, Anne, come out to us.

01:11:36.000 --> 01:11:38.560
Anne, Anne, we want a playmate.

01:11:39.220 --> 01:11:40.520
But it's better not.

01:11:41.140 --> 01:11:45.400
There is no use in loving things if you have to be torn from them, is there?

01:11:45.960 --> 01:11:48.820
And it's so hard to keep from loving things, isn't it?

01:11:49.440 --> 01:11:52.660
That was why I was so glad when I thought I was going to live here.

01:11:52.940 --> 01:11:56.260
I thought I'd have so many things to love and nothing to hinder me.

01:11:56.960 --> 01:11:58.860
But that brief dream is over.

01:11:59.080 --> 01:12:03.140
I am resigned to my fate now, so I don't think I'll go out.

01:12:03.260 --> 01:12:05.280
For fear I'll get unresigned again.

01:12:06.480 --> 01:12:09.820
What is the name of that geranium on the windowsill, please?

01:12:10.860 --> 01:12:12.660
That's the apple-scented geranium.

01:12:13.680 --> 01:12:15.280
Oh, I don't mean that sort of a name.

01:12:15.460 --> 01:12:17.300
I mean just a name you gave it yourself.

01:12:17.920 --> 01:12:18.920
Didn't you give it a name?

01:12:19.640 --> 01:12:20.780
May I give it one, then?

01:12:21.260 --> 01:12:23.480
May I call it... let me see.

01:12:24.260 --> 01:12:25.000
Bonnie will do.

01:12:25.080 --> 01:12:26.760
May I call it Bonnie while I'm here?

01:12:27.160 --> 01:12:28.300
Oh, do let me.

01:12:29.360 --> 01:12:30.720
Goodness, I don't care.

01:12:30.940 --> 01:12:33.860
But where on earth is the sense of naming a geranium?

01:12:34.520 --> 01:12:38.860
Oh, I like things to have handles, even if they are only geraniums.

01:12:38.880 --> 01:12:40.900
It makes them seem more like people.

01:12:41.600 --> 01:12:46.900
How do you know but that it hurts a geranium's feelings just to be called a geranium and nothing else?

01:12:47.340 --> 01:12:50.220
You wouldn't like to be called nothing but a woman all the time.

01:12:50.980 --> 01:12:52.620
Yes, I shall call it Bonnie.

01:12:53.480 --> 01:12:56.660
I named that cherry tree outside my bedroom window this morning.

01:12:57.120 --> 01:13:00.460
I called it Snow Queen because it was so white.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:03.120
Of course it won't always be in blossom.

01:13:03.120 --> 01:13:06.080
One can imagine that it is, can't one?

01:13:07.260 --> 01:13:12.420
I never in all my life saw or heard anything to equal her, muttered Marilla,

01:13:12.680 --> 01:13:15.400
beating a retreat down cellar after potatoes.

01:13:16.140 --> 01:13:19.020
She is kind of interesting, as Matthew says.

01:13:19.580 --> 01:13:23.380
I can feel already that I'm wondering what on earth she'll say next.

01:13:23.860 --> 01:13:26.100
She'll be casting a spell over me, too.

01:13:26.400 --> 01:13:27.860
She's casted over Matthew.

01:13:27.860 --> 01:13:34.060
That look he gave me when he went out said everything he said or hinted last night over again.

01:13:34.740 --> 01:13:37.760
I wish he was like other men and would talk things out.

01:13:38.200 --> 01:13:40.900
A body could answer back then and argue him into reason.

01:13:41.280 --> 01:13:43.860
But what's to be done with a man who just looks?

01:13:45.380 --> 01:13:50.540
Anne had relapsed into reverie with her chin in her hands and her eyes on the sky

01:13:50.540 --> 01:13:53.500
when Marilla returned from her cellar pilgrimage.

01:13:53.500 --> 01:13:58.060
There Marilla left her until the early dinner was on the table.

01:13:59.020 --> 01:14:03.400
I suppose I can have the mare and buggy this afternoon, Matthew, said Marilla.

01:14:04.460 --> 01:14:07.260
Matthew nodded and looked wistfully at Anne.

01:14:08.160 --> 01:14:10.820
Marilla intercepted the look and said grimly,

01:14:11.100 --> 01:14:14.200
I'm going to drive over to White Sands and settle this thing.

01:14:14.640 --> 01:14:20.420
I'll take Anne with me and Mrs. Spencer will probably make arrangements to send her back to Nova Scotia at once.

01:14:20.420 --> 01:14:24.680
I'll set your tea out for you and I'll be home in time to milk the cows.

01:14:25.920 --> 01:14:31.300
Still Matthew said nothing and Marilla had a sense of having wasted words and breath.

01:14:32.020 --> 01:14:37.900
There is nothing more aggravating than a man who won't talk back unless it is a woman who won't.

01:14:38.520 --> 01:14:43.960
Matthew hitched the sorrel into the buggy in due time and Marilla and Anne set off.

01:14:44.640 --> 01:14:49.760
Matthew opened the yard gate for them and as they drove slowly through he said,

01:14:49.760 --> 01:14:52.260
to nobody in particular as it seemed.

01:14:53.040 --> 01:14:58.480
Little Jerry Boot from the creek was here this morning and I told him I guess I'd hire him for the summer.

01:15:00.020 --> 01:15:06.940
Marilla made no reply but she hit the unlucky sorrel such a vicious clip with a whip that the fat mare,

01:15:07.300 --> 01:15:12.880
unused to such treatment, whizzed indignantly down the lane at an alarming pace.

01:15:12.880 --> 01:15:21.260
Marilla looked back once as the buggy bounced along and saw that aggravating Matthew leaning over the gate,

01:15:21.780 --> 01:15:24.420
looking wistfully after them.

01:15:54.960 --> 01:15:56.640
Anne's History

01:16:25.040 --> 01:16:26.280
Isn't it lovely?

01:16:27.120 --> 01:16:29.800
Don't you think it must be glad to be a rose?

01:16:30.440 --> 01:16:32.320
Wouldn't it be nice if roses could talk?

01:16:32.740 --> 01:16:35.380
I'm sure they could tell us such lovely things.

01:16:35.840 --> 01:16:38.960
And isn't pink the most bewitching colour in the world?

01:16:39.480 --> 01:16:41.820
I love it, but I can't wear it.

01:16:42.340 --> 01:16:46.020
Red-headed people can't wear pink, not even in imagination.

01:16:46.860 --> 01:16:50.620
Did you ever know of anybody whose hair was red when she was young,

01:16:51.060 --> 01:16:53.440
but got to be another colour when she grew up?

01:16:53.440 --> 01:16:59.400
No, I don't know as I ever did, said Marilla mercilessly,

01:16:59.660 --> 01:17:03.120
and I shouldn't think it likely to happen in your case either.

01:17:04.740 --> 01:17:05.700
Anne sighed.

01:17:06.180 --> 01:17:08.780
Well, that is another hope gone.

01:17:09.400 --> 01:17:12.940
My life is a perfect graveyard of buried hopes.

01:17:13.580 --> 01:17:15.660
That's a sentence I read in a book once,

01:17:15.960 --> 01:17:20.260
and I say it over to comfort myself whenever I'm disappointed in anything.

01:17:20.260 --> 01:17:25.180
I don't see where the comforting comes in myself, said Marilla.

01:17:25.720 --> 01:17:28.360
Why, because it sounds so nice and romantic,

01:17:28.800 --> 01:17:31.280
just as if I were a heroine in a book, you know.

01:17:31.680 --> 01:17:33.800
I am so fond of romantic things,

01:17:34.160 --> 01:17:40.440
and a graveyard full of buried hopes is about as romantic a thing as one can imagine, isn't it?

01:17:41.000 --> 01:17:42.660
I'm rather glad I have one.

01:17:43.200 --> 01:17:45.880
Are we going across the Lake of Shining Waters today?

01:17:46.620 --> 01:17:48.980
We're not going over Barry's pond,

01:17:49.040 --> 01:17:52.000
if that's what you mean by your Lake of Shining Waters.

01:17:52.500 --> 01:17:54.040
We're going by the Shore Road.

01:17:55.100 --> 01:17:58.520
Shore Road sounds nice, said Anne dreamily.

01:17:59.100 --> 01:18:00.700
Is it as nice as it sounds?

01:18:01.360 --> 01:18:03.680
Just when you said Shore Road,

01:18:04.100 --> 01:18:07.220
I saw it in a picture in my mind as quick as that,

01:18:07.820 --> 01:18:10.300
and White Sands is a pretty name too,

01:18:10.620 --> 01:18:13.300
but I don't like it as well as Avonlea.

01:18:13.300 --> 01:18:15.740
Avonlea is a lovely name.

01:18:16.100 --> 01:18:17.920
It just sounds like music.

01:18:18.620 --> 01:18:20.880
How far is it to White Sands?

01:18:21.800 --> 01:18:23.100
It's five miles,

01:18:23.400 --> 01:18:25.760
and as you're evidently bent on talking,

01:18:26.060 --> 01:18:28.280
you might as well talk to some purpose

01:18:28.280 --> 01:18:30.800
by telling me what you know about yourself.

01:18:31.960 --> 01:18:35.220
Oh, what I know about myself isn't really worth telling,

01:18:35.700 --> 01:18:36.600
said Anne eagerly.

01:18:36.800 --> 01:18:40.360
If you'll only let me tell you what I imagine about myself,

01:18:40.360 --> 01:18:43.120
you'll think it ever so much more interesting.

01:18:44.120 --> 01:18:46.640
No, I don't want any of your imaginings.

01:18:47.400 --> 01:18:49.360
Just you stick to bald facts.

01:18:49.880 --> 01:18:51.180
Begin at the beginning.

01:18:51.800 --> 01:18:54.280
Where were you born, and how old are you?

01:18:55.240 --> 01:18:58.000
I was eleven last March, said Anne,

01:18:58.240 --> 01:19:01.140
resigning herself to bald facts with a little sigh,

01:19:01.260 --> 01:19:04.540
and I was born in Bolingbroke, Nova Scotia.

01:19:05.440 --> 01:19:07.540
My father's name was Walter Shirley,

01:19:07.540 --> 01:19:10.960
and he was a teacher in the Bolingbroke High School.

01:19:11.900 --> 01:19:13.620
My mother's name was Bertha Shirley.

01:19:14.300 --> 01:19:16.980
Aren't Walter and Bertha lovely names?

01:19:17.540 --> 01:19:19.940
I'm so glad my parents had nice names.

01:19:20.500 --> 01:19:23.040
It would be a real disgrace to have a father named,

01:19:23.420 --> 01:19:26.520
well, say, Jedidiah, wouldn't it?

01:19:27.100 --> 01:19:30.080
I guess it doesn't matter what a person's name is

01:19:30.080 --> 01:19:33.380
as long as he behaves himself, said Marilla,

01:19:33.760 --> 01:19:35.400
feeling herself called upon

01:19:35.400 --> 01:19:38.480
to inculcate a good and useful moral.

01:19:39.400 --> 01:19:42.420
Well, I don't know, Anne looked thoughtful.

01:19:43.060 --> 01:19:46.680
I read in a book once that a rose by any other name

01:19:46.680 --> 01:19:48.020
would smell as sweet,

01:19:48.540 --> 01:19:50.760
but I've never been able to believe it.

01:19:51.000 --> 01:19:53.260
I don't believe a rose would be as nice

01:19:53.260 --> 01:19:56.460
if it was called a thistle or a skunk cabbage.

01:19:57.280 --> 01:20:00.800
I suppose my father could have been a good man,

01:20:00.840 --> 01:20:03.220
even if he had been called Jedidiah,

01:20:03.220 --> 01:20:05.300
but I'm sure it would have been a cross.

01:20:06.220 --> 01:20:09.280
Well, my mother was a teacher in the high school, too,

01:20:09.540 --> 01:20:12.260
but when she married father she gave up teaching, of course.

01:20:12.780 --> 01:20:14.660
A husband was enough responsibility.

01:20:15.620 --> 01:20:18.260
Mrs. Thomas said that they were a pair of babies

01:20:18.260 --> 01:20:20.040
and as poor as church mice.

01:20:20.680 --> 01:20:22.580
They went to live in a weeny-teeny

01:20:22.580 --> 01:20:24.640
little yellow house in Bolingbroke.

01:20:24.960 --> 01:20:26.380
I've never seen that house,

01:20:26.420 --> 01:20:28.620
but I've imagined it thousands of times.

01:20:29.100 --> 01:20:30.920
I think it must have had honeysuckle

01:20:30.920 --> 01:20:34.600
over the parlor window and lilacs in the front yard

01:20:34.600 --> 01:20:37.480
and lilies of the valley just inside the gate.

01:20:38.100 --> 01:20:40.840
Yes, and muslin curtains in all the windows.

01:20:41.420 --> 01:20:44.000
Muslin curtains give a house such an air.

01:20:44.540 --> 01:20:46.040
I was born in that house.

01:20:46.540 --> 01:20:49.820
Mrs. Thomas said I was the homeliest baby she ever saw.

01:20:50.140 --> 01:20:53.360
I was so scrawny and tiny and nothing but eyes,

01:20:53.600 --> 01:20:56.180
but that mother thought I was perfectly beautiful.

01:20:56.800 --> 01:20:59.200
I should think a mother would be a better judge

01:20:59.200 --> 01:21:02.360
than a poor woman who came into scrub, wouldn't you?

01:21:03.080 --> 01:21:05.520
I'm glad she was satisfied with me anyhow.

01:21:06.080 --> 01:21:09.200
I would feel so sad if I thought I was a disappointment to her,

01:21:09.540 --> 01:21:12.160
because she didn't live very long after that, you see.

01:21:12.460 --> 01:21:15.280
She died of fever when I was just three months old.

01:21:15.860 --> 01:21:17.920
I do wish she'd lived long enough

01:21:17.920 --> 01:21:19.700
for me to remember calling her mother.

01:21:20.280 --> 01:21:22.080
I think it would be so sweet to say,

01:21:22.360 --> 01:21:23.960
Mother, don't you?

01:21:24.700 --> 01:21:28.040
And father died four days afterwards from fever, too.

01:21:28.600 --> 01:21:32.200
That left me an orphan, and folks were at their wits end,

01:21:32.440 --> 01:21:35.060
so Mrs. Thomas said what to do with me.

01:21:35.680 --> 01:21:38.160
You see, nobody wanted me even then.

01:21:38.680 --> 01:21:40.080
It seems to be my fate.

01:21:40.800 --> 01:21:44.300
Father and mother had both come from places far away,

01:21:44.640 --> 01:21:47.660
and it was well known they hadn't any relatives living.

01:21:48.560 --> 01:21:51.480
Finally, Mrs. Thomas said she'd take me,

01:21:51.620 --> 01:21:54.100
though she was poor and had a drunken husband.

01:21:54.540 --> 01:21:56.200
She brought me up by hand.

01:21:56.200 --> 01:21:59.760
Do you know if there's anything in being brought up by hand

01:21:59.760 --> 01:22:02.260
that ought to make people who were brought up that way

01:22:02.260 --> 01:22:03.740
better than other people?

01:22:04.340 --> 01:22:05.820
Because whenever I was naughty,

01:22:06.360 --> 01:22:09.280
Mrs. Thomas would ask me how I could be such a bad girl

01:22:09.280 --> 01:22:12.880
when she had brought me up by hand, reproachful-like.

01:22:14.020 --> 01:22:17.340
Mr. and Mrs. Thomas moved away from Bolingbrook to Marysville,

01:22:17.700 --> 01:22:20.600
and I lived with them until I was eight years old.

01:22:21.060 --> 01:22:23.080
I helped look after the Thomas children.

01:22:23.300 --> 01:22:25.200
There were four of them younger than me,

01:22:25.200 --> 01:22:28.560
and I can tell you they took a lot of looking after.

01:22:29.320 --> 01:22:32.300
Then Mr. Thomas was killed falling under a train,

01:22:32.860 --> 01:22:35.760
and his mother offered to take Mrs. Thomas and the children,

01:22:36.160 --> 01:22:37.700
but she didn't want me.

01:22:38.360 --> 01:22:40.540
Mrs. Thomas was at her wits' end,

01:22:40.660 --> 01:22:42.800
so she said what to do with me.

01:22:43.680 --> 01:22:47.560
Then Mrs. Hammond from up the river came down and said she'd take me,

01:22:47.860 --> 01:22:49.600
seeing I was handy with children,

01:22:49.920 --> 01:22:52.060
and I went up the river to live with her

01:22:52.060 --> 01:22:54.040
in a little clearing among the stumps.

01:22:54.040 --> 01:22:56.440
It was a very lonesome place.

01:22:56.840 --> 01:23:00.400
I'm sure I could never have lived there if I hadn't had an imagination.

01:23:01.940 --> 01:23:04.480
Mr. Hammond worked a little sawmill up there,

01:23:04.860 --> 01:23:06.680
and Mrs. Hammond had eight children.

01:23:07.300 --> 01:23:09.280
She had twins three times.

01:23:09.920 --> 01:23:11.760
I like babies in moderation,

01:23:12.140 --> 01:23:15.960
but twins three times in succession is too much.

01:23:16.600 --> 01:23:20.520
I told Mrs. Hammond so firmly when the last pair came.

01:23:20.520 --> 01:23:24.500
I used to get so dreadfully tired carrying them about.

01:23:25.520 --> 01:23:28.440
I lived upriver with Mrs. Hammond over two years,

01:23:28.900 --> 01:23:30.440
and then Mr. Hammond died,

01:23:30.660 --> 01:23:32.480
and Mrs. Hammond broke up housekeeping.

01:23:33.200 --> 01:23:36.700
She divided her children among her relatives and went to the States.

01:23:37.380 --> 01:23:41.700
I had to go to the asylum at Hopeton because nobody would take me.

01:23:42.260 --> 01:23:44.300
They didn't want me at the asylum either.

01:23:44.640 --> 01:23:46.720
They said they were overcrowded as it was,

01:23:47.160 --> 01:23:48.580
but they had to take me,

01:23:48.580 --> 01:23:51.860
and I was there four months until Mrs. Spencer came.

01:23:52.780 --> 01:23:56.200
Anne finished up with another sigh of relief this time.

01:23:56.900 --> 01:23:59.840
Evidently, she did not like talking about her experiences

01:23:59.840 --> 01:24:02.360
in a world that had not wanted her.

01:24:03.140 --> 01:24:04.860
Did you ever go to school?

01:24:05.280 --> 01:24:09.180
demanded Marilla, turning the sorrel mare down the shore road.

01:24:10.060 --> 01:24:11.200
Not a great deal.

01:24:11.320 --> 01:24:14.380
I went a little the last year I stayed with Mrs. Thomas.

01:24:14.900 --> 01:24:17.800
When I went upriver we were so far from a school

01:24:17.800 --> 01:24:19.860
that I couldn't walk it in winter,

01:24:20.340 --> 01:24:22.100
and there was a vacation in summer,

01:24:22.160 --> 01:24:24.200
so I could only go in the spring and fall.

01:24:24.760 --> 01:24:27.160
But of course I went while I was at the asylum.

01:24:27.780 --> 01:24:28.980
I can read pretty well,

01:24:29.120 --> 01:24:32.060
and I know ever so many pieces of poetry by heart.

01:24:32.840 --> 01:24:33.800
The Battle of Hohenlinden,

01:24:34.920 --> 01:24:36.780
and Edinburgh after Flodden,

01:24:37.340 --> 01:24:38.980
and Bingen of the Rhine,

01:24:39.200 --> 01:24:40.800
and lots of The Lady of the Lake,

01:24:41.300 --> 01:24:43.860
and most of The Seasons by James Thompson.

01:24:44.580 --> 01:24:45.980
Don't you just love poetry

01:24:45.980 --> 01:24:48.860
that gives you a crinkly feeling up and down your back?

01:24:50.040 --> 01:24:51.860
There is a piece in the fifth reader,

01:24:52.320 --> 01:24:53.780
The Downfall of Poland,

01:24:54.200 --> 01:24:56.100
that is just full of thrills.

01:24:56.620 --> 01:24:58.460
Of course I wasn't in the fifth reader.

01:24:58.640 --> 01:24:59.960
I was only in the fourth.

01:25:00.460 --> 01:25:02.840
But the big girls used to lend me theirs to read.

01:25:04.060 --> 01:25:08.160
Were those women, Mrs. Thomas and Mrs. Hammond, good to you?

01:25:08.400 --> 01:25:11.500
asked Marilla, looking at Anne out of the corner of her eye.

01:25:12.700 --> 01:25:14.400
Oh, faltered Anne.

01:25:14.400 --> 01:25:18.260
Her sensitive little face suddenly flushed scarlet,

01:25:18.620 --> 01:25:20.560
and embarrassment sat on her brow.

01:25:21.500 --> 01:25:23.020
Oh, they meant to be.

01:25:23.140 --> 01:25:26.220
I know they meant to be just as good and kind as possible.

01:25:26.800 --> 01:25:28.840
And when people mean to be good to you,

01:25:29.060 --> 01:25:32.100
you don't mind very much when they're not quite, always.

01:25:32.640 --> 01:25:34.820
They had a good deal to worry them, you know.

01:25:35.100 --> 01:25:38.240
It's very trying to have a drunken husband, you see.

01:25:38.500 --> 01:25:40.880
And it must be very trying to have twins

01:25:40.880 --> 01:25:43.080
three times in succession, don't you think?

01:25:43.080 --> 01:25:46.200
But I feel sure they meant to be good to me.

01:25:47.160 --> 01:25:48.900
Marilla asked no more questions.

01:25:49.540 --> 01:25:53.480
Anne gave herself up to a silent rapture over the shore road,

01:25:54.080 --> 01:25:58.520
and Marilla guided the sorrel abstractedly while she pondered deeply.

01:25:59.580 --> 01:26:02.520
Pity was suddenly stirring in her heart for the child.

01:26:03.160 --> 01:26:05.940
What a starved, unloved life she had led.

01:26:06.420 --> 01:26:09.900
A life of drudgery and poverty and neglect.

01:26:09.900 --> 01:26:14.700
For Marilla was shrewd enough to read between the lines of Anne's history

01:26:14.700 --> 01:26:16.520
and divine the truth.

01:26:17.280 --> 01:26:21.200
No wonder she had been so delighted at the prospect of a real home.

01:26:22.140 --> 01:26:24.600
It was a pity she had to be sent back.

01:26:25.380 --> 01:26:29.400
What if she, Marilla, should indulge Matthew's unaccountable whim

01:26:29.400 --> 01:26:30.380
and let her stay?

01:26:31.280 --> 01:26:35.300
He was set on it, and the child seemed a nice, teachable little thing.

01:26:36.120 --> 01:26:39.160
She's got too much to say, thought Marilla,

01:26:39.500 --> 01:26:41.300
but she might be trained out of that,

01:26:41.620 --> 01:26:44.940
and there's nothing rude or slangy in what she does say.

01:26:45.380 --> 01:26:48.800
She's ladylike. It's likely her people were nice folks.

01:26:49.680 --> 01:26:53.500
The shore road was woodsy and wild and lonesome.

01:26:54.020 --> 01:26:56.560
On the right hand scrubbed firs,

01:26:56.760 --> 01:27:01.420
their spirits, quite unbroken by long years of tussle with the gulf winds,

01:27:01.940 --> 01:27:03.040
grew thickly.

01:27:03.040 --> 01:27:07.400
On the left were the steep red sandstone cliffs,

01:27:07.940 --> 01:27:13.080
so near the tracking places that a mare of less steadiness than the sorrel

01:27:13.080 --> 01:27:16.000
might have tried the nerves of the people behind her.

01:27:16.800 --> 01:27:23.020
Down at the base of the cliffs were heaps of surf-worn rocks or little sandy coves,

01:27:23.300 --> 01:27:25.820
inlaid with pebbles as with ocean jewels.

01:27:26.300 --> 01:27:29.820
Beyond lay the sea, shimmering and blue,

01:27:29.820 --> 01:27:35.740
and over it soared the gulls, their pinions flashing silvery in the sunlight.

01:27:37.180 --> 01:27:43.020
Isn't the sea wonderful? said Anne, rousing from a long, wide-eyed silence.

01:27:43.660 --> 01:27:48.200
Once, when I lived in Marysville, Mr. Thomas hired an express wagon

01:27:48.200 --> 01:27:52.340
and took us all to spend the day at the shore ten miles away.

01:27:52.840 --> 01:27:58.620
I enjoyed every moment of that day, even if I had to look after the children all the time.

01:27:58.620 --> 01:28:02.220
I lived it over in happy dreams for years,

01:28:02.740 --> 01:28:05.720
but this shore is nicer than the Marysville shore.

01:28:06.240 --> 01:28:07.900
Aren't those gulls splendid?

01:28:08.560 --> 01:28:09.940
Would you like to be a gull?

01:28:10.140 --> 01:28:13.800
I think I would, that is, if I couldn't be a human girl.

01:28:14.600 --> 01:28:19.620
Don't you think it would be nice to wake up at sunrise and swoop down over the water

01:28:19.620 --> 01:28:23.100
and away out over that lovely blue all day,

01:28:23.400 --> 01:28:26.200
and then at night to fly back to one's nest?

01:28:26.200 --> 01:28:29.360
Oh, I can just imagine myself doing it.

01:28:30.140 --> 01:28:32.600
What big house is that just ahead, please?

01:28:33.800 --> 01:28:35.740
That's the White Sands Hotel.

01:28:36.320 --> 01:28:39.680
Mr. Kirk runs it, but the season hasn't begun yet.

01:28:40.180 --> 01:28:43.060
There are heaps of Americans come there for the summer.

01:28:43.540 --> 01:28:46.140
They think this shore is just about right.

01:28:47.020 --> 01:28:51.240
I was afraid it might be Mrs. Spencer's place, said Anne mournfully.

01:28:51.640 --> 01:28:53.140
I don't want to get there.

01:28:53.140 --> 01:28:56.480
Somehow it will seem like the end of everything.

01:29:14.440 --> 01:29:22.200
Reading by Annie Coleman in St. Louis, Missouri on December 16th, 2005.

01:29:23.100 --> 01:29:27.040
Anne of Green Gables by Lucy Maude Montgomery.

01:29:28.540 --> 01:29:32.580
Marilla Makes Up Her Mind

01:29:33.460 --> 01:29:37.180
Get there they did, however, in due season.

01:29:37.180 --> 01:29:41.600
Mrs. Spencer lived in a big yellow house at White Sands Cove,

01:29:42.000 --> 01:29:47.240
and she came to the door with surprise and welcome mingled on her benevolent face.

01:29:47.860 --> 01:29:49.720
Dear, dear! she exclaimed.

01:29:50.140 --> 01:29:54.040
You're the last folks I was looking for today, but I'm real glad to see you.

01:29:54.340 --> 01:29:57.020
You'll put your horse in? And how are you, Anne?

01:29:57.740 --> 01:30:02.620
I'm as well as can be expected, thank you, said Anne smilelessly.

01:30:03.360 --> 01:30:06.300
A blight seemed to have descended on her.

01:30:06.300 --> 01:30:11.520
I suppose we'll stay a little while to rest the mare, said Marilla,

01:30:12.000 --> 01:30:14.480
but I promised Matthew I'd be home early.

01:30:15.180 --> 01:30:19.280
The fact is, Mrs. Spencer, there's been a queer mistake somewhere,

01:30:19.520 --> 01:30:22.000
and I've come over to see where it is.

01:30:22.500 --> 01:30:27.400
We sent word, Matthew and I, for you to bring us a boy from the asylum.

01:30:27.960 --> 01:30:32.660
We told your brother Robert to tell you we wanted a boy ten or eleven years old.

01:30:33.580 --> 01:30:37.940
Marilla Cuthbert, you don't say so, said Mrs. Spencer in distress.

01:30:38.520 --> 01:30:43.440
Why, Robert sent the word down by his daughter Nancy, and she said you wanted a girl.

01:30:43.860 --> 01:30:48.600
Didn't she, Flora Jane? Appealing to her daughter, who had come out to the steps.

01:30:49.260 --> 01:30:53.520
She certainly did, Mrs. Cuthbert, corroborated Flora Jane earnestly.

01:30:54.260 --> 01:30:57.200
I'm dreadfully sorry, said Mrs. Spencer.

01:30:57.740 --> 01:31:02.060
It is too bad, but it certainly wasn't my fault, you see, Mrs. Cuthbert.

01:31:02.060 --> 01:31:06.240
I did the best I could, and I thought I was following your instructions.

01:31:07.060 --> 01:31:09.200
Nancy is a terrible flighty thing.

01:31:09.600 --> 01:31:12.320
I've often had to scold her well for her heedlessness.

01:31:13.140 --> 01:31:16.980
It was our own fault, said Marilla, resignedly.

01:31:17.460 --> 01:31:21.580
We should have come to you ourselves, and not left an important message

01:31:21.580 --> 01:31:24.060
to be passed along by word of mouth in that fashion.

01:31:25.200 --> 01:31:29.680
Anyhow, the mistake has been made, and the only thing to do now is to set it right.

01:31:29.680 --> 01:31:31.880
Can we send the child back to the asylum?

01:31:32.520 --> 01:31:34.480
I suppose they'll take her back, won't they?

01:31:35.220 --> 01:31:38.580
I suppose so, said Mrs. Spencer thoughtfully,

01:31:39.100 --> 01:31:41.840
but I don't think it will be necessary to send her back.

01:31:42.560 --> 01:31:46.460
Mrs. Peter Blewett was up here yesterday, and she was saying to me

01:31:46.460 --> 01:31:50.120
how much she wished she'd sent by me for a little girl to help her.

01:31:50.720 --> 01:31:54.860
Mrs. Peter has a large family, you know, and she finds it hard to get help,

01:31:55.380 --> 01:31:57.120
and will be the very girl for her.

01:31:57.120 --> 01:32:00.040
I call it positively providential.

01:32:01.300 --> 01:32:05.540
Marilla did not look as if she thought providence had much to do with the matter.

01:32:06.280 --> 01:32:11.260
Here was an unexpectedly good chance to get this unwelcome orphan off her hands,

01:32:11.560 --> 01:32:14.180
and she did not even feel grateful for it.

01:32:14.860 --> 01:32:21.240
She knew Mrs. Peter Blewett only by sight as a small, shrewish-faced woman

01:32:21.240 --> 01:32:25.100
without an ounce of superfluous flesh on her bones,

01:32:25.100 --> 01:32:27.000
but she had heard of her.

01:32:27.720 --> 01:32:31.300
A terrible worker and driver, Mrs. Peter was said to be,

01:32:31.780 --> 01:32:36.540
and discharged servant girls told fearsome tales of her temper and stinginess,

01:32:37.020 --> 01:32:39.960
and her family of pert, quarrelsome children.

01:32:40.840 --> 01:32:46.260
Marilla felt a qualm of conscience at the thought of handing Anne over to her tender mercies.

01:32:47.280 --> 01:32:50.980
Well, I'll go in and we'll talk the matter over, she said.

01:32:50.980 --> 01:32:57.320
And if there isn't Mrs. Peter coming up the lane this blessed minute, exclaimed Mrs. Spencer,

01:32:57.900 --> 01:33:00.720
bustling her guests through the hall into the parlor,

01:33:00.960 --> 01:33:05.260
where a deadly chill struck on them as if the air had been strained so long

01:33:05.260 --> 01:33:12.600
through dark green, closely drawn blinds that it had lost every particle of warmth it had ever possessed.

01:33:13.120 --> 01:33:16.480
That is real lucky, for we can settle the matter right away.

01:33:16.480 --> 01:33:22.020
Take the armchair, Miss Cuthbert. Anne, you sit here on the ottoman, and don't wriggle.

01:33:22.560 --> 01:33:23.740
Let me take your hats.

01:33:24.560 --> 01:33:26.720
Flora Jane, go out and put the kettle on.

01:33:27.280 --> 01:33:32.220
Good afternoon, Mrs. Blewett. We were just saying how fortunate it was you happened along.

01:33:32.760 --> 01:33:37.000
Let me introduce you two ladies. Mrs. Blewett, Miss Cuthbert.

01:33:37.680 --> 01:33:42.580
Please excuse me for just a moment, I forgot to tell Flora Jane to take the buns out of the oven.

01:33:43.300 --> 01:33:47.980
Mrs. Spencer whisked away after pulling up the blinds.

01:33:48.260 --> 01:33:55.980
Anne, sitting mutely on the ottoman with her hands clasped tightly in her lap, stared at Mrs. Blewett as one fascinated.

01:33:56.700 --> 01:34:01.360
Was she to be given into the keeping of this sharp-faced, sharp-eyed woman?

01:34:01.880 --> 01:34:07.240
She felt a lump coming up in her throat, and her eyes smarted painfully.

01:34:07.240 --> 01:34:14.980
She was beginning to be afraid she couldn't keep the tears back when Mrs. Spencer returned, flushed and beaming,

01:34:15.200 --> 01:34:24.540
quite capable of taking any and every difficulty, physical, mental, or spiritual, into consideration and settling it out of hand.

01:34:25.240 --> 01:34:29.880
It seems there has been a mistake about this little girl, Mrs. Blewett, she said.

01:34:30.440 --> 01:34:35.220
I was under the impression that Mr. and Miss Cuthbert wanted a little girl to adopt.

01:34:35.220 --> 01:34:43.040
I was certainly told so, but it seems it was a boy they wanted, so if you're still of the same mind you were yesterday,

01:34:43.480 --> 01:34:45.660
I think she'll be just the thing for you.

01:34:46.120 --> 01:34:49.760
Mrs. Blewett darted her eyes over Anne from head to foot.

01:34:50.460 --> 01:34:53.160
How old are you and what's your name? she demanded.

01:34:54.060 --> 01:35:03.500
Anne Shirley, faltered the shrinking child, not daring to make any stipulations regarding the spelling thereof, and I'm eleven years old.

01:35:05.060 --> 01:35:12.080
You don't look as if there was much to you, but you're wiry, and I don't know but the wiry ones are the best after all.

01:35:12.660 --> 01:35:17.980
Well, if I take you you'll have to be a good girl, you know, good and smart and respectful.

01:35:18.520 --> 01:35:21.480
I'll expect you to earn your keep and no mistake about that.

01:35:22.240 --> 01:35:25.440
Yes, I suppose I might as well take her off your hands, Miss Cuthbert.

01:35:26.000 --> 01:35:29.960
The baby's awful fractious and I'm clean, worn out, attending to him.

01:35:30.440 --> 01:35:32.680
If you like, I can take her right home now.

01:35:33.780 --> 01:35:40.920
Marilla looked at Anne and softened at sight of the child's pale face with its look of mute misery,

01:35:41.680 --> 01:35:48.140
the misery of a helpless little creature who finds itself once more caught in the trap from which it had escaped.

01:35:49.020 --> 01:35:56.960
Marilla felt an uncomfortable conviction that, if she denied the appeal of that look, it would haunt her to her dying day.

01:35:57.880 --> 01:36:05.060
Moreover, she did not fancy Mrs. Blewett to hand a sensitive, high-strung child over to such a woman.

01:36:05.780 --> 01:36:09.000
No, she could not take the responsibility of doing that.

01:36:10.180 --> 01:36:13.000
Well, I don't know, she said slowly.

01:36:13.540 --> 01:36:18.300
I didn't say that Matthew and I had absolutely decided that we wouldn't keep her.

01:36:18.540 --> 01:36:21.540
In fact, I may say that Matthew is disposed to keep her.

01:36:21.780 --> 01:36:24.620
I just came over to find out how the mistake had occurred.

01:36:24.620 --> 01:36:28.160
I think I'd better take her home again and talk it over with Matthew.

01:36:28.740 --> 01:36:32.500
I feel that I oughtn't to decide on anything without consulting him.

01:36:33.160 --> 01:36:38.320
If we make up our mind not to keep her, we'll bring or send her over to you tomorrow night.

01:36:38.660 --> 01:36:41.640
If we don't, you may know that she is going to stay with us.

01:36:41.920 --> 01:36:43.820
Will that suit you, Mrs. Blewett?

01:36:44.460 --> 01:36:48.720
Well, I suppose it'll have to, said Mrs. Blewett ungraciously.

01:36:49.700 --> 01:36:54.480
During Marilla's speech a sunrise had been dawning on Anne's face.

01:36:55.080 --> 01:36:57.840
First, the look of despair faded out.

01:36:58.380 --> 01:37:00.480
Then came a faint flush of hope.

01:37:00.980 --> 01:37:04.260
Her eyes grew deep and bright as morning stars.

01:37:04.980 --> 01:37:08.660
The child was quite transfigured, and a moment later,

01:37:08.980 --> 01:37:14.700
when Mrs. Spencer and Mrs. Blewett went out in quest of a recipe the latter had come to borrow,

01:37:15.240 --> 01:37:18.020
she sprang up and flew across the room to Marilla.

01:37:18.020 --> 01:37:23.740
Oh, Miss Cuthbert, did you really say that perhaps you would let me stay at Green Gables?

01:37:24.200 --> 01:37:29.920
she said in a breathless whisper, as if speaking aloud might shatter the glorious possibility.

01:37:30.600 --> 01:37:34.200
Did you really say it, or did I only imagine that you did?

01:37:35.060 --> 01:37:38.760
I think you'd better learn to control that imagination of yours, Anne,

01:37:38.820 --> 01:37:43.780
if you can't distinguish between what is real and what isn't, said Marilla crossly.

01:37:43.780 --> 01:37:47.580
Yes, you did hear me say just that and no more.

01:37:47.980 --> 01:37:53.320
It isn't decided yet, and perhaps we will conclude to let Mrs. Blewett take you after all.

01:37:53.760 --> 01:37:56.300
She certainly needs you much more than I do.

01:37:57.260 --> 01:38:02.180
I'd rather go back to the asylum than go to live with her, said Anne passionately.

01:38:02.580 --> 01:38:05.760
She looks exactly like a, like a gimlet.

01:38:06.880 --> 01:38:12.940
Marilla smothered a smile under the conviction that Anne must be reproved for such a speech.

01:38:12.940 --> 01:38:19.840
A little girl like you should be ashamed of talking so about a lady and a stranger, she said severely.

01:38:20.540 --> 01:38:24.920
Go back and sit down quietly and hold your tongue and behave as a good girl should.

01:38:25.960 --> 01:38:33.240
I'll try to do and be anything you want me if you'll only keep me, said Anne, returning meekly to her ottoman.

01:38:34.280 --> 01:38:39.460
When they arrived back at Green Gables that evening, Matthew met them in the lane.

01:38:40.180 --> 01:38:44.660
Marilla from afar had noted him prowling along it and guessed his motive.

01:38:45.440 --> 01:38:52.360
She was prepared for the relief she read in his face when he saw that she had at least brought Anne back with her.

01:38:52.720 --> 01:38:59.820
But she said nothing to him relative to the affair until they were both out in the yard behind the barn milking the cows.

01:39:00.580 --> 01:39:05.840
Then she briefly told him Anne's history and the result of the interview with Mrs. Spencer.

01:39:07.120 --> 01:39:13.420
I wouldn't give a dog I like to that blue-it woman, said Matthew with unusual vim.

01:39:14.280 --> 01:39:20.920
I don't fancy her style myself, admitted Marilla, but it's that or keeping her ourselves, Matthew.

01:39:21.500 --> 01:39:26.400
And since you seem to want her, I suppose I'm willing, or have to be.

01:39:26.880 --> 01:39:32.140
I've been thinking over the idea until I've got kind of used to it. It seems a sort of duty.

01:39:32.140 --> 01:39:40.380
I've never brought up a child, especially a girl, and I dare say I'll make a terrible mess of it, but I'll do my best.

01:39:40.920 --> 01:39:43.580
So far as I'm concerned, Matthew, she may stay.

01:39:44.860 --> 01:39:47.740
Matthew's shy face was a glow of delight.

01:39:48.420 --> 01:39:53.080
Well now, I reckoned you'd come to see it in that light, Marilla, he said.

01:39:53.460 --> 01:39:55.640
She's such an interesting little thing.

01:39:56.540 --> 01:40:02.060
It'd be more to the point if you could say she was a useful little thing, retorted Marilla,

01:40:02.460 --> 01:40:05.660
but I'll make it my business to see she's trained to be that.

01:40:06.160 --> 01:40:09.840
And mind, Matthew, you're not to go interfering with my methods.

01:40:10.420 --> 01:40:16.820
Perhaps an old maid doesn't know much about bringing up a child, but I guess she knows more than an old bachelor.

01:40:17.480 --> 01:40:22.860
So you just leave me to manage her. When I fail, it'll be time enough to put your oar in.

01:40:23.620 --> 01:40:29.100
There, there, Marilla, you can have your own way, said Matthew reassuringly.

01:40:29.440 --> 01:40:33.920
Only be as good and kind to her as you can be without spoiling her.

01:40:34.240 --> 01:40:39.740
I kind of think she's one of the sort you can do anything with if you only get her to love you.

01:40:40.940 --> 01:40:49.620
Marilla sniffed to express her contempt for Matthew's opinions concerning anything feminine, and walked off to the dairy with the pails.

01:40:50.380 --> 01:40:56.420
I won't tell her tonight that she can stay, she reflected as she strained the milk into the creamers.

01:40:56.780 --> 01:40:59.580
She'd be so excited that she wouldn't sleep a wink.

01:41:00.500 --> 01:41:02.720
Marilla Cuthbert, you're fairly in for it.

01:41:03.120 --> 01:41:06.720
Did you ever suppose you'd see the day when you'd be adopting an orphan girl?

01:41:07.240 --> 01:41:12.380
It's surprising enough, but not so surprising as that Matthew should be at the bottom of it,

01:41:12.780 --> 01:41:16.400
him that always seemed to have such a mortal dread of little girls.

01:41:17.340 --> 01:41:22.400
Anyhow, we've decided on the experiment, and goodness only knows what will come of it.

01:41:52.340 --> 01:41:54.340
Anne Says Her Prayers.

01:42:22.340 --> 01:42:27.740
I was so harrowed up in my mind last night that I didn't think about my clothes at all,

01:42:27.900 --> 01:42:28.420
said Anne.

01:42:28.900 --> 01:42:30.540
All fold them nicely tonight.

01:42:30.920 --> 01:42:32.880
They always made us do that at the asylum.

01:42:33.620 --> 01:42:38.200
Half the time though I'd forget, I'd be in such a hurry to get into bed, nice and quiet

01:42:38.200 --> 01:42:39.380
and imagine things.

01:42:40.160 --> 01:42:44.780
You'll have to remember a little better if you stay here, admonished Marilla.

01:42:45.460 --> 01:42:47.200
There, that looks something like.

01:42:48.180 --> 01:42:50.160
Say your prayers now and get into bed.

01:42:50.160 --> 01:42:54.120
I never say any prayers, announced Anne.

01:42:54.560 --> 01:42:57.160
Marilla looked horrified with astonishment.

01:42:58.100 --> 01:42:59.920
Why Anne, what do you mean?

01:43:00.560 --> 01:43:02.400
Were you never taught to say your prayers?

01:43:02.980 --> 01:43:05.440
God always wants little girls to say their prayers.

01:43:05.860 --> 01:43:07.580
Don't you know who God is, Anne?

01:43:08.560 --> 01:43:17.220
God is a spirit, infinite, eternal, and unchangeable, in His being, wisdom, power, holiness, justice,

01:43:17.480 --> 01:43:18.760
goodness, and truth.

01:43:19.680 --> 01:43:22.960
Responded Anne, promptly and glibly.

01:43:23.920 --> 01:43:25.340
Marilla looked rather relieved.

01:43:26.300 --> 01:43:30.180
So you do know something then, thank goodness, you're not quite a heathen.

01:43:30.560 --> 01:43:31.760
Where did you learn that?

01:43:32.720 --> 01:43:34.680
Oh, at the Asylum Sunday School.

01:43:34.820 --> 01:43:36.600
They made us learn the whole catechism.

01:43:37.120 --> 01:43:38.400
I liked it pretty well.

01:43:38.840 --> 01:43:44.240
There's something splendid about some of the words, infinite, eternal, and unchangeable.

01:43:44.780 --> 01:43:45.900
Isn't that grand?

01:43:45.900 --> 01:43:50.320
It has such a role to it, just like a big organ playing.

01:43:50.920 --> 01:43:55.660
You couldn't quite call it poetry, I suppose, but it sounds a lot like it, doesn't it?

01:43:56.560 --> 01:43:58.820
We're not talking about poetry, Anne.

01:43:58.840 --> 01:44:00.920
We are talking about saying your prayers.

01:44:01.460 --> 01:44:05.260
Don't you know it's a terrible wicked thing not to say your prayers every night?

01:44:05.700 --> 01:44:08.300
I'm afraid you are a very bad little girl.

01:44:09.460 --> 01:44:15.020
You'd find it easier to be bad than good if you had red hair, said Anne reproachfully.

01:44:15.540 --> 01:44:18.980
People who haven't red hair don't know what trouble is.

01:44:19.340 --> 01:44:25.340
Mrs. Thomas told me that God made my hair red on purpose, and I've never cared about him since.

01:44:25.960 --> 01:44:29.880
And anyhow, I'd always be too tired at night to bother saying prayers.

01:44:30.520 --> 01:44:34.120
People who have to look after twins can't be expected to say their prayers.

01:44:34.820 --> 01:44:36.640
Now do you honestly think they can?

01:44:37.640 --> 01:44:41.720
Marilla decided that Anne's religious training must be begun at once.

01:44:42.320 --> 01:44:44.600
Plainly there was no time to be lost.

01:44:45.200 --> 01:44:48.520
You must say your prayers while you are under my roof, Anne.

01:44:49.260 --> 01:44:55.200
Why, of course, if you want me to, assented Anne cheerfully, I'd do anything to oblige you.

01:44:55.720 --> 01:44:58.200
But you'll have to tell me what to say for this once.

01:44:58.740 --> 01:45:03.640
After I get into bed, I'll imagine out a real nice prayer to say always.

01:45:04.040 --> 01:45:07.640
I believe that it will be quite interesting now that I come to think of it.

01:45:08.260 --> 01:45:11.600
You must kneel down, said Marilla in embarrassment.

01:45:12.740 --> 01:45:15.580
Anne knelt at Marilla's knee and looked up gravely.

01:45:16.420 --> 01:45:18.540
Why must people kneel down to pray?

01:45:19.080 --> 01:45:22.560
If I really wanted to pray, I'll tell you what I'd do.

01:45:22.960 --> 01:45:29.460
I'd go out into a great big field all alone, or into the deep, deep woods,

01:45:29.800 --> 01:45:34.160
and I'd look up into the sky, up, up, up,

01:45:34.160 --> 01:45:39.800
into that lovely blue sky that looks as if there was no end to its blueness.

01:45:40.060 --> 01:45:43.620
And then I'd just feel a prayer.

01:45:44.880 --> 01:45:47.000
Well, I'm ready. What am I to say?

01:45:48.100 --> 01:45:50.500
Marilla felt more embarrassed than ever.

01:45:50.900 --> 01:45:56.060
She had intended to teach Anne the childish classic, Now I Lay Me Down to Sleep.

01:45:56.580 --> 01:46:00.700
But she had, as I have told you, the glimmerings of a sense of humor,

01:46:00.700 --> 01:46:04.900
which is simply another name for a sense of the fitness of things.

01:46:05.360 --> 01:46:08.320
And it suddenly occurred to her that that simple little prayer,

01:46:08.920 --> 01:46:12.140
sacred to white-robed children lisping at motherly knees,

01:46:12.540 --> 01:46:16.040
was entirely unsuited to this freckled witch of a girl

01:46:16.040 --> 01:46:18.600
who knew and cared nothing about God's love,

01:46:19.060 --> 01:46:23.840
since she had never had it translated to her through the medium of human love.

01:46:24.840 --> 01:46:28.480
You're old enough to pray for yourself, Anne, she said finally.

01:46:28.480 --> 01:46:33.800
Just thank God for your blessings and ask him humbly for the things you want.

01:46:35.100 --> 01:46:40.180
Well, I'll do my best, promised Anne, burying her face in Marilla's lap.

01:46:41.340 --> 01:46:45.420
Gracious Heavenly Father, that's the way the ministers say it in church.

01:46:45.780 --> 01:46:48.580
So I suppose it's all right in a private prayer, isn't it?

01:46:48.740 --> 01:46:51.480
She interjected, lifting her head for a moment.

01:46:52.620 --> 01:46:58.040
Gracious Heavenly Father, I thank thee for the white way of delight.

01:46:58.040 --> 01:47:03.100
And the lake of shining waters, and Bonnie, and the Snow Queen.

01:47:03.820 --> 01:47:06.180
I'm really extremely grateful for them.

01:47:06.680 --> 01:47:10.280
And that's all the blessings I can think of just now to thank thee for.

01:47:10.940 --> 01:47:16.280
As for the things I want, they're so numerous that it would take a great deal of time to name them all.

01:47:16.580 --> 01:47:19.360
So I will only mention the two most important.

01:47:20.080 --> 01:47:25.740
Please let me stay at Green Gables, and please let me be good looking when I grow up.

01:47:25.740 --> 01:47:30.420
I remain yours respectfully, Anne Shirley.

01:47:31.580 --> 01:47:35.120
There, did I do it all right? she asked eagerly, getting up.

01:47:35.560 --> 01:47:39.960
I could have made it much more flowery if I'd had a little more time to think it over.

01:47:41.060 --> 01:47:46.900
Poor Marilla was only preserved from complete collapse by remembering that it was not irreverence,

01:47:47.280 --> 01:47:52.960
but simply spiritual ignorance on the part of Anne that was responsible for this extraordinary petition.

01:47:53.520 --> 01:47:59.560
She tucked the child up in bed, mentally vowing that she should be taught a prayer the very next day,

01:47:59.820 --> 01:48:03.480
and was leaving the room with the light when Anne called her back.

01:48:04.160 --> 01:48:05.440
I've just thought of it now.

01:48:05.780 --> 01:48:10.900
I should have said, Amen, in place of yours respectfully, shouldn't I?

01:48:11.180 --> 01:48:12.440
The way the ministers do.

01:48:12.880 --> 01:48:18.120
I'd forgotten it, but I felt a prayer should be finished off in some way, so I put in the other.

01:48:18.800 --> 01:48:20.620
Do you suppose it will make any difference?

01:48:21.420 --> 01:48:24.780
I don't suppose it will, said Marilla.

01:48:25.180 --> 01:48:27.200
Go to sleep now, like a good child.

01:48:27.760 --> 01:48:28.340
Good night.

01:48:29.600 --> 01:48:33.960
I can say good night tonight with a clear conscience, said Anne,

01:48:34.180 --> 01:48:37.020
cuddling luxuriously down among her pillows.

01:48:37.820 --> 01:48:44.340
Marilla retreated to the kitchen, set the candle firmly on the table, and glared at Matthew.

01:48:45.240 --> 01:48:49.700
Matthew Cuthbert, it's about time somebody adopted that child and taught her something.

01:48:49.700 --> 01:48:52.920
She's next door to a perfect heathen.

01:48:53.160 --> 01:48:56.560
Would you believe that she never said a prayer in her life till tonight?

01:48:57.540 --> 01:49:01.300
I'll send to the manse tomorrow and borrow the peep of day series.

01:49:01.520 --> 01:49:02.560
That's what I'll do.

01:49:03.020 --> 01:49:07.780
And she shall go to Sunday school just as soon as I can get some suitable clothes made for her.

01:49:08.560 --> 01:49:10.660
I foresee that I shall have my hands full.

01:49:11.540 --> 01:49:15.660
Well, well, we can't get through this world without our share of trouble.

01:49:16.180 --> 01:49:18.680
I've had a pretty easy life of it so far.

01:49:18.680 --> 01:49:24.040
But my time has come at last, and I suppose I'll just have to make the best of it.

01:49:41.820 --> 01:49:49.420
Reading by Annie Coleman in St. Louis, Missouri on December 16, 2005.

01:49:50.780 --> 01:49:54.600
Anne of Green Gables by Lucy Maude Montgomery.

01:49:55.960 --> 01:49:59.800
Anne's Bringing Up is Begun.

01:50:01.420 --> 01:50:09.100
For reasons best known to herself, Marilla did not tell Anne that she was to stay at Green Gables until the next afternoon.

01:50:09.780 --> 01:50:17.300
During the forenoon she kept the child busy with various tasks and watched over her with a keen eye while she did them.

01:50:17.900 --> 01:50:24.680
By noon she had concluded that Anne was smart and obedient, willing to work, and quick to learn.

01:50:25.220 --> 01:50:38.360
Her most serious shortcoming seemed to be a tendency to fall into daydreams in the middle of a task and forget all about it until such a time as she was sharply recalled to earth by a reprimand or a catastrophe.

01:50:39.360 --> 01:50:48.900
When Anne had finished washing the dinner dishes, she suddenly confronted Marilla with the air and expression of one desperately determined to learn the worst.

01:50:49.700 --> 01:50:57.460
Her thin little body trembled from head to foot, her face flushed, and her eyes dilated until they were almost black.

01:50:58.000 --> 01:51:02.240
She clasped her hands tightly and said in an imploring voice,

01:51:02.240 --> 01:51:08.200
Oh, please, Miss Cuthbert, won't you tell me if you are going to send me away or not?

01:51:08.720 --> 01:51:14.320
I've tried to be patient all the morning, but I really feel that I cannot bear not knowing any longer.

01:51:14.940 --> 01:51:18.500
It's a dreadful feeling. Please tell me.

01:51:18.840 --> 01:51:25.240
You haven't scalded the dishcloth in clean hot water as I told you to, said Marilla immovably.

01:51:26.180 --> 01:51:29.500
Just go and do it before you ask any more questions, Anne.

01:51:30.300 --> 01:51:32.640
Anne went and attended to the dishcloth.

01:51:33.380 --> 01:51:38.500
Then she returned to Marilla and fastened imploring eyes on the latter's face.

01:51:39.920 --> 01:51:45.620
Well, said Marilla, unable to find any excuse for deferring her explanation longer,

01:51:46.540 --> 01:51:51.580
I suppose I might as well tell you, Matthew and I have decided to keep you.

01:51:51.700 --> 01:51:56.340
That is, if you will try to be a good little girl and show yourself grateful.

01:51:57.000 --> 01:51:59.180
White child, whatever is the matter?

01:52:00.040 --> 01:52:03.740
I'm crying, said Anne in a tone of bewilderment.

01:52:04.280 --> 01:52:07.860
I can't think why. I'm as glad as glad can be.

01:52:08.500 --> 01:52:10.940
Oh, glad doesn't seem the right word at all.

01:52:11.280 --> 01:52:17.280
I was glad about the white way and the cherry blossoms, but this, oh, it's something more than glad.

01:52:17.660 --> 01:52:20.700
I'm so happy. I'll try to be so good.

01:52:20.960 --> 01:52:25.960
It will be uphill work, I expect, for Mrs. Thomas often told me I was desperately wicked.

01:52:25.960 --> 01:52:30.160
However, I'll do my very best. But can you tell me why I'm crying?

01:52:31.400 --> 01:52:36.840
I suppose it's because you're all excited and worked up, said Marilla disapprovingly.

01:52:36.840 --> 01:52:39.280
Sit down on that chair and try to calm yourself.

01:52:39.680 --> 01:52:43.040
I'm afraid you both cry and laugh far too easily.

01:52:43.720 --> 01:52:46.780
Yes, you can stay here and we will try to do right by you.

01:52:47.020 --> 01:52:50.660
You must go to school, but it's only a fortnight till vacation,

01:52:50.660 --> 01:52:55.140
so it isn't worthwhile for you to start before it opens again in September.

01:52:56.220 --> 01:52:58.620
What am I to call you? asked Anne.

01:52:59.060 --> 01:53:01.020
Shall I always say Miss Cuthbert?

01:53:01.660 --> 01:53:03.300
Can I call you Aunt Marilla?

01:53:04.260 --> 01:53:06.980
No, you'll call me just plain Marilla.

01:53:07.540 --> 01:53:10.780
I'm not used to being called Miss Cuthbert and it would make me nervous.

01:53:11.720 --> 01:53:16.300
It sounds awfully disrespectful to say just Marilla, protested Anne.

01:53:16.300 --> 01:53:21.380
I guess there'll be nothing disrespectful in it if you're careful to speak respectfully.

01:53:22.400 --> 01:53:27.580
Everybody, young and old, in Avonlea calls me Marilla except the minister.

01:53:28.220 --> 01:53:31.260
He says Miss Cuthbert when he thinks of it.

01:53:32.040 --> 01:53:35.660
I'd love to call you Aunt Marilla, said Anne wistfully.

01:53:36.160 --> 01:53:40.500
I've never had an aunt or any relation at all, not even a grandmother.

01:53:41.120 --> 01:53:44.120
It would make me feel as if I really belonged to you.

01:53:44.120 --> 01:53:46.280
Can't I call you Aunt Marilla?

01:53:47.020 --> 01:53:52.740
No, I'm not your aunt and I don't believe in calling people names that don't belong to them.

01:53:53.300 --> 01:53:55.540
But we could imagine you were my aunt.

01:53:56.140 --> 01:53:59.300
I couldn't, said Marilla grimly.

01:53:59.960 --> 01:54:05.780
Do you never imagine things different from what they really are? asked Anne wide-eyed.

01:54:06.620 --> 01:54:06.960
No.

01:54:07.880 --> 01:54:10.820
Oh, Anne drew in a long breath.

01:54:10.820 --> 01:54:16.200
Oh, Miss Marilla, how much you miss.

01:54:17.600 --> 01:54:22.660
I don't believe in imagining things different from what they really are, retorted Marilla.

01:54:23.320 --> 01:54:28.740
When the Lord puts us in certain circumstances, he doesn't mean for us to imagine them away.

01:54:29.620 --> 01:54:30.960
Anne, that reminds me.

01:54:31.220 --> 01:54:32.860
Go into the sitting room, Anne.

01:54:33.140 --> 01:54:36.580
Be sure your feet are clean and don't let any flies in.

01:54:36.580 --> 01:54:40.440
And bring me out the illustrated card that's on the mantelpiece.

01:54:41.040 --> 01:54:47.200
The Lord's Prayer is on it and you'll devote your spare time this afternoon to learning it off by heart.

01:54:47.740 --> 01:54:51.380
There's to be no more of such praying as I heard last night.

01:54:52.680 --> 01:54:56.520
I suppose I was very awkward, said Anne apologetically.

01:54:56.960 --> 01:54:59.540
But then you see, I've never had any practice.

01:55:00.060 --> 01:55:04.160
You couldn't really expect a person to pray very well the first time she tried, could you?

01:55:04.160 --> 01:55:09.900
I thought out a splendid prayer after I went to bed, just as I promised you I would.

01:55:10.540 --> 01:55:14.240
It wasn't nearly as long as a minister's and so poetical.

01:55:14.760 --> 01:55:15.820
But would you believe it?

01:55:16.080 --> 01:55:18.940
I couldn't remember one word when I woke up this morning.

01:55:19.460 --> 01:55:23.020
And I'm afraid I'll never be able to think out another one as good.

01:55:23.860 --> 01:55:28.040
Somehow things never are so good when they're thought out a second time.

01:55:28.620 --> 01:55:29.920
Have you ever noticed that?

01:55:30.700 --> 01:55:32.900
Here is something for you to notice, Anne.

01:55:32.980 --> 01:55:39.540
When I tell you to do a thing, I want you to obey me at once and not stand stock still and discourse about it.

01:55:39.900 --> 01:55:41.980
Just you go and do as I bid you.

01:55:42.780 --> 01:55:45.840
Anne promptly departed for the sitting room across the hall.

01:55:46.420 --> 01:55:47.920
She failed to return.

01:55:48.700 --> 01:55:54.760
After waiting ten minutes, Marilla laid down her knitting and marched after her with a grim expression.

01:55:54.760 --> 01:56:04.560
She found Anne standing motionless before a picture hanging on the wall between the two windows with her hands clasped behind her,

01:56:04.900 --> 01:56:09.160
her face uplifted and her eyes a star with dreams.

01:56:09.860 --> 01:56:16.040
The white and green light, strained through apple trees and clustering vines outside,

01:56:16.800 --> 01:56:21.080
fell over the wrapped little figure with a half unearthly radiance.

01:56:21.080 --> 01:56:25.680
Anne, what ever are you thinking of? demanded Marilla sharply.

01:56:26.560 --> 01:56:28.640
Anne came back to earth with a start.

01:56:29.340 --> 01:56:36.820
That, she said pointing to the picture, a rather vivid chromo entitled Christ Blessing Little Children.

01:56:37.580 --> 01:56:40.060
And I was just imagining I was one of them.

01:56:40.480 --> 01:56:47.780
That I was the little girl in the blue dress, danding off by herself in the corner as if she didn't belong to anybody, like me.

01:56:47.780 --> 01:56:50.700
She looks lonely and sad, don't you think?

01:56:51.260 --> 01:56:54.000
I guess she hadn't any father or mother of her own.

01:56:54.340 --> 01:57:04.320
But she wanted to be blessed too, so she just crept shyly up on the outside of the crowd, hoping nobody would notice her, except him.

01:57:05.040 --> 01:57:07.340
I'm sure I know just how she felt.

01:57:07.840 --> 01:57:14.480
Her heart must have beat and her hands must have got cold like mine did when I asked you if I could stay.

01:57:14.480 --> 01:57:19.600
She was afraid he mightn't notice her, but it's likely he did, don't you think?

01:57:20.140 --> 01:57:27.440
I've been trying to imagine it all out, her edging a little nearer all the time until she was quite close to him.

01:57:27.820 --> 01:57:36.300
And then he would look at her and put his hand on her hair, and oh, such a thrill of joy as would run over her.

01:57:36.980 --> 01:57:40.760
But I wish the artist hadn't painted him so sorrowful looking.

01:57:40.760 --> 01:57:49.780
All his pictures are like that, if you've noticed, but I don't believe he could really have looked so sad, or the children would have been afraid of him.

01:57:50.740 --> 01:57:58.260
Anne, said Marilla, wondering why she had not broken into this speech long before, you shouldn't talk that way.

01:57:58.680 --> 01:58:01.760
It's irreverent, positively irreverent.

01:58:02.480 --> 01:58:03.820
Anne's eyes marveled.

01:58:04.800 --> 01:58:08.320
Why? I felt just as reverent as could be.

01:58:08.320 --> 01:58:11.360
I'm sure I didn't mean to be irreverent.

01:58:12.440 --> 01:58:18.980
Well, I don't suppose you did, but it doesn't sound right to talk so familiarly about such things.

01:58:19.520 --> 01:58:28.960
And another thing, Anne, when I send you after something you're to bring it at once and not fall into mooning and imagining before pictures, remember that.

01:58:29.540 --> 01:58:32.280
Take that card and come right to the kitchen.

01:58:32.880 --> 01:58:36.160
Now sit down in the corner and learn that prayer by heart.

01:58:37.440 --> 01:58:43.540
Anne set the card up against the jug full of apple blossoms she had brought in to decorate the dinner table.

01:58:44.340 --> 01:58:55.480
Marilla had eyed that decoration askance, but had said nothing, propped her chin on her hands, and fell to studying it intently for several silent minutes.

01:58:56.200 --> 01:58:58.760
I like this, she announced at length.

01:58:59.100 --> 01:59:00.240
It's beautiful.

01:59:00.800 --> 01:59:02.020
I've heard it before.

01:59:02.020 --> 01:59:08.520
I heard the superintendent of the asylum Sunday school say it over once, but I didn't like it then.

01:59:08.900 --> 01:59:12.780
He had such a cracked voice, and he prayed it so mournfully.

01:59:13.360 --> 01:59:16.820
I really felt sure he thought praying was a disagreeable duty.

01:59:17.600 --> 01:59:21.840
This isn't poetry, but it makes me feel just the same way poetry does.

01:59:22.600 --> 01:59:28.720
Our Father, who art in heaven, hallowed be thy name.

01:59:29.520 --> 01:59:31.720
That is just like a line of music.

01:59:32.260 --> 01:59:36.220
I'm so glad you thought of making me learn this, Miss Marilla.

01:59:37.180 --> 01:59:40.980
Well, learn it and hold your tongue, said Marilla shortly.

01:59:40.980 --> 01:59:52.780
Anne tipped the vase of apple blossoms near enough to bestow a soft kiss on a pink cupped bud, and then studied diligently for some moments longer.

01:59:53.900 --> 01:59:59.980
Marilla, she demanded presently, do you think that I shall ever have a bosom friend in Avonlea?

02:00:00.800 --> 02:00:02.880
A what kind of friend?

02:00:02.880 --> 02:00:04.700
A bosom friend.

02:00:05.060 --> 02:00:06.500
An intimate friend, you know.

02:00:06.920 --> 02:00:11.720
A really kindred spirit, to whom I can confide my inmost soul.

02:00:12.260 --> 02:00:14.540
I've dreamed of meeting her all my life.

02:00:15.040 --> 02:00:22.260
I never really supposed I would, but so many of my loveliest dreams have come true all at once that perhaps this one will too.

02:00:22.780 --> 02:00:24.040
Do you think it's possible?

02:00:25.340 --> 02:00:29.300
Diana Berry lives over at Orchard Slope, and she's about your age.

02:00:29.300 --> 02:00:34.760
She's a very nice little girl, and perhaps she will be a playmate for you when she comes home.

02:00:35.460 --> 02:00:38.180
She's visiting her aunt over at Carmody just now.

02:00:38.660 --> 02:00:41.300
You'll have to be careful how you behave yourself, though.

02:00:41.860 --> 02:00:44.280
Mrs. Berry is a very particular woman.

02:00:44.760 --> 02:00:49.060
She won't let Diana play with any little girl who isn't nice and good.

02:00:50.200 --> 02:00:55.940
Anne looked at Marilla through the apple blossoms, her eyes aglow with interest.

02:00:57.000 --> 02:00:58.660
What does Diana like?

02:00:58.660 --> 02:01:00.640
Her hair isn't red, is it?

02:01:01.040 --> 02:01:02.260
Oh, I hope not.

02:01:02.560 --> 02:01:07.900
It's bad enough to have red hair myself, but I positively couldn't endure it in a bosom friend.

02:01:09.140 --> 02:01:11.280
Diana is a very pretty little girl.

02:01:11.500 --> 02:01:18.180
She has black eyes and hair and rosy cheeks, and she is good and smart, which is better than being pretty.

02:01:19.240 --> 02:01:23.480
Marilla was as fond of morals as the Duchess in Wonderland,

02:01:23.780 --> 02:01:29.680
and was firmly convinced that one should be tacked on to every remark made to a child who was being brought up.

02:01:30.420 --> 02:01:37.420
But Anne waved the moral inconsequently aside and seized only on the delightful possibilities before it.

02:01:37.820 --> 02:01:39.580
Oh, I'm so glad she's pretty.

02:01:40.060 --> 02:01:44.240
Next to being beautiful oneself, and that's impossible in my case,

02:01:44.240 --> 02:01:47.420
it would be best to have a beautiful bosom friend.

02:01:48.140 --> 02:01:52.880
When I lived with Mrs. Thomas, she had a bookcase in her sitting room with glass doors.

02:01:53.500 --> 02:01:55.000
There weren't any books in it.

02:01:55.240 --> 02:02:00.980
Mrs. Thomas kept her best china and her preserves there, when she had any preserves to keep.

02:02:01.680 --> 02:02:03.000
One of the doors was broken.

02:02:03.520 --> 02:02:06.980
Mr. Thomas smashed it one night when he was slightly intoxicated.

02:02:06.980 --> 02:02:13.980
But the other was whole, and I used to pretend that my reflection in it was another little girl who lived in it.

02:02:15.140 --> 02:02:18.480
I called her Katie Maurice, and we were very intimate.

02:02:19.040 --> 02:02:23.960
I used to talk to her by the hour, especially on Sunday, and tell her everything.

02:02:24.680 --> 02:02:27.760
Katie was the comfort and consolation of my life.

02:02:28.360 --> 02:02:30.840
We used to pretend that the bookcase was enchanted,

02:02:30.840 --> 02:02:37.620
and that if I only knew the spell, I could open the door and step right into the room where Katie Maurice lived,

02:02:38.080 --> 02:02:41.620
instead of into Mrs. Thomas's shelves of preserves in China.

02:02:42.140 --> 02:02:47.940
And then Katie Maurice would have taken me by the hand and led me out into a wonderful place,

02:02:48.560 --> 02:02:55.140
all flowers and sunshine and fairies, and we would have lived there happily forever after.

02:02:55.960 --> 02:03:00.160
When I went to live with Mrs. Hammond, it just broke my heart to leave Katie Maurice.

02:03:00.160 --> 02:03:07.220
She felt it dreadfully, too, I know she did, for she was crying when she kissed me goodbye through the bookcase door.

02:03:08.020 --> 02:03:15.040
There was no bookcase at Mrs. Hammond's, but just up the river a little way from the house there was a long green little valley,

02:03:15.500 --> 02:03:17.400
and the loveliest echo lived there.

02:03:17.880 --> 02:03:22.460
It echoed back every word you said, even if you didn't talk a bit loud.

02:03:23.020 --> 02:03:26.460
So I imagined that it was a little girl called Violetta,

02:03:26.460 --> 02:03:31.140
and we were great friends, and I loved her almost as well as I loved Katie Maurice.

02:03:31.660 --> 02:03:33.720
Not quite, but almost, you know.

02:03:34.520 --> 02:03:38.740
The night before I went to the asylum, I said goodbye to Violetta,

02:03:39.240 --> 02:03:43.680
and oh, her goodbye came back to me in such sad, sad tones.

02:03:44.360 --> 02:03:49.960
I had become so attached to her that I had into the heart to imagine a bosom friend at the asylum,

02:03:50.380 --> 02:03:53.560
even if there had been any scope for the imagination there.

02:03:54.440 --> 02:03:58.760
I think it's just as well there wasn't, said Marilla, dryly.

02:03:59.200 --> 02:04:01.180
I don't approve of such goings-on.

02:04:01.800 --> 02:04:04.100
You seem to half believe your own imaginations.

02:04:04.620 --> 02:04:09.180
It will be well for you to have a real, live friend to put such nonsense out of your head.

02:04:09.720 --> 02:04:14.560
But don't let Mrs. Barry hear you talking about your Katie Maurice's and your Violetta's,

02:04:15.240 --> 02:04:16.800
or she'll think you tell stories.

02:04:17.980 --> 02:04:20.680
Oh, I won't. I couldn't talk of them to everybody.

02:04:20.680 --> 02:04:23.740
Their memories are just too sacred for that.

02:04:24.240 --> 02:04:26.520
But I thought I'd like to have you know about them.

02:04:27.340 --> 02:04:31.380
Oh, look, here's a big bee that tumbled out of an apple blossom.

02:04:32.080 --> 02:04:35.600
Just think what a lovely place to live, in an apple blossom.

02:04:36.420 --> 02:04:39.600
Fancy going to sleep in it when the wind was rocking it.

02:04:40.120 --> 02:04:45.580
If I wasn't a human girl, I think I'd like to be a bee and live among the flowers.

02:04:46.540 --> 02:04:49.860
Yesterday you wanted to be a seagull, sniffed Marilla.

02:04:49.860 --> 02:04:52.340
I think you are rather fickle-minded.

02:04:53.060 --> 02:04:55.720
I told you to learn that prayer and not talk,

02:04:56.060 --> 02:05:00.680
but it seems impossible for you to stop talking if you've got anybody that will listen to you.

02:05:00.980 --> 02:05:02.980
So go up to your room and learn it.

02:05:03.700 --> 02:05:05.860
Oh, I know it pretty nearly all now.

02:05:06.200 --> 02:05:07.620
All but just the last line.

02:05:08.640 --> 02:05:10.700
Well, never mind. Do as I tell you.

02:05:10.800 --> 02:05:12.760
Go to your room and finish learning it well,

02:05:13.080 --> 02:05:15.820
and stay there until I call you down to help me get tea.

02:05:16.480 --> 02:05:20.460
Can I take the apple blossoms with me for company? pleaded Anne.

02:05:21.460 --> 02:05:24.320
No, you don't want your room cluttered up with flowers.

02:05:24.700 --> 02:05:27.200
You should have left them on the tree in the first place.

02:05:28.260 --> 02:05:31.180
I did feel a little that way too, said Anne.

02:05:31.540 --> 02:05:35.180
I kind of felt I shouldn't shorten their lovely lives by picking them.

02:05:35.660 --> 02:05:38.480
I wouldn't want to be picked if I were an apple blossom,

02:05:39.000 --> 02:05:41.840
but the temptation was irresistible.

02:05:41.840 --> 02:05:45.680
What do you do when you meet with an irresistible temptation?

02:05:46.860 --> 02:05:49.340
Anne, did you hear me tell you to go to your room?

02:05:50.360 --> 02:05:55.940
Anne sighed, retreated to the east gable and sat down in a chair by the window.

02:05:57.320 --> 02:05:58.860
There, I know this prayer.

02:05:59.200 --> 02:06:01.520
I learned that last sentence coming upstairs.

02:06:02.360 --> 02:06:07.840
Now I'm going to imagine things into this room so that they'll always stay imagined.

02:06:07.840 --> 02:06:14.540
The floor is covered with a white velvet carpet with pink roses all over it,

02:06:14.700 --> 02:06:17.740
and there are pink silk curtains at the windows.

02:06:18.560 --> 02:06:22.140
The walls are hung with gold and silver brocade tapestry.

02:06:23.240 --> 02:06:25.240
The furniture is mahogany.

02:06:25.460 --> 02:06:29.320
I never saw any mahogany, but it does sound so luxurious.

02:06:30.060 --> 02:06:33.980
This is a couch and all heaped with gorgeous silken cushions,

02:06:33.980 --> 02:06:40.460
pink and blue and crimson and gold, and I am reclining gracefully on it.

02:06:40.860 --> 02:06:45.600
I can see my reflection in that splendid big mirror hanging on the wall.

02:06:46.300 --> 02:06:51.640
I am tall and regal, clad in a gown of trailing white lace

02:06:51.640 --> 02:06:56.300
with a pearl cross on my breast and pearls in my hair.

02:06:57.000 --> 02:07:03.240
My hair is of midnight darkness, and my skin is a clear ivory pallor.

02:07:03.240 --> 02:07:07.240
My name is the Lady Cordelia Fitzgerald.

02:07:08.800 --> 02:07:11.740
No, it isn't. I can't make that seem real.

02:07:12.760 --> 02:07:17.220
She danced up to the little looking glass and peered into it.

02:07:17.540 --> 02:07:22.000
Her pointed freckled face and solemn gray eyes peered back at her.

02:07:23.040 --> 02:07:26.300
You're only Anne of Green Gables, she said earnestly,

02:07:26.840 --> 02:07:32.430
and I see you just as you are looking now whenever I try to imagine I'm the Lady Cordelia.

02:07:32.430 --> 02:07:36.750
But it's a million times nicer to be Anne of Green Gables

02:07:36.750 --> 02:07:39.770
than Anne of nowhere in particular, isn't it?

02:07:40.470 --> 02:07:43.430
She bent forward, kissed her reflection affectionately,

02:07:44.770 --> 02:07:46.870
and betook herself to the open window.

02:07:47.970 --> 02:07:50.570
Dear Snow Queen, good afternoon.

02:07:51.250 --> 02:07:53.690
And good afternoon, dear birches down in the hollow.

02:07:54.350 --> 02:07:57.950
And good afternoon, dear gray house up on the hill.

02:07:58.590 --> 02:08:01.410
I wonder if Diana is to be my bosom friend.

02:08:01.410 --> 02:08:05.430
I hope she will, and I shall love her very much.

02:08:05.970 --> 02:08:10.170
But I must never quite forget Katie Maurice and Violetta.

02:08:10.770 --> 02:08:15.390
They would feel so hurt if I did, and I'd hate to hurt anybody's feelings,

02:08:15.970 --> 02:08:19.370
even a little bookcase girls or a little echo girls.

02:08:19.810 --> 02:08:24.290
I must be careful to remember them and send them a kiss every day.

02:08:25.350 --> 02:08:30.770
Anne blew a couple of airy kisses from her fingertips past the cherry blossoms,

02:08:30.770 --> 02:08:38.770
and then, with her chin in her hands, drifted luxuriously out on a sea of daydreams.

02:09:03.090 --> 02:09:07.910
IX. Mrs. Rachel Lind is Properly Horrified

02:09:09.490 --> 02:09:15.150
Anne had been a fortnight at Green Gables before Mrs. Lind arrived to inspect her. Mrs.

02:09:15.370 --> 02:09:20.590
Rachel, to do her justice, was not to blame for this. A severe and unseasonable attack

02:09:20.590 --> 02:09:25.370
of grip had confined that good lady to her house ever since the occasion of her last

02:09:25.370 --> 02:09:31.030
visit to Green Gables. Mrs. Rachel was not often sick and had a well-defined contempt

02:09:31.030 --> 02:09:36.570
for people who were, but grip, she asserted, was like no other illness on earth and could

02:09:36.570 --> 02:09:42.450
only be interpreted as one of the special visitations of Providence. As soon as her

02:09:42.450 --> 02:09:47.290
doctor allowed her to put her foot out of doors, she hurried up to Green Gables, bursting

02:09:47.290 --> 02:09:52.310
with curiosity to see Matthew and Marilla's orphan, concerning whom all sorts of stories

02:09:52.310 --> 02:09:58.470
and suppositions had gone abroad in Avonlea. Anne had made good use of every waking moment

02:09:58.470 --> 02:10:03.550
of that fortnight. Already she was acquainted with every tree and shrub about the place.

02:10:04.250 --> 02:10:08.730
She had discovered that a lane opened out below the apple orchard and ran up through

02:10:08.730 --> 02:10:14.030
a belt of woodland, and she had explored it to its furthest end in all its delicious vagaries

02:10:14.030 --> 02:10:20.290
of brook and bridge, fir coppice and wild cherry arch, corners thick with fern, and

02:10:20.290 --> 02:10:25.930
branching byways of maple and mountain ash. She had made friends with the spring down

02:10:25.930 --> 02:10:31.810
in the hollow, that wonderful deep, clear, icy-cold spring. It was set about with smooth

02:10:31.810 --> 02:10:38.090
red sandstones and rimmed in by great palm-like clumps of water fern, and beyond it was a

02:10:38.090 --> 02:10:44.770
log bridge over the brook. That bridge led Anne's dancing feet up over a wooded hill

02:10:44.770 --> 02:10:50.610
beyond where perpetual twilight rained under the straight, thick-growing firs and spruces.

02:10:51.230 --> 02:10:57.330
The only flowers there were myriads of delicate june bells, those shyest and sweetest of woodland

02:10:57.330 --> 02:11:03.430
blooms, and a few pale aerial star-flowers like the spirits of last year's blossoms.

02:11:04.710 --> 02:11:09.710
Gossamers glimmered like threads of silver among the trees, and the fir boughs and tassels

02:11:09.710 --> 02:11:17.590
seemed to utter friendly speech. All these raptured voyages of exploration were made

02:11:17.590 --> 02:11:23.330
in the odd half-hours which she was allowed for play, and Anne talked Matthew and Marilla

02:11:23.330 --> 02:11:29.830
half-deaf over her discoveries. Not that Matthew complained, to be sure. He listened to it

02:11:29.830 --> 02:11:35.390
all with a wordless smile of enjoyment on his face. Marilla permitted the chatter until

02:11:35.390 --> 02:11:39.850
she found herself becoming too interested in it, whereupon she always promptly quenched

02:11:39.850 --> 02:11:46.630
Anne by a curt command to hold her tongue. Anne was out in the orchard when Mrs. Rachel

02:11:46.630 --> 02:11:52.110
came, wandering at her own sweet will through the lush tremulous grasses splashed with ruddy

02:11:52.110 --> 02:11:57.330
evening sunshine, so that good lady had an excellent chance to talk her illness fully

02:11:57.330 --> 02:12:02.730
over, describing every ache and pulse beat with such evident enjoyment that Marilla thought

02:12:02.730 --> 02:12:08.970
even grip must bring its compensations. When details were exhausted, Mrs. Rachel introduced

02:12:08.970 --> 02:12:10.570
the real reason of her call.

02:12:11.630 --> 02:12:14.470
I've been hearing some surprising things about you and Matthew.

02:12:16.370 --> 02:12:20.870
I don't suppose you are any more surprised than I am myself, said Marilla. I'm getting

02:12:20.870 --> 02:12:22.310
over my surprise now.

02:12:24.050 --> 02:12:28.470
It was too bad there was such a mistake, said Mrs. Rachel sympathetically. Couldn't you

02:12:28.470 --> 02:12:29.310
have sent her back?

02:12:30.830 --> 02:12:36.150
I suppose we could, but we decided not to. Matthew took a fancy to her, and I must say

02:12:36.150 --> 02:12:40.830
I like her myself, though I admit she has her faults. The house seems a different place

02:12:40.830 --> 02:12:43.090
already. She's a real bright little thing.

02:12:45.250 --> 02:12:49.850
Marilla said more than she had intended to say when she began, for she read disapproval

02:12:49.850 --> 02:12:51.250
in Mrs. Rachel's expression.

02:12:53.090 --> 02:12:57.790
It's a great responsibility you've taken on yourself, said that lady gloomily, especially

02:12:57.790 --> 02:13:02.110
when you've never had any experience with children. You don't know much about her or

02:13:02.110 --> 02:13:06.030
her real disposition, I suppose, and there's no guessing how a child like that will turn

02:13:06.030 --> 02:13:08.990
out. But I don't want to discourage you, I'm sure, Marilla.

02:13:10.470 --> 02:13:15.790
I'm not feeling discouraged, was Marilla's dry response. When I make up my mind to do

02:13:15.790 --> 02:13:20.610
something, it stays made up. I suppose you'd like to see Anne. I'll call her in.

02:13:22.170 --> 02:13:28.190
Anne came running in presently, her face sparkling with the delight of her orchard rovings, but

02:13:28.190 --> 02:13:33.570
abashed at finding herself in the unexpected presence of her stranger, she halted confusedly

02:13:33.570 --> 02:13:38.990
inside the door. She certainly was an odd-looking little creature in the short, tight, wincey

02:13:38.990 --> 02:13:44.510
dress she had worn from the asylum, below which her thin legs seemed ungracefully long.

02:13:45.250 --> 02:13:50.330
Her freckles were more numerous and obtrusive than ever. The wind had ruffled her hatless

02:13:50.330 --> 02:13:54.810
hair into over-brilliant disorder. It had never looked redder than at that moment.

02:13:57.030 --> 02:14:00.910
Well, they didn't pick you for your looks, that's sure and certain, was Mrs. Rachel Lynn's

02:14:00.910 --> 02:14:06.810
emphatic comment. Mrs. Rachel was one of those delightful and popular people who pride themselves

02:14:06.810 --> 02:14:09.150
on speaking their mind without fear or favor.

02:14:10.190 --> 02:14:14.950
She's terrible skinny and homely, Marilla. Come here, child, and let me have a look at you.

02:14:15.430 --> 02:14:21.430
Lawful heart, did anyone ever see such freckles? And hair as red as carrots. Come here, child, I say.

02:14:23.050 --> 02:14:29.370
Anne came there, but not exactly as Mrs. Rachel expected. With one bound she crossed the kitchen

02:14:29.370 --> 02:14:34.450
floor and stood before Mrs. Rachel, her face scarlet with anger, her lips quivering and

02:14:34.450 --> 02:14:37.350
her whole slender form trembling from head to foot.

02:14:38.250 --> 02:14:42.430
I hate you, she cried in a choked voice, stamping her foot on the floor.

02:14:43.150 --> 02:14:48.550
I hate you, I hate you, I hate you, a louder stamp with each assertion of hatred.

02:14:49.290 --> 02:14:53.130
How dare you call me skinny and ugly? How dare you say I'm freckled and redheaded?

02:14:53.530 --> 02:14:55.870
You are a rude, impolite, unfeeling woman.

02:14:57.310 --> 02:14:59.730
Anne exclaimed Marilla in consternation.

02:15:00.930 --> 02:15:06.590
But Anne continued to face Mrs. Rachel undauntedly, head up, eyes blazing, hands clenched,

02:15:06.590 --> 02:15:09.650
passionate indignation exhaling from her like an atmosphere.

02:15:10.770 --> 02:15:13.510
How dare you say such things about me, she repeated vehemently.

02:15:13.970 --> 02:15:15.930
How would you like to have such things said about you?

02:15:16.250 --> 02:15:20.690
How would you like to be told that you are fat and clumsy and probably hadn't a spark of imagination in you?

02:15:20.950 --> 02:15:24.630
I don't care if I do hurt your feelings by saying so. I hope I hurt them.

02:15:25.010 --> 02:15:29.450
You have hurt mine worse than they were ever hurt before, even by Mrs. Thomas's intoxicated husband.

02:15:29.750 --> 02:15:34.190
And I'll never forgive you for it. Never, never. Stamp, stamp.

02:15:35.930 --> 02:15:40.010
Did anybody ever see such a temper, exclaimed the horrified Mrs. Rachel.

02:15:41.570 --> 02:15:46.730
Anne, go to your room and stay there until I come up, said Marilla, recovering her powers of speech with difficulty.

02:15:48.610 --> 02:15:55.950
Anne, bursting into tears, rushed to the hall door, slammed it until the tins on the porch wall outside rattled in sympathy,

02:15:56.590 --> 02:15:59.190
and fled through the hall and up the stairs like a whirlwind.

02:15:59.890 --> 02:16:04.870
A subdued slam above told that the door of the East Gable had been shut with equal vehemence.

02:16:06.330 --> 02:16:12.270
Well, I don't envy you your job bringing that up, Marilla, said Mrs. Rachel, with unspeakable solemnity.

02:16:14.830 --> 02:16:18.650
Marilla opened her lips to say she knew not what of apology or deprecation.

02:16:19.310 --> 02:16:23.290
What she did say was a surprise to herself then and ever afterwards.

02:16:24.450 --> 02:16:26.950
You shouldn't have tweeted her about her looks, Rachel.

02:16:29.110 --> 02:16:36.270
Marilla Cuthbert, you don't mean to say that you are upholding her in such a terrible display of temper as we've just seen, demanded Mrs. Rachel indignantly.

02:16:37.750 --> 02:16:44.230
No, said Marilla slowly, I'm not trying to excuse her. She's been very naughty and I'll have to give her a talking to about it.

02:16:44.590 --> 02:16:50.170
But we must make allowances for her. She's never been taught what is right. And you were too hard on her, Rachel.

02:16:51.950 --> 02:16:56.670
Marilla could not help tacking on that last sentence, although she was again surprised at herself for doing it.

02:16:57.690 --> 02:17:00.350
Mrs. Rachel got up with an air of offended dignity.

02:17:01.610 --> 02:17:10.830
Well, I see that I'll have to be very careful what I say after this, Marilla, since the fine feelings of orphans, brought from goodness knows where, have to be considered before anything else.

02:17:11.270 --> 02:17:16.830
Oh no, I'm not vexed, don't worry yourself. I'm too sorry for you to leave any room for anger in my mind.

02:17:17.370 --> 02:17:19.070
You'll have your own troubles with that child.

02:17:19.770 --> 02:17:24.590
But if you'll take my advice, which I suppose you won't do, although I've brought up ten children and buried two,

02:17:24.590 --> 02:17:28.070
you'll do that talking to who you mentioned with a fair-sized birch switch.

02:17:28.690 --> 02:17:34.170
I should think that would be the most effective language for that kind of a child. Her temper matches her hair, I guess.

02:17:34.870 --> 02:17:38.650
Well, good evening, Marilla. I hope you'll come down to see me often, as usual.

02:17:39.170 --> 02:17:46.070
But you can't expect me to visit here again in a hurry, if I'm liable to be flown at and insulted in such a fashion. It's something new in my experience.

02:17:47.850 --> 02:17:53.290
Whereat Mrs. Rachel swept out and away, if a fat woman who always waddled could be said to sweep away.

02:17:53.290 --> 02:17:57.550
And Marilla, with a very solemn face, betook herself to the East Gable.

02:17:59.690 --> 02:18:03.250
On the way upstairs, she pondered uneasily as to what she ought to do.

02:18:04.030 --> 02:18:07.250
She felt no little dismay over the scene that had just been enacted.

02:18:08.110 --> 02:18:12.450
How unfortunate that Anne should have displayed such temper before Mrs. Rachel Lynde of all people.

02:18:13.690 --> 02:18:17.590
Then Marilla suddenly became aware of an uncomfortable and rebuking consciousness,

02:18:17.590 --> 02:18:24.370
that she felt more humiliation over this than sorrow over the discovery of such a serious defect in Anne's disposition.

02:18:25.510 --> 02:18:27.570
And how was she to punish her?

02:18:28.250 --> 02:18:35.170
The amiable suggestion of the birch switch, to the efficiency of which all of Mrs. Rachel's own children could have borne smarting testimony,

02:18:35.830 --> 02:18:40.010
did not appeal to Marilla. She did not believe she could whip a child.

02:18:41.130 --> 02:18:47.030
No, some other method of punishment must be found to bring Anne to a proper realization of the enormity of her offence.

02:18:49.290 --> 02:18:56.590
Marilla found Anne face downward on her bed, crying bitterly, quite oblivious of muddy boots on a clean counterpane.

02:18:58.770 --> 02:19:02.870
Anne, she said, not un-gently. No answer.

02:19:04.310 --> 02:19:09.070
Anne, with greater severity, get off that bed this minute and listen to what I have to say to you.

02:19:10.670 --> 02:19:14.450
Anne squirmed off the bed and sat rigidly on a chair beside it,

02:19:14.450 --> 02:19:19.010
her face swollen and tear-stained and her eyes fixed stubbornly on the floor.

02:19:20.450 --> 02:19:23.550
This is a nice way for you to behave, Anne. Aren't you ashamed of yourself?

02:19:24.410 --> 02:19:29.070
She hadn't any right to call me ugly and redheaded, retorted Anne, evasive and defiant.

02:19:30.210 --> 02:19:33.910
You hadn't any right to fly into such a fury and talk the way you did to her, Anne.

02:19:34.530 --> 02:19:37.050
I was ashamed of you, thoroughly ashamed of you.

02:19:37.430 --> 02:19:41.870
I wanted you to behave nicely to Mrs. Lind, and instead of that you have disgraced me.

02:19:42.290 --> 02:19:47.290
I'm sure I don't know why you should lose your temper like that, just because Mrs. Lind said you were red-haired and homely.

02:19:47.630 --> 02:19:49.070
You say it yourself often enough.

02:19:50.490 --> 02:19:54.950
Oh, but there's such a difference between saying a thing yourself and hearing other people say it, wailed Anne.

02:19:55.750 --> 02:20:00.050
You may know a thing as so, but you can't help hoping other people don't quite think it is.

02:20:00.530 --> 02:20:03.670
I suppose you think I have an awful temper, but I couldn't help it.

02:20:03.930 --> 02:20:09.070
When she said those things, something just rose right up in me and choked me. I had to fly out at her.

02:20:10.410 --> 02:20:13.370
Well, you made a fine exhibition of yourself, I must say.

02:20:13.970 --> 02:20:18.030
Mrs. Lind will have a nice story to tell about you everywhere, and she'll tell it too.

02:20:18.570 --> 02:20:21.410
It was a dreadful thing for you to lose your temper like that, Anne.

02:20:23.290 --> 02:20:29.010
Just imagine how you would feel if somebody told you to your face that you were skinny and ugly, pleaded Anne tearfully.

02:20:30.650 --> 02:20:33.410
An old remembrance suddenly rose up before Marilla.

02:20:34.330 --> 02:20:38.370
She had been a very small child when she had heard one aunt say of her to another.

02:20:39.070 --> 02:20:41.610
What a pity she is such a dark, homely little thing.

02:20:42.750 --> 02:20:45.930
Marilla was every day a fifty before the sting had gone out of that memory.

02:20:48.350 --> 02:20:54.430
I don't say that I think Mrs. Lind was exactly right in saying what she did to you, Anne, she admitted in a softer tone.

02:20:55.330 --> 02:20:59.650
Rachel is too outspoken, but that is no excuse for such behavior on your part.

02:21:00.250 --> 02:21:03.490
She was a stranger and an elderly person and my visitor.

02:21:03.910 --> 02:21:06.830
All three very good reasons why you should have been respectful to her.

02:21:06.830 --> 02:21:11.710
You are rude and saucy and Marilla had a saving inspiration of punishment.

02:21:12.430 --> 02:21:17.190
You must go to her and tell her you are very sorry for your bad temper and ask her to forgive you.

02:21:18.070 --> 02:21:22.010
I can never do that, said Anne, determinedly and darkly.

02:21:22.550 --> 02:21:24.570
You can punish me in any way you like, Marilla.

02:21:25.010 --> 02:21:31.810
You can shut me up in a dark, damp dungeon inhabited by snakes and toads and feed me only on bread and water and I shall not complain.

02:21:32.270 --> 02:21:34.890
But I cannot ask Mrs. Lind to forgive me.

02:21:36.530 --> 02:21:43.570
We're not in the habit of shutting people up in dark, damp dungeons, said Marilla, dryly, especially as they're rather scarce and avidly.

02:21:44.210 --> 02:21:50.930
But apologize to Mrs. Lind you must and shall and you'll stay here in your room until you can tell me you're willing to do it.

02:21:52.190 --> 02:21:59.030
I shall have to stay here forever then, said Anne, mournfully, because I can't tell Mrs. Lind I'm sorry I said those things to her.

02:21:59.030 --> 02:22:06.830
How can I? I'm not sorry. I'm sorry I vexed you, but I'm glad I told her just what I did. It was a great satisfaction.

02:22:07.610 --> 02:22:11.850
I can't say I'm sorry when I'm not, can I? I can't even imagine I'm sorry.

02:22:13.790 --> 02:22:18.810
Perhaps your imagination will be in better working order by the morning, said Marilla, rising to depart.

02:22:19.690 --> 02:22:23.970
You'll have the night to think over your conduct in and come to a better frame of mind.

02:22:23.970 --> 02:22:30.890
You said you would try to be a very good girl if we kept you at Green Gables, but I must say it hasn't seemed very much like it this evening.

02:22:32.650 --> 02:22:41.390
Leaving this Parthian shaft to rankle in Anne's stormy bosom, Marilla descended to the kitchen, grievously troubled in mind and vexed in soul.

02:22:42.270 --> 02:22:53.330
She was as angry with herself as with Anne, because, whenever she recalled Mrs. Rachel's dumbfounded countenance, her lips twitched with amusement and she felt a most reprehensible desire to laugh.

02:23:13.410 --> 02:23:16.510
Anne of Green Gables by L. M. Montgomery.

02:23:18.070 --> 02:23:20.210
Anne's Apology

02:23:22.350 --> 02:23:25.110
Marilla said nothing to Matthew about the affair that evening.

02:23:25.650 --> 02:23:29.930
But when Anne proved still refractory the next morning, an explanation had to be made

02:23:29.930 --> 02:23:32.050
to account for her absence from the breakfast table.

02:23:33.090 --> 02:23:36.730
Marilla told Matthew the whole story, taking pains to impress him

02:23:36.730 --> 02:23:39.130
with the due sense of the enormity of Anne's behavior.

02:23:40.990 --> 02:23:43.470
It's a good thing Rachel Lynn got a calling down.

02:23:43.970 --> 02:23:47.690
She's a meddlesome old gossip, was Matthew's consolatory rejoinder.

02:23:49.070 --> 02:23:51.170
Matthew Cuthbert, I'm astonished at you.

02:23:51.590 --> 02:23:54.490
You know that Anne's behavior was dreadful, and yet you take her part.

02:23:55.090 --> 02:23:58.450
I suppose you'll be saying next thing that she oughtn't to be punished at all.

02:24:00.090 --> 02:24:04.970
Well now, no, not exactly, said Matthew uneasily.

02:24:05.570 --> 02:24:07.490
I reckon she ought to be punished a little.

02:24:07.950 --> 02:24:09.810
But don't be too hard on her, Marilla.

02:24:10.410 --> 02:24:12.730
Recollect she hasn't ever had anyone to teach her right.

02:24:13.590 --> 02:24:15.950
You're going to give her something to eat, aren't you?

02:24:17.190 --> 02:24:20.190
When did you ever hear of me starving people into good behavior,

02:24:20.310 --> 02:24:21.730
demanded Marilla indignantly.

02:24:22.450 --> 02:24:25.290
She'll have her meals regular, and I'll carry them out to her myself.

02:24:25.770 --> 02:24:28.630
But she'll stay up there until she's willing to apologize to Mrs. Lynn,

02:24:28.730 --> 02:24:29.830
and that's final, Matthew.

02:24:31.670 --> 02:24:36.890
Breakfast, dinner, and supper were very silent meals, for Anne still remained obdurate.

02:24:37.950 --> 02:24:41.370
After each meal, Marilla carried a well-filled tray to the East Gable

02:24:41.370 --> 02:24:45.310
and brought it down later on, not noticeably depleted.

02:24:46.210 --> 02:24:48.710
Matthew eyed its last descent with a troubled eye.

02:24:49.250 --> 02:24:51.110
Had Anne eaten anything at all?

02:24:52.570 --> 02:24:56.130
When Marilla went out that evening to bring the cows from the back pasture,

02:24:56.790 --> 02:24:59.590
Matthew, who had been hanging about the barns and watching,

02:25:00.210 --> 02:25:03.570
slipped into the house with the air of a burglar and crept upstairs.

02:25:05.030 --> 02:25:08.030
As a general thing, Matthew gravitated between the kitchen

02:25:08.030 --> 02:25:10.130
and the little bedroom off the hall where he slept.

02:25:10.810 --> 02:25:14.850
Once in a while, he ventured uncomfortably into the parlor or sitting room

02:25:14.850 --> 02:25:16.470
when the minister came to tea.

02:25:17.230 --> 02:25:20.530
But he had never been upstairs in his own house since the spring

02:25:20.530 --> 02:25:24.450
he helped Marilla paper the spare bedroom, and that was four years ago.

02:25:25.910 --> 02:25:29.770
He tiptoed along the hall and stood for several minutes outside the door

02:25:29.770 --> 02:25:33.870
of the East Gable before he summoned courage to tap on it with his fingers

02:25:33.870 --> 02:25:36.410
and then opened the door to peep in.

02:25:38.430 --> 02:25:41.250
Anne was sitting on the yellow chair by the window,

02:25:41.530 --> 02:25:43.390
gazing mournfully out into the garden.

02:25:44.530 --> 02:25:48.250
Very small and unhappy, she looked, and Matthew's heart smote him.

02:25:49.490 --> 02:25:52.790
He softly closed the door and tiptoed over to her.

02:25:54.150 --> 02:25:57.370
Anne, he whispered, as if afraid of being overheard.

02:25:58.190 --> 02:25:59.650
How are you making it, Anne?

02:26:01.370 --> 02:26:03.190
Anne smiled wanly.

02:26:04.130 --> 02:26:05.090
Pretty well.

02:26:05.350 --> 02:26:07.850
I imagine a good deal, and that helps to pass the time.

02:26:08.390 --> 02:26:09.950
Of course, it's rather lonesome.

02:26:10.190 --> 02:26:12.510
But then I may as well get used to that.

02:26:13.690 --> 02:26:17.090
Anne smiled again, bravely facing the long years

02:26:17.090 --> 02:26:19.510
of solitary imprisonment before her.

02:26:21.210 --> 02:26:23.830
Matthew recollected that he must say what he had come to say

02:26:23.830 --> 02:26:27.450
without loss of time, lest Marilla return prematurely.

02:26:28.750 --> 02:26:32.510
Well now, Anne, don't you think you'd better do it and have it over with?

02:26:32.510 --> 02:26:33.570
He whispered.

02:26:34.270 --> 02:26:36.630
It'll have to be done sooner or later, you know,

02:26:36.890 --> 02:26:38.950
for Marilla's a dreadful determined woman.

02:26:39.230 --> 02:26:40.510
Dreadful determined, Anne.

02:26:41.090 --> 02:26:43.030
Do it right off, I say, and have it over.

02:26:44.730 --> 02:26:47.010
Do you mean apologize to Mrs. Lind?

02:26:48.930 --> 02:26:49.890
Yes, apologize.

02:26:50.130 --> 02:26:52.510
That's the very word, said Matthew eagerly.

02:26:52.950 --> 02:26:54.690
Just smooth it over, so to speak.

02:26:55.010 --> 02:26:56.510
That's what I was trying to get at.

02:26:58.450 --> 02:27:02.010
I suppose I could do it to oblige you, said Anne thoughtfully.

02:27:02.910 --> 02:27:06.310
It would be true enough to say I am sorry, because I am sorry now.

02:27:06.730 --> 02:27:08.370
I wasn't a bit sorry last night.

02:27:08.630 --> 02:27:11.010
I was mad clear through, and I stayed mad all night.

02:27:11.650 --> 02:27:13.510
I know I did, because I woke up three times,

02:27:13.510 --> 02:27:15.390
and I was just furious every time.

02:27:15.970 --> 02:27:17.350
But this morning it was over.

02:27:17.770 --> 02:27:22.510
I wasn't in a temper any more, and it left a dreadful sort of gone-ness, too.

02:27:22.890 --> 02:27:24.390
I felt so ashamed of myself.

02:27:24.390 --> 02:27:28.010
But I just couldn't think of going and telling Mrs. Lind so.

02:27:28.550 --> 02:27:29.910
It would be so humiliating.

02:27:30.590 --> 02:27:33.730
I made up my mind I'd stay shut up here forever rather than do that.

02:27:34.690 --> 02:27:38.930
But still, I'd do anything for you if you really want me to.

02:27:40.250 --> 02:27:42.310
Well, now, of course I do.

02:27:42.670 --> 02:27:45.130
It's terrible lonesome downstairs without you.

02:27:45.790 --> 02:27:47.350
Just go and smooth things over.

02:27:47.490 --> 02:27:48.450
That's a good girl.

02:27:50.350 --> 02:27:52.510
Very well, said Anne resignedly.

02:27:53.050 --> 02:27:54.090
I'll tell Marilla.

02:27:54.170 --> 02:27:56.370
As soon as she comes in, I've repented.

02:27:57.630 --> 02:27:58.370
That's right.

02:27:58.710 --> 02:27:59.630
That's right, Anne.

02:28:00.270 --> 02:28:02.530
But don't tell Marilla I said anything about it.

02:28:02.850 --> 02:28:06.110
She might think I was putting my oar in, and I promised not to do that.

02:28:07.590 --> 02:28:10.970
Wild horses won't drag the secret from me, promised Anne solemnly.

02:28:11.530 --> 02:28:14.010
How would wild horses drag a secret from a person anyhow?

02:28:15.810 --> 02:28:18.690
But Matthew was gone, scared at his own success.

02:28:19.450 --> 02:28:22.610
He fled hastily to the remotest corner of the horse pasture,

02:28:23.110 --> 02:28:25.590
lest Marilla should suspect what he had been up to.

02:28:26.690 --> 02:28:29.350
Marilla herself, upon her return to the house,

02:28:29.730 --> 02:28:32.090
was agreeably surprised to hear a plaintive voice calling,

02:28:32.650 --> 02:28:34.250
Marilla, over the banisters.

02:28:35.970 --> 02:28:37.970
Well, she said, going into the hall.

02:28:39.110 --> 02:28:41.550
I'm sorry I lost my temper and said rude things,

02:28:41.630 --> 02:28:43.690
and I'm willing to go and tell Mrs. Lind so.

02:28:45.210 --> 02:28:49.030
Very well, Marilla's Christmas gave no sign of her relief.

02:28:49.790 --> 02:28:52.210
She had been wondering what under the canopy she should do

02:28:52.210 --> 02:28:53.690
if Anne did not give in.

02:28:54.330 --> 02:28:56.150
I'll take you down after milking.

02:28:57.630 --> 02:29:01.330
Accordingly, after milking, behold Marilla and Anne walking

02:29:01.330 --> 02:29:04.350
down the lane, the former erect and triumphant,

02:29:04.810 --> 02:29:06.670
the latter drooping and ejected.

02:29:07.470 --> 02:29:11.370
But halfway down, Anne's dejection vanished as if by enchantment.

02:29:12.070 --> 02:29:15.830
She lifted her head and stepped lightly along, her eyes fixed

02:29:15.830 --> 02:29:20.390
on the sunset sky, and an air of subdued exhilaration about her.

02:29:21.590 --> 02:29:23.930
Marilla beheld the change disapprovingly.

02:29:24.550 --> 02:29:27.510
This was no meek penitent, such as it behooved her to take

02:29:27.510 --> 02:29:29.470
into the presence of the offended Mrs. Lind.

02:29:31.270 --> 02:29:33.090
What are you thinking of, Anne?

02:29:33.130 --> 02:29:34.130
she asked sharply.

02:29:35.490 --> 02:29:37.810
I'm imagining out what I must say to Mrs. Lind,

02:29:38.150 --> 02:29:39.250
answered Anne dreamily.

02:29:41.470 --> 02:29:44.730
This was satisfactory, or should have been so.

02:29:45.430 --> 02:29:48.110
But Marilla could not rid herself of the notion that something

02:29:48.110 --> 02:29:50.770
in her scheme of punishment was going askew.

02:29:51.350 --> 02:29:53.970
Anne had no business to look so rapt and radiant.

02:29:55.630 --> 02:29:59.030
Rapt and radiant, Anne continued until they were in the very presence

02:29:59.030 --> 02:30:02.450
of Mrs. Lind, who was sitting knitting by her kitchen window.

02:30:03.550 --> 02:30:05.090
Then the radiance vanished.

02:30:06.110 --> 02:30:08.350
Mournful penitence appeared on every feature.

02:30:09.150 --> 02:30:13.530
Before a word was spoken, Anne suddenly went down on her knees before the

02:30:13.530 --> 02:30:16.550
astonished Mrs. Rachel, and held out her hands beseechingly.

02:30:17.950 --> 02:30:22.590
Oh, Mrs. Lind, I am so extremely sorry, she said with a quiver in her voice.

02:30:22.950 --> 02:30:24.990
I could never express all my sorrow.

02:30:25.270 --> 02:30:27.370
No, not if I used up a whole dictionary.

02:30:27.790 --> 02:30:29.190
You must just imagine it.

02:30:29.390 --> 02:30:32.730
I behaved terribly to you, and I've disgraced the dear friends,

02:30:32.850 --> 02:30:35.470
Matthew and Marilla, who have let me stay at Green Gables,

02:30:35.490 --> 02:30:36.490
although I'm not a boy.

02:30:37.090 --> 02:30:40.550
I'm a dreadfully wicked and ungrateful girl, and I deserve to be punished

02:30:40.550 --> 02:30:42.590
and cast out by respectable people forever.

02:30:43.130 --> 02:30:46.290
It was very wicked of me to fly into a temper because you told me the truth.

02:30:46.550 --> 02:30:47.670
It was the truth.

02:30:48.090 --> 02:30:49.430
Every word you said was true.

02:30:49.810 --> 02:30:52.510
My hair is red, and I'm freckled and skinny and ugly.

02:30:53.130 --> 02:30:55.730
What I said to you was true, too, but I shouldn't have said it.

02:30:56.190 --> 02:30:58.330
Oh, Mrs. Lind, please, please forgive me.

02:30:58.590 --> 02:31:01.110
If you refuse, it will be a lifelong sorrow to me.

02:31:01.390 --> 02:31:04.610
You wouldn't like to inflict a lifelong sorrow on a poor little orphan girl,

02:31:04.610 --> 02:31:06.490
would you, even if she had a dirtful temper?

02:31:07.110 --> 02:31:08.450
Oh, I am sure you wouldn't.

02:31:08.790 --> 02:31:10.350
Please say you forgive me, Mrs. Lind.

02:31:12.110 --> 02:31:15.010
Anne clasped her hands together, bowed her head,

02:31:15.190 --> 02:31:16.670
and waited for the word of judgment.

02:31:18.950 --> 02:31:20.850
There was no mistaking her sincerity.

02:31:21.090 --> 02:31:23.230
It breathed in every tone of her voice.

02:31:23.990 --> 02:31:27.390
Both Marilla and Mrs. Lind recognized its unmistakable ring,

02:31:27.950 --> 02:31:32.210
but the former understood in dismay that Anne was actually enjoying her valley

02:31:32.210 --> 02:31:36.150
of humiliation, was reveling in the thoroughness of her abasement.

02:31:37.070 --> 02:31:40.830
Where was the wholesome punishment upon which she, Marilla, had plumed herself?

02:31:41.810 --> 02:31:44.530
Anne had turned it into a species of positive pleasure.

02:31:46.430 --> 02:31:50.990
Good Mrs. Lind, not being overburdened with perception, did not see this.

02:31:51.590 --> 02:31:54.690
She only perceived that Anne had made a very thorough apology,

02:31:54.950 --> 02:31:58.710
and all resentment vanished from her kindly, if somewhat officious, heart.

02:31:59.890 --> 02:32:02.810
There, there, get up, child, she said heartily.

02:32:03.210 --> 02:32:04.530
Of course I forgive you.

02:32:04.690 --> 02:32:06.690
I guess I was a little too hard on you anyway.

02:32:07.170 --> 02:32:08.750
But I'm such an outspoken person.

02:32:09.130 --> 02:32:10.770
You just mustn't mind me, that's what.

02:32:11.370 --> 02:32:13.450
It can't be denied your hair is terrible red.

02:32:13.850 --> 02:32:16.450
But I knew a girl once, went to school with her in fact,

02:32:16.850 --> 02:32:19.490
whose hair was every mite as red as yours when she was young.

02:32:19.710 --> 02:32:22.390
But when she grew up, it darkened to a real handsome auburn.

02:32:22.910 --> 02:32:25.850
I wouldn't be a mite surprised if yours did too, not a mite.

02:32:27.550 --> 02:32:31.670
Oh, Mrs. Lind, Anne drew a long breath as she rose to her feet.

02:32:32.150 --> 02:32:33.270
You have given me a hope.

02:32:33.710 --> 02:32:35.730
I shall always feel that you are a benefactor.

02:32:36.410 --> 02:32:39.550
Oh, I could endure anything if I only thought my hair would be a handsome

02:32:39.550 --> 02:32:40.610
auburn when I grew up.

02:32:41.110 --> 02:32:44.350
It would be so much easier to be good if one's hair was a handsome auburn,

02:32:44.390 --> 02:32:45.050
don't you think?

02:32:45.610 --> 02:32:48.190
And now may I go out into your garden and sit on that bench

02:32:48.190 --> 02:32:50.390
under the apple trees while you and Marilla are talking?

02:32:50.970 --> 02:32:53.610
There is so much more scope for imagination out there.

02:32:55.450 --> 02:32:57.130
Laws, yes, run along, child.

02:32:57.550 --> 02:33:00.590
And you can pick a bouquet of them white June lilies over in the corner

02:33:00.590 --> 02:33:01.590
if you like.

02:33:03.850 --> 02:33:08.630
As the door closed behind Anne, Mrs. Lind got briskly up to light a lamp.

02:33:10.010 --> 02:33:11.530
She's a real odd little thing.

02:33:12.130 --> 02:33:13.150
Take this chair, Marilla.

02:33:13.270 --> 02:33:14.730
It's easier than the one you've got.

02:33:14.990 --> 02:33:17.250
I just keep that for the hired boy to sit on.

02:33:17.830 --> 02:33:19.490
Yes, she certainly is an odd child.

02:33:19.490 --> 02:33:22.090
But there is something kind of taking about her after all.

02:33:22.090 --> 02:33:26.190
I don't feel so surprised at you and Matthew keeping her as I did,

02:33:26.410 --> 02:33:27.770
nor so sorry for you either.

02:33:28.210 --> 02:33:29.630
She may turn out all right.

02:33:30.150 --> 02:33:33.050
Of course, she has a queer way of expressing herself,

02:33:33.650 --> 02:33:37.310
a little too, well, too kind of forcible, you know.

02:33:37.670 --> 02:33:40.990
But she'll likely get over that now that she's come to live among civilized folks.

02:33:41.470 --> 02:33:43.690
And then her temper's pretty quick, I guess.

02:33:44.070 --> 02:33:45.130
But there's one comfort.

02:33:45.470 --> 02:33:48.490
A child that has a quick temper, just blaze up and cool down,

02:33:48.850 --> 02:33:50.790
ain't never likely to be sly or deceitful.

02:33:51.270 --> 02:33:53.470
Preserve me from a sly child, that's what.

02:33:54.130 --> 02:33:55.970
On the whole, Marilla, I kind of like her.

02:33:58.410 --> 02:34:02.170
When Marilla went home, Anne came out of the fragrant twilight of the orchard

02:34:02.170 --> 02:34:04.450
with a sheaf of white narcissi in her hands.

02:34:05.710 --> 02:34:07.550
I apologized pretty well, didn't I?

02:34:07.670 --> 02:34:09.490
She said proudly as they went down the lane.

02:34:10.330 --> 02:34:12.830
I thought since I had to do it, I might as well do it thoroughly.

02:34:14.550 --> 02:34:17.170
You did it thoroughly all right enough, was Marilla's comment.

02:34:18.450 --> 02:34:22.450
Marilla was dismayed at finding herself inclined to laugh over the recollection.

02:34:23.150 --> 02:34:27.410
She had also an uneasy feeling that she ought to scold Anne for apologizing so well.

02:34:27.750 --> 02:34:29.350
But then, that was ridiculous.

02:34:30.430 --> 02:34:33.010
She compromised with her conscience by saying severely,

02:34:33.790 --> 02:34:36.410
I hope you won't have occasion to make many more such apologies.

02:34:36.930 --> 02:34:39.090
I hope you'll try to control your temper now, Anne.

02:34:40.690 --> 02:34:43.470
That wouldn't be so hard if people wouldn't tweet me about my looks,

02:34:43.750 --> 02:34:44.910
said Anne with a sigh.

02:34:44.910 --> 02:34:47.590
I don't get cross about other things,

02:34:47.810 --> 02:34:50.390
but I'm so tired of being tweeted about my hair,

02:34:50.510 --> 02:34:52.230
and it just makes me boil right over.

02:34:52.950 --> 02:34:56.350
Do you suppose my hair will really be a handsome Auburn when I grow up?

02:34:57.490 --> 02:34:59.810
You shouldn't think so much about your looks, Anne.

02:35:00.310 --> 02:35:02.750
I'm afraid you are a very vain little girl.

02:35:04.370 --> 02:35:07.290
How can I be vain when I know I'm homely, protested Anne?

02:35:08.130 --> 02:35:12.210
I love pretty things, and I hate to look in the glass and see something that isn't pretty.

02:35:12.610 --> 02:35:16.570
It makes me feel so sorrowful, just as I feel when I look at any ugly thing.

02:35:16.930 --> 02:35:18.830
I pity it because it isn't beautiful.

02:35:21.070 --> 02:35:23.570
Handsome is as handsome does, quoted Marilla.

02:35:24.950 --> 02:35:27.370
I've had that said to me before, but I have my doubts about it,

02:35:27.490 --> 02:35:29.970
remarked skeptical Anne, sniffing at her narcissi.

02:35:30.790 --> 02:35:32.310
Oh, aren't these flowers sweet?

02:35:32.770 --> 02:35:33.670
It was lovely of Mrs.

02:35:33.790 --> 02:35:34.790
Lynn to give them to me.

02:35:34.970 --> 02:35:36.610
I have no hard feelings against Mrs.

02:35:36.730 --> 02:35:37.270
Lynn now.

02:35:37.870 --> 02:35:40.990
It gives you a lovely, comfortable feeling to apologize and be forgiven,

02:35:40.990 --> 02:35:41.870
doesn't it?

02:35:42.330 --> 02:35:43.530
Aren't the stars bright tonight?

02:35:44.010 --> 02:35:46.150
If you could live on a star, which one would you pick?

02:35:46.630 --> 02:35:49.850
I'd like that lovely, clear big one away over there above the dark hill.

02:35:51.650 --> 02:35:53.810
Anne, do hold your tongue, said Marilla,

02:35:54.130 --> 02:35:57.190
thoroughly worn out trying to follow the gyrations of Anne's thoughts.

02:35:58.910 --> 02:36:01.710
Anne said no more until they turned into their own lane.

02:36:02.830 --> 02:36:05.470
A little gypsy wind came down it to meet them,

02:36:05.810 --> 02:36:09.750
laden with the spicy perfume of young dew-wet ferns.

02:36:09.750 --> 02:36:13.290
Far up in the shadows, a cheerful light gleamed out through the trees from the

02:36:13.290 --> 02:36:14.290
kitchen at Green Gables.

02:36:15.570 --> 02:36:19.210
Anne suddenly came close to Marilla and slipped her hand into the older woman's

02:36:19.210 --> 02:36:19.930
hard palm.

02:36:21.550 --> 02:36:24.130
It's lovely to be going home and know it's home, she said.

02:36:24.870 --> 02:36:27.990
I love Green Gables already, and I never loved any place before.

02:36:28.670 --> 02:36:30.230
No place ever seemed like home.

02:36:30.950 --> 02:36:32.570
Oh, Marilla, I'm so happy.

02:36:33.310 --> 02:36:35.910
I could pray right now and not find it a bit hard.

02:36:37.670 --> 02:36:41.570
Something warm and pleasant welled up in Marilla's heart at the touch of that

02:36:41.570 --> 02:36:46.430
thin little hand in her own, a throb of the maternity she had missed, perhaps.

02:36:47.570 --> 02:36:51.190
It's very unaccustomedness and sweetness disturbed her.

02:36:52.210 --> 02:36:56.850
She hastened to restore her sensations to their normal calm by inculcating a moral.

02:36:58.350 --> 02:37:01.330
If you'll be a good girl, you'll always be happy, Anne.

02:37:01.650 --> 02:37:03.970
And you should never find it hard to say your prayers.

02:37:05.910 --> 02:37:09.450
Saying one's prayers isn't exactly the same thing as praying, said Anne

02:37:09.930 --> 02:37:10.410
meditatively.

02:37:11.230 --> 02:37:14.470
But I'm going to imagine that I'm the wind that is blowing up there in those

02:37:14.470 --> 02:37:15.030
tree tops.

02:37:15.670 --> 02:37:19.030
When I get tired of the trees, I'll imagine I'm gently waving down here in the

02:37:19.030 --> 02:37:19.830
ferns.

02:37:19.830 --> 02:37:21.170
And then I'll fly over to Mrs.

02:37:21.270 --> 02:37:23.330
Lynn's garden and set the flowers dancing.

02:37:23.830 --> 02:37:26.610
And then I'll go with one great swoop over the clover field.

02:37:27.270 --> 02:37:29.930
And then I'll blow over the lake of shining waters and

02:37:29.930 --> 02:37:32.070
ripple it all up into little sparkling waves.

02:37:32.610 --> 02:37:35.210
Oh, there's so much scope for imagination in a wind.

02:37:35.910 --> 02:37:38.070
So I'll not talk any more just now, Marilla.

02:37:39.550 --> 02:37:43.330
Thanks be to goodness for that, breathed Marilla in devout relief.

02:37:48.390 --> 02:37:52.590
Recorded January 22nd, 2006 in Longmont, Colorado.

02:38:22.370 --> 02:38:25.550
Anne's Impressions of Sunday School.

02:38:28.330 --> 02:38:30.870
Well, how do you like them? said Marilla.

02:38:32.730 --> 02:38:38.690
Anne was standing in the gable-room, looking solemnly at three new dresses spread out on the bed.

02:38:39.270 --> 02:38:46.690
One was of snuffy-coloured gingham, which Marilla had been tempted to buy from a peddler the preceding summer, because it looked so serviceable.

02:38:47.650 --> 02:38:53.290
One was of a black-and-white checkered sateen, which she had picked up at a bargain-counter in the winter.

02:38:54.150 --> 02:39:00.750
And one was a stiff print of an ugly blue shade, which she had purchased that week at a Carmody store.

02:39:01.910 --> 02:39:13.950
She had made them up herself, and they were all made alike. Plain skirts fold tightly to plain waists, with sleeves as plain as waist and skirt, and tight as sleeves could be.

02:39:15.470 --> 02:39:19.370
"'I'll imagine that I like them,' said Anne, soberly.

02:39:20.230 --> 02:39:23.850
"'I don't want you to imagine it,' said Marilla, offended.

02:39:24.310 --> 02:39:30.190
"'Oh, I can see you don't like the dresses. What is the matter with them? Aren't they neat and clean and new?'

02:39:32.330 --> 02:39:32.890
"'Yes.'

02:39:32.890 --> 02:39:34.870
"'Then why don't you like them?'

02:39:36.370 --> 02:39:39.990
"'They're—they're not pretty,' said Anne, reluctantly.

02:39:41.910 --> 02:39:43.590
"'Pretty?' Marilla sniffed.

02:39:43.630 --> 02:39:50.710
"'I didn't trouble my head about getting pretty dresses for you. I don't believe in pampering vanity, Anne. I'll tell you that right off.

02:39:51.050 --> 02:39:59.290
Those dresses are good, sensible, serviceable dresses, without any frills or furbelows about them, and they're all you'll get this summer.

02:39:59.290 --> 02:40:16.290
The brown gingham and the blue print will do you for school when you begin to go. The sateen is for church and Sunday school. I'll expect you to keep them neat and clean, and not to tear them. I should think you'd be grateful to get most anything after those skimpy, wincey things you've been wearing.'

02:40:17.450 --> 02:40:35.990
"'Oh, I am grateful,' protested Anne. But I'd be ever so much gratefuler if—if you'd made just one of them with puffed sleeves. Puffed sleeves are so fashionable now. It would give me such a thrill, Marilla, just to wear a dress with puffed sleeves.'

02:40:35.990 --> 02:40:46.990
"'Well, you'll have to do without your thrill. I hadn't any material to waste on puffed sleeves. I think they are ridiculous-looking things anyhow. I prefer the plain, sensible ones.'

02:40:48.350 --> 02:40:57.290
"'But I'd rather look ridiculous when everybody else does, than plain and sensible all by myself,' persisted Anne mournfully.

02:40:58.870 --> 02:41:15.490
"'Trust you for that. Well, hang those dresses carefully up in your closet, and then sit down and learn the Sunday school lesson. I got a quarterly from Mr. Bell for you, and you'll go to Sunday school tomorrow,' said Marilla, disappearing downstairs in high-dudgeon.

02:41:16.650 --> 02:41:20.330
Anne clasped her hands, and looked at the dresses.

02:41:21.870 --> 02:41:27.630
"'I did hope there would be a white one with puffed sleeves,' she whispered disconsolately.

02:41:28.610 --> 02:41:49.630
"'I prayed for one, but I didn't much expect it on that account. I didn't suppose God would have time to bother about a little orphan girl's dress. I knew I'd just have to depend on Marilla for it. Well, fortunately, I can imagine that one of them is of snow-white muslin, with lovely lace frills, and three puffed sleeves.'

02:41:50.630 --> 02:41:56.730
The next morning warnings of a sick headache prevented Marilla from going to Sunday school with Anne.

02:41:57.970 --> 02:42:02.150
"'You'll have to go down and call for Mrs. Lind, Anne,' she said.

02:42:02.750 --> 02:42:12.750
"'She'll see that you get into the right class. Now, mind you behave yourself properly. Stay to preaching afterwards, and ask Mrs. Lind to show you our pew.

02:42:13.990 --> 02:42:21.750
"'Here's a scent for collection. Don't stare at people, and don't fidget. I shall expect you to tell me the text when you come home.'

02:42:22.950 --> 02:42:40.010
Anne started off irreproachable, arrayed in the stiff black-and-white sateen, which, while decent as regards length, and certainly not open to the charge of skimpiness, contrived to emphasize every corner and angle of her thin figure.

02:42:40.010 --> 02:42:53.190
Her hat was a little flat glossy new sailor, the extreme plainness of which had likewise much disappointed Anne, who had permitted herself secret visions of ribbon and flowers.

02:42:54.450 --> 02:43:10.990
The latter, however, were supplied before Anne reached the main road, for being confronted half-way down the lane with a golden frenzy of wind-stirred buttercups and a glory of wild roses, Anne promptly and liberally garlanded her hat with a heavy wreath of them.

02:43:12.030 --> 02:43:23.710
Whatever other people might have thought of the result, it satisfied Anne, and she tripped gaily down the road, holding her ruddy head with its decoration of pink and yellow very proudly.

02:43:26.190 --> 02:43:49.250
When she had reached Mrs. Lynde's house, she found that lady gone. Nothing daunted, Anne proceeded onward to the church alone. In the porch she found a crowd of little girls, all more or less gaily attired in whites and blues and pinks, and all staring with curious eyes at this stranger in their midst with her extraordinary head-adornment.

02:43:50.530 --> 02:44:05.130
Avonlea little girls had already heard queer stories about Anne. Mrs. Lynde said she had an awful temper. Jerry Bote, the hired boy at Green Gables, said she talked all the time to herself or to the trees and flowers like a crazy girl.

02:44:06.190 --> 02:44:19.590
They looked at her and whispered to each other behind their quarterlies. Nobody made any friendly advances, then or later on, when the opening exercises were over, and Anne found herself in Miss Rogerson's class.

02:44:22.050 --> 02:44:37.610
Miss Rogerson was a middle-aged lady who had taught a Sunday-school class for twenty years. Her method of teaching was to ask the printed questions from the quarterly, and look sternly over its edge at the particular little girl she thought ought to answer the question.

02:44:38.810 --> 02:44:50.390
She looked very often at Anne, and Anne, thanks to Marilla's drilling, answered promptly, but it may be questioned if she understood very much about either question or answer.

02:44:51.950 --> 02:45:04.230
She did not think she liked Miss Rogerson, and she felt very miserable. Every other little girl in the class had puffed sleeves. Anne felt that life was really not worth living without puffed sleeves.

02:45:06.370 --> 02:45:18.690
Well, how did you like Sunday-school? Marilla wanted to know when Anne came home. Her wreath having faded, Anne had discarded it in the lane, so Marilla was spared the knowledge of that for a time.

02:45:19.810 --> 02:45:22.390
I didn't like it a bit. It was horrid.

02:45:23.930 --> 02:45:35.990
Anne, surely! said Marilla, rebukingly. Anne sat down on the rocker with a long sigh, kissed one of Bonnie's leaves, and waved her hand to a blossoming fuchsia.

02:45:37.290 --> 02:45:57.850
They might have been lonesome while I was away, she explained. And now, about the Sunday-school. I behaved well, just as you told me. Mrs. Lynde was gone, but I went right on myself. I went into the church, with a lot of other little girls, and I sat in the corner of a pew by the window while the opening exercises went on.

02:45:59.190 --> 02:46:14.110
Mr. Bell made an awfully long prayer. I would have been dreadfully tired before he got through, if I hadn't been sitting by that window. But it looked right out on the lake of shining waters. So I just gazed at that, and imagined all sorts of splendid things.

02:46:15.470 --> 02:46:19.750
You shouldn't have done anything of the sort. You should have listened to Mr. Bell.

02:46:21.550 --> 02:46:49.630
But he wasn't talking to me, protested Anne. He was talking to God, and he didn't seem to be very much interested in it either. I think he thought God was too far off, though. There was a long row of white birches hanging over the lake, and the sunshine fell down through them, way, way down, deep into the water. Oh, Marilla, it was like a beautiful dream. It gave me a thrill, and I just said, Thank you for it, God.

02:46:49.750 --> 02:46:51.430
Two or three times.

02:46:52.630 --> 02:46:55.670
Not out loud, I hope, said Marilla anxiously.

02:46:56.510 --> 02:47:09.110
Oh, no, just under my breath. Well, Mr. Bell did get through at last, and they told me to go into the classroom with Miss Rogerson's class. There were nine other girls in it. They all had puffed sleeves.

02:47:10.110 --> 02:47:24.050
I tried to imagine mine were puffed, too, but I couldn't. Why couldn't I? It was as easy as could be to imagine they were puffed while I was alone in the East Gable, but it was awfully hard there among the others, who had really truly puffs.

02:47:25.290 --> 02:47:32.010
You shouldn't have been thinking about your sleeves in Sunday school. You should have been attending to the lesson. I hope you knew it.

02:47:32.670 --> 02:47:45.870
Oh, yes, and they answered a lot of questions. Miss Rogerson asked ever so many. I don't think it was fair for her to do all the asking. There were lots I wanted to ask her, but I didn't like to, because I didn't think she was a kindred spirit.

02:47:47.530 --> 02:47:55.510
Then all the other little girls recited a paraphrase. She asked me if I knew any. I told her I didn't, but I could recite—

02:47:55.510 --> 02:48:06.930
The dog at his master's grave, if she liked. That's in the Third Royal Reader. It isn't a really truly religious piece of poetry, but it's so sad and melancholy that it might as well be.

02:48:06.930 --> 02:48:19.370
She said it wouldn't do, and she told me to learn the nineteenth paraphrase for next Sunday. I read it over in church afterwards, and it's splendid. There are two lines in particular that just thrill me.

02:48:20.670 --> 02:48:25.010
Quick as the slaughtered squadrons fell in Midian's evil day.

02:48:26.170 --> 02:48:35.750
I don't know what squadrons means, nor Midian either, but it sounds so tragical. I can hardly wait until next Sunday to recite it. I'll practise it all the week.

02:48:36.970 --> 02:48:52.270
After Sunday school I asked Miss Rogerson, because Mrs. Lynde was too far away, to show me to your pew. I sat just as still as I could, and the text was Revelations, third chapter, second and third verses. It was a very long text.

02:48:53.290 --> 02:49:04.670
If I was a minister, I'd pick the short snappy ones. The sermon was awfully long, too. I suppose the minister had to match it to the text. I don't think he was a bit interesting.

02:49:05.210 --> 02:49:15.110
The trouble with him seems to be that he hasn't enough imagination. I didn't listen to him very much. I just let my thoughts run, and I thought of the most surprising things.

02:49:16.350 --> 02:49:36.330
Marilla felt helplessly that all this should be sternly reproved, but she was hampered by the undeniable fact that some of the things Anne had said, especially about the minister's sermons and Mr. Bell's prayers, were what she herself had really thought deep down in her heart for years, but had never given expression to.

02:49:36.330 --> 02:49:50.130
It almost seemed to her that those secret, unuttered, critical thoughts had suddenly taken visible and accusing shape and form in the person of this outspoken morsel of neglected humanity.

02:50:19.350 --> 02:50:22.110
A Solemn Vow and Promise.

02:50:23.610 --> 02:50:28.710
It was not until the next Friday that Marilla heard the story of the flower-wreathed hat.

02:50:29.450 --> 02:50:33.410
She came home from Mrs. Lynde's and called Anne to account.

02:50:34.410 --> 02:50:39.230
Anne, Mrs. Rachel says that you went to church last Sunday with your hat

02:50:39.230 --> 02:50:42.430
rigged out ridiculous with roses and buttercups.

02:50:43.090 --> 02:50:45.490
What on earth put you up to such a caper?

02:50:45.730 --> 02:50:48.090
A pretty-looking object you must have been.

02:50:48.790 --> 02:50:53.390
Oh, I know, pink and yellow aren't becoming to me, began Anne.

02:50:54.290 --> 02:50:58.330
Becoming of fiddlesticks! It was putting flowers on your hat at all,

02:50:58.370 --> 02:51:01.150
no matter what color they are, that was ridiculous.

02:51:01.810 --> 02:51:03.870
You are the most aggravating child.

02:51:05.170 --> 02:51:09.970
I don't see why it's any more ridiculous to wear flowers on your hat than on your dress,

02:51:10.290 --> 02:51:11.140
protested Anne.

02:51:11.730 --> 02:51:14.650
Lots of little girls there had bouquets pinned on their dresses.

02:51:15.230 --> 02:51:16.230
What's the difference?

02:51:17.550 --> 02:51:23.710
Marilla was not to be drawn from the safe concrete into dubious paths of the abstract.

02:51:24.910 --> 02:51:26.870
Don't answer me back like that, Anne.

02:51:27.310 --> 02:51:29.790
It was very silly of you to do such a thing.

02:51:30.410 --> 02:51:32.630
Never let me catch you at such a trick again.

02:51:33.470 --> 02:51:37.250
Mrs. Rachel says she thought she would sink through the floor when she saw you come in,

02:51:37.450 --> 02:51:38.930
all rigged out like that.

02:51:39.410 --> 02:51:42.810
She couldn't get near enough to tell you to take them off till it was too late.

02:51:43.470 --> 02:51:45.930
She says people talked about it something dreadful.

02:51:46.230 --> 02:51:50.490
Of course they would think I had no better sense than to let you go decked out like that.

02:51:51.810 --> 02:51:56.930
Oh, I'm so sorry, said Anne, tears welling into her eyes.

02:51:57.390 --> 02:51:59.010
I never thought you'd mind.

02:51:59.570 --> 02:52:02.370
The roses and buttercups were so sweet and pretty.

02:52:02.830 --> 02:52:04.850
I thought they'd look lovely on my hat.

02:52:05.670 --> 02:52:08.830
Lots of the little girls had artificial flowers on their hats.

02:52:09.650 --> 02:52:12.410
I'm afraid I'm going to be a dreadful trial to you.

02:52:13.010 --> 02:52:15.090
Maybe you'd better send me back to the asylum.

02:52:15.090 --> 02:52:16.770
That would be terrible.

02:52:17.450 --> 02:52:19.070
I don't think I could endure it.

02:52:19.150 --> 02:52:21.030
Most likely I would go into consumption.

02:52:21.670 --> 02:52:23.470
I'm so thin as it is, you see.

02:52:24.050 --> 02:52:26.390
But that would be better than being a trial to you.

02:52:27.330 --> 02:52:31.810
Nonsense, said Marilla, vexed at herself for having made the child cry.

02:52:32.330 --> 02:52:35.370
I don't want to send you back to the asylum, I'm sure.

02:52:36.090 --> 02:52:40.510
All I want is that you should behave like other little girls and not make yourself ridiculous.

02:52:41.450 --> 02:52:42.790
Don't cry any more.

02:52:43.130 --> 02:52:44.650
I've got some news for you.

02:52:44.650 --> 02:52:47.310
Diana Barry came home this afternoon.

02:52:48.010 --> 02:52:51.250
I'm going up to see if I can borrow a skirt pattern from Mrs. Barry.

02:52:51.850 --> 02:52:55.190
And if you like, you can come with me and get acquainted with Diana.

02:52:56.690 --> 02:53:02.110
Anne rose to her feet with clasped hands, the tears still glistening on her cheeks.

02:53:02.630 --> 02:53:06.670
The dish towel she had been hemming slipped unheated to the floor.

02:53:07.590 --> 02:53:09.930
Oh, Marilla, I'm frightened.

02:53:10.310 --> 02:53:12.490
Now that it has come, I'm actually frightened.

02:53:13.070 --> 02:53:14.630
What if she shouldn't like me?

02:53:14.650 --> 02:53:18.250
It would be the most tragic disappointment of my life.

02:53:19.830 --> 02:53:21.730
Now, don't get into a fluster.

02:53:22.210 --> 02:53:24.770
And I do wish you wouldn't use such long words.

02:53:25.250 --> 02:53:27.090
It sounds so funny in a little girl.

02:53:27.790 --> 02:53:29.870
I guess Diana will like you well enough.

02:53:30.530 --> 02:53:32.190
It's your mother you've got to reckon with.

02:53:32.530 --> 02:53:35.750
If she doesn't like you, it won't matter how much Diana does.

02:53:36.570 --> 02:53:39.270
If she has heard about your outburst, Mrs. Lind,

02:53:39.730 --> 02:53:41.790
and going to church with buttercups around your hat,

02:53:42.190 --> 02:53:43.810
I don't know what she'll think of you.

02:53:43.810 --> 02:53:48.910
You must be polite and well behaved, and don't make any of your startling speeches.

02:53:49.690 --> 02:53:52.190
For pity's sake, if the child isn't actually trembling.

02:53:53.390 --> 02:53:54.630
Anne was trembling.

02:53:55.430 --> 02:53:57.330
Her face was pale and tense.

02:53:57.990 --> 02:54:00.650
Oh, Marilla, you'd be excited, too.

02:54:00.990 --> 02:54:04.610
If you were going to meet a little girl, you hoped to be your bosom friend,

02:54:05.070 --> 02:54:09.650
and whose mother mightn't like you, she said, as she hastened to get her hat.

02:54:10.250 --> 02:54:14.390
They went over to Orchard Slope by the short cut across the brook

02:54:14.390 --> 02:54:15.990
and up the furry hill grove.

02:54:17.130 --> 02:54:20.390
Mrs. Barry came to the kitchen door and answered to Marilla's knock.

02:54:21.110 --> 02:54:26.470
She was a tall, black-haired woman with a very resolute mouth.

02:54:27.170 --> 02:54:30.370
She had the reputation of being very strict with her children.

02:54:31.230 --> 02:54:33.030
How do you do, Marilla?

02:54:33.470 --> 02:54:34.670
She said cordially.

02:54:35.150 --> 02:54:35.810
Come in.

02:54:36.410 --> 02:54:39.130
And this is the little girl you have adopted, I suppose.

02:54:40.210 --> 02:54:43.470
Yes, this is Anne Shirley, said Marilla.

02:54:44.230 --> 02:54:49.310
Spelled with an E, gasped Anne, who, tremulous and excited as she was,

02:54:49.710 --> 02:54:53.670
was determined there should be no misunderstanding on that important point.

02:54:54.810 --> 02:54:59.830
Mrs. Barry, not hearing or not comprehending, merely shook hands and said kindly,

02:55:00.390 --> 02:55:01.330
How are you?

02:55:02.050 --> 02:55:05.090
I am well in body, although considerable rumpled up in spirit.

02:55:05.250 --> 02:55:07.470
Thank you, ma'am, said Anne gravely.

02:55:07.470 --> 02:55:10.750
Then, aside to Marilla, in an audible whisper,

02:55:11.270 --> 02:55:13.970
There wasn't anything startling in that, was there, Marilla?

02:55:15.490 --> 02:55:20.150
Diana was sitting on the sofa, reading a book which she dropped when the callers entered.

02:55:20.870 --> 02:55:25.050
She was a very pretty little girl, with her mother's black eyes and hair

02:55:25.050 --> 02:55:30.190
and her rosy cheeks and the merry expression which was her inheritance from her father.

02:55:31.410 --> 02:55:34.610
This is my little girl, Diana, said Mrs. Barry.

02:55:35.270 --> 02:55:39.310
Diana, you might take Anne out into the garden and show her your flowers.

02:55:39.970 --> 02:55:43.310
It will be better for you than straining your eyes over that book.

02:55:44.150 --> 02:55:46.290
She reads entirely too much.

02:55:46.850 --> 02:55:49.170
This to Marilla as the little girls went out.

02:55:49.630 --> 02:55:52.870
And I can't prevent her, for her father aids and abets her.

02:55:53.350 --> 02:55:55.250
She's always pouring over a book.

02:55:55.830 --> 02:55:57.870
I'm glad she has the prospect of a playmate.

02:55:58.370 --> 02:56:00.470
Perhaps it will take her more out of doors.

02:56:01.550 --> 02:56:09.050
Outside, in the garden, which was full of mellow sunset light streaming through the dark old firs to the west of it,

02:56:09.610 --> 02:56:15.990
stood Anne and Diana, gazing bashfully at each other over a clump of gorgeous tiger lilies.

02:56:16.890 --> 02:56:20.310
The Barry garden was a bowery wilderness of flowers,

02:56:20.790 --> 02:56:25.190
which would have delighted Anne's heart at any time, less fraught with destiny.

02:56:25.970 --> 02:56:30.090
It was encircled by huge old willows and tall firs,

02:56:30.090 --> 02:56:33.530
beneath which flourished flowers that loved the shade.

02:56:34.490 --> 02:56:40.930
Prim, right-angled paths, neatly bordered with clamshells, intersected it like moist red ribbons,

02:56:41.290 --> 02:56:44.650
and in the beds between old-fashioned flowers ran riot.

02:56:45.510 --> 02:56:49.450
There were rosy bleeding hearts and great splendid crimson peonies,

02:56:50.370 --> 02:56:54.390
white fragrant narcissi and thorny sweet scotch roses,

02:56:54.830 --> 02:56:59.850
pink and blue and white columbines and lilac-tinted bouncing bets.

02:57:00.090 --> 02:57:06.270
Clumps of southern wood and ribbon grass and mint, purple Adam and Eve daffodils,

02:57:06.790 --> 02:57:12.150
and masses of sweet clover, white with its delicate fragrant feathery sprays.

02:57:13.210 --> 02:57:17.930
Scarlet lightning that shot its fiery lances over prim white musk flowers.

02:57:18.830 --> 02:57:26.030
A garden it was where sunshine lingered and bees hummed and winds beguiled into loitering,

02:57:26.310 --> 02:57:27.610
purred and rustled.

02:57:28.690 --> 02:57:35.030
Oh, Diana, said Anne at last, clasping her hands and speaking almost in a whisper.

02:57:35.810 --> 02:57:40.310
Oh, do you think you can like me a little, enough to be my bosom friend?

02:57:41.230 --> 02:57:42.270
Diana laughed.

02:57:42.890 --> 02:57:45.110
Diana always laughed before she spoke.

02:57:45.930 --> 02:57:48.310
Why, I guess so, she said frankly.

02:57:48.690 --> 02:57:51.330
I'm awfully glad you've come to live at Green Gables.

02:57:51.870 --> 02:57:54.290
It will be jolly to have somebody to play with.

02:57:54.810 --> 02:57:57.590
There isn't any other girl who lives near enough to play with.

02:57:57.610 --> 02:57:59.590
And I have no sisters big enough.

02:58:00.830 --> 02:58:05.130
Will you swear to be my friend forever and ever? demanded Anne eagerly.

02:58:06.510 --> 02:58:07.650
Diana looked shocked.

02:58:08.610 --> 02:58:12.570
Why, it's dreadfully wicked to swear, she said rebukingly.

02:58:13.610 --> 02:58:15.970
Oh, no, not my kind of swearing.

02:58:16.270 --> 02:58:17.790
There are two kinds, you know.

02:58:18.890 --> 02:58:22.710
I never heard of but one kind, said Diana doubtfully.

02:58:23.570 --> 02:58:24.710
There really is another.

02:58:25.250 --> 02:58:26.730
Oh, it isn't wicked at all.

02:58:26.730 --> 02:58:30.090
It just means vowing and promising solemnly.

02:58:31.190 --> 02:58:35.210
Well, I don't mind doing that, agreed Diana, relieved.

02:58:35.650 --> 02:58:36.710
How do you do it?

02:58:37.710 --> 02:58:41.730
We must join hands, so, said Anne gravely.

02:58:42.330 --> 02:58:43.950
It ought to be over running water.

02:58:44.570 --> 02:58:47.030
We'll just imagine this path is running water.

02:58:47.650 --> 02:58:49.410
I'll repeat the oath first.

02:58:50.290 --> 02:58:55.150
I solemnly swear to be faithful to my bosom friend, Diana Berry,

02:58:55.150 --> 02:58:58.870
as long as the sun and moon shall endure.

02:58:59.910 --> 02:59:02.050
Now you say it and put my name in.

02:59:03.050 --> 02:59:06.730
Diana repeated the oath with a laugh for and aft.

02:59:07.350 --> 02:59:10.750
Then she said, You're a queer girl, Anne.

02:59:11.070 --> 02:59:12.810
I heard before that you were queer,

02:59:13.290 --> 02:59:15.870
but I believe I'm going to like you real well.

02:59:17.270 --> 02:59:22.490
When Marilla and Anne went home, Diana went with them as far as the log bridge.

02:59:22.490 --> 02:59:26.030
The two little girls walked with their arms about each other.

02:59:26.750 --> 02:59:31.270
At the brook, they parted with many promises to spend the next afternoon together.

02:59:32.330 --> 02:59:35.510
Well, did you find Diana a kindred spirit?

02:59:35.890 --> 02:59:39.590
asked Marilla as they went up through the garden of Green Gables.

02:59:40.630 --> 02:59:47.570
Oh, yes, sighed Anne, blissfully unconscious of any sarcasm on Marilla's part.

02:59:48.110 --> 02:59:52.970
Oh, Marilla, I'm the happiest girl on Prince Edward Island this very moment.

02:59:53.590 --> 02:59:57.890
I assure you all say my prayers with a right goodwill tonight.

02:59:58.870 --> 03:00:03.330
Diana and I are going to build a playhouse in Mr. William Bell's birch grove tomorrow.

03:00:04.230 --> 03:00:07.530
Can I have those broken pieces of china that are out in the woodshed?

03:00:08.130 --> 03:00:11.490
Diana's birthday is in February and mine is in March.

03:00:12.010 --> 03:00:14.310
Don't you think that is a very strange coincidence?

03:00:14.990 --> 03:00:16.930
Diana is going to lend me a book to read.

03:00:16.930 --> 03:00:20.470
She says it's perfectly splendid and tremendously exciting.

03:00:21.150 --> 03:00:24.890
She's going to show me a place back in the woods where rice lilies grow.

03:00:25.710 --> 03:00:28.810
Don't you think Diana has got very soulful eyes?

03:00:29.410 --> 03:00:31.550
I wish I had soulful eyes.

03:00:32.230 --> 03:00:36.370
Diana is going to teach me to sing a song called Nelly in the Hazel Dell.

03:00:37.030 --> 03:00:39.370
She's going to give me a picture to put up in my room.

03:00:39.690 --> 03:00:42.270
It's a perfectly beautiful picture, she says.

03:00:42.670 --> 03:00:45.330
A lovely lady in a pale blue silk dress.

03:00:45.330 --> 03:00:48.210
A sewing machine agent gave it to her.

03:00:48.970 --> 03:00:50.690
I wish I had something to give Diana.

03:00:51.450 --> 03:00:55.150
I'm an inch taller than Diana but she is ever so much fatter.

03:00:55.670 --> 03:00:58.650
She says she'd like to be thin because it's so much more graceful

03:00:58.650 --> 03:01:01.530
but I'm afraid she only said it to soothe my feelings.

03:01:02.390 --> 03:01:04.790
We're going to the shore some day to gather shells.

03:01:05.330 --> 03:01:09.390
We've agreed to call the spring down by the log bridge the Dryad's Bubble.

03:01:10.110 --> 03:01:12.290
Isn't that a perfectly elegant name?

03:01:12.770 --> 03:01:15.310
I've read a story once about a spring called that.

03:01:15.330 --> 03:01:18.770
A Dryad is sort of a grown-up fairy, I think.

03:01:20.190 --> 03:01:25.070
Well, all I hope is you won't talk Diana to death, said Marilla.

03:01:25.650 --> 03:01:28.090
But remember this in all your planning, Anne.

03:01:28.430 --> 03:01:31.310
You're not going to play all the time, nor most of it.

03:01:31.670 --> 03:01:34.950
You have your work to do and it'll have to be done first.

03:01:36.330 --> 03:01:40.830
Anne's cup of happiness was full and Matthew caused it to overflow.

03:01:41.710 --> 03:01:44.890
He had just got home from a trip to the store at Carmody

03:01:44.890 --> 03:01:48.510
and he sheepishly produced a small parcel from his pocket

03:01:48.510 --> 03:01:53.030
and handed it to Anne with a deprecatory look at Marilla.

03:01:54.150 --> 03:01:58.830
I heard you say you liked chocolate sweeties so I got you some, he said.

03:02:00.070 --> 03:02:01.550
Hmph! sniffed Marilla.

03:02:02.130 --> 03:02:03.850
It'll ruin her teeth and stomach.

03:02:04.830 --> 03:02:06.750
There, there, child, don't look so dismal.

03:02:06.750 --> 03:02:09.470
You can eat those since Matthew has gone and got them.

03:02:10.010 --> 03:02:11.730
He'd better have brought you peppermints.

03:02:12.110 --> 03:02:12.970
They're wholesomer.

03:02:12.970 --> 03:02:16.050
Don't sicken yourself eating all them at once now.

03:02:17.150 --> 03:02:20.190
Oh no, indeed, I won't, said Anne eagerly.

03:02:20.650 --> 03:02:25.710
I'll just eat one tonight, Marilla, and I can give Diana half of them, can't I?

03:02:26.190 --> 03:02:30.230
The other half will taste twice as sweet to me if I give some to her.

03:02:30.910 --> 03:02:33.370
It's delightful to think I have something to give her.

03:02:34.590 --> 03:02:38.870
I will say it for the child, said Marilla when Anne had gone to her gable.

03:02:39.510 --> 03:02:40.930
She isn't stingy.

03:02:40.930 --> 03:02:45.350
I'm glad, for of all faults I detest stinginess in a child.

03:02:46.290 --> 03:02:51.450
Dear me, it's only three weeks since she came, and it seems as if she'd been here always.

03:02:51.990 --> 03:02:54.170
I can't imagine the place without her.

03:02:54.670 --> 03:02:56.930
Now, don't be looking I told you so, Matthew.

03:02:57.410 --> 03:03:01.010
That's bad enough in a woman, but it isn't to be endured in a man.

03:03:01.590 --> 03:03:05.570
I'm perfectly willing to own up that I'm glad I consented to keep the child

03:03:05.570 --> 03:03:07.310
and that I'm getting fond of her.

03:03:07.590 --> 03:03:09.690
But don't you rub it in, Matthew Cuthbert.

03:03:37.130 --> 03:03:39.790
The Delights of Anticipation.

03:03:41.170 --> 03:03:50.810
It's time Anne was in to do her sewing, said Marilla, glancing at the clock and then out into the yellow August afternoon, where everything drowsed in the heat.

03:03:51.450 --> 03:03:59.190
She stayed playing with Diana more than half an hour more than I gave her leave to, and now she's perched out there on the woodpile talking to Matthew,

03:03:59.190 --> 03:04:07.210
19 to the dozen, when she knows perfectly well she ought to be at her work. And of course he's listening to her like a perfect ninny.

03:04:07.910 --> 03:04:16.090
I never saw such an infatuated man. The more she talks and the odder the things she says, the more he's delighted evidently.

03:04:16.770 --> 03:04:19.790
Anne Shirley, you come right in here this minute, do you hear me?

03:04:19.790 --> 03:04:33.910
A series of staccato taps on the west window brought Anne flying in from the yard, eyes shining, cheeks faintly flushed with pink, unbraided hair streaming behind her in a torrent of brightness.

03:04:34.590 --> 03:04:45.550
Oh, Marilla, she exclaimed breathlessly, there's going to be a Sunday School Picnic next week in Mr. Harmon Andrews's field, right near the Lake of Shining Waters,

03:04:46.030 --> 03:04:56.210
and Mrs. Superintendent Bell and Mrs. Rachel Linder going to make ice cream. Think of it, Marilla, ice cream! And, oh, Marilla, can I go to it?

03:04:57.030 --> 03:05:01.830
Just look at the clock, if you please, Anne. What time did I tell you to come in?

03:05:02.590 --> 03:05:14.070
Two o'clock. But isn't it splendid about the picnic, Marilla? Please can I go? Oh, I've never been to a picnic. I've dreamed of picnics, but I've never...

03:05:14.810 --> 03:05:22.730
Yes, I told you to come at two o'clock, and it's a quarter to three. I'd like to know why you didn't obey me, Anne.

03:05:23.690 --> 03:05:34.790
Why, I meant to, Marilla, as much as could be. But you have no idea how fascinating Idlewild is. And then, of course, I had to tell Matthew about the picnic.

03:05:35.450 --> 03:05:39.870
Matthew is such a sympathetic listener. Please can I go?

03:05:40.550 --> 03:05:50.330
You'll have to learn to resist the fascination of Idlewhateveryoucallit. When I tell you to come in at a certain time, I mean that time and not half an hour later,

03:05:50.330 --> 03:05:54.910
and you needn't stop to discourse with sympathetic listeners on your way, either.

03:05:55.710 --> 03:06:03.410
As for the picnic, of course you can go. You're a Sunday school scholar, and it's not likely I'd refuse to let you go when all the other little girls are going.

03:06:04.370 --> 03:06:11.310
But, but, faltered Anne, Diana says that everybody must take a basket of things to eat.

03:06:11.310 --> 03:06:23.710
I can't cook, as you know, Marilla, and, and I don't mind going a picnic without puffed sleeves so much, but I'd feel terribly humiliated if I had to go without a basket.

03:06:24.210 --> 03:06:27.650
It's been preying on my mind ever since Diana told me.

03:06:28.730 --> 03:06:32.630
Well, it needn't pray any longer. I'll bake you a basket.

03:06:33.570 --> 03:06:40.530
Oh, you dear good Marilla. Oh, you are so kind to me. Oh, I'm so much obliged to you.

03:06:40.530 --> 03:06:48.430
Getting through with her ohs, Anne cast herself into Marilla's arms and rapturously kissed her sallow cheek.

03:06:49.030 --> 03:06:54.670
It was the first time in her whole life that childish lips had voluntarily touched Marilla's face.

03:06:55.430 --> 03:06:59.570
Again, that sudden sensation of startling sweetness thrilled her.

03:07:00.070 --> 03:07:07.190
She was secretly vastly pleased at Anne's impulsive caress, which was probably the reason why she said brusquely,

03:07:07.690 --> 03:07:13.110
There, there, never mind your kissing nonsense. I'd sooner see you doing strictly as you're told.

03:07:13.910 --> 03:07:18.130
As for cooking, I mean to begin giving you lessons in that sum of these days.

03:07:18.730 --> 03:07:24.710
But you're so feather-brained, Anne, I've been waiting to see if you'd sober down a little and learn to be steady before I begin.

03:07:25.410 --> 03:07:31.670
You've got to keep your wits about you in cooking, and not stop in the middle of things to let your thoughts rove all over creation.

03:07:31.670 --> 03:07:36.350
Now, get out your patchwork and have your square done before tea time.

03:07:37.510 --> 03:07:47.310
I do not like patchwork, said Anne dolefully, hunting out her work basket and sitting down before a little heap of red and white diamonds with a sigh.

03:07:48.290 --> 03:07:54.390
I think some kinds of sewing would be nice, but there's no scope for imagination in patchwork.

03:07:54.850 --> 03:07:58.530
It's just one little seam after another and you never seem to be getting anywhere.

03:07:59.090 --> 03:08:05.750
But of course, I'd rather be Anne of Green Gables sewing patchwork than Anne of any other place with nothing to do but play.

03:08:06.750 --> 03:08:11.070
I wish time went as quick sewing patches as it does when I'm playing with Diana, though.

03:08:11.850 --> 03:08:19.590
Oh, we do have such elegant times, Marilla. I have to furnish most of the imagination, but I'm well able to do that.

03:08:20.190 --> 03:08:22.890
Diana is simply perfect in every other way.

03:08:23.470 --> 03:08:28.170
You know that little piece of land across the brook that runs up between our farm and Mr. Berry's?

03:08:28.170 --> 03:08:37.370
It belongs to Mr. William Bell, and right in the corner there's a little ring of white birch trees, the most romantic spot, Marilla.

03:08:37.970 --> 03:08:41.190
Diana and I have our playhouse there. We call it Idlewild.

03:08:42.190 --> 03:08:47.490
Isn't that a poetical name? I assure you it took me some time to think it out.

03:08:47.890 --> 03:08:50.810
I stayed awake nearly a whole night before I invented it.

03:08:51.290 --> 03:08:56.030
Then, just as I was dropping off to sleep, it came, like an inspiration.

03:08:57.010 --> 03:08:59.970
Diana was enraptured when she heard it.

03:09:00.390 --> 03:09:05.270
We have got our house fixed up elegantly. You must come and see it, Marilla, won't you?

03:09:05.850 --> 03:09:12.390
We have great big stones all covered with moss for seats and boards from tree to tree for shelves.

03:09:12.650 --> 03:09:19.150
And we have our dishes on them. Of course they're all broken, but it's the easiest thing in the world to imagine that they are whole.

03:09:19.150 --> 03:09:25.970
There's a piece of a plate with a spray of red and yellow ivy on it that is especially beautiful.

03:09:26.710 --> 03:09:30.430
We keep it in the parlor, and we have the fairy glass there, too.

03:09:30.910 --> 03:09:33.750
The fairy glass is as lovely as a dream.

03:09:34.590 --> 03:09:37.350
Diana found it out in the woods behind their chicken house.

03:09:37.870 --> 03:09:42.790
It's all full of rainbows, just little young rainbows that haven't grown big yet.

03:09:43.390 --> 03:09:47.850
And Diana's mother told her it was broken off a hanging lamp they once had.

03:09:47.850 --> 03:09:54.230
But it's nice to imagine the fairies lost it one night when they had a ball, so we call it the fairy glass.

03:09:55.250 --> 03:09:56.950
Matthew is going to make us a table.

03:09:57.730 --> 03:10:02.610
Oh, we have named that little round pool over in Mr. Berry's field Willowmere.

03:10:03.070 --> 03:10:05.550
I got that name out of a book Diana lent me.

03:10:05.890 --> 03:10:10.130
That was a thrilling book, Marilla. The heroine had five lovers.

03:10:10.610 --> 03:10:12.870
I'd be satisfied with one, wouldn't you?

03:10:13.570 --> 03:10:16.810
She was very handsome, and she went through great tribulations.

03:10:16.810 --> 03:10:19.170
She could faint as easy as anything.

03:10:19.910 --> 03:10:22.970
I'd love to be able to faint, wouldn't you, Marilla?

03:10:23.350 --> 03:10:24.910
It's so romantic.

03:10:25.530 --> 03:10:28.230
But I'm really very healthy for all I'm so thin.

03:10:28.910 --> 03:10:31.590
I believe I'm getting fatter, though. Don't you think I am?

03:10:32.110 --> 03:10:36.030
I look at my elbows every morning when I get up to see if any dimples are coming.

03:10:37.070 --> 03:10:40.450
Diana is having a new dress made with elbow sleeves.

03:10:40.850 --> 03:10:42.470
She's going to wear it to the picnic.

03:10:43.190 --> 03:10:46.750
Oh, I do hope it will be fine next Wednesday.

03:10:47.390 --> 03:10:50.930
I don't feel that I can endure the disappointment if anything happened

03:10:50.930 --> 03:10:53.010
to prevent me from getting to the picnic.

03:10:53.790 --> 03:10:57.710
I suppose I'd live through it, but I'm certain it would be a lifelong sorrow.

03:10:58.850 --> 03:11:02.150
It wouldn't matter if I got to a hundred picnics in after years.

03:11:02.490 --> 03:11:04.810
They wouldn't make up for missing this one.

03:11:05.510 --> 03:11:10.390
They're going to have boats on the Lake of Shining Waters and ice cream, as I told you.

03:11:10.390 --> 03:11:12.790
I have never tasted ice cream.

03:11:13.510 --> 03:11:15.330
Diana tried to explain what it was like,

03:11:15.710 --> 03:11:19.350
but I guess ice cream is one of those things that are beyond imagination.

03:11:21.090 --> 03:11:25.670
Anne, you have talked even on for ten minutes by the clock, said Marilla.

03:11:26.170 --> 03:11:31.890
Now, just for curiosity's sake, see if you can hold your tongue for the same length of time.

03:11:32.850 --> 03:11:35.070
Anne held her tongue as desired,

03:11:35.070 --> 03:11:40.710
but for the rest of the week she talked picnic and thought picnic and dreamed picnic.

03:11:41.490 --> 03:11:45.950
On Saturday it rained, and she worked herself up into such a frantic state,

03:11:46.470 --> 03:11:49.290
lest it should keep on raining until and over Wednesday,

03:11:49.930 --> 03:11:54.550
that Marilla made her sew an extra patchwork square by way of steadying her nerves.

03:11:55.330 --> 03:11:59.590
On Sunday, Anne confided to Marilla on the way home from church

03:11:59.590 --> 03:12:02.950
that she actually grew cold all over with excitement

03:12:02.950 --> 03:12:05.870
when the minister announced the picnic from the pulpit.

03:12:06.830 --> 03:12:09.630
Such a thrill as went up and down my back, Marilla.

03:12:10.250 --> 03:12:14.770
I don't think I'd ever really believed until then that there was honestly going to be a picnic.

03:12:15.350 --> 03:12:17.870
I couldn't help fearing I'd only imagined it.

03:12:18.210 --> 03:12:21.970
But when a minister says a thing in the pulpit, you just have to believe it.

03:12:22.850 --> 03:12:27.050
You set your heart too much on things, Anne, said Marilla with a sigh.

03:12:27.530 --> 03:12:31.850
I'm afraid there'll be a great many disappointments in store for you through life.

03:12:32.410 --> 03:12:38.170
Oh, Marilla, looking forward to things is half the pleasure of them, exclaimed Anne.

03:12:38.770 --> 03:12:40.010
You mayn't get the things themselves,

03:12:40.850 --> 03:12:44.610
but nothing can prevent you from having the fun of looking forward to them.

03:12:45.130 --> 03:12:50.050
Mrs. Lynde says, Blessed are they who expect nothing, for they shall not be disappointed.

03:12:50.970 --> 03:12:54.690
But I think it would be worse to expect nothing than to be disappointed.

03:12:56.250 --> 03:13:00.470
Marilla wore her amethyst brooch to church that day as usual.

03:13:00.470 --> 03:13:04.050
Marilla always wore her amethyst brooch to church.

03:13:04.790 --> 03:13:07.470
She would have thought it rather sacrilegious to leave it off,

03:13:07.810 --> 03:13:10.990
as bad as forgetting her Bible or her collection dime.

03:13:11.870 --> 03:13:15.450
The amethyst brooch was Marilla's most treasured possession.

03:13:16.110 --> 03:13:21.350
A seafaring uncle had given it to her mother, who in turn had bequeathed it to Marilla.

03:13:22.070 --> 03:13:26.450
It was an old-fashioned oval containing a braid of her mother's hair,

03:13:26.450 --> 03:13:30.710
surrounded by a border of very fine amethysts.

03:13:30.930 --> 03:13:36.190
Marilla knew too little about precious stones to realize how fine the amethysts actually were,

03:13:36.630 --> 03:13:40.590
but she thought them very beautiful and was always pleasantly conscious

03:13:40.590 --> 03:13:45.650
of their violet shimmer at her throat above her good brown satin dress,

03:13:45.910 --> 03:13:48.290
even though she could not see it.

03:13:48.850 --> 03:13:53.370
Anne had been smitten with delighted admiration when she first saw that brooch.

03:13:53.890 --> 03:13:57.830
Oh, Marilla, it's a perfectly elegant brooch.

03:13:58.010 --> 03:14:01.810
I don't know how you can pay attention to the sermon or the prayers when you have it on.

03:14:02.370 --> 03:14:03.650
I couldn't, I know.

03:14:04.270 --> 03:14:06.530
I think amethysts are just sweet.

03:14:07.070 --> 03:14:09.130
They are what I used to think diamonds were like.

03:14:09.790 --> 03:14:13.670
Long ago, before I had ever seen a diamond, I read about them,

03:14:13.870 --> 03:14:16.150
and I tried to imagine what they would be like.

03:14:16.470 --> 03:14:19.790
I thought they would be lovely, glimmering purple stones.

03:14:19.790 --> 03:14:25.890
When I saw a real diamond in a lady's ring one day, I was so disappointed I cried.

03:14:26.590 --> 03:14:30.290
Of course it was very lovely, but it wasn't my idea of a diamond.

03:14:30.970 --> 03:14:33.570
Will you let me hold the brooch for one minute, Marilla?

03:14:34.270 --> 03:14:37.950
Do you think amethysts can be the soul of good violets?

03:15:07.290 --> 03:15:13.310
On the Monday evening before the picnic, Marilla came down from her room with a troubled face.

03:15:14.010 --> 03:15:26.170
Anne, she said to that small personage, who was shelling peas by the spotless table, and singing Nelly of the Hazel Dell, with a vigor and expression that did credit to Diana's teaching,

03:15:27.030 --> 03:15:35.750
did you see anything of my amethyst brooch? I thought I stuck it in my pin-cushion when I came home from church yesterday evening, but I can't find it anywhere.

03:15:37.470 --> 03:15:48.830
I saw it this afternoon, when you were away at the AIDS Society, said Anne a little slowly. I was passing your door when I saw it on the cushion, so I went in to look at it.

03:15:49.330 --> 03:15:52.990
Did you touch it? said Marilla sternly.

03:15:53.590 --> 03:15:59.830
Yes, admitted Anne. I took it up and pinned it on my breast, just to see how it would look.

03:16:00.570 --> 03:16:13.430
You had no business to do anything of the sort. It's very wrong in a little girl to meddle. You shouldn't have gone into my room in the first place and you shouldn't have touched a brooch that didn't belong to you in the second. Where did you put it?

03:16:14.310 --> 03:16:27.270
Oh, I put it back on the bureau. I hadn't it on a minute. Truly I didn't mean to meddle, Marilla. I didn't think about its being wrong to go in and try on the brooch, but I see now that it was, and I'll never do it again.

03:16:27.270 --> 03:16:32.090
That's one good thing about me. I never do the same naughty thing twice.

03:16:33.150 --> 03:16:40.030
You didn't put it back, said Marilla. That brooch isn't anywhere on the bureau. You've taken it out or something, Anne.

03:16:40.730 --> 03:16:53.490
I did put it back, said Anne quickly. Partly, Marilla thought. I don't just remember whether I stuck it on the pin cushion or laid it in the china tray, but I'm perfectly certain I put it back.

03:16:54.410 --> 03:17:04.870
I'll go and have another look, said Marilla, determining to be just. If you put that brooch back, it's still there. If it isn't, I'll know you didn't, that's all.

03:17:05.790 --> 03:17:18.030
Marilla went to her room and made a thorough search not only over the bureau, but in every other place she thought the brooch might possibly be. It was not to be found, and she returned to the kitchen.

03:17:18.990 --> 03:17:30.350
Anne, the brooch is gone. By your own admission, you were the last person to handle it. Now what have you done with it? Tell me the truth at once. Did you take it out and lose it?

03:17:30.910 --> 03:17:48.690
No, I didn't, said Anne solemnly, meeting Marilla's angry gaze squarely. I never took the brooch out of your room, and that is the truth, if I was to be led to the block for it, although I'm not very certain what a block is. So there, Marilla.

03:17:49.970 --> 03:17:57.110
Anne's so there was only intended to emphasize her assertion, but Marilla took it as a display of defiance.

03:17:57.970 --> 03:18:10.270
I believe you are telling me a falsehood, Anne, she said sharply. I know you are. There now, don't say anything more unless you are prepared to tell the whole truth. Go to your room and stay there until you are ready to confess.

03:18:11.050 --> 03:18:18.790
Will I take the peas with me? said Anne meekly. No, I'll finish shelling them myself. Do as I bid you.

03:18:20.010 --> 03:18:37.770
When Anne had gone, Marilla went about her evening tasks in a very disturbed state of mind. She was worried about her valuable brooch. What if Anne had lost it? And how wicked of the child to deny having taken it when anybody could see she must have, with such an innocent face, too.

03:18:38.450 --> 03:18:52.510
I don't know what I wouldn't sooner have had happen, thought Marilla, as she nervously shelled the peas. Of course I don't suppose she meant to steal it or anything like that. She's just taken it to play with or help along that imagination of hers.

03:18:52.510 --> 03:19:03.850
She must have taken it, that's clear, for there hasn't been a soul in that room since she was in it, by her own story, until I went up to night. And the brooch is gone, there's nothing surer.

03:19:04.470 --> 03:19:18.790
I suppose she has lost it and is afraid to own up for fear she'll be punished. It's a dreadful thing to think she tells falsehoods. It's a far worse thing than her fit of temper. It's a fearful responsibility to have a child in your house you can't trust.

03:19:19.610 --> 03:19:30.590
Slyness and untruthfulness, that's what she has displayed. I declare I feel worse about that than about the brooch. If she'd only have told the truth about it I wouldn't mind so much.

03:19:31.670 --> 03:19:48.250
Marilla went to her room at intervals all through the evening and searched for the brooch without finding it. A bedtime visit to the East Gable produced no result. Anne persisted in denying that she knew anything about the brooch, but Marilla was only the more firmly convinced that she did.

03:19:48.250 --> 03:20:00.230
She told Matthew the story the next morning. Matthew was confounded and puzzled. He could not so quickly lose faith in Anne, but he had to admit that circumstances were against her.

03:20:00.230 --> 03:20:13.250
You're sure it hasn't fell down behind the bureau? was the only suggestion he could offer. I've moved the bureau and I've taken out the drawers and I've looked in every crack and cranny, was Marilla's positive answer.

03:20:14.150 --> 03:20:22.390
The brooch is gone and that child has taken it and lied about it. That's the plain ugly truth, Matthew Cuthbert, and we might as well look it in the face.

03:20:23.270 --> 03:20:37.310
Well now, what are you going to do about it? Matthew asked forlornly, feeling secretly thankful that Marilla and not he had to deal with the situation. He felt no desire to put his oar in this time.

03:20:38.190 --> 03:20:55.150
She'll stay in her room until she confesses, said Marilla, grimly, remembering the success of this method in the former case. Then we'll see. Perhaps we'll be able to find the brooch if she'll only tell where she put it, but in any case she'll have to be severely punished, Matthew.

03:20:56.290 --> 03:21:05.570
Well now, you'll have to punish her, said Matthew, reaching for his hat. I've nothing to do with it, remember? You warned me off yourself.

03:21:06.930 --> 03:21:22.550
Marilla felt deserted by everyone. She could not even go to Mrs. Lind for advice. She went up to the East Gable with a very serious face and left it with a face more serious still. Anne steadfastly refused to confess.

03:21:22.550 --> 03:21:37.290
She persisted in asserting that she had not taken the brooch. The child had evidently been crying, and Marilla felt a pang of pity which she sternly repressed. By night she was, as she expressed it, beat out.

03:21:37.870 --> 03:21:43.550
You'll stay in this room until you confess, Anne. You can make up your mind to that, she said firmly.

03:21:44.210 --> 03:21:58.810
But the picnic is to-morrow, Marilla, cried Anne. You won't keep me away from going to that, will you? You'll just let me out for the afternoon, won't you? Then I'll stay here as long as you like afterwards, cheerfully. But I must go to the picnic.

03:21:58.810 --> 03:22:03.870
You'll not go to picnics nor anywhere else until you've confessed, Anne.

03:22:04.650 --> 03:22:10.250
Oh, Marilla, gasped Anne. But Marilla had gone out and shut the door.

03:22:11.190 --> 03:22:31.750
Wednesday morning dawned as bright and fair as if expressly made to order for the picnic. Birds sang around Green Gables. The Madonna lilies in the garden sent out whiffs of perfume that entered in on viewless winds at every door and window and wandered through halls and rooms like spirits of benediction.

03:22:31.750 --> 03:22:51.930
The birches in the hollow waved joyful hands as if watching for Anne's usual morning greeting from the East Gable. But Anne was not at her window. When Marilla took her breakfast up to her, she found the child sitting primly on her bed, pale and resolute, with tight shut lips and gleaming eyes.

03:22:52.770 --> 03:22:54.690
Marilla, I'm ready to confess.

03:22:55.650 --> 03:23:06.450
Ah! Marilla laid down her tray. Once again her method had succeeded, but her success was very bitter to her. Let me hear what you have to say then, Anne.

03:23:07.250 --> 03:23:23.530
I took the amethyst brooch, said Anne, as if repeating a lesson she had learned. I took it just as you said. I didn't mean to take it when I went in, but it did look so beautiful, Marilla, when I pinned it on my breast, that I was overcome by an irresistible temptation.

03:23:23.530 --> 03:23:37.070
I imagined how perfectly thrilling it would be to take it to Idlewild and play I was the Lady Cordelia Fitzgerald. It would be so much easier to imagine I was the Lady Cordelia if I had a real amethyst brooch on.

03:23:37.870 --> 03:23:47.150
Diana and I make necklaces of roseberries, but what are roseberries compared to amethysts? So I took the brooch. I thought I could put it back before you came home.

03:23:47.150 --> 03:24:00.090
I went all the way around by the road to lengthen out the time. When I was going over the bridge, across the Lake of Shining Waters, I took the brooch off to have another look at it. Oh, how it did shine in the sunlight!

03:24:00.690 --> 03:24:13.830
And then, when I was leaning over the bridge, it just slipped through my fingers, so, and went down, down, down, all purply sparkling, and sank forevermore beneath the Lake of Shining Waters.

03:24:13.830 --> 03:24:17.150
And that's the best I can do at confessing, Marilla.

03:24:18.310 --> 03:24:32.390
Marilla felt hot anger surge up into her heart again. This child had taken and lost her treasured amethyst brooch, and now sat there calmly reciting the details thereof, without the least apparent compunction or repentance.

03:24:33.090 --> 03:24:40.050
Anne, this is terrible, she said, trying to speak calmly. You are the very wickedest girl I ever heard of.

03:24:40.990 --> 03:24:53.850
Yes, I suppose I am, agreed Anne, tranquilly, and I know I'll have to be punished. It'll be your duty to punish me, Marilla. Won't you please get it over with right off, because I'd like to go to the picnic with nothing on my mind.

03:24:54.910 --> 03:25:03.350
Picnic, indeed. You'll go to no picnic today, Anne Shirley. That shall be your punishment, and it isn't half severe enough either for what you've done.

03:25:04.030 --> 03:25:15.430
Not go to the picnic? Anne sprang to her feet and clutched Marilla's hand. But you promised me I might. Oh, Marilla, I must go to the picnic. That was why I confessed.

03:25:15.430 --> 03:25:26.930
Just punish me any way you like but that. Oh, Marilla, please, please let me go to the picnic. Think of the ice cream. For anything you know, I may never have a chance to taste ice cream again.

03:25:28.170 --> 03:25:38.550
Marilla disengaged Anne's clinging hands, stonily. You needn't plead, Anne. You are not going to the picnic, and that's final. No, not a word.

03:25:39.590 --> 03:25:55.110
Anne realized that Marilla was not to be moved. She clasped her hands together, gave a piercing shriek, and then flung herself face downward on the bed, crying and writhing in an utter abandonment of disappointment and despair.

03:25:55.810 --> 03:26:15.190
For the land's sake! gasped Marilla, hastening from the room. I believe the child is crazy. No child in her senses would behave as she does. If she isn't, she's utterly bad. Oh dear, I'm afraid Rachel was right from the first. But I've put my hand to the plow and I won't look back.

03:26:16.190 --> 03:26:29.230
That was a dismal morning. Marilla worked fiercely and scrubbed the porch floor and the dairy shelves when she could find nothing else to do. Neither the shelves nor the porch needed it, but Marilla did.

03:26:29.970 --> 03:26:39.690
Then she went out and raked the yard. When dinner was ready, she went to the stairs and called Anne. A tear-stained face appeared, looking tragically over the banisters.

03:26:39.690 --> 03:26:41.790
Come down to your dinner, Anne.

03:26:41.790 --> 03:27:07.090
I don't want any dinner, Marilla, said Anne sobbingly. I couldn't eat anything. My heart is broken. You'll feel remorse of conscience some day I expect for breaking it, Marilla, but I forgive you. Remember when the time comes that I forgive you. But please don't ask me to eat anything, especially boiled pork and greens. Boiled pork and greens are so unromantic when one is in affliction.

03:27:08.850 --> 03:27:20.790
Exasperated, Marilla returned to the kitchen and poured out her tale of woe to Matthew, who, between his sense of justice and his unlawful sympathy with Anne, was a miserable man.

03:27:21.610 --> 03:27:47.170
Well, now, she shouldn't have taken the brooch, Marilla, or told stories about it, he admitted, mournfully surveying his plate full of unromantic pork and greens, as if he, like Anne, thought it a food unsuited to crises of feeling. But she's such a little thing, such an interesting little thing. Don't you think it's pretty rough not to let her go to the picnic when she's so set on it?

03:27:48.270 --> 03:28:07.790
Matthew Cuthbert, I'm amazed at you. I think I've let her off entirely too easy, and she doesn't appear to realize how wicked she's been at all. That's what worries me most. If she'd really felt sorry it wouldn't be so bad, and you don't seem to realize it neither. You're making excuses for her all the time to yourself. I can see that.

03:28:08.590 --> 03:28:20.190
Well, now, she's such a little thing, feebly reiterated Matthew, and there should be allowances made, Marilla. You know she's never had any bringing up.

03:28:20.190 --> 03:28:23.990
Well, she's having it now, retorted Marilla.

03:28:24.970 --> 03:28:40.510
The retort silenced Matthew if it did not convince him. That dinner was a very dismal meal. The only cheerful thing about it was Jerry Butte, the hired boy, and Marilla resented his cheerfulness as a personal insult.

03:28:41.150 --> 03:28:57.550
When her dishes were washed and her bread sponge set and her hands fed, Marilla remembered that she had noticed a small rent in her best black lace shawl when she had taken it off on Monday afternoon on returning from the lady's aid. She would go and mend it.

03:28:57.550 --> 03:29:14.430
The shawl was in a box in her trunk. As Marilla lifted it out, the sunlight falling through the vines that clustered thickly about the window struck upon something caught in the shawl, something that glittered and sparkled in facets of violet light.

03:29:15.210 --> 03:29:22.690
Marilla snatched at it with a gasp. It was the amethyst brooch, hanging to a thread, of the lace by its catch.

03:29:23.550 --> 03:29:32.150
Dear life and heart! said Marilla blankly. What does this mean? Here's my brooch safe and sound that I thought was at the bottom of Barry's pond.

03:29:32.990 --> 03:29:35.930
Whatever did that girl mean by saying she took it and lost it?

03:29:36.590 --> 03:29:47.690
I declare I believe Green Gables is bewitched. I remember now that when I took off my shawl on Monday afternoon I laid it on the bureau for a minute. I suppose the brooch got caught in it somehow.

03:29:48.390 --> 03:29:58.770
Well, Marilla betook herself to the East Gable, brooch in hand. Anne had cried herself out and was sitting dejectedly by the window.

03:29:59.690 --> 03:30:10.050
Anne, surely, said Marilla solemnly, I've just found my brooch hanging to my black lace shawl. Now I want to know what that rigmarole you told me this morning meant.

03:30:11.170 --> 03:30:20.570
Why, you said you'd keep me here until I confessed, returned Anne wearily. And so I decided to confess because I was bound to get to the picnic.

03:30:21.370 --> 03:30:29.790
I thought out a confession last night after I went to bed, and made it as interesting as I could, and I said it over and over so that I wouldn't forget it.

03:30:30.130 --> 03:30:34.090
But you wouldn't let me go to the picnic after all, so all my trouble was wasted.

03:30:35.450 --> 03:30:40.110
Marilla had to laugh in spite of herself, but her conscience pricked her.

03:30:41.010 --> 03:30:49.610
Anne, you do beat all. But I was wrong, I see that now. I shouldn't have doubted your word when I'd never known you to tell a story.

03:30:50.330 --> 03:30:56.870
Of course it wasn't right for you to confess to a thing you hadn't done, it was very wrong to do so. But I drove you to it.

03:30:56.870 --> 03:31:03.890
So if you'll forgive me, Anne, I'll forgive you, and we'll start square again. And now get yourself ready for the picnic.

03:31:04.930 --> 03:31:06.790
Anne flew up like a rocket.

03:31:07.450 --> 03:31:09.510
Oh, Marilla, isn't it too late?

03:31:10.210 --> 03:31:16.110
No, it's only two o'clock. They won't be more than well gathered yet, and it'll be an hour before they have tea.

03:31:16.770 --> 03:31:21.430
Wash your face and comb your hair and put on your gingham. I'll fill a basket for you.

03:31:21.430 --> 03:31:28.030
There's plenty of stuff baked in the house, and I'll get Jerry to hitch up the sorrel and take you down to the picnic ground.

03:31:28.870 --> 03:31:40.790
Oh, Marilla! exclaimed Anne, flying to the washstand. Five minutes ago I was so miserable I was wishing I'd never been born, and now I wouldn't change places with an angel.

03:31:41.890 --> 03:31:52.290
That night, a thoroughly happy, completely tired out Anne returned to Green Gables in a state of beatification impossible to describe.

03:31:53.070 --> 03:32:03.710
Oh, Marilla, I've had a perfectly scrumptious time. Scrumptious is the new word I learned today. I heard Mary Alice Bell use it. Isn't it very expressive?

03:32:04.790 --> 03:32:13.890
Everything was lovely. We had a splendid tea, and then Mr. Harmon Andrews took us all for a row on the Lake of Shining Waters, six of us at a time.

03:32:14.410 --> 03:32:25.290
And Jane Andrews nearly fell overboard. She was leaning out to pick water lilies, and if Mr. Andrews hadn't caught her by her sash just in the nick of time, she'd fallen in and probably been drowned.

03:32:25.290 --> 03:32:34.330
I wish it had been me. It would have been such a romantic experience to have been nearly drowned. It would be such a thrilling tale to tell.

03:32:34.890 --> 03:32:43.190
And we had the ice cream. Words fail me to describe that ice cream. Marilla, I assure you, it was sublime.

03:32:44.310 --> 03:32:48.870
That evening, Marilla told the whole story to Matthew over her stocking basket.

03:32:49.890 --> 03:33:02.310
I'm willing to own up that I made a mistake, she concluded candidly, but I've learned a lesson. I have to laugh when I think of Anne's confession, although I suppose I shouldn't, for it really was a falsehood.

03:33:02.810 --> 03:33:08.750
But it doesn't seem as bad as the other would have been, somehow. And anyhow, I'm responsible for it.

03:33:08.750 --> 03:33:20.830
That child is hard to understand in some respects, but I believe she'll turn out all right yet. And there's one thing certain, no house will ever be dull that she's in.

03:33:47.410 --> 03:33:51.490
What a splendid day, said Anne, drawing a long breath.

03:33:51.490 --> 03:33:54.550
Isn't it just good to be alive on a day like this?

03:33:54.850 --> 03:33:57.430
I pity the people who aren't born yet for missing it.

03:33:57.610 --> 03:34:01.150
They may have good days, of course, but they can never have this one.

03:34:01.370 --> 03:34:05.070
And it's splendider still to have such a lovely way to go to school by, isn't it?

03:34:06.010 --> 03:34:08.370
It's a lot nicer than going round by the road.

03:34:08.730 --> 03:34:13.450
That is so dusty and hot, said Diana practically, peeping into her dinner basket,

03:34:13.750 --> 03:34:18.590
and mentally calculating if the three juicy, toothsome raspberry tarts reposing there

03:34:18.590 --> 03:34:22.590
were divided among ten girls, how many bites each girl would have.

03:34:23.510 --> 03:34:26.590
The little girls of Avonlea School always pooled their lunches,

03:34:26.830 --> 03:34:31.330
and to eat three raspberry tarts all alone, or even to share them only with one's best chum,

03:34:31.630 --> 03:34:35.430
would have forever and ever branded as awful mean the girl who did it.

03:34:35.690 --> 03:34:40.890
And yet, when the tarts were divided among ten girls, you just got enough to tantalize you.

03:34:41.910 --> 03:34:44.610
The way Anne and Diana went to school was a pretty one.

03:34:44.610 --> 03:34:50.350
Anne thought those walks to and from school with Diana couldn't be improved upon even by imagination.

03:34:51.030 --> 03:34:53.770
Going around by the main road would have been so unromantic.

03:34:54.170 --> 03:35:00.410
But to go by Lovers Lane and Willowmere and Violet Vale and the Birch Path was romantic, if ever anything was.

03:35:01.670 --> 03:35:04.070
Lovers Lane opened out below the orchard at Green Gables,

03:35:04.290 --> 03:35:07.410
and stretched far up into the woods to the end of the Cuthbert Farm.

03:35:08.130 --> 03:35:12.710
It was the way by which the cows were taken to the back pasture, and the wood hauled home in winter.

03:35:12.710 --> 03:35:16.570
Anne had named it Lovers Lane before she had been a month at Green Gables.

03:35:17.970 --> 03:35:21.010
Not that lovers ever really walk there, she explained to Marilla,

03:35:21.350 --> 03:35:25.850
but Diana and I are reading a perfectly magnificent book, and there's a Lovers Lane in it.

03:35:25.950 --> 03:35:30.730
So we want to have one, too. And it's a very pretty name, don't you think? So romantic.

03:35:31.150 --> 03:35:37.170
We can imagine the lovers into it, you know. I like that lane, because you can think out loud there without people calling you crazy.

03:35:37.790 --> 03:35:42.290
Anne, starting out alone in the morning, went down Lovers Lane as far as the brook.

03:35:43.750 --> 03:35:48.830
Here Diana met her, and the two little girls went on up the lane under the leafy arch of maples.

03:35:49.270 --> 03:35:53.890
Maples are such sociable trees, said Anne, they're always rustling and whispering to you.

03:35:54.110 --> 03:36:00.270
Until they came to a rustic bridge. Then they left the lane and walked through Mr. Barry's back field and past Willowmere.

03:36:01.050 --> 03:36:06.330
Beyond Willowmere came Violet Vale, a little green dimple in the shadow of Mr. Andrew Bell's big woods.

03:36:06.330 --> 03:36:12.270
Of course there are no violets there now, Anne told Marilla, but Diana says there are millions of them in spring.

03:36:12.850 --> 03:36:16.750
Oh, Marilla, can't you just imagine you see them? It actually takes away my breath.

03:36:17.410 --> 03:36:22.550
I named it Violet Vale. Diana says she never saw the beat of me for hitting on fancy names for places.

03:36:23.030 --> 03:36:26.930
It's nice to be clever at something, isn't it? But Diana named the birch path.

03:36:27.190 --> 03:36:32.150
She wanted to, so I let her, but I'm sure I could have found something more poetical than plain birch path.

03:36:32.150 --> 03:36:37.810
Anybody can think of a name like that, but the birch path is one of the prettiest places in the world, Marilla.

03:36:38.450 --> 03:36:42.370
It was. Other people besides Anne thought so when they stumbled on it.

03:36:42.550 --> 03:36:47.830
It was a little narrow, twisting path, winding down over a long hill straight through Mr. Bell's woods,

03:36:48.170 --> 03:36:53.630
where the light came down and sifted through so many emerald screens that it was as flawless as the heart of a diamond.

03:36:54.330 --> 03:36:59.210
It was fringed in all its length with slim young birches, white-stemmed and lissom-bowed,

03:36:59.210 --> 03:37:05.650
ferns and star-flowers and wild lilies of the valley, and scarlet tufts of pigeon-berries grew thickly along it.

03:37:06.050 --> 03:37:13.070
And always there was a delightful spiciness in the air, and music of bird calls, and the murmur and laugh of woodwinds in the trees overhead.

03:37:13.790 --> 03:37:20.370
Now and then you might see a rabbit skipping across the road if you were quiet, which, with Anne and Diana, happened about once in a blue moon.

03:37:21.190 --> 03:37:26.050
Down in the valley the path came out to the main road, and then it was just up the spruce hill to the school.

03:37:26.730 --> 03:37:31.350
The Avonlea School was a whitewashed building, low in the eaves and wide in the windows,

03:37:31.730 --> 03:37:35.750
furnished inside with comfortable substantial old-fashioned desks that opened and shut,

03:37:36.150 --> 03:37:41.290
and were carved all over their lids with the initials and hieroglyphics of three generations of schoolchildren.

03:37:41.970 --> 03:37:46.250
The schoolhouse was set back from the road, and behind it was a dusky fir wood,

03:37:46.590 --> 03:37:51.490
and a brook where all the children put their bottles of milk in the morning to keep cool and sweet until dinner hour.

03:37:52.330 --> 03:37:57.530
Marilla had seen Anne start off to school on the first day of September with many secret misgivings.

03:37:57.810 --> 03:38:01.210
Anne was such an odd girl. How would she get on with the other children?

03:38:01.610 --> 03:38:05.070
And how on earth would she ever manage to hold her tongue during school hours?

03:38:05.950 --> 03:38:10.390
Things went better than Marilla feared, however. Anne came home that evening in high spirits.

03:38:11.290 --> 03:38:15.770
I think I'm going to like school here, she announced. I don't think much of the Master, though.

03:38:15.950 --> 03:38:19.550
He's all the time curling his mustache and making eyes at Prissy Andrews.

03:38:19.550 --> 03:38:27.210
Prissy has grown up, you know. She's sixteen, and she's studying for the entrance examination into Queen's Academy at Charlottetown next year.

03:38:27.710 --> 03:38:30.410
Tilly Boulter says the Master is dead gone on her.

03:38:30.710 --> 03:38:34.990
She's got a beautiful complexion and curly brown hair, and she does it up so elegantly.

03:38:35.390 --> 03:38:39.210
She sits in the long seat at the back, and he sits there, too, most of the time.

03:38:39.510 --> 03:38:44.490
To explain her lessons, he says, but Ruby Gillis says she saw him writing something on her slate,

03:38:44.530 --> 03:38:47.610
and when Prissy read it she blushed red as a beet and giggled,

03:38:47.610 --> 03:38:51.190
and Ruby Gillis says she doesn't believe it had anything to do with the lesson.

03:38:52.110 --> 03:38:57.330
Anne Shirley, don't let me hear you talking about your teacher in that way again, said Marilla sharply.

03:38:57.730 --> 03:39:03.830
You don't go to school to criticize the Master. I guess he can teach you something, and it's your business to learn,

03:39:04.090 --> 03:39:08.370
and I want you to understand right off that you are not to come home telling tales about him.

03:39:08.610 --> 03:39:11.950
That is something I won't encourage. I hope you were a good girl.

03:39:12.530 --> 03:39:16.990
Indeed I was, said Anne comfortably. It wasn't so hard as you might imagine, either.

03:39:17.230 --> 03:39:22.150
I sit with Diana. Our seat is right by the window, and we can look down to the lake of shining waters.

03:39:22.730 --> 03:39:26.550
There are a lot of nice girls in school, and we had scrumptious fun playing at dinnertime.

03:39:27.090 --> 03:39:32.410
It's so nice to have a lot of little girls to play with. But of course I like Diana best, and I always will.

03:39:32.730 --> 03:39:38.230
I adore Diana. I'm dreadfully far behind the others. They're all in the fifth book, and I'm only in the fourth.

03:39:38.230 --> 03:39:44.830
I feel that it's kind of a disgrace, but there's not one of them has such an imagination as I have, and I soon found that out.

03:39:45.210 --> 03:39:48.530
We had reading and geography and Canadian history and dictation today.

03:39:49.050 --> 03:39:54.670
Mr. Phillip said my spelling was disgraceful, and he held up my slate so that everybody could see it, all marked over.

03:39:55.130 --> 03:39:59.490
I felt so mortified, Marilla. He might have been politer to a stranger, I think.

03:40:00.050 --> 03:40:04.490
Ruby Gillis gave me an apple, and Sophia Sloane sent me a lovely pink card with,

03:40:04.490 --> 03:40:11.230
May I see you home on it? I'm going to give it back to her tomorrow. And Tilly Boulter let me wear her bead ring all the afternoon.

03:40:12.350 --> 03:40:16.950
Can I have some of those pearl beads off the old pincushion in the garret to make myself a ring?

03:40:17.390 --> 03:40:25.330
And oh, Marilla, Jane Andrews told me that Minnie MacPherson told her that she heard Prissy Andrews tell Sarah Gillis that I had a very pretty nose.

03:40:25.830 --> 03:40:31.430
Marilla, that is the first compliment I have ever had in my life, and you can't imagine what a strange feeling it gave me.

03:40:31.430 --> 03:40:35.170
Marilla, have I really a pretty nose? I know you'll tell me the truth.

03:40:36.050 --> 03:40:44.250
Your nose is well enough, said Marilla shortly. Secretly she thought Anne's nose was a remarkably pretty one, but she had no intention of telling her so.

03:40:45.190 --> 03:40:56.230
That was three weeks ago, and all had gone smoothly so far. And now, this crisp September morning, Anne and Diana were tripping blithely down the birch path, two of the happiest little girls in Avonlea.

03:40:56.230 --> 03:41:05.070
I guess Gilbert Blythe will be in school today, said Diana. He's been visiting his cousins over in New Brunswick all summer, and he only came home Saturday night.

03:41:05.550 --> 03:41:11.310
He's awfully handsome, Anne, and he teases the girls something terrible. He just torments our lives out.

03:41:11.850 --> 03:41:15.750
Diana's voice indicated that she rather liked having her life tormented out than not.

03:41:16.670 --> 03:41:23.710
Gilbert Blythe, said Anne, isn't his name that's written up on the porch wall with Julia Bell's and a big take notice over them?

03:41:24.310 --> 03:41:32.750
Yes, said Diana, tossing her head, but I'm sure he doesn't like Julia Bell so very much. I've heard him say he studied the multiplication table by her freckles.

03:41:33.670 --> 03:41:43.090
Oh, don't speak about freckles to me, implored Anne. It isn't delicate when I've got so many. But I do think that writing take notices up on the wall about the boys and girls is the silliest ever.

03:41:43.090 --> 03:41:50.230
I should just like to see anybody dare to write my name up with a boy's. Not of course, she hastened to add, that anybody would.

03:41:50.890 --> 03:41:56.830
Anne sighed. She didn't want her name written up, but it was a little humiliating to know that there was no danger of it.

03:41:57.630 --> 03:42:07.010
Nonsense, said Diana, whose black eyes and glossy tresses had played such havoc with the hearts of Avonlea schoolboys that her name figured on the porch walls in half a dozen take notices.

03:42:07.010 --> 03:42:20.890
It's only meant as a joke. And don't you be too sure your name won't ever be written up. Charlie Sloan is dead gone on you. He told his mother, his mother, mind you, that you were the smartest girl in school. That's better than being good-looking.

03:42:21.650 --> 03:42:35.630
No, it isn't, said Anne, feminine to the core. I'd rather be pretty than clever. And I hate Charlie Sloan. I can't bear a boy with goggle eyes. If anyone wrote my name up with his, I'd never get over it, Diana Berry. But it is nice to keep head of your class.

03:42:36.970 --> 03:42:50.770
You'll have Gilbert in your class after this, said Diana. And he's used to being head of his class, I can tell you. He's only in the fourth book, although he's nearly fourteen. Four years ago his father was sick, and he had to go out to Alberta for his health, and Gilbert went with him.

03:42:51.390 --> 03:42:58.110
They were there three years, and Gil didn't go to school hardly any until they came back. You won't find it so easy to keep head after this, Anne.

03:42:58.630 --> 03:43:04.690
I'm glad, said Anne quickly. I couldn't really feel proud of keeping head of little boys and girls of just nine or ten.

03:43:05.590 --> 03:43:20.450
I got up yesterday spelling Ebolition. Josie Pye was head, and mind you, she peeped in her book. Mr. Phillips didn't see her. He was looking at Prissy Andrews. But I did. I just swept her a look of freezing scorn, and she got as red as a beet and spelled it wrong after all.

03:43:21.070 --> 03:43:33.310
Those Pye girls are cheats all round, said Diana indignantly, as they climbed the fence of the main road. Gertie Pye actually went and put her milk bottle in my place in the brook yesterday. Did you ever? I don't speak to her now.

03:43:33.790 --> 03:43:39.030
When Mr. Phillips was in the back of the room hearing Prissy Andrews's Latin, Diana whispered to Anne,

03:43:39.470 --> 03:43:44.830
That's Gilbert Blythe sitting right across the aisle from you, Anne. Just look at him and see if you don't think he's handsome.

03:43:45.490 --> 03:43:56.050
Anne looked accordingly. She had a good chance to do so, for the said Gilbert Blythe was absorbed in stealthily pinning the long yellow braid of Ruby Gillis, who sat in front of him, to the back of her seat.

03:43:56.670 --> 03:44:11.070
He was a tall boy with curly brown hair, roguish hazel eyes, and a mouth twisted into a teasing smile. Presently Ruby Gillis started up to take a sum to the master. She fell back into her seat with a little shriek, believing that her hair was pulled out by the roots.

03:44:11.630 --> 03:44:26.210
Everybody looked at her and Mr. Phillips glared so sternly that Ruby began to cry. Gilbert had whisked the pin out of sight and was studying his history with the soberest face in the world, but when the commotion subsided, he looked at Anne and winked with inexpressible drollery.

03:44:26.870 --> 03:44:35.210
I think your Gilbert Blythe is handsome, confided Anne to Diana, but I think he's very bold. It isn't good manners to wink at a strange girl.

03:44:35.210 --> 03:44:53.690
But it was not until the afternoon that things really began to happen. Mr. Phillips was back in the corner explaining a problem in algebra to Prissy Andrews, and the rest of the scholars were doing pretty much as they pleased, eating green apples, whispering, drawing pictures on their slates, and driving crickets harnessed to strings up and down the aisle.

03:44:54.230 --> 03:45:05.930
Gilbert Blythe was trying to make Anne Shirley look at him and failing utterly, because Anne was at that moment totally oblivious not only to the very existence of Gilbert Blythe, but of every other scholar in Avonlea School itself.

03:45:06.650 --> 03:45:18.550
With her chin propped on her hands and her eyes fixed on the blue glimpse of the lake of shining waters that the west window afforded, she was far away in a gorgeous dreamland, hearing and seeing nothing save her own wonderful visions.

03:45:19.370 --> 03:45:31.890
Gilbert Blythe wasn't used to putting himself out to make a girl look at him and meeting with failure. She should look at him, that red-haired Shirley girl, with the little pointed chin and the big eyes that weren't like the eyes of any other girl in Avonlea School.

03:45:31.890 --> 03:45:39.350
Gilbert reached across the aisle, picked up the end of Anne's long red braid, held it out at arm's length, and said in a piercing whisper,

03:45:39.850 --> 03:45:41.270
Carrots, carrots!

03:45:42.050 --> 03:45:56.270
Then Anne looked at him with a vengeance. She did more than look. She sprang to her feet, her bright fancies fallen into cureless ruin. She flashed one indignant glance at Gilbert from eyes whose angry sparkle was swiftly quenched in equally angry tears.

03:45:56.270 --> 03:46:01.130
You mean, hateful boy! she exclaimed passionately. How dare you!

03:46:01.550 --> 03:46:08.290
And then, THWACK! Anne had brought her slate down on Gilbert's head and cracked it. Slate, not head. Clear across.

03:46:09.190 --> 03:46:16.470
Avonlea School always enjoyed a scene. This was an especially enjoyable one. Everybody said, Oh, in horrified delight.

03:46:16.950 --> 03:46:21.510
Diana gasped. Ruby Gillis, who was inclined to be hysterical, began to cry.

03:46:22.010 --> 03:46:27.490
Tommy Sloan let his team of crickets escape him altogether while he stared open-mouthed at the tableau.

03:46:28.430 --> 03:46:32.110
Mr. Phillips stalked down the aisle and laid his hand heavily on Anne's shoulder.

03:46:32.750 --> 03:46:46.890
Anne, surely, what does this mean? he said angrily. Anne returned no answer. It was asking too much of flesh and blood to expect her to tell before the whole school that she had been called Carrots. Gilbert it was, who spoke up stoutly.

03:46:46.890 --> 03:46:53.130
It was my fault, Mr. Phillips. I teased her. Mr. Phillips paid no heed to Gilbert.

03:46:54.230 --> 03:47:08.390
I am sorry to see a pupil of mine displaying such a temper and such a vindictive spirit, he said in a solemn tone, as if the mere fact of being a pupil of his ought to root out all evil passions from the hearts of small imperfect mortals.

03:47:09.090 --> 03:47:13.170
Anne, go and stand on the platform in front of the blackboard for the rest of the afternoon.

03:47:13.870 --> 03:47:22.170
Anne would have infinitely preferred a whipping to this punishment, under which her sensitive spirit quivered as from a whiplash, with a white set face she obeyed.

03:47:22.870 --> 03:47:37.850
Mr. Phillips took a chalk crayon and wrote on the blackboard above her head, Anne, surely, has a very bad temper. Anne, surely, must learn to control her temper, and then read it aloud so that even the primer class who couldn't read writing should understand it.

03:47:37.850 --> 03:47:49.230
Anne stood there the rest of the afternoon with that legend above her. She did not cry or hang her head. Anger was still too hot in her heart for that, and it sustained her amid all her agony of humiliation.

03:47:49.810 --> 03:47:59.250
With resentful eyes and passion-red cheeks, she confronted alike Diana's sympathetic gaze and Charlie Sloan's indignant nods and Josie Pye's malicious smiles.

03:47:59.850 --> 03:48:06.130
As for Gilbert Blythe, she would not even look at him. She would never look at him again. She would never speak to him.

03:48:06.130 --> 03:48:13.670
When school was dismissed, Anne marched out with her red head held high. Gilbert Blythe tried to intercept her at the porch door.

03:48:14.430 --> 03:48:24.790
I'm awfully sorry I made fun of your hair, Anne, he whispered contritely. Honest I am. Don't be mad for keeps now. Anne swept by disdainfully, without look or sign of hearing.

03:48:24.790 --> 03:48:34.950
Oh, how could you, Anne? breathed Diana as they went down the road half reproachfully, half admiringly. Diana felt that she could never have resisted Gilbert's plea.

03:48:35.790 --> 03:48:44.530
I shall never forgive Gilbert Blythe, said Anne firmly, and Mr. Phillips spelled my name without an E, too. The iron has entered into my soul, Diana.

03:48:45.510 --> 03:48:49.730
Diana hadn't the least idea what Anne meant, but she understood it was something terrible.

03:48:50.290 --> 03:49:03.630
You mustn't mind Gilbert making fun of your hair, she said soothingly. Why, he makes fun of all the girls. He laughs at mine because it's so black. He's called me a crow a dozen times, and I never heard him apologize for anything before, either.

03:49:04.570 --> 03:49:14.690
There's a great deal of difference between being called a crow and being called carrots, said Anne with dignity. Gilbert Blythe has hurt my feelings excruciatingly, Diana.

03:49:14.690 --> 03:49:24.210
It is possible the matter might have blown over, without more excruciation, if nothing else had happened, but when things begin to happen they are apt to keep on.

03:49:25.190 --> 03:49:35.850
Avonlea scholars often spent noon-hour picking gum in Mr. Bell's spruce grove over the hill and across his big pasture field. From there they could keep an eye on Eben Wright's house, where the master boarded.

03:49:35.850 --> 03:49:48.510
When they saw Mr. Phillips emerging there from, they ran for the schoolhouse, but the distance being about three times longer than Mr. Wright's lane, they were very apt to arrive there, breathless and gasping, some three minutes too late.

03:49:49.350 --> 03:50:01.990
On the following day Mr. Phillips was seized with one of his spasmodic fits of reform, and announced before going home to dinner that he should expect to find all the scholars in their seats when he returned. Anyone who came in late would be punished.

03:50:02.670 --> 03:50:09.630
All the boys and some of the girls went to Mr. Bell's spruce grove as usual, fully intending to stay only long enough to pick a chew.

03:50:10.250 --> 03:50:23.190
But spruce groves are seductive, and yellow nuts of gum beguiling. They picked and loitered and strayed, and as usual the first thing that recalled them to a sense of the flight of time was Jimmy Glover shouting from the top of a patriarchal old spruce,

03:50:24.930 --> 03:50:34.970
The girls who were on the ground started first, and managed to reach the schoolhouse in time, but without a second to spare. The boys, who had to wriggle hastily down from the trees, were later.

03:50:35.410 --> 03:50:50.710
And Anne, who had not been picking gum at all, but was wandering happily in the far end of the grove, waist deep among the bracken, singing softly to herself, with a wreath of rice lilies on her hair, as if she were some wild divinity of the shadowy places, was latest of all.

03:50:50.710 --> 03:51:01.890
Anne could run like a deer, however, run she did with the impish result that she overtook the boys at the door, and was swept into the schoolhouse among them, just as Mr. Phillips was in the act of hanging up his hat.

03:51:02.930 --> 03:51:10.830
Mr. Phillips's brief reforming energy was over. He didn't want the bother of punishing a dozen pupils, but it was necessary to do something to save his word.

03:51:10.830 --> 03:51:22.570
So he looked about for a scapegoat, and found it in Anne, who had dropped into her seat, gasping for breath, with a forgotten lily wreath hanging askew over one ear, and giving her a particularly rakish and disheveled appearance.

03:51:23.390 --> 03:51:35.290
Anne Shirley. Since you seem to be so fond of the boys' company, we shall indulge your taste for it this afternoon, he said sarcastically. Take those flowers out of your hair, and sit with Gilbert Blythe.

03:51:35.690 --> 03:51:44.830
The other boys snickered. Diana, turning pale with pity, plucked the wreath from Anne's hair and squeezed her hand. Anne stared at the master as if turned to stone.

03:51:45.370 --> 03:51:49.210
Did you hear what I said, Anne? queried Mr. Phillips sternly.

03:51:50.010 --> 03:51:54.090
Yes, sir, said Anne slowly, but I didn't suppose you really meant it.

03:51:54.530 --> 03:52:03.930
I assure you I did. Still with the sarcastic inflection which all the children, and Anne especially, hated, it flicked on the raw. Obey me at once.

03:52:04.490 --> 03:52:17.110
For a moment Anne looked as if she meant to disobey. Then, realizing that there was no help for it, she rose haughtily, stepped across the aisle, sat down beside Gilbert Blythe, and buried her face in her arms on the desk.

03:52:17.570 --> 03:52:27.650
Ruby Gillis, who got a glimpse of it as it went down, told the others, going home from school, that she'd actually never seen anything like it. It was so white, with awful little red spots in it.

03:52:27.650 --> 03:52:44.350
To Anne, this was the end of all things. It was bad enough to be singled out for punishment from among a dozen equally guilty ones. It was worse still to be sent to sit with a boy, but that that boy, should be Gilbert Blythe, was heaping insult on injury to a degree utterly unbearable.

03:52:44.910 --> 03:52:51.970
Anne felt that she could not bear it, and it would be of no use to try. Her whole being seethed with shame and anger and humiliation.

03:52:51.970 --> 03:53:06.050
At first the other scholars looked and whispered and giggled and nudged, but as Anne never lifted her head, and as Gilbert worked fractions as if his whole soul was absorbed in them and them only, they soon returned to their own tasks, and Anne was forgotten.

03:53:06.870 --> 03:53:20.270
When Mr. Phillips called the history class out, Anne should have gone, but Anne did not move, and Mr. Phillips, who had been writing some verses to Priscilla before he called the class, was thinking about an obstinate rhyme still, and never missed her.

03:53:21.150 --> 03:53:31.750
Once, when nobody was looking, Gilbert took from his desk a little pink candy heart with a gold motto on it, You Are Sweet, and slipped it under the curve of Anne's arm.

03:53:32.190 --> 03:53:44.230
Whereupon Anne arose, took the pink heart gingerly between the tips of her fingers, dropped it on the floor, grounded to powder beneath her heel, and resumed her position without dainting to bestow a glance on Gilbert.

03:53:44.830 --> 03:53:56.410
When school went out, Anne marched to her desk, ostentatiously took out everything therein, books and writing tablet, pen and ink, testament and arithmetic, and piled them neatly on her cracked slate.

03:53:57.230 --> 03:54:05.350
What are you taking all those things home for, Anne? Diana wanted to know, as soon as they were out on the road. She had not dared to ask the question before.

03:54:05.830 --> 03:54:09.050
I am not coming back to school any more, said Anne.

03:54:09.570 --> 03:54:12.470
Diana gasped and stared at Anne to see if she meant it.

03:54:12.790 --> 03:54:14.910
Will Marilla let you stay home, she asked?

03:54:15.530 --> 03:54:19.290
She'll have to, said Anne. I'll never go to school to that man again.

03:54:19.990 --> 03:54:32.350
Oh, Anne! Diana looked as if she were ready to cry. I do think you're mean. What shall I do? Mr. Phillips will make me sit with that horrid, girdy pie. I know he will, because she is sitting alone. Do come back, Anne.

03:54:33.110 --> 03:54:46.490
I'd do almost anything in the world for you, Diana, said Anne sadly. I'd let myself be torn limb from limb if it would do you any good. But I can't do this, so please don't ask it. You harrow up my very soul.

03:54:47.270 --> 03:55:11.650
Just think of all the fun you will miss, mourned Diana. We are going to build the loveliest new house down by the brook, and we'll be playing ball next week, and you've never played ball, Anne. It's tremendously exciting. And we're going to learn a new song. Jane Andrews is practicing it up now, and Alice Andrews is going to bring a new pansy book next week, and we're all going to read it out loud, chapter about, down by the brook. And you know you are so fond of reading out loud, Anne.

03:55:12.130 --> 03:55:20.030
Nothing moved Anne in the least. Her mind was made up. She would not go to school to Mr. Phillips again. She told Marilla so when she got home.

03:55:20.790 --> 03:55:21.990
Nonsense, said Marilla.

03:55:22.630 --> 03:55:29.950
It isn't nonsense at all, said Anne, gazing at Marilla with solemn, reproachful eyes. Don't you understand, Marilla? I've been insulted.

03:55:31.170 --> 03:55:34.250
Insulted, Fiddlesticks. You'll go to school tomorrow as usual.

03:55:34.250 --> 03:55:48.630
Oh, no. Anne shook her head gently. I'm not going back, Marilla. I'll learn my lessons at home, and I'll be as good as I can be and hold my tongue all the time if it's possible at all. But I will not go back to school, I assure you.

03:55:49.110 --> 03:55:59.550
Marilla saw something remarkably like unyielding stubbornness looking out of Anne's small face. She understood that she would have trouble in overcoming it, but she resolved wisely to say nothing more just then.

03:56:00.250 --> 03:56:10.330
I'll run down and see Rachel about it this evening, she thought. There's no use reasoning with Anne now. She's too worked up, and I've an idea she can be awful stubborn if she takes the notion.

03:56:10.790 --> 03:56:19.470
Far as I can make out from her story, Mr. Phillips has been carrying matters with a rather high hand, but it would never do to say so to her. I'll just talk it over with Rachel.

03:56:19.870 --> 03:56:26.150
She sent ten children to school, and she ought to know something about it. She'll have heard the whole story, too, by this time.

03:56:26.770 --> 03:56:31.450
Marilla found Mrs. Lynde knitting quilts as industriously and cheerfully as usual.

03:56:32.430 --> 03:56:38.130
I suppose you know what I've come about, she said, a little shame-facedly. Mrs. Rachel nodded.

03:56:38.410 --> 03:56:40.930
About Anne's fuss in school, I reckon, she said.

03:56:41.930 --> 03:56:45.290
Tilly Boulter was in on her way home from school and told me about it.

03:56:45.770 --> 03:56:52.170
I don't know what to do with her, said Marilla. She declared she won't go back to school. I never saw a child so worked up.

03:56:52.170 --> 03:57:00.710
I've been expecting trouble ever since she started to school. I knew things were going too smooth to last. She's so high strung. What would you advise, Rachel?

03:57:01.490 --> 03:57:07.990
Well, since you've asked my advice, Marilla, said Mrs. Lynde amiably. Mrs. Lynde dearly loved to be asked for advice.

03:57:08.450 --> 03:57:16.530
I'd just humour her a little at first. That's what I'd do. It's my belief that Mr. Phillips was in the wrong. Of course it doesn't do to say so to the children, you know.

03:57:16.530 --> 03:57:21.690
And of course he did write to punish her yesterday for giving way to temper. But today it was different.

03:57:22.170 --> 03:57:29.690
The others who were late should have been punished as well as Anne, that's what. And I don't believe in making the girls sit with the boys for punishment. It isn't modest.

03:57:30.130 --> 03:57:40.350
Tilly Boulter was real indignant. She took Anne's part right through and said all the scholars did, too. Anne seems real popular among them, somehow. I never thought she'd take with them so well.

03:57:40.830 --> 03:57:49.430
Then you really think I'd better let her stay home, said Marilla in amazement. Yes, that is, I wouldn't say school to her again until she said it herself.

03:57:50.030 --> 03:57:55.830
Depend upon it, Marilla. She'll cool off in a week or so and be ready enough to go back of her own accord, that's what.

03:57:56.250 --> 03:58:02.750
While, if you were to make her go back right off, dear knows what freak or tantrum she'd take next and make more trouble than ever.

03:58:02.750 --> 03:58:11.530
The less fuss made the better, in my opinion. She won't miss much by not going to school, as far as that goes. Mr. Phillips isn't any good at all as a teacher.

03:58:12.010 --> 03:58:19.090
The order he keeps is scandalous, that's what, and he neglects the young fry and puts all his time on those big scholars he's getting ready for Queens.

03:58:19.630 --> 03:58:31.090
He'd never have got the school for another year if his uncle hadn't been a trustee—the trustee—for he just leads the other two around by the nose, that's what. I declare, I don't know what education in this island is coming to.

03:58:31.090 --> 03:58:39.670
Mrs. Rachel shook her head. As much as to say, if she were only at the head of the educational system of the province, things would be much better managed.

03:58:40.610 --> 03:58:45.170
Marilla took Mrs. Rachel's advice, and not another word was said to Anne about going back to school.

03:58:45.490 --> 03:58:50.990
She learned her lessons at home, did her chores, and played with Diana in the chilly purple autumn twilights.

03:58:50.990 --> 03:59:00.990
But when she met Gilbert Blythe on the road, or encountered him in Sunday school, she passed him by with an icy contempt that was no wit thawed by his evident desire to appease her.

03:59:01.490 --> 03:59:09.650
Even Diana's efforts as a peacemaker were of no avail. Anne had evidently made up her mind to hate Gilbert Blythe to the end of life.

03:59:10.190 --> 03:59:18.190
As much as she hated Gilbert, however, did she love Diana, with all the love of her passionate little heart, equally intense in its likes and dislikes.

03:59:18.190 --> 03:59:26.490
One evening Marilla, coming in from the orchard with a basket of apples, found Anne sitting along by the east window in the twilight, crying bitterly.

03:59:27.050 --> 03:59:29.290
"'Whatever's the matter now, Anne?' she asked.

03:59:29.750 --> 03:59:32.630
"'It's about Diana,' sobbed Anne luxuriously.

03:59:32.850 --> 03:59:41.250
"'I love Diana so, Marilla. I cannot ever live without her. But I know very well when we grow up that Diana will get married and go away and leave me.

03:59:41.250 --> 04:00:03.250
And oh, what shall I do? I hate her husband. I just hate him furiously. I've been imagining it all out, the wedding and everything, Diana dressed in snowy garments with a veil and looking as beautiful and regal as a queen, and me the bridesmaid with a lovely dress too and puffed sleeves but with a breaking heart hid beneath my smiling face, and then bidding Diana good-bye.'

04:00:03.830 --> 04:00:07.210
Here Anne broke down entirely and wept with increasing bitterness.

04:00:07.850 --> 04:00:23.150
Marilla turned quickly away to hide her twitching face, but it was no use. She collapsed on the nearest chair and burst into such a hearty and unusual peal of laughter that Matthew, crossing the yard outside, halted in amazement. When had he heard Marilla laugh like that before?

04:00:23.790 --> 04:00:35.150
"'Well, Anne Shirley,' said Marilla, as soon as she could speak, "'if you must borrow trouble, for pity's sake borrow it handy or home. I should think you had an imagination, sure enough.'"

04:01:02.110 --> 04:01:05.530
Diana is invited to tea, with tragic results.

04:01:07.270 --> 04:01:13.530
October was a beautiful month at Green Gables, when the birches in the hollow turned as golden as sunshine,

04:01:13.970 --> 04:01:19.770
and the maples behind the orchard were royal crimson and the wild cherry trees along the lane

04:01:19.770 --> 04:01:26.470
put on the loveliest shades of dark red and bronzy green, while the fields sunned themselves in

04:01:27.810 --> 04:01:30.670
Anne reveled in the world of colour about her.

04:01:56.470 --> 04:02:00.930
said Marilla, whose aesthetic sense was not noticeably developed.

04:02:01.270 --> 04:02:05.290
You clutter up your room entirely too much with out-of-doors stuff, Anne.

04:02:05.810 --> 04:02:07.910
Bedrooms were made to sleep in.

04:02:09.010 --> 04:02:15.290
Oh, and dream in too, Marilla, and you know one can dream so much better in a room where there

04:02:15.290 --> 04:02:21.070
are pretty things. I'm going to put these boughs in the old blue jug and set them on my table.

04:02:21.970 --> 04:02:27.650
Mind you don't drop leaves all over the stairs, then. I'm going on a meeting of the

04:02:27.650 --> 04:02:32.850
Aid Society at Carmody this afternoon, Anne, and I won't likely be home before dark.

04:02:33.650 --> 04:02:38.310
You'll have to get Matthew and Jerry their supper, so mind you don't forget to put the

04:02:38.310 --> 04:02:42.090
tea to draw until you sit down at the table as you did last time.

04:02:42.450 --> 04:02:48.070
It was dreadful of me to forget, said Anne apologetically, but that was the afternoon

04:02:48.070 --> 04:02:52.650
I was trying to think of a name for Violet Vale, and it crowded other things out.

04:02:53.490 --> 04:02:59.830
Matthew was so good he never scolded a bit. He put the tea down himself and said he could

04:02:59.830 --> 04:03:04.890
wait a while as well as not, and I told him a lovely fairy story while we were waiting,

04:03:05.310 --> 04:03:10.650
so he didn't find the time long at all. It was a beautiful fairy story, Marilla.

04:03:11.190 --> 04:03:16.870
I forgot the end of it, so I made up an end for it myself, and Matthew said he couldn't

04:03:16.870 --> 04:03:21.570
tell where the join came in. Matthew would think it all right, Anne,

04:03:21.570 --> 04:03:24.950
if you took a notion to get up and have dinner in the middle of the night,

04:03:25.330 --> 04:03:31.330
but you keep your wits about you this time, and I don't really know if I'm doing right.

04:03:31.550 --> 04:03:36.770
It may make you more adulpated than ever, but you can ask Diana to come over and spend

04:03:36.770 --> 04:03:42.950
the afternoon with you and have tea here. Oh, Marilla! Anne clasped her hands.

04:03:42.950 --> 04:03:49.770
How perfectly lovely! You are able to imagine things after all, or else you'd never have

04:03:49.770 --> 04:03:55.510
understood how I've longed for that very thing. It will seem so nice and grown-up-ish.

04:03:56.030 --> 04:03:59.670
No fear of my forgetting to put the tea to draw when I have company.

04:04:00.510 --> 04:04:04.010
Oh, Marilla, can I use the rosebud spray tea set?

04:04:05.410 --> 04:04:13.710
No, indeed, the rosebud tea set. Well, what next? You know I never use that except for the minister

04:04:13.710 --> 04:04:20.110
or the aides. You'll put down the old brown tea set. But you can open the little yellow

04:04:20.110 --> 04:04:26.090
crock of cherry preserves. It's time it was being used, anyhow. I believe it's beginning to work.

04:04:26.590 --> 04:04:29.990
And you can cut some fruitcake and have some of the cookies and snaps.

04:04:30.550 --> 04:04:36.010
I can just imagine myself sitting down at the head of the table and pouring out the tea,

04:04:36.350 --> 04:04:42.110
said Anne, shutting her eyes ecstatically and asking Diana if she takes sugar. I know she

04:04:42.110 --> 04:04:48.110
doesn't, but of course I'll ask her just as if I didn't know, and then pressing her to take another

04:04:48.110 --> 04:04:54.490
piece of fruitcake and another helping of preserves. Oh, Marilla, it's a wonderful sensation just to

04:04:54.490 --> 04:04:59.970
think of it. Can I take her into the spare room to lay off her hat when she comes, and then

04:04:59.970 --> 04:05:07.390
the parlor to sit? No, the sitting room will do for you and your company. But there's a bottle

04:05:07.390 --> 04:05:11.730
half full of raspberry cordial that was left over from the church social the other night.

04:05:12.170 --> 04:05:17.090
It's on the second shelf of the sitting-room closet, and you and Diana can have it if you like,

04:05:17.530 --> 04:05:21.650
and a cookie to eat with it along in the afternoon, for I dare say Matthew will be

04:05:21.650 --> 04:05:27.490
late coming into tea since he's hauling potatoes to the vessel. Anne flew down to the hollow,

04:05:27.490 --> 04:05:33.690
passed the dryad's bubble, and up the spruce path to Orchard Slope to ask Diana to tea.

04:05:34.790 --> 04:05:41.690
As a result, just after Marilla had driven off to Carmody, Diana came over, dressed in her second

04:05:41.690 --> 04:05:49.370
best dress and looking exactly as it is proper to look when asked out to tea. At other times she was

04:05:49.370 --> 04:05:54.610
wont to run into the kitchen without knocking, but now she knocked primly at the front door,

04:05:54.610 --> 04:06:00.930
and when Anne, dressed in her second best, as primly opened it, both girls shook hands as

04:06:00.930 --> 04:06:07.630
gravely as if they had never met before. This unnatural solemnity lasted until after Diana

04:06:07.630 --> 04:06:13.130
had been taken to the East Gable to lay off her hat, and then had sat for ten minutes in the

04:06:13.130 --> 04:06:20.310
sitting-room, toes in position. How is your mother? inquired Anne politely, just as if she

04:06:20.310 --> 04:06:24.990
had not seen Mrs. Barry picking apples that morning in excellent health and spirits.

04:06:26.170 --> 04:06:31.990
She is very well, thank you. I suppose Mr. Cuffbert is hauling potatoes to the Lily Sands this

04:06:31.990 --> 04:06:38.350
afternoon, is he? asked Diana, who had ridden down to Mr. Harmon Andrews that morning in Matthew's

04:06:38.350 --> 04:06:45.630
cart. Yes, our potato crop is very good this year. I hope your father's crop is good too.

04:06:45.630 --> 04:06:50.730
It is fairly good, thank you. Have you picked many of your apples yet?

04:06:51.750 --> 04:06:57.470
Oh, ever so many, said Anne, forgetting to be dignified and jumping up quickly. Let's go out

04:06:57.470 --> 04:07:02.490
to the orchard and get some of the red sweetings, Diana. Marilla says we can have all that are left

04:07:02.490 --> 04:07:08.570
on the tree. Marilla is a very generous woman. She said we could have fruit cake and cherry

04:07:08.570 --> 04:07:12.950
preserves for tea, but it isn't good manners to tell your company what you are going to

04:07:12.950 --> 04:07:18.810
give them to eat, so I won't tell you what she said we could have to drink. Only it begins with

04:07:18.810 --> 04:07:27.070
an R and a C and its bright red colour. I love bright red drinks, don't you? They taste twice as

04:07:27.070 --> 04:07:33.270
good as any other colour. The orchard with its great sweeping boughs that bent to the ground with

04:07:33.270 --> 04:07:42.830
fruit proved so delightful that the little girls spent most of the afternoon in it, sitting in a

04:07:42.830 --> 04:07:50.370
sunshine lingered warmly, eating apples and talking as hard as they could. Diana had much to tell Anne

04:07:50.370 --> 04:07:56.350
of what went on in school. She had to sit with Gertie Pie and she hated it. Gertie squeaked her

04:07:56.350 --> 04:08:04.290
pencil all the time and it just made her, Diana's, blood run cold. Ruby Gillis had charmed all her

04:08:04.290 --> 04:08:10.990
warts away, true as you live, with a magic pebble that old Mary Jo from the creek gave her. You had

04:08:10.990 --> 04:08:15.750
rub the warts with the pebble and then throw it away over your left shoulder at the time of the

04:08:15.750 --> 04:08:21.810
new moon and the warts would all go. Charlie Sloan's name was written up with M. White's on

04:08:21.810 --> 04:08:28.950
the porch wall and M. White was awful mad about it. Sam Bolter had sassed Mr. Phillips in class

04:08:28.950 --> 04:08:34.250
and Mr. Phillips whipped him and Sam's father came down to the school and dared Mr. Phillips

04:08:34.250 --> 04:08:40.630
to lay a hand on one of his children again. And Maddie Andrews had a new red hood and a blue

04:08:40.630 --> 04:08:45.950
crossover with tassels on it and the airs she put on about it were perfectly sickening.

04:08:46.510 --> 04:08:51.870
And Lizzie Wright didn't speak to Mamie Wilson because Mamie Wilson's grown-up sister had cut

04:08:51.870 --> 04:08:58.190
out Lizzie Wright's grown-up sister with her bow. And everybody missed Anne so and wished she'd come

04:08:58.190 --> 04:09:03.550
to school again. And Gilbert Blythe, but Anne didn't want to hear about Gilbert Blythe,

04:09:04.250 --> 04:09:08.750
she jumped up hurriedly and said, Suppose they go in and have some raspberry cordial.

04:09:09.950 --> 04:09:14.270
Anne looked on the second shelf of the room pantry, but there was no bottle of raspberry

04:09:14.270 --> 04:09:20.310
cordial there. Search revealed it away back on the top shelf. Anne put it on a tray and

04:09:20.310 --> 04:09:27.310
set it on the table with a tumbler. Now please help yourself, Diana, she said politely. I don't

04:09:27.310 --> 04:09:32.710
believe I'll have any just now. I don't feel as if I wanted any after all those apples.

04:09:33.670 --> 04:09:38.690
Diana poured herself out a tumbler full, looked at its bright red hue admiringly,

04:09:38.810 --> 04:09:45.390
then sipped it daintily. That's awfully nice raspberry cordial, Anne, she said. I didn't

04:09:45.390 --> 04:09:51.350
know raspberry cordial was so nice. I'm real glad you like it. Take as much as you want.

04:09:51.710 --> 04:09:56.830
I'm going to run out and stir the fire up. There are so many responsibilities on a person's mind

04:09:56.830 --> 04:10:01.210
when their keeping house isn't there. When Anne came back from the kitchen,

04:10:01.510 --> 04:10:06.310
Diana was drinking her second glass full of cordial. And being treated there too by Anne,

04:10:06.590 --> 04:10:11.310
she offered no particular objection to the drinking of a third. The tumbler fulls were

04:10:11.310 --> 04:10:17.050
generous ones and the raspberry cordial was certainly very nice. The nicest I ever drank,

04:10:17.330 --> 04:10:23.490
said Diana. It's ever so much nicer than Mrs. Lynn's, although she brags of hers so much.

04:10:23.490 --> 04:10:25.730
It doesn't taste a bit like hers.

04:10:26.610 --> 04:10:31.370
I should think Marilla's raspberry cordial would probably be much nicer than Mrs. Lynn's,

04:10:31.430 --> 04:10:36.690
said Anne loyally. Marilla is a famous cook. She is trying to teach me to cook,

04:10:36.710 --> 04:10:42.330
but I assure you, Diana, it is uphill work. There's so little scope for imagination in

04:10:42.330 --> 04:10:48.570
cookery. You just have to go by rules. The last time I made a cake I forgot to put the

04:10:48.570 --> 04:10:54.590
flower in. I was thinking the loveliest story about you and me, Diana. I thought you were

04:10:54.590 --> 04:11:00.850
desperately ill with smallpox and everybody deserted you, but I went boldly to your bedside

04:11:00.850 --> 04:11:05.910
and nursed you back to life. And then I took the smallpox and died and I was buried under

04:11:05.910 --> 04:11:11.350
those poplar trees in the graveyard and you planted a rose bush on my grave and watered

04:11:11.350 --> 04:11:17.190
it with your tears and you never, never forgot the friend of your youth who sacrificed her

04:11:17.190 --> 04:11:23.630
life for you. Oh, it was such a pathetic tale, Diana. The tears just rained down over my

04:11:23.630 --> 04:11:28.390
cheeks while I mixed the cake. But I forgot the flower and the cake was a dismal failure.

04:11:28.930 --> 04:11:34.490
Flower is so essential to cakes, you know. Marilla was very cross and I don't wonder.

04:11:34.870 --> 04:11:40.450
I'm a great trial to her. She was terribly mortified about the pudding sauce last week.

04:11:40.750 --> 04:11:45.330
We had a plum pudding for dinner on Tuesday and there was half the pudding and a pitcher

04:11:45.330 --> 04:11:50.610
full of sauce left over. Marilla said there was enough for another dinner and told me to

04:11:50.610 --> 04:11:57.190
set it in the pantry shelf and cover it. I meant to cover it, just as much as could be, Diana,

04:11:57.530 --> 04:12:03.650
but when I carried it in I was imagining I was a nun. Of course I'm a Protestant, but I imagined

04:12:03.650 --> 04:12:10.210
I was Catholic, taking the veil to bury a broken heart in cloistered seclusion. And I forgot all

04:12:10.210 --> 04:12:16.730
out covering the pudding sauce. I thought of it next morning and ran to the pantry. Diana, fancy,

04:12:16.790 --> 04:12:23.430
if you can, my extreme horror at finding a mouse drowned in that pudding sauce. I lifted the mouse

04:12:23.430 --> 04:12:28.630
out with a spoon and threw it out in the yard and then I washed the spoon in three waters.

04:12:29.430 --> 04:12:34.570
Marilla was out milking and I fully intended to ask her when she came in if I'd give the

04:12:34.570 --> 04:12:40.270
sauce to the pigs. But when she came in I was imagining that I was a frost fairy going through

04:12:40.270 --> 04:12:45.930
the woods, turning the trees red and yellow, whichever they wanted to be. So I never thought

04:12:45.930 --> 04:12:52.150
about the pudding sauce again and Marilla sent me out to pick apples. Well, Mr. and Mrs. Chester

04:12:52.150 --> 04:12:58.270
Ross from Spencervale came here that morning. You know, they are very stylish people, especially

04:12:58.270 --> 04:13:04.430
Mrs. Chester Ross. When Marilla called me in dinner was all ready and everybody was at the table.

04:13:04.570 --> 04:13:10.730
I tried to be as polite and dignified as I could be, for I wanted Mrs. Chester Ross to think I was

04:13:10.730 --> 04:13:16.870
a ladylike little girl, even if I wasn't pretty. Everything went right until I saw Marilla coming

04:13:16.870 --> 04:13:22.670
with the plum pudding in one hand and the pitcher of pudding sauce warmed up in the other. Diana,

04:13:22.730 --> 04:13:28.630
that was a terrible moment. I remembered everything and I just stood up in my place and shrieked out,

04:13:29.210 --> 04:13:34.190
Marilla, you mustn't use that pudding sauce. There was a mouse drowned in it. I forgot to

04:13:34.190 --> 04:13:40.490
tell you before. Oh, Diana, I shall never forget that awful moment if I lived to be a hundred.

04:13:41.090 --> 04:13:46.210
Mrs. Chester Ross just looked at me and I thought I would sink through the floor with mortification.

04:13:46.650 --> 04:13:50.830
She is such a perfect housekeeper and fancy what she must have thought of us.

04:13:51.630 --> 04:13:58.030
Marilla turned red as fire, but she never said a word then. She just carried that sauce and

04:13:58.030 --> 04:14:03.750
pudding out and brought in some cherry preserves. She even offered me some, but I couldn't swallow

04:14:03.750 --> 04:14:10.390
a mouthful. It was like heaping coals of fire on my head. After Mrs. Chester Ross went away,

04:14:10.730 --> 04:14:17.950
Marilla gave me a dreadful scolding. Why, Diana, what is the matter? Diana had stood up very

04:14:17.950 --> 04:14:25.890
unsteadily. Then she sat down again, putting her hands to her head. I'm, I'm awful sick,

04:14:25.890 --> 04:14:35.010
she said a little thickly. I, I must go right home. Oh, you mustn't dream of going home without your

04:14:35.010 --> 04:14:41.190
tea, cried Anne in distress. I'll get it right off. I'll go and put the tea down this very minute.

04:14:42.010 --> 04:14:49.390
I must go home, repeated Diana, stupidly but determinedly. Let me get you a lunch anyhow,

04:14:49.870 --> 04:14:54.310
implored Anne. Let me give you a bit of fruitcake and some of the cherry preserves.

04:14:54.310 --> 04:14:58.930
Lie down on the sofa for a little while and you'll be better. Where do you feel bad?

04:14:59.750 --> 04:15:06.390
I must go home, said Diana, and that was all she would say. In vain, Anne pleaded.

04:15:06.750 --> 04:15:12.870
I never heard of company going home without tea, she mourned. Oh, Diana, do you suppose that it's

04:15:12.870 --> 04:15:18.870
possible you're really taking the smallpox? If you are, I'll go and nurse you. You can depend

04:15:18.870 --> 04:15:25.290
on that. I'll never forsake you, but I do wish you'd stay till after tea. Where do you feel bad?

04:15:25.970 --> 04:15:33.970
I'm awfully dizzy, said Diana, and indeed she walked very dizzily. Anne, with tears of

04:15:33.970 --> 04:15:40.010
disappointment in her eyes, got Diana's hat and went with her as far as the berry yard fence.

04:15:40.670 --> 04:15:46.250
Then she wept all the way back to Green Gables, where she sorrowfully put the remainder of the

04:15:46.250 --> 04:15:52.270
cordial back into the pantry and got tea ready for Matthew and Jerry, with all the zest gone

04:15:52.270 --> 04:15:59.750
out of the performance. The next day was Sunday, and as the rain poured down in Torrance from dusk

04:15:59.750 --> 04:16:07.030
till dawn, Anne did not stir abroad from Green Gables. Monday afternoon, Marilla sent her down

04:16:07.030 --> 04:16:13.210
to Mrs. Lynde's on an errand. In a very short space of time, Anne came flying back up the lane

04:16:13.210 --> 04:16:19.910
with tears rolling down her cheeks. Into the kitchen she dashed and flung herself face downward

04:16:19.910 --> 04:16:27.890
on the sofa in an agony. Whatever has gone wrong now, Anne? queried Marilla in doubt and dismay.

04:16:28.170 --> 04:16:33.750
I do hope you haven't gone and been saucy to Mrs. Lynde again. No answer from Anne,

04:16:34.070 --> 04:16:41.030
save more tears and stormier sobs. Anne Shirley, when I ask you a question I want to be answered,

04:16:41.030 --> 04:16:48.290
sit right up this very minute and tell me what you're crying about. Anne sat up, tragedy

04:16:48.930 --> 04:16:56.210
personified. Mrs. Lynde was up to see Mrs. Barry today, and Mrs. Barry was in an awful state,

04:16:56.610 --> 04:17:03.110
she wailed. She says that I set Diana drunk Saturday and sent her home in a disgraceful

04:17:03.110 --> 04:17:09.110
condition, and she says I must be a thoroughly bad, wicked little girl, and she's never,

04:17:09.110 --> 04:17:15.230
never going to let Diana play with me again. Oh, Marilla, I'm just overcome with woe.

04:17:16.550 --> 04:17:23.550
Marilla stared in blank amazement. Set Diana drunk, she said when she found her voice. Anne,

04:17:23.570 --> 04:17:31.490
are you or Mrs. Barry crazy? What on earth did you give her? Not a thing but raspberry cordial,

04:17:31.910 --> 04:17:38.090
sobbed Anne. I never thought raspberry cordial would set people drunk, Marilla, not even if they

04:17:38.090 --> 04:17:45.030
drank three big tumblerfuls as Diana did. Oh, it sounds so, so like Mrs. Thomas's husband,

04:17:45.610 --> 04:17:51.590
but I didn't mean to set her drunk. Drunk fiddlesticks, said Marilla, marching to the

04:17:51.590 --> 04:17:56.950
sitting-room pantry. There on the shelf was a bottle which she at once recognized as one

04:17:56.950 --> 04:18:02.590
containing some of her three-year-old homemade current wine, for which she was celebrated in

04:18:03.270 --> 04:18:09.010
Although certain of the stricter sort, Mrs. Barry among them, disapproved strongly of it.

04:18:09.670 --> 04:18:14.270
And at the same time, Marilla recollected that she had put the bottle of raspberry cordial

04:18:14.270 --> 04:18:19.770
down in the cellar instead of in the pantry, as she had told Anne. She went back to the kitchen

04:18:19.770 --> 04:18:26.490
with the wine bottle in her hand. Her face was twitching in spite of herself. Anne, you certainly

04:18:26.490 --> 04:18:32.090
have a genius for getting into trouble. You went and gave Diana current wine instead of raspberry

04:18:32.090 --> 04:18:39.090
cordial. Didn't you know the difference yourself? I never tasted it, said Anne. I thought it was the

04:18:39.090 --> 04:18:45.310
cordial. I meant to be so, so hospitable. Diana got awfully sick and had to go home.

04:18:46.030 --> 04:18:51.430
Mrs. Barry told Mrs. Lynn she was simply dead drunk. She just laughed silly like when her mother

04:18:51.430 --> 04:18:56.930
asked her what was the matter and went to sleep and slept for hours. Her mother smelled her breath

04:18:56.930 --> 04:19:03.690
and knew she was drunk. She had a fearful headache all day yesterday. Mrs. Barry is so indignant she

04:19:03.690 --> 04:19:09.710
will never believe but what I did it on purpose. I should think she would better punish Diana for

04:19:09.710 --> 04:19:16.530
being so greedy as to drink three glassfuls of anything, said Marilla shortly. Why, three of

04:19:16.530 --> 04:19:22.450
those big glasses would have made her sick even if it had only been cordial. Well, this story will be

04:19:22.450 --> 04:19:28.190
a nice handle for those folks who are so down on me for making current wine, although I haven't made

04:19:28.190 --> 04:19:33.630
any for three years ever since I found out that the minister didn't approve. I just kept that bottle

04:19:33.630 --> 04:19:40.610
for sickness. There, there, child, don't cry. I can't see as you were to blame, although I'm sorry

04:19:40.610 --> 04:19:49.290
it happened so. I must cry, said Anne. My heart is broken. The stars in their courses fight against

04:19:49.290 --> 04:19:56.570
me, Marilla. Diana and I are parted forever. Oh, Marilla, I little dreamed of this when first we

04:19:56.570 --> 04:20:02.630
swore our vows of friendship. Don't be foolish, Anne. Mrs. Barry will think better of it when

04:20:02.630 --> 04:20:07.710
she finds out you're not to blame. I suppose she thinks you've gone and done it for a silly joke

04:20:07.710 --> 04:20:13.930
or something of that sort. You'd best go up this evening and tell her how it was. My courage fails

04:20:13.930 --> 04:20:19.330
me at the thought of facing Diana's injured mother, sighed Anne. I wish you'd go, Marilla.

04:20:19.550 --> 04:20:24.590
You're so much more dignified than I am. Likely she'd listen to you quicker than to me.

04:20:25.630 --> 04:20:31.790
Well, I will, said Marilla, reflecting that it would probably be the wiser course. Don't cry

04:20:31.790 --> 04:20:38.070
any more, Anne. It will be all right. Marilla had changed her mind about it being all right by the

04:20:38.070 --> 04:20:43.510
time she got back from Orchard Slope. Anne was watching for her coming and flew to the porch door

04:20:43.510 --> 04:20:49.570
to meet her. Oh, Marilla, I know by your face that it's been no use, she said sorrowfully.

04:20:50.170 --> 04:20:58.230
Mrs. Barry won't forgive me? Mrs. Barry, indeed, snapped Marilla. Of all the unreasonable women I

04:20:58.230 --> 04:21:05.450
ever saw, she's the worst. I told her it was all a mistake and you weren't to blame. But she just

04:21:05.450 --> 04:21:11.090
simply didn't believe me, and she rubbed it well in about my current wine and how I've always said

04:21:11.090 --> 04:21:17.230
couldn't have the least effect on anybody. I just told her plainly that current wine wasn't meant

04:21:17.230 --> 04:21:23.330
to be drunk three tumblerfuls at a time and that if a child I had to do with was so greedy I'd

04:21:23.330 --> 04:21:29.170
sober her up with a right good spanking. Marilla whisked into the kitchen, grievously disturbed,

04:21:29.390 --> 04:21:35.710
leaving a very much distracted little soul in the porch behind her. Presently Anne stepped out

04:21:35.710 --> 04:21:40.970
bareheaded into the chill autumn dusk, very determinedly and steadily, she took her way

04:21:40.970 --> 04:21:46.230
down through the Sear Cloverfield, over the Lager Bridge, and up through the Spruce Grove,

04:21:46.870 --> 04:21:53.810
lighted by a pale little moon hanging low over the western woods. Mrs. Barry, coming to the door in

04:21:53.810 --> 04:22:00.710
answer to a timid knock, found a white-lipped, eager-eyed suppliant on the doorstep. Her face

04:22:01.350 --> 04:22:07.430
Mrs. Barry was a woman of strong prejudices and dislikes, and her anger was of the cold,

04:22:07.630 --> 04:22:13.710
sullen sort which is always hardest to overcome. To do her justice, she really believed Anne had

04:22:13.710 --> 04:22:18.830
made Diana drunk out of sheer malice prepense, and she was honestly anxious to preserve her

04:22:18.830 --> 04:22:22.790
little daughter from the contamination of further intimacy with such a child.

04:22:23.610 --> 04:22:30.230
What do you want? she said stiffly. Anne clasped her hands. Oh, Mrs. Barry,

04:22:30.450 --> 04:22:38.830
please forgive me. I did not mean to intoxicate Diana. How could I? Just imagine if you were a

04:22:38.830 --> 04:22:44.370
poor little orphan girl that kind people had adopted, and you had just one bosom friend in

04:22:44.370 --> 04:22:50.250
all the world. Do you think you would intoxicate her on purpose? I thought it was only raspberry

04:22:50.250 --> 04:22:56.430
cordial. I was firmly convinced it was raspberry cordial. Oh, please don't say that you won't let

04:22:56.430 --> 04:23:01.910
Diana play with me any more. If you do, you will cover my life with a dark cloud of woe.

04:23:02.530 --> 04:23:06.770
This speech, which would have softened good Mrs. Lynn's heart in a twinkling,

04:23:07.270 --> 04:23:13.710
had no effect on Mrs. Barry except to irritate her still more. She was suspicious of Anne's

04:23:13.710 --> 04:23:20.010
big words and dramatic gestures, and imagined that the child was making fun of her. So she said

04:23:20.010 --> 04:23:26.130
coldly and cruelly, I don't think you are a fit little girl for Diana to associate with.

04:23:26.450 --> 04:23:33.290
You'd better go home and behave yourself. Anne's lips quivered. Won't you let me see Diana

04:23:33.290 --> 04:23:40.130
just once to say farewell? she implored. Diana has gone to Carmody with her father,

04:23:40.590 --> 04:23:47.470
said Mrs. Barry, going in and shutting the door. Anne went back to Green Gables calm with despair.

04:23:48.330 --> 04:23:54.650
My last hope is gone, she told Marilla. I went up and saw Mrs. Barry myself,

04:23:54.890 --> 04:24:00.910
and she treated me very insultingly. Marilla, I do not think she is a well-bred woman.

04:24:01.390 --> 04:24:06.270
There is nothing more to do except to pray, and I haven't much hope that'll do much good,

04:24:06.290 --> 04:24:11.670
because, Marilla, I do not believe that God himself can do very much with such an obstinate

04:24:11.670 --> 04:24:19.630
person as Mrs. Barry. Anne, you shouldn't say such things, rebuked Marilla, striving to overcome

04:24:19.630 --> 04:24:25.770
that unholy tendency to laughter which she was dismayed to find growing upon her. And indeed,

04:24:25.890 --> 04:24:31.190
when she told the whole story to Matthew that night, she did laugh heartily over Anne's

04:24:31.190 --> 04:24:36.750
tribulations. But when she slipped into the East Gable before going to bed, and found that Anne

04:24:36.750 --> 04:24:43.230
had cried herself to sleep, an unaccustomed softness crept into her face. Poor little soul,

04:24:43.410 --> 04:24:48.010
she murmured, lifting a loose curl of hair from the child's tear-stained face.

04:24:48.590 --> 04:24:52.230
Then she bent down and kissed the flushed cheek on the pillow.

04:25:17.950 --> 04:25:21.530
The next afternoon Anne, bending over her patchwork at the kitchen

04:25:21.530 --> 04:25:27.410
happened to glance out and beheld Diana down by the diet's bubble beckoning mysteriously.

04:25:27.950 --> 04:25:31.270
In a trice Anne was out of the house and flying down the hollow,

04:25:31.850 --> 04:25:34.670
astonishment and hope struggling in her expressive eyes.

04:25:35.090 --> 04:25:38.310
But the hope faded when she saw Diana's dejected countenance.

04:25:38.750 --> 04:25:41.410
Your mother hasn't relented? she gasped.

04:25:41.650 --> 04:25:43.330
Diana shook her head mournfully.

04:25:43.830 --> 04:25:47.710
No, and oh, Anne, she says I'm never to play with you again.

04:25:47.870 --> 04:25:50.750
I've cried and cried and I told her it wasn't your fault,

04:25:50.750 --> 04:25:52.210
but it wasn't any use.

04:25:52.490 --> 04:25:56.670
I had ever such a time coaxing her to let me come down and say goodbye to you.

04:25:56.970 --> 04:26:00.590
She said I was only to stay ten minutes and she's timing me by the clock.

04:26:01.570 --> 04:26:06.370
Ten minutes isn't very long to say an eternal farewell in, said Anne tearfully.

04:26:06.970 --> 04:26:10.390
Oh, Diana, will you promise faithfully never to forget me,

04:26:10.450 --> 04:26:13.950
the friend of your youth, no matter what dearer friends may caress thee?

04:26:15.250 --> 04:26:19.890
Indeed I will, sobbed Diana, and I'll never have another bosom friend.

04:26:19.890 --> 04:26:21.290
I don't want to have.

04:26:21.590 --> 04:26:23.890
I couldn't love anybody as I love you.

04:26:24.510 --> 04:26:27.630
Oh, Diana, cried Anne, clasping her hands.

04:26:27.990 --> 04:26:29.350
Do you love me?

04:26:30.690 --> 04:26:32.130
Why, of course I do.

04:26:32.310 --> 04:26:33.530
Didn't you know that?

04:26:34.230 --> 04:26:37.190
No, Anne drew a long breath.

04:26:38.030 --> 04:26:41.650
I thought you liked me, of course, but I never hoped you loved me.

04:26:42.030 --> 04:26:44.910
Why, Diana, I didn't think anybody could love me.

04:26:45.250 --> 04:26:47.950
Nobody ever has loved me since I can remember.

04:26:47.950 --> 04:26:49.730
Oh, this is wonderful.

04:26:50.090 --> 04:26:54.030
It's a ray of light which will forever shine on the darkness of the path,

04:26:54.210 --> 04:26:55.570
severed from thee, Diana.

04:26:55.950 --> 04:26:57.550
Oh, just say it once again.

04:26:58.310 --> 04:27:02.090
I love you devotedly, Anne, said Diana staunchly,

04:27:02.170 --> 04:27:03.690
and I always will.

04:27:03.830 --> 04:27:05.350
You may be sure of that.

04:27:06.190 --> 04:27:12.150
And I will always love thee, Diana, said Anne solemnly extending her hand.

04:27:12.670 --> 04:27:17.050
In the years to come, thy memory will shine like a star

04:27:17.050 --> 04:27:21.510
over my lonely life, as that last story we read together says.

04:27:22.070 --> 04:27:26.430
Diana, wilt thou give me a lock of thy jet-black tresses

04:27:26.430 --> 04:27:29.130
imparting to treasure forevermore?

04:27:30.230 --> 04:27:31.990
Have you got anything to cut it with?

04:27:32.170 --> 04:27:36.730
queried Diana, wiping away the tears which Anne's affecting accents

04:27:36.730 --> 04:27:40.390
had caused to flow fresh and returning to practicalities.

04:27:41.210 --> 04:27:46.210
Yes, I've got my patchwork scissors in my apron pocket, fortunately, said Anne.

04:27:46.210 --> 04:27:49.350
She solemnly clipped one of Diana's curls.

04:27:50.270 --> 04:27:52.730
Fare thee well, my beloved friend.

04:27:53.290 --> 04:27:57.050
Henceforth we must be as strangers, though living side by side,

04:27:57.290 --> 04:28:00.290
but my heart will ever be faithful to thee.

04:28:01.470 --> 04:28:04.070
Anne stood and watched Diana out of sight,

04:28:04.570 --> 04:28:07.850
mournfully waving her hand to the latter whenever she turned to look.

04:28:08.630 --> 04:28:10.550
Then she returned to the house,

04:28:10.890 --> 04:28:14.530
not a little consoled for the time being by this romantic parting.

04:28:16.450 --> 04:28:19.910
It's all over, she informed Marilla.

04:28:20.430 --> 04:28:22.490
I shall never have another friend.

04:28:23.050 --> 04:28:24.890
I'm really worse off than ever before,

04:28:25.030 --> 04:28:27.610
for I haven't Katie Morris and Violetta now.

04:28:28.570 --> 04:28:31.070
And even if I had, it wouldn't be the same.

04:28:31.610 --> 04:28:36.210
Somehow little dream girls are not satisfying after a real friend.

04:28:37.070 --> 04:28:40.530
Diana and I had such an affecting farewell down by the spring.

04:28:40.870 --> 04:28:43.370
It will be sacred in my memory forever.

04:28:43.370 --> 04:28:46.870
I used the most pathetic language I could think of and said,

04:28:47.230 --> 04:28:51.750
Thou and thee. Thou and thee seem so much more romantic than you.

04:28:52.610 --> 04:28:54.210
Diana gave me a lock of her hair,

04:28:54.250 --> 04:28:58.670
and I'm going to sew it up in a little bag and wear it around my neck all my life.

04:28:59.350 --> 04:29:03.550
Please see that it is buried with me, for I don't believe I'll live very long.

04:29:04.010 --> 04:29:07.910
Perhaps when she sees me lying cold and dead before her,

04:29:08.050 --> 04:29:10.970
Mrs. Berry might feel remorse for what she has done

04:29:10.970 --> 04:29:13.410
and will let Diana come to my funeral.

04:29:14.850 --> 04:29:18.690
I don't think there is much fear of your dying of grief,

04:29:18.990 --> 04:29:23.070
as long as you can talk, Anne, said Marilla unsympathetically.

04:29:23.710 --> 04:29:27.770
The following Monday, Anne surprised Marilla by coming down from her room

04:29:27.770 --> 04:29:32.970
with her basket of books on her arm and hip and her lips primmed up into a line of determination.

04:29:33.690 --> 04:29:36.050
I am going back to school, she announced.

04:29:36.390 --> 04:29:38.730
That is all that is left in life for me,

04:29:38.730 --> 04:29:41.690
now that my friend has been ruthlessly torn from me.

04:29:42.030 --> 04:29:45.070
In school I can look at her and muse over days departed.

04:29:46.070 --> 04:29:50.510
You had better muse over your lessons and sums, said Marilla,

04:29:51.250 --> 04:29:54.170
concealing her delight at this development of the situation.

04:29:54.810 --> 04:29:59.110
If you are going back to school, I hope we'll hear no more of breaking slates

04:29:59.110 --> 04:30:05.070
over people's heads and such careings on. Behave yourself and do just what your teacher tells you.

04:30:06.210 --> 04:30:09.470
I'll try to be a model pupil, agreed Anne dolefully.

04:30:10.390 --> 04:30:12.150
There won't be much fun in it, I expect.

04:30:12.830 --> 04:30:16.070
Mr. Phillips said Minnie Andrews was a model pupil,

04:30:16.190 --> 04:30:19.090
and there isn't a spark of imagination or life in her.

04:30:19.350 --> 04:30:23.310
She is just dull and pokey and never seems to have a good time.

04:30:23.810 --> 04:30:27.510
But I feel so depressed that perhaps it will come easy to me now.

04:30:28.090 --> 04:30:29.810
I'm going round by the road.

04:30:30.070 --> 04:30:33.110
I couldn't bear to go by the birch path all alone.

04:30:33.110 --> 04:30:35.970
I should weep bitter tears if I did.

04:30:38.510 --> 04:30:41.290
Anne was welcomed back to school with open arms.

04:30:41.610 --> 04:30:45.590
Her imagination had been sorely missed in games, her voice in the singing,

04:30:45.790 --> 04:30:49.690
and her dramatic ability in the perusal or loud of books at dinner hour.

04:30:50.350 --> 04:30:54.650
Ruby Gillis smuggled three blue plums over to her during testament reading.

04:30:55.230 --> 04:31:01.230
Ella MacPherson gave her an enormous yellow pansy cut from the covers of a floral catalogue,

04:31:01.230 --> 04:31:05.050
a species of desk decoration much prized in Evanley School.

04:31:06.070 --> 04:31:10.930
Sophia Sloan offered to teach her a perfectly elegant new pattern of knit lace,

04:31:11.350 --> 04:31:13.310
so nice for trimming aprons.

04:31:13.830 --> 04:31:17.590
Katie Bolter gave her a perfume bottle to keep slate water in.

04:31:18.270 --> 04:31:22.370
And Julia Bell copied carefully on a piece of pale pink paper

04:31:22.370 --> 04:31:24.650
scalloped on the edges the falling effusion.

04:31:25.330 --> 04:31:29.410
When twilight drops her curtain down and pins it with a star,

04:31:29.410 --> 04:31:32.930
remember that you have a friend, though she may wander far.

04:31:34.250 --> 04:31:39.270
It is so nice to be appreciated, sighed Anne rapturously to Marilla that night.

04:31:40.750 --> 04:31:44.050
The girls were not the only scholars who appreciated her.

04:31:44.610 --> 04:31:46.930
When Anne went to her seat after dinner hour,

04:31:47.130 --> 04:31:50.870
she had been told by Mr. Phillips to sit with the model Minnie Andrews.

04:31:51.050 --> 04:31:54.530
She found on her desk a big luscious strawberry apple.

04:31:55.210 --> 04:31:58.530
Anne cut it up all ready to take a bite when she remembered

04:31:58.530 --> 04:32:02.050
that the only place in Evanley where strawberry apples grew

04:32:02.050 --> 04:32:07.510
was in the old Blythe Orchard on the other side of Lake of Shining Waters.

04:32:08.570 --> 04:32:11.470
Anne dropped the apple as if it were a red-hot coal

04:32:11.470 --> 04:32:15.010
and ostentatiously wiped her fingers on her handkerchief.

04:32:16.190 --> 04:32:19.330
The apple lay untouched on her desk until the next morning

04:32:19.330 --> 04:32:24.230
when little Timothy Andrews, who swept the school and kindled the fire,

04:32:24.490 --> 04:32:26.290
annexed it as one of his prerequisites.

04:32:27.490 --> 04:32:34.090
Charlie Sloane's slate pencil, gorgeously bedizened with striped red and yellow paper,

04:32:34.570 --> 04:32:38.470
costing two cents, where ordinary pencils cost only one,

04:32:38.950 --> 04:32:43.370
which he sent up to her after dinner hour, met with a more favourable reception.

04:32:44.330 --> 04:32:48.850
Anne was graciously pleased to accept it and rewarded the donor with a smile,

04:32:49.190 --> 04:32:54.110
which exalted that infatuated youth straight away into the seventh heaven of delight,

04:32:54.750 --> 04:32:58.250
and caused him to make such fearful errors in his dictation

04:32:58.250 --> 04:33:01.250
that Mr. Phillips kept him in after school to rewrite it.

04:33:02.010 --> 04:33:05.910
But as the Caesar's pageants, shorn of Brutus Bus,

04:33:06.190 --> 04:33:09.110
did but of Rome's best son remind her more.

04:33:09.870 --> 04:33:13.930
So the market absent of any tribute or recognition from Diana Barry,

04:33:14.030 --> 04:33:17.990
who was sitting with Gertie Pyle, embittered Anne's little triumph.

04:33:19.270 --> 04:33:24.270
"'Diana might just have smiled at me once, I think,' she mourned to Marilla that night.

04:33:24.950 --> 04:33:30.210
The next morning a note most fearfully and wonderfully twisted and folded

04:33:30.210 --> 04:33:33.050
and a small parcel were passed across to Anne.

04:33:33.770 --> 04:33:35.510
"'Dear Anne,' ran the former,

04:33:35.690 --> 04:33:39.890
"'Mother says I'm not to play with you or talk to you even in school.

04:33:40.070 --> 04:33:44.450
It isn't my fault, and don't be cross at me because I love you as much as ever.

04:33:44.450 --> 04:33:50.670
I miss you awfully to tell all my secrets to, and I don't like Gertie Pyle one bit.

04:33:51.350 --> 04:33:54.570
I made one of the new bookmarkers out of red tissue paper.

04:33:54.930 --> 04:33:59.610
They are awfully fashionable now, and only three girls in school know how to make them.

04:34:00.090 --> 04:34:04.050
When you look at it, remember your true friend, Diana Barry.'

04:34:05.790 --> 04:34:10.030
Anne read the note, kissed the bookmark, and dispatched a prompt reply

04:34:10.030 --> 04:34:11.790
back to the other side of the school.

04:34:12.910 --> 04:34:19.070
"'My own darling Diana, of course I am not cross at you because you have to obey your mother.

04:34:19.570 --> 04:34:23.990
Our spirits can commune. I shall keep your lovely present forever.

04:34:24.750 --> 04:34:28.590
Minnie Andrews is a very nice little girl, although she has no imagination.

04:34:29.050 --> 04:34:33.150
But after having been Diana's bosom friend, I cannot be Minnie's.

04:34:34.010 --> 04:34:38.890
Please excuse mistakes, as my spelling isn't very good yet, although much improved.

04:34:39.530 --> 04:34:44.630
Yours until death us do part, Anne or Cordelia, surely.

04:34:45.630 --> 04:34:51.010
P.S. I shall sleep with your letter under my pillow tonight, A or C.S.'

04:34:54.110 --> 04:34:59.010
Marilla pessimistically expected more trouble since Anne had again begun to go to school,

04:34:59.330 --> 04:35:03.530
but none developed. Perhaps Anne caught something of the

04:35:04.170 --> 04:35:09.330
from Minnie Andrews. At least she got on very well with Mr. Phillips thenceforth.

04:35:09.970 --> 04:35:16.030
She flung herself into her study's heart and soul, determined not to be outdone in any class by

04:35:16.030 --> 04:35:22.150
Gilbert Blythe. The rivalry between them was soon apparent. It was entirely good-natured

04:35:22.150 --> 04:35:27.090
on Gilbert's side, but it is much to be feared that the same thing cannot be said of Anne,

04:35:27.210 --> 04:35:31.170
who had certainly an unpraised worthy tenacity for holding grudges.

04:35:31.930 --> 04:35:38.050
She was as intense in her hatreds as in her loves. She would not stoop to admit that she

04:35:38.050 --> 04:35:42.990
meant to rival Gilbert in schoolwork, because that would have been to acknowledge his existence,

04:35:43.210 --> 04:35:49.730
which Anne persistently ignored. But the rivalry was there, and honours fluctuated between them.

04:35:50.290 --> 04:35:56.210
Now Gilbert was head of the spelling class, now Anne, with a toss of her long red braids,

04:35:56.210 --> 04:36:02.490
spelled him down. One morning Gilbert had all his sums done correctly and had his name written on

04:36:02.490 --> 04:36:08.770
the blackboard on the roll of honour. The next morning Anne, having wrestled wildly with

04:36:08.770 --> 04:36:15.090
decimals the entire evening before, would be first. One awful day they were ties,

04:36:15.470 --> 04:36:20.330
and their names were written up together. It was almost as bad as a take notice,

04:36:20.330 --> 04:36:25.030
and Anne's mortification was as evident as Gilbert's satisfaction.

04:36:26.030 --> 04:36:30.910
When the written examinations at the end of each month were held, the suspense was terrible.

04:36:31.430 --> 04:36:37.810
The first month, Gilbert came out three marks ahead. The second, Anne beat him by five. But

04:36:37.810 --> 04:36:43.030
her triumph was marred by the fact that Gilbert congratulated her heartily before the whole school.

04:36:43.550 --> 04:36:48.030
It would have been ever so much sweeter to her if he had felt the sting of his defeat.

04:36:48.030 --> 04:36:55.510
Mr. Phillips might not be a very good teacher, but a pupil so inflexibly determined on learning

04:36:55.510 --> 04:36:59.970
as Anne was, could hardly escape making progress under any kind of teacher.

04:37:00.790 --> 04:37:06.230
By the end of term, Anne and Gilbert were both promoted into the fifth class and allowed to

04:37:06.230 --> 04:37:12.390
begin studying the elements of the branches, by which Latin, Geometry, French and Algebra were

04:37:13.210 --> 04:37:16.210
In geometry, Anne met her Waterloo.

04:37:17.150 --> 04:37:24.870
It's perfectly awful stuff, Marilla, she groaned. I'm sure I'll never be able to make head or

04:37:24.870 --> 04:37:31.670
tail of it. There is no scope for imagination in it at all. Mr. Phillips says I'm the worst

04:37:31.670 --> 04:37:38.150
dunce he ever saw at it, and Gil, I mean some of the others, are so smart at it. It is extremely

04:37:38.150 --> 04:37:44.910
mortifying, Marilla. Even Diana gets along better than I do, but I don't mind being beaten by Diana.

04:37:45.690 --> 04:37:49.450
Even though we meet as strangers now, I still love her with an

04:37:50.250 --> 04:37:54.530
inextinguishable love. It makes me very sad at times to think about her.

04:37:55.390 --> 04:38:01.030
But really, Marilla, one can't stay sad very long in such an interesting world can one?

04:38:08.150 --> 04:38:11.590
February 11, 2006

04:38:40.090 --> 04:38:43.310
All things great are wound up with all things little.

04:38:44.250 --> 04:38:49.990
At first glance it might not seem that the decision of a certain Canadian Premier to

04:38:49.990 --> 04:38:55.710
include Prince Edward Island in a political tour could have much or anything to do with

04:38:55.710 --> 04:39:00.390
the fortunes of little Anne Shirley at Green Gables, but it had.

04:39:01.230 --> 04:39:08.390
It was a January the Premier came, to address his loyal supporters and such of his non-supporters

04:39:08.390 --> 04:39:13.790
as chose to be present at the monster mass meeting held in Charlottetown.

04:39:14.710 --> 04:39:20.410
Most of the Avonlea people were on the Premier's side of politics, hence on the night of the

04:39:20.410 --> 04:39:27.090
meeting nearly all the men and a goodly proportion of the women had gone to town thirty miles

04:39:27.090 --> 04:39:27.710
away.

04:39:28.710 --> 04:39:30.950
Mrs. Rachel Lynde had gone too.

04:39:31.450 --> 04:39:37.090
Mrs. Rachel Lynde was a red-hot politician and couldn't have believed that the political

04:39:37.090 --> 04:39:42.110
rally could be carried through without her, although she was on the opposite side of the

04:39:42.110 --> 04:39:42.610
politics.

04:39:43.330 --> 04:39:48.690
So she went to town and took her husband, Thomas would be useful in looking after the

04:39:48.690 --> 04:39:51.510
horse, and Marilla Cuthbert with her.

04:39:52.430 --> 04:39:58.310
Marilla had a sneaking interest in politics herself, and as she thought it might be her

04:39:58.310 --> 04:40:04.790
only chance to see a real live Premier, she promptly took it, leaving Anne and Matthew

04:40:04.790 --> 04:40:07.830
to keep house until her return the following day.

04:40:08.830 --> 04:40:15.370
Hence while Marilla and Mrs. Rachel were enjoying themselves hugely at the mass meeting, Anne

04:40:15.370 --> 04:40:19.430
and Matthew had the cheerful kitchen at Green Gables all to themselves.

04:40:20.010 --> 04:40:26.790
A bright fire was glowing in the old-fashioned Waterloo stove, and blue-white frost crystals

04:40:26.790 --> 04:40:29.230
were shining on the window panes.

04:40:29.790 --> 04:40:35.990
Matthew nodded over a farmer's advocate on the sofa, and Anne at the table studied her

04:40:35.990 --> 04:40:43.450
lessons with grim determination, despite sundry, wistful glances at the clock-shelf where lay

04:40:43.450 --> 04:40:47.250
a new book that Jane Andrews had lent her that day.

04:40:48.110 --> 04:40:54.130
Jane had assured her that it was warranted to produce any number of thrills or words

04:40:54.130 --> 04:40:58.670
to that effect, and Anne's fingers tingled to reach out for it.

04:40:58.970 --> 04:41:03.130
But that would mean Gilbert Blythe triumph on the moral.

04:41:04.070 --> 04:41:08.790
Anne turned her back on the clock-shelf and tried to imagine it wasn't there.

04:41:09.770 --> 04:41:14.010
Matthew, did you ever study geometry when you went to school?

04:41:14.830 --> 04:41:19.930
Well, now, no, I didn't, said Matthew, coming out of his doze with a start.

04:41:20.460 --> 04:41:25.570
I wish you had, sighed Anne, because then you'd be able to sympathize with me.

04:41:25.790 --> 04:41:29.450
You can't sympathize properly if you've never studied it.

04:41:29.910 --> 04:41:33.590
It is casting a cloud over my whole life.

04:41:33.890 --> 04:41:36.310
I'm such a dunce at it, Matthew.

04:41:36.890 --> 04:41:42.210
Well now, I don't know, said Matthew soothingly, I guess you're all right at anything.

04:41:42.750 --> 04:41:48.670
Mr. Phillips told me last week in Blair's store at Carmody that you was the smartest

04:41:48.670 --> 04:41:52.230
scholar in school and was making rapid progress.

04:41:52.930 --> 04:41:55.570
Rapid progress was his very words.

04:41:56.250 --> 04:42:02.210
There's them as runs down Teddy Phillips and says he ain't much of a teacher, but I guess

04:42:02.210 --> 04:42:03.210
he's all right.

04:42:04.070 --> 04:42:08.230
Matthew would have thought anyone who praised Anne was all right.

04:42:08.690 --> 04:42:14.230
I'm sure I'd get on better with geometry if only he wouldn't change the letters, complained

04:42:14.230 --> 04:42:14.770
Anne.

04:42:14.770 --> 04:42:21.330
I learn the proposition off by heart and then he draws it on the blackboard and puts different

04:42:21.330 --> 04:42:25.190
letters from what are in the book and I get all mixed up.

04:42:25.630 --> 04:42:29.910
I don't think a teacher should take such a mean advantage, do you?

04:42:30.350 --> 04:42:35.990
We're studying agriculture now and I found out at last what makes the roads red.

04:42:36.410 --> 04:42:37.770
It's a great comfort.

04:42:38.230 --> 04:42:41.610
I wonder how Marilla and Mrs. Lynde are enjoying themselves.

04:42:42.170 --> 04:42:47.910
Mrs. Lynde says Canada is going to the dogs the way things are being run at Ottawa and

04:42:47.910 --> 04:42:50.670
that it's an awful warning to the electors.

04:42:51.070 --> 04:42:55.690
She says if women were allowed to vote we would soon see a blessed change.

04:42:56.350 --> 04:42:57.890
What way do you vote, Matthew?

04:42:58.770 --> 04:43:00.610
Conservative, said Matthew promptly.

04:43:01.170 --> 04:43:04.090
To vote Conservative was part of Matthew's religion.

04:43:04.730 --> 04:43:07.970
Then I'm Conservative too, said Anne decidedly.

04:43:07.970 --> 04:43:13.010
I'm glad because, Gill, because some of the boys in school are grits.

04:43:13.310 --> 04:43:19.710
I guess Mr. Phillips is a grit too because Prissy Andrews' father is one and Ruby Gillis

04:43:19.710 --> 04:43:25.070
says that when a man is courting he always has to agree with a girl's mother in religion

04:43:25.070 --> 04:43:27.170
and her father in politics.

04:43:27.590 --> 04:43:29.030
Is that true, Matthew?

04:43:29.510 --> 04:43:31.970
Well now, I don't know, said Matthew.

04:43:32.390 --> 04:43:34.390
Did you ever go courting, Matthew?

04:43:34.990 --> 04:43:36.450
Well now, no.

04:43:36.450 --> 04:43:41.910
I don't know as I ever did, said Matthew, who had certainly never thought of such a

04:43:41.910 --> 04:43:46.490
thing in his whole existence, and reflected with her chin in her hands.

04:43:46.890 --> 04:43:50.250
It might be rather interesting, don't you think, Matthew?

04:43:50.570 --> 04:43:56.830
Ruby Gillis says when she grows up she's going to have ever so many bows on the string and

04:43:56.830 --> 04:43:58.750
have them all crazy about her.

04:43:58.990 --> 04:44:01.190
But I think that would be too exciting.

04:44:01.610 --> 04:44:04.550
I'd rather have just one in his right mind.

04:44:04.550 --> 04:44:10.230
But Ruby Gillis knows a great deal about such matters because she has so many big sisters.

04:44:10.750 --> 04:44:14.690
And Mrs. Lynn says the Gillis girls have gone off like hotcakes.

04:44:15.370 --> 04:44:19.410
Mr. Phillips goes to see Prissy Andrews nearly every evening.

04:44:19.810 --> 04:44:25.350
He says it is to help her with her lessons, but Miranda Sloan is studying for Queens too,

04:44:25.670 --> 04:44:31.290
and I should think she needed help a lot more than Prissy because she's ever so much stupider.

04:44:31.750 --> 04:44:34.930
But he never goes to help her in the evenings at all.

04:44:35.530 --> 04:44:40.410
There are a great many things in this world that I can't understand very well, Matthew.

04:44:41.150 --> 04:44:46.710
Well now, I don't know as I comprehend them all myself, acknowledged Matthew.

04:44:48.210 --> 04:44:51.330
Well I suppose I must finish up my lessons.

04:44:51.710 --> 04:44:55.850
I won't allow myself to open that new book Jane lent me till I'm through.

04:44:56.350 --> 04:44:58.750
But it's a terrible temptation, Matthew.

04:44:58.750 --> 04:45:03.110
Even when I turn my back on it, I can see it there just as plain.

04:45:03.690 --> 04:45:06.230
Jane said she cried herself sick over it.

04:45:06.490 --> 04:45:11.710
I love a book that makes me cry, but I think I'll carry that book into the sitting room

04:45:11.710 --> 04:45:15.490
and lock it in the jam closet and give you the key.

04:45:15.850 --> 04:45:20.290
And you must not give it to me, Matthew, until my lessons are done.

04:45:20.690 --> 04:45:24.230
Not even if I implore you on my bended knees.

04:45:24.230 --> 04:45:30.430
It's all very well to say resist temptation, but it's ever so much easier to resist it

04:45:30.430 --> 04:45:31.890
if you can't get the key.

04:45:32.350 --> 04:45:35.870
And then, shall I run down the cellar and get some russets, Matthew?

04:45:36.190 --> 04:45:37.690
Would you like some russets?

04:45:38.150 --> 04:45:44.410
Well now, I don't know but what I would, said Matthew, who never ate russets but knew

04:45:44.410 --> 04:45:45.850
Anne's weakness for them.

04:45:46.810 --> 04:45:51.890
Just as Anne emerged triumphantly from the cellar with her plateful of russets came the

04:45:51.890 --> 04:45:58.350
round of flying footsteps on the icy boardwalk outside and the next moment the kitchen door

04:45:58.350 --> 04:46:05.470
was flung open and in rushed Diana Berry, white-faced and breathless, with a shawl wrapped

04:46:05.470 --> 04:46:11.130
hastily around her head, Anne promptly let go of her candle and plate in her surprise

04:46:11.130 --> 04:46:17.410
and plate, candle and apples crashed together down the cellar ladder and were found at the

04:46:17.410 --> 04:46:23.050
bottom, embedded in melted grease, the next day, by Marilla, who gathered them up and

04:46:23.050 --> 04:46:26.010
thanked mercy the house hadn't been set on fire.

04:46:26.470 --> 04:46:28.310
Whatever is the matter, Diana?

04:46:28.550 --> 04:46:29.090
cried Anne.

04:46:29.430 --> 04:46:31.310
Has your mother relented at last?

04:46:31.630 --> 04:46:35.150
Oh, Anne, do come quick, implored Diana nervously.

04:46:35.670 --> 04:46:37.310
Minnie May is awful sick.

04:46:37.650 --> 04:46:38.830
She's got croup.

04:46:39.190 --> 04:46:40.530
Young Mary Jo says.

04:46:40.950 --> 04:46:45.210
And father and mother are away to town and there's nobody to go for the doctor.

04:46:45.770 --> 04:46:51.650
Minnie May is awful bad and young Mary Jo doesn't know what to do and oh, Anne, I'm

04:46:51.650 --> 04:46:52.730
so scared.

04:46:53.710 --> 04:46:59.290
Matthew without a word reached out for coat and cap, slipped past Diana and away into

04:46:59.290 --> 04:47:00.430
the darkness of the yard.

04:47:01.170 --> 04:47:06.750
He's gone to harness the sorrel mare to go to Carmody for the doctor, said Anne, who was

04:47:06.750 --> 04:47:08.310
hurrying on hood and jacket.

04:47:08.670 --> 04:47:11.210
I know it as well as if he'd said so.

04:47:11.210 --> 04:47:15.970
Matthew and I are such kindred spirits, I can read his thoughts without words at all.

04:47:16.610 --> 04:47:20.430
I don't believe he'll find the doctor at Carmody, sobbed Diana.

04:47:21.050 --> 04:47:26.050
I know that Dr. Blair went to town and I guess Dr. Spencer would go too.

04:47:26.530 --> 04:47:30.950
Young Mary Jo never saw anybody with croup and Mrs. Lynde is away.

04:47:31.310 --> 04:47:32.370
Oh, Anne.

04:47:32.850 --> 04:47:35.130
Don't cry, Dee, said Anne cheerfully.

04:47:35.430 --> 04:47:37.590
I know exactly what to do for croup.

04:47:37.590 --> 04:47:40.910
You forget that Mrs. Hammond had twins three times.

04:47:41.250 --> 04:47:45.850
When you look after three pairs of twins you naturally get a lot of experience.

04:47:46.270 --> 04:47:48.050
They all had croup regularly.

04:47:48.950 --> 04:47:51.470
Just wait till I get the Epikak bottle.

04:47:51.790 --> 04:47:53.690
You mayn't have any at your house.

04:47:53.990 --> 04:47:54.790
Come on now.

04:47:55.710 --> 04:48:00.630
The two little girls hastened out hand in hand and hurried through Lover's Lane and

04:48:00.630 --> 04:48:06.090
crossed the crusted field beyond, for the snow was too deep to go by the shorter wood

04:48:06.830 --> 04:48:12.830
Anne, although sincerely sorry for many, way, was far from being insensible to the romance

04:48:12.830 --> 04:48:18.610
of the situation and to the sweetness of once more sharing that romance with a kindred spirit.

04:48:19.150 --> 04:48:25.250
The night was clear and frosty, all ebony of shadow and silver of snowy slope.

04:48:25.790 --> 04:48:28.650
Big stars were shining over the silent fields.

04:48:29.110 --> 04:48:35.010
Here and there the dark pointed firs stood up with snow powdering their branches and

04:48:35.010 --> 04:48:36.810
the wind whistling through them.

04:48:37.490 --> 04:48:43.430
Anne thought it was truly delightful to go skimming through all this mystery and loveliness

04:48:43.430 --> 04:48:47.430
with your bosom friend who had been so long estranged.

04:48:48.470 --> 04:48:51.490
Minnie May, age three, was really very sick.

04:48:51.890 --> 04:48:57.230
She lay on this kitchen sofa feverish and restless, while her hoarse breathing could

04:48:57.230 --> 04:48:59.010
be heard all over the house.

04:48:59.410 --> 04:49:06.070
Young Mary Jo, a buxom broad-faced French girl from the creek, who Mrs. Barry had engaged

04:49:06.070 --> 04:49:12.070
to stay with the children during her absence, was helpless and bewildered, quite incapable

04:49:12.070 --> 04:49:15.790
of thinking what to do, or doing it if she thought of it.

04:49:16.970 --> 04:49:19.610
Anne went to work with skill and promptness.

04:49:20.370 --> 04:49:24.890
Minnie May has croup all right, she's pretty bad, but I've seen them worse.

04:49:25.310 --> 04:49:27.390
First we must have lots of hot water.

04:49:27.390 --> 04:49:31.530
I declare, Diana, there isn't more than a cupful in the kettle.

04:49:32.050 --> 04:49:35.870
There, I filled it up, and, Mary Jo, you may put some wood in the stove.

04:49:36.210 --> 04:49:39.930
I don't want to hurt your feelings, but it seems to me you might have thought of this

04:49:39.930 --> 04:49:42.130
before if you'd any imagination.

04:49:42.650 --> 04:49:48.250
Now I'll undress Minnie May and put her to bed, and you try to find some soft flannel

04:49:48.250 --> 04:49:49.110
cloths, Diana.

04:49:49.430 --> 04:49:53.130
I'm going to give her a dose of Ipecac first of all.

04:49:53.730 --> 04:49:59.890
Minnie May did not take kindly to the Ipecac, but Anne had not brought up three pairs of

04:49:59.890 --> 04:50:00.710
twins for nothing.

04:50:01.410 --> 04:50:07.930
Down that Ipecac went, not only once but many times during the long anxious night when the

04:50:07.930 --> 04:50:14.030
two little girls worked patiently over the suffering Minnie May, and young Mary Jo, honestly

04:50:14.030 --> 04:50:20.090
anxious to do all she could, kept up a roaring fire and heated more water than would have

04:50:20.090 --> 04:50:23.270
been needed for a hospital full of creepy babies.

04:50:24.070 --> 04:50:29.070
It was three o'clock when Matthew came with a doctor, for he had been obliged to go all

04:50:29.070 --> 04:50:33.910
the way to Spencer Vale for one, but the pressing need for assistance was past.

04:50:34.590 --> 04:50:37.690
Minnie May was much better and was sleeping soundly.

04:50:38.030 --> 04:50:41.810
I was awfully near giving up in despair, explained Anne.

04:50:41.990 --> 04:50:47.570
She got worse and worse until she was sicker than ever the Hammond twins were, even the

04:50:47.570 --> 04:50:48.410
last pair.

04:50:48.930 --> 04:50:51.310
I actually thought she was going to choke to death.

04:50:51.710 --> 04:50:57.250
I gave her every last drop of Ipecac in that bottle, and when the last dose went down I

04:50:57.250 --> 04:51:03.290
said to myself, not to Diana or young Mary Jo, because I didn't want to worry them any

04:51:03.290 --> 04:51:08.290
more than they were worried, but I had to say it to myself just to relieve my feelings.

04:51:08.750 --> 04:51:13.010
This is the last lingering hope, and I fear to savain one.

04:51:13.350 --> 04:51:18.470
But in about three minutes she coughed up the phlegm and began to get better right away.

04:51:18.790 --> 04:51:23.810
You must just imagine my relief, Doctor, because I can't express it in words.

04:51:24.210 --> 04:51:27.610
You know there are some things that cannot be expressed in words.

04:51:28.110 --> 04:51:30.130
Yes, I know, nodded the Doctor.

04:51:30.590 --> 04:51:35.250
He looked at Anne as if he were thinking some things about her that couldn't be expressed

04:51:35.250 --> 04:51:35.850
in words.

04:51:36.370 --> 04:51:39.830
Later on, however, he expressed them to Mr. and Mrs. Barry.

04:51:40.490 --> 04:51:47.050
That little red-headed girl they have over at Cuthbert's is as smart as they make them.

04:51:47.350 --> 04:51:52.190
I tell you she saved that baby's life, for it would have been too late by the time I

04:51:52.190 --> 04:51:52.810
got there.

04:51:53.090 --> 04:51:57.970
She seems to have a skill and presence of mind perfectly wonderful in a child of her

04:51:57.970 --> 04:51:58.250
age.

04:51:58.670 --> 04:52:03.310
I never saw anything like the eyes of her when she was explaining the case to me.

04:52:04.270 --> 04:52:09.550
Anne had gone home in the wonderful white frosted winter morning, heavy-eyed from loss

04:52:09.550 --> 04:52:15.390
of sleep, but still talking un-weirdly to Matthew as they crossed the long white field

04:52:15.390 --> 04:52:19.570
and walked under the glittering fairy arch of the lovers' lane maples.

04:52:20.210 --> 04:52:23.090
Oh, Matthew, isn't it a wonderful morning?

04:52:23.470 --> 04:52:28.850
The world looks like something God had just imagined for his own pleasure, doesn't it?

04:52:29.250 --> 04:52:33.030
Those trees look as if I could blow them away with a breath.

04:52:33.470 --> 04:52:33.910
Poof!

04:52:34.470 --> 04:52:38.750
I'm so glad I live in a world where there are white frosts, aren't you?

04:52:39.050 --> 04:52:42.910
And I'm so glad Mrs. Hammond had three pairs of twins after all.

04:52:43.310 --> 04:52:47.310
If she hadn't, I might not have known what to do for Minnie May.

04:52:47.750 --> 04:52:51.890
I'm real sorry I was ever cross with Mrs. Hammond for having twins.

04:52:52.370 --> 04:52:54.770
But oh, Matthew, I'm so sleepy.

04:52:55.030 --> 04:52:56.430
I can't go to school.

04:52:56.790 --> 04:53:00.530
I just know I couldn't keep my eyes open and I'd be so stupid.

04:53:00.930 --> 04:53:03.230
But I hate to stay home for Gill.

04:53:03.230 --> 04:53:08.950
Some of the others will get ahead of the class, and it's so hard to get up again.

04:53:09.270 --> 04:53:15.010
Although, of course, the harder it is, the more satisfaction you have when you do get up, haven't you?

04:53:15.550 --> 04:53:21.110
Well, now I guess you'll manage all right, said Matthew, looking at Anne's white little face

04:53:21.110 --> 04:53:23.110
and the dark shadows under her eyes.

04:53:23.450 --> 04:53:25.810
You just go right to bed and have a good sleep.

04:53:25.970 --> 04:53:27.450
I'll do all the chores.

04:53:28.310 --> 04:53:36.370
Anne accordingly went to bed and slept so long and soundly that it was well on in the white and rosy winter afternoon

04:53:36.370 --> 04:53:43.150
when she awoke and descended to the kitchen where Marilla, who had arrived home in the meantime, was sitting knitting.

04:53:43.850 --> 04:53:46.750
Oh, did you see the Premier? exclaimed Anne at once.

04:53:46.970 --> 04:53:48.750
What did he look like for Marilla?

04:53:49.370 --> 04:53:55.710
Well, he never got to be Premier on account of his looks, said Marilla, such a nose as that man had.

04:53:55.710 --> 04:53:57.110
But he can speak.

04:53:57.670 --> 04:53:59.570
I was proud to be a Conservative.

04:54:00.110 --> 04:54:03.230
Rachel Lynde, of course, being a Liberal, had no use for him.

04:54:03.750 --> 04:54:09.070
Your dinner is in the oven, Anne, and you can get yourself some blue plum preserve out of the pantry.

04:54:09.450 --> 04:54:10.670
I guess you're hungry.

04:54:11.250 --> 04:54:13.350
Matthew has been telling me about last night.

04:54:13.710 --> 04:54:16.450
I must say it was fortunate you knew what to do.

04:54:16.950 --> 04:54:21.510
I wouldn't have had any idea myself, for I never saw a case of croup.

04:54:21.990 --> 04:54:24.870
There now, never mind talking till you've had your dinner.

04:54:24.870 --> 04:54:30.050
I can tell by the look of you that you're just full up with speeches, but they'll keep.

04:54:30.810 --> 04:54:37.810
Marilla had something to tell Anne, but she did not tell it just then, for she knew if she did, Anne's consequent excitement

04:54:37.810 --> 04:54:43.330
would lift her clear out of the region of such material matters as appetite or dinner.

04:54:43.970 --> 04:54:48.450
Not until Anne had finished her saucer of blue plums did Marilla say,

04:54:48.950 --> 04:54:51.270
Mrs. Barry was here this afternoon, Anne.

04:54:51.510 --> 04:54:54.050
She wanted to see you, but I wouldn't wake you up.

04:54:54.050 --> 04:55:02.250
She says you saved Minnie May's life, and she is very sorry she acted as she did in that affair of the current wine.

04:55:02.950 --> 04:55:08.350
She says she knows now you didn't mean to set Diana drunk, and she hopes you'll forgive her,

04:55:08.470 --> 04:55:10.690
and be good friends with Diana again.

04:55:11.350 --> 04:55:18.710
You're to go over this evening if you like, for Diana can't stir outside the door on account of a bad cold she caught last night.

04:55:19.250 --> 04:55:23.370
Now, Anne, surely, for pity's sake, don't fly up into the air.

04:55:23.370 --> 04:55:26.270
The warning seemed not unnecessary.

04:55:26.690 --> 04:55:32.330
So uplifted and aerial was Anne's expression and attitude as she sprang to her feet,

04:55:32.710 --> 04:55:35.810
her face irradiated with the flame of her spirit.

04:55:36.250 --> 04:55:40.250
Oh, Marilla, can I go right now, without washing my dishes?

04:55:40.470 --> 04:55:46.590
I'll wash them when I come back, but I cannot tie myself down to anything so unromantic as

04:55:46.590 --> 04:55:48.770
dishwashing at this thrilling moment.

04:55:49.190 --> 04:55:52.190
Yes, yes, run along, said Marilla indulgently.

04:55:53.210 --> 04:55:55.410
Anne, surely, are you crazy?

04:55:55.710 --> 04:55:58.150
Come back this instant and put something on.

04:55:58.370 --> 04:56:00.270
I might as well call to the wind.

04:56:00.630 --> 04:56:02.690
She's gone without a cap or wrap.

04:56:03.130 --> 04:56:06.150
Look at her tearing through the orchard with her hair streaming.

04:56:06.570 --> 04:56:09.550
It'll be a mercy if she doesn't catch her death cold.

04:56:10.510 --> 04:56:15.190
Anne came dancing home in the purple winter twilight across the snowy places.

04:56:15.190 --> 04:56:22.610
Afar in the southwest was the great shimmering pearl-like sparkle of an evening star in a sky

04:56:22.610 --> 04:56:29.490
that was pale golden and rose over gleaming white spaces and dark glens of spruce.

04:56:29.990 --> 04:56:36.890
The tinkles of sleigh bells among the snowy hills came like elfin chimes through the frosty air,

04:56:37.130 --> 04:56:42.550
but their music was not sweeter than the song in Anne's heart and on her lips.

04:56:43.050 --> 04:56:47.250
You see before you a perfectly happy person, Marilla, she announced.

04:56:47.930 --> 04:56:51.590
I'm perfectly happy, yes, in spite of my red hair.

04:56:51.910 --> 04:56:54.930
Just at present I have a soul above red hair.

04:56:55.370 --> 04:57:01.070
Mrs. Barry kissed me and cried and said she was so sorry, and she could never repay me.

04:57:01.770 --> 04:57:06.810
I felt fearfully embarrassed, Marilla, but I just said as politely as I could.

04:57:07.150 --> 04:57:09.690
I have no hard feelings for you, Mrs. Barry.

04:57:09.690 --> 04:57:14.330
I assure you once for all that I did not mean to intoxicate Diana,

04:57:14.830 --> 04:57:19.090
and henceforth I shall cover the past with the mantle of oblivion.

04:57:19.390 --> 04:57:22.930
That was a pretty dignified way of speaking, wasn't it, Marilla?

04:57:23.690 --> 04:57:29.750
I felt that I was heaping coals of fire on Mrs. Barry's head, and Diana and I had a lovely

04:57:29.750 --> 04:57:36.250
afternoon. Diana showed me a new fancy crochet stitch her aunt over in Carmody taught her.

04:57:36.250 --> 04:57:42.830
Not a soul in Avonlea knows it but us, and we pledged a solemn vow never to reveal it

04:57:42.830 --> 04:57:49.770
to anyone else. Diana gave me a beautiful card with a wreath of roses on it and a verse of poetry.

04:57:50.490 --> 04:57:55.730
If you love me as I love you, nothing but death can part us too.

04:57:56.090 --> 04:58:01.810
And that is true, Marilla. We're going to ask Mr. Phillips to let us sit together in school again,

04:58:01.810 --> 04:58:05.190
and Gertie Pie can go with Minnie Andrews.

04:58:05.190 --> 04:58:10.190
We had an elegant tea. Mrs. Barry had the very best china set out, Marilla,

04:58:10.590 --> 04:58:15.010
just as if I was real company. I can't tell you what a thrill it gave me.

04:58:15.330 --> 04:58:19.470
Nobody ever used their very best china on my account before.

04:58:20.010 --> 04:58:25.810
And we had fruit cake and pound cake and donuts and two kinds of preserves, Marilla.

04:58:25.810 --> 04:58:28.990
And Mrs. Barry asked me if I took tea and said,

04:58:29.390 --> 04:58:34.670
Pa, why don't you pass the biscuits to Anne? It must be lovely to be grown up, Marilla,

04:58:34.990 --> 04:58:38.550
when just being treated as if you were is so nice.

04:58:38.890 --> 04:58:42.110
I don't know about that, said Marilla with a brief sigh.

04:58:42.610 --> 04:58:48.350
Well, anyway, when I am grown up, said Anne decidedly, I'm always going to talk to little

04:58:48.350 --> 04:58:55.250
girls as if they were too, and I'll never laugh when they use big words. I know from sorrowful

04:58:55.250 --> 04:59:03.250
experience how that hurts one's feelings. After tea Diana and I made taffy. The taffy wasn't very

04:59:03.250 --> 04:59:10.050
good, I suppose, because neither Diana nor I had ever made any before. Diana left me to stir it

04:59:10.050 --> 04:59:15.370
while she buttered the plates and I forgot and let it burn, and then when we set it out on the

04:59:15.370 --> 04:59:22.070
platform to cool, the cat walked over one plate and that had to be thrown away. But the making of it

04:59:22.070 --> 04:59:28.190
was splendid fun. Then when I came home Mrs. Barry asked me to come over as often as I could,

04:59:28.690 --> 04:59:35.350
and Diana stood at the window and threw kisses at me, all the way down to Lover's Lane. I assure

04:59:35.350 --> 04:59:41.430
you, Marilla, that I feel like praying tonight and I'm going to think out a special brand new prayer

04:59:41.430 --> 04:59:47.090
in honor of the occasion.

05:00:18.670 --> 05:00:25.610
Marilla, can I go over to see Diana just for a minute? asked Anne, running breathlessly down the East Gable one February evening.

05:00:26.550 --> 05:00:30.510
I don't see what you want to be traipsing about after dark for, said Marilla shortly.

05:00:31.090 --> 05:00:41.130
You and Diana walked home from school together and then stood there in the snow for half an hour more, your tongue's going the whole blessed time, clickety-clack, so I don't think you're very badly off to see her again.

05:00:41.130 --> 05:00:46.630
But she wants to see me, pleaded Anne. She has something very important to tell me.

05:00:47.430 --> 05:00:49.010
How do you know she has?

05:00:49.530 --> 05:01:02.850
Because she just signaled to me from her window. We've arranged a way to signal with our candles and cardboard. We set the candle on the window sill and make flashes by passing the cardboard back and forth. So many flashes mean a certain thing. It was my idea, Marilla.

05:01:03.430 --> 05:01:09.990
I'll warrant you it was, said Marilla emphatically, and the next thing you'll be setting fire to the curtains with your signaling nonsense.

05:01:09.990 --> 05:01:27.230
Oh, we're very careful, Marilla, and it's so interesting. Two flashes mean, are you there? Three mean, yes, and four, no. Five mean, come over as soon as possible because I have something important to reveal. Diana has just signaled five flashes, and I'm really suffering to know what it is.

05:01:28.350 --> 05:01:36.010
Well, you needn't suffer any longer, said Marilla sarcastically. You can go, but you're to be back here in just ten minutes. Remember that.

05:01:36.870 --> 05:01:50.210
Anne did remember it, and was back in the stipulated time, although probably no mortal will ever know just what it cost her to confine the discussion of Diana's important communication within the limits of ten minutes. But at least she had made good use of them.

05:01:50.770 --> 05:02:12.490
Oh, Marilla, what do you think? You know tomorrow is Diana's birthday. Well, their mother told her she could ask me to go home with her from school and stay all night with her. And her cousins are coming over from Newbridge in a big, punk sleigh to go to the debating club concert at the hall tomorrow night. And they're going to take Diana and me to the concert, if you'll let me go, that is. You will, won't you, Marilla? Oh, I feel so excited.

05:02:13.190 --> 05:02:22.870
You can calm down, then, because you're not going. You're better at home in your own bed, and as for that club concert, it's all nonsense, and little girls should not be allowed to go out to such places at all.

05:02:23.950 --> 05:02:27.650
I'm sure the debating club is a most respectable affair, pleaded Anne.

05:02:28.450 --> 05:02:38.230
I'm not saying it isn't, but you're not going to be in gadding about to concerts and staying out all hours of the night. Pretty doings for children. I'm surprised at Mrs. Berry's letting Diana go.

05:02:39.210 --> 05:02:44.170
But it's such a very special occasion, mourned Anne on the verge of tears.

05:02:44.910 --> 05:02:55.730
Diana has only one birthday in a year. It isn't as if birthdays were common things, Marilla. Prissy Andrews is going to recite Curfew Must Not Ring Tonight. That is such a good moral piece, Marilla.

05:02:55.730 --> 05:03:12.650
I'm sure it'll do me lots of good to hear it, and the choir are going to sing four lovely pathetic songs that are pretty near as good as Hem's, and oh, Marilla, the minister is going to take part. Yes, indeed, he is. He's going to give an address. That'll be just about the same thing as a sermon. Please, May and I go, Marilla.

05:03:13.730 --> 05:03:18.970
You heard what I said, Anne, didn't you? Take off your boots now and go to bed. It's past eight.

05:03:19.870 --> 05:03:33.530
There's just one more thing, Marilla, said Anne, with the air of producing the last shot in her locker. Mrs. Berry told Diana that we might sleep in the spare room bed. Think of the honor of your little Anne being put in the spare room bed.

05:03:35.050 --> 05:03:40.850
It's an honor you'll have to get along without. Go to bed, Anne, and don't let me hear another word out of you.

05:03:41.950 --> 05:03:53.690
When Anne, with tears rolling over her cheeks, had gone sorrowfully upstairs, Matthew, who had been apparently sound asleep on the lounge during the whole dialogue, opened his eyes and said decidedly,

05:03:54.730 --> 05:03:58.050
Well now, Marilla, I think you ought to let Anne go.

05:03:59.070 --> 05:04:05.090
I don't then, retorted Marilla. Who's bringing this child up, Matthew, you or me?

05:04:05.630 --> 05:04:10.550
Well now, you, admitted Matthew, don't interfere then.

05:04:11.450 --> 05:04:18.430
Well now, I ain't interfering. It ain't interfering to have your own opinion. And my opinion is that you ought to let Anne go.

05:04:19.770 --> 05:04:26.450
You'd think I ought to let Anne go to the moon if she took the notion, I've no doubt, was Marilla's amiable rejoinder.

05:04:26.450 --> 05:04:36.190
I might have let her spend the night with Diana, if that was all, but I don't approve of this concert plan. She'd go there and catch cold like it's not and have her head filled up with nonsense and excitement.

05:04:36.670 --> 05:04:42.890
It would unsettle her for a week. I understand that child's disposition, and what's good for it, better than you, Matthew.

05:04:44.010 --> 05:04:48.050
I think you ought to let Anne go, repeated Matthew firmly.

05:04:48.790 --> 05:04:57.050
Argument was not his strong point, but holding fast to his opinion certainly was. Marilla gave a gasp of helplessness and took refuge in silence.

05:04:58.070 --> 05:05:05.070
The next morning, when Anne was washing the breakfast dishes in the pantry, Matthew paused on his way out to the barn to say to Marilla again,

05:05:05.610 --> 05:05:07.910
I think you ought to let Anne go, Marilla.

05:05:08.790 --> 05:05:15.690
For a moment, Marilla looked things not lawful to be uttered. Then she yielded to the inevitable and said tartly,

05:05:15.690 --> 05:05:20.330
Very well. She can go, since nothing else will please you.

05:05:21.150 --> 05:05:27.650
Anne flew out of the pantry, dripping dishcloth in hand. Oh, Marilla, Marilla, say those blessed words again.

05:05:28.710 --> 05:05:33.790
I guess once is enough to say them. This is Matthew's doings, and I wash my hands of it.

05:05:33.970 --> 05:05:40.870
If you catch pneumonia sleeping in a strange bed or coming out of that hot hall in the middle of the night, don't blame me. Blame Matthew.

05:05:40.870 --> 05:05:46.630
And surely, you're dripping greasy water all over the floor. I never saw such a careless child.

05:05:47.670 --> 05:05:57.190
Oh, I know I'm a great trial to you, Marilla, said Anne repentantly. I make so many mistakes. But then just think of all the mistakes I don't make, although I might.

05:05:58.130 --> 05:06:04.570
I'll get some sand and scrub up the spots before I go to school. Oh, Marilla, my heart was just set on going to that concert.

05:06:04.570 --> 05:06:10.450
I never was to a concert in my life, and when the other girls talk about them in school I feel so left out of it.

05:06:10.470 --> 05:06:18.090
You don't know just how I felt about it, but you see Matthew did. Matthew understands me, and it's so nice to be understood, Marilla.

05:06:19.110 --> 05:06:23.570
Anne was too excited to do her self-justice as to lessons that morning in school.

05:06:24.010 --> 05:06:28.430
Gilbert blithed, spelled her down in class, and left her clear out of sight in mental arithmetic.

05:06:29.210 --> 05:06:35.210
Anne's consequent humiliation was less than it might have been, however, in view of the concert and the spare-room bed.

05:06:35.770 --> 05:06:44.030
She and Diana talked so constantly about it all day that with a stricter teacher than Mr. Phillips, dire disgrace must have inevitably been their portion.

05:06:45.170 --> 05:06:51.350
Anne felt that she could not have borne it if she had not been going to the concert, for nothing else was discussed that day in school.

05:06:51.350 --> 05:07:02.350
The Avonlea Debating Club, which met for nightly all winter, had had several smaller free entertainments, but this was to be a big affair, admission ten cents, and aid at the library.

05:07:03.150 --> 05:07:11.990
The Avonlea young people had been practicing for weeks, and all the scholars were especially interested in it by reason of older brothers and sisters who were going to take part.

05:07:12.670 --> 05:07:22.410
Everybody in school over nine years of age expected to go, except Carrie Sloane, whose father shared Marilla's opinions about small girls going to night concerts.

05:07:23.670 --> 05:07:28.630
Carrie Sloane cried into her grammar all afternoon and felt that life was not worth living.

05:07:30.030 --> 05:07:39.350
For Anne, the real excitement began with the dismissal of school and increased therefrom in crescendo until it reached to a crash of positive ecstasy in the concert itself.

05:07:39.350 --> 05:07:46.590
They had a perfectly elegant tea, and then came the delicious occupation of dressing in Diana's little room upstairs.

05:07:47.570 --> 05:07:58.450
Diana did Anne's front hair in the new pompadour style, and Anne tied Diana's bows with the especial knack she possessed, and they experimented with at least a half a dozen different ways of arranging their back hair.

05:07:59.030 --> 05:08:03.030
At last they were ready, cheeks scarlet and eyes glowing with excitement.

05:08:04.110 --> 05:08:20.910
True, Anne could not help a little pang when she contrasted her plain black tam and shapeless tight-sleeved homemade gray cloth coat with Diana's jaunty fur cap and smart little jacket, but she remembered in time that she had an imagination and could use it.

05:08:20.910 --> 05:08:24.850
Then Diana's cousins, the Murrays from Newbridge, came.

05:08:25.450 --> 05:08:30.230
They all crowded into the big pang sleigh among straw and fur robes.

05:08:30.910 --> 05:08:37.450
Anne reveled in the drive to the hall, slipping along the satin-smooth roads with the snow crisping under the runners.

05:08:38.230 --> 05:08:53.410
There was a magnificent sunset, and the snowy hills and deep blue water of the St. Lawrence Gulf seemed to rim in the splendor, like a huge bowl of pearl and sapphire brimmed with wine and fire.

05:08:54.610 --> 05:09:01.170
Tinkles of sleigh bells and distant laughter that seemed like the mirth of wood elves came from every quarter.

05:09:02.510 --> 05:09:15.470
Oh, Diana, breathed Anne, squeezing Diana's mitten hand under the fur robe. Isn't it all like a beautiful dream? Do I really look the same as usual? I feel so different that it seems to me it must show in my looks.

05:09:16.290 --> 05:09:25.630
You look awfully nice, said Diana, who having just received a compliment from one of her cousins, felt she ought to pass it on. You've got the loveliest color.

05:09:27.530 --> 05:09:37.570
The program that night was a series of thrills for at least one listener in the audience, and as Anne assured Diana, every succeeding thrill was thrillier than the last.

05:09:38.090 --> 05:09:46.690
When Prissy Andrews attired in a new pink silk waist with a string of pearls about her smooth white throat and real carnations in her hair,

05:09:46.690 --> 05:09:57.430
rumor whispered that the master had sent all the way to town for them for her, climbed the slimy ladder dark without one ray of light, and shivered in luxurious sympathy.

05:09:57.870 --> 05:10:05.370
When the choir sang far above the gentle daisies, Anne gazed at the ceiling as if it were frescoed with angels.

05:10:05.370 --> 05:10:13.630
When Sam Sloan proceeded to explain and illustrate how Socrates set a hand, Anne laughed until people sitting near her laughed too.

05:10:14.170 --> 05:10:19.130
More out of sympathy with her than with amusement at a selection that was rather threadbare, even in Avoli.

05:10:20.170 --> 05:10:29.490
And when Mr. Phillips gave Mark Antony's oration over the dead body of Caesar in the most heart-stirring tones, looking at Prissy Andrews at the end of every sentence,

05:10:29.490 --> 05:10:35.490
Anne felt that she could rise in mutiny on the spot if but one Roman citizen led the way.

05:10:37.070 --> 05:10:47.750
Only one number on the program failed to interest her. When Gilbert Blythe recited Bingen on the Rhine, Anne picked up Rhoda Murray's library book and read it until he had finished.

05:10:48.170 --> 05:10:53.430
When she sat rigidly stiff and motionless while Diana clapped her hands until they tingled.

05:10:53.430 --> 05:11:01.610
It was eleven when they got home, sated with dissipation but with the exceeding sweet pleasure of talking it all over still to come.

05:11:02.390 --> 05:11:12.350
Everybody seemed to sleep, and the house was dark and silent. Anne and Diana tiptoed into the parlor, a long narrow room out of which the spare room opened.

05:11:13.050 --> 05:11:17.390
It was pleasantly warm and dimly lighted by the embers of a fire in the grate.

05:11:17.990 --> 05:11:21.950
Let's undress here, said Diana. It's so nice and warm.

05:11:23.510 --> 05:11:31.770
Hasn't it been a delightful time? sighed Anne rapturously. It must be splendid to get up and recite there.

05:11:32.750 --> 05:11:35.050
Do you suppose we will ever be asked to do it, Diana?

05:11:36.630 --> 05:11:45.250
Yes, of course, some day. They're always wanting the big scholars to recite. Gilbert Blythe does often, and he's only two years older than us.

05:11:45.250 --> 05:11:54.230
Oh, Anne, how could you pretend not to listen to him? When he came to the line, there's another, not a sister. He looked right down at you.

05:11:55.930 --> 05:12:03.970
Diana, said Anne with dignity, you are my boozing friend, but I cannot allow even you to speak to me of that person.

05:12:05.710 --> 05:12:09.690
Are you ready for bed? Let's run a race and see who will get to bed first.

05:12:10.530 --> 05:12:20.030
The suggestion appealed to Diana. The two little white-clad figures flew down the long room, through the spare room door, and bounded on the bed at the same moment.

05:12:20.890 --> 05:12:27.470
And then, something moved beneath them. There was a gasp and a cry, and somebody said in muffled accents,

05:12:27.470 --> 05:12:29.070
You're such a goodness!

05:12:30.210 --> 05:12:40.170
Anne and Diana were never able to tell just how they got off that bed and out of the room. They only knew that after one frantic rush they found themselves tiptoeing shiveringly upstairs.

05:12:42.290 --> 05:12:49.110
Who was it? Why was it? whispered Anne, her teeth chattering with cold and fright.

05:12:49.110 --> 05:13:06.470
It was Aunt Josephine, said Diana, gasping with laughter. Oh, man, it was Aunt Josephine, however she came to be there. Oh, and I know she will be furious. It's dreadful. It's really dreadful. But did you ever know anything so funny, Anne?

05:13:07.530 --> 05:13:09.210
Who is your Aunt Josephine?

05:13:10.310 --> 05:13:27.830
She's father's aunt, and she lives in Charlottetown. She's awfully old, seventy anyhow, and I don't believe she was ever a little girl. We were expecting her out for a visit, but not so soon. She's awfully prim and proper, and she'll scold dreadfully about this, I know.

05:13:29.790 --> 05:13:34.810
Well, we'll have to sleep with Minnie May, and you can't think how she kicks.

05:13:36.570 --> 05:13:44.130
Miss Josephine Berry did not appear at early breakfast the next morning. Mrs. Berry smiled kindly at the two little girls.

05:13:44.810 --> 05:13:58.490
Did you have a good time last night? I tried to stay awake until you came home, for I wanted to tell you Aunt Josephine had come and that you would have to go upstairs after all. But I was so tired I fell asleep. I hope we didn't disturb your Aunt Diana.

05:14:00.030 --> 05:14:20.050
Diana preserved a discreet silence, but she and Anne exchanged furtive smiles of guilty amusement across the table. Anne hurried home after breakfast and so remained in blissful ignorance of the disturbance which presently resulted in the Berry household until the late afternoon, when she went down to Mrs. Lynn's on an errand for Marilla.

05:14:21.070 --> 05:14:29.290
So, you and Diana nearly frightened poor old Miss Berry to death last night, said Mrs. Lynn severely, but with a twinkle in her eye.

05:14:30.010 --> 05:14:44.390
Mrs. Berry was here a few minutes ago on her way to Carmody. She's feeling real worried over it. Old Miss Berry was in a terrible temper when she got up this morning, and Josephine Berry's temper is no joke, I tell you that. She wouldn't speak to Diana at all.

05:14:44.390 --> 05:14:52.910
It wasn't Diana's fault, said Anne contritely. It was mine. I suggested racing to see who would get into bed first.

05:14:53.970 --> 05:15:04.150
I knew it, said Mrs. Lynn with the exultation of a correct guesser. I knew that idea came out of your head. Well, it's made a nice lot of trouble, that's what.

05:15:04.590 --> 05:15:16.090
Old Miss Berry came out to stay for a month, but she declares she won't stay another day and is going to go right back to town tomorrow, Sunday and all as it is. She'd have gone today if they could have taken her.

05:15:16.090 --> 05:15:27.150
She had promised to pay for a quarter's music lessons for Diana, but now she's determined to do nothing at all for such a tomboy. Oh, I guess they had a lively time of it there this morning.

05:15:28.090 --> 05:15:39.410
The Berries must feel cut up. Old Miss Berry is rich, and they like to keep on the good side of her. Of course, Mrs. Berry didn't say just that to me, but I'm a pretty good judge of human nature, that's what.

05:15:40.590 --> 05:15:55.810
I'm such an unlucky girl, mourned Anne. I'm always getting into scrapes myself and getting my best friends, people I'd shed my heart's blood for, into them too. Can you tell me why it is so, Mrs. Lynn?

05:15:56.690 --> 05:16:07.090
It's because you're too heedless and impulsive, child, that's what. You never stop to think. Whatever comes into your head to say or do, you say or do it without a moment's reflection.

05:16:07.990 --> 05:16:21.450
Oh, but that's the best of it, protested Anne. Something just flashes into your mind, so exciting, and you must out with it. If you stop to think it over, you spoil it all. Haven't you ever felt that yourself, Mrs. Lynn?

05:16:22.310 --> 05:16:26.570
No, Mrs. Lynn had not. She shook her head sagely.

05:16:26.570 --> 05:16:35.790
You must learn to think a little, Anne, that's what. The proverb you need to go by is, look before you leap, especially in despair-room beds.

05:16:36.890 --> 05:16:56.850
Mrs. Lynn laughed comfortably over her mild joke, but Anne remained pensive. She saw nothing to laugh at in the situation, which to her eyes appeared very serious. When she left Mrs. Lynn's, she made her way across the crusted fields to Orchard Slope. Diana met her at the kitchen door.

05:16:57.450 --> 05:17:03.210
Your Aunt Josephine was very cross about it, wasn't she? whispered Anne.

05:17:03.990 --> 05:17:28.990
Yes, answered Diana, stifling a giggle with an apprehensive glance over her shoulder at the closed sitting-room door. She was fairly dancing with rage, Anne. Oh, how she scolded. She said I was the worst behaved girl she ever saw, and that my parents ought to be ashamed of the way they had brought me up. She says she won't stay, and I'm sure I don't care. But father and mother do.

05:17:29.750 --> 05:17:33.770
Why didn't you tell them it was my fault? demanded Anne.

05:17:35.130 --> 05:17:46.410
It's likely I'd do such a thing, isn't it? said Diana with just scorn. I'm no tell-tale, Anne Shirley. And anyhow, I was just as much to blame as you.

05:17:47.250 --> 05:17:53.750
Well, I'm going in to tell her myself, said Anne resolutely.

05:17:54.890 --> 05:18:02.490
Diana stared. Anne Shirley, you'd never. Why, she'll eat you alive.

05:18:04.150 --> 05:18:08.350
Don't frighten me any more than I am frightened, implored Anne.

05:18:09.210 --> 05:18:17.210
I'd rather walk up to a cannon's mouth. But I've got to do it, Diana. It was my fault, and I've got to confess.

05:18:18.830 --> 05:18:22.050
I've had practice in confessing, fortunately.

05:18:23.490 --> 05:18:32.430
Well, she's in the room, said Diana. You can go in if you want to. I wouldn't dare, and I don't believe you'll do a bit of good.

05:18:33.130 --> 05:18:45.030
With this encouragement, Anne bearded the lion in its den, that is to say, walked resolutely up to the sitting-room door and knocked faintly. A sharp, come in, followed.

05:18:46.790 --> 05:18:57.990
Miss Josephine Barry, thin, prim and rigid, was knitting fiercely by the fire, her wrath quite unappeased and her eyes snapping through her gold-rimmed glasses.

05:18:58.770 --> 05:19:09.530
She wheeled around in her chair, expecting to see Diana, and beheld a white-faced girl whose great eyes were brimmed up with a mixture of desperate courage and shrinking terror.

05:19:10.470 --> 05:19:15.930
Who are you? demanded Miss Josephine Barry, without ceremony.

05:19:17.010 --> 05:19:28.530
I'm Anne of Green Gables, said the small visitor tremulously, clasping her hands with her characteristic gesture. And I've come to confess, if you please.

05:19:29.610 --> 05:19:30.490
Confess what?

05:19:30.490 --> 05:19:44.030
That it was all my fault about jumping into bed on you last night. I suggested it. Diana would never have thought of such a thing, I am sure. Diana's a very ladylike girl, Miss Barry, so you must see how unjust it is to blame her.

05:19:44.830 --> 05:19:52.890
Oh, I must, hey? I'd rather think Diana did her share of the jumping, at least. Such carrying's on in a respectable house.

05:19:52.890 --> 05:19:57.030
But we were only in fun, persisted Anne.

05:19:57.930 --> 05:20:05.650
I think you ought to forgive us, Miss Barry, now that we've apologized. And anyhow, please forgive Diana and let her have her music lessons.

05:20:06.410 --> 05:20:23.550
Diana's heart is set on her music lessons, Miss Barry, and I know too well what it is to set your heart on a thing and not get it. If you must be cross with anyone, be cross with me. I've been so used in my early days to having people cross at me that I can endure it much better than Diana can.

05:20:24.450 --> 05:20:33.650
Much of the snap had gone out of the old lady's eyes by this time, and was replaced by a twinkle of amused interest. But she still said severely.

05:20:35.010 --> 05:20:52.430
I don't think it is any excuse for you that you were only in fun. Little girls never indulged in that kind of fun when I was young. You don't know what it is to be awakened out of a sound sleep after a long and arduous journey by two great girls coming bounced down on you.

05:20:52.430 --> 05:21:07.050
I don't know, but I can imagine, said Anne eagerly. I'm sure it must have been very disturbing. But then there is our side of it too. Have you any imagination, Miss Barry? If you have, just put yourself in our place.

05:21:07.050 --> 05:21:25.930
We didn't know there was anybody in that bed, and you nearly scared us to death. It was simply awful the way we felt, and then we couldn't sleep in a spare room after being promised. I suppose you were used to sleeping in spare rooms, but just imagine what you would feel like if you were a little orphan girl who had never had such an honor.

05:21:27.090 --> 05:21:40.110
All the snap had gone by this time. Miss Barry actually laughed, a sound which caused Diana, waiting in speechless anxiety in the kitchen outside, to give a great gasp of relief.

05:21:40.990 --> 05:21:57.910
I'm afraid my imagination is a little rusty. It's so long since I used it, she said. I dare say your claim to sympathy is just as strong as mine. It all depends on the way we look at it. Sit down here and tell me about yourself.

05:21:57.910 --> 05:22:24.570
I am very sorry I can't, said Anne firmly. I would like to, because you seem like an interesting lady, and you might even be a kindred spirit, although you don't look very much like it. But it is my duty to go home to Miss Marilla Cuthbert. Miss Marilla Cuthbert is a very kind lady who has taken me to bring up properly. She is doing her best, but it is very discouraging work. You must not blame her because I jumped on the bed.

05:22:25.170 --> 05:22:31.750
But before I go, I do wish you would tell me if you would forgive Diana and stay just as long as you meant to in Avonlea.

05:22:31.910 --> 05:22:33.550
I think perhaps I will.

05:22:34.050 --> 05:22:37.810
If you will come over and talk to me occasionally, said Miss Barry.

05:22:38.530 --> 05:22:47.350
That evening, Miss Barry gave Diana a silver bangle bracelet and told the senior members of the household that she had unpacked her valise.

05:22:47.350 --> 05:23:01.170
I have made up my mind to stay simply for the sake of getting better acquainted with that Anne girl, she said frankly. She amuses me, and at my time of life an amusing person is a rarity.

05:23:02.870 --> 05:23:06.010
Marilla's only comment when she heard the story was,

05:23:06.410 --> 05:23:07.490
I told you so.

05:23:08.230 --> 05:23:09.910
This was for Matthew's benefit.

05:23:10.970 --> 05:23:20.990
Miss Barry stayed her month out and over. She was a more agreeable guest than usual, for Anne kept her in good humor. They became firm friends.

05:23:21.750 --> 05:23:24.230
When Miss Barry went away, she said,

05:23:24.750 --> 05:23:32.010
Remember, you Anne girl, when you come to town you're to visit me, and I'll put you in my very sparrest spare room to sleep.

05:23:32.970 --> 05:23:37.670
Miss Barry was a kindred spirit after all, Anne confided to Marilla.

05:23:38.470 --> 05:23:50.590
You wouldn't think so to look at her, but she is. You didn't find it right out at first, as in Matthew's case, but after a while you come to see it. Kindred spirits are not so scarce as I used to think.

05:23:51.190 --> 05:23:54.670
It's splendid to find out there are so many of them in the world.

05:24:35.230 --> 05:24:43.350
Spring had come once more to Green Gables, the beautiful, capricious, reluctant Canadian spring,

05:24:43.990 --> 05:24:50.190
lingering along through April and May, and a succession of sweet, fresh, chilly days,

05:24:50.750 --> 05:24:54.950
with pink sunsets and miracles of resurrection and growth.

05:24:54.950 --> 05:25:02.870
The maples in Lover's Lane were red-budded, and little curly ferns pushed up around the Dryad's Bubble.

05:25:03.930 --> 05:25:11.250
Away up in the Barrens, behind Mr. Silas Sloane's place, the Mayflowers blossomed out,

05:25:12.290 --> 05:25:16.730
pink and white stars of sweetness under their brown leaves.

05:25:17.890 --> 05:25:23.210
All the schoolgirls and boys had one golden afternoon gathering them,

05:25:23.210 --> 05:25:30.750
coming home in the clear, echoing twilight, with arms in baskets full of flowery spoil.

05:25:32.910 --> 05:25:38.230
I'm so sorry for people who live in lands where there are no Mayflowers, said Anne.

05:25:38.730 --> 05:25:43.930
Diana says perhaps they have something better, but there couldn't be anything better than Mayflowers, could there, Marilla?

05:25:44.650 --> 05:25:49.790
And Diana says if they don't know what they are like they don't miss them, but I think that is the saddest thing of all.

05:25:49.790 --> 05:25:54.890
I think it would be tragic, Marilla, not to know what Mayflowers are like and not to miss them.

05:25:55.250 --> 05:25:57.410
Do you know what I think Mayflowers are, Marilla?

05:25:57.690 --> 05:26:01.810
I think they must be the souls of the flowers that died last summer, and this is their heaven.

05:26:02.670 --> 05:26:05.310
But we had a splendid time today, Marilla.

05:26:05.850 --> 05:26:09.010
We had our lunch down in Big Mossy Hollow by an old well.

05:26:09.530 --> 05:26:11.350
Such a romantic spot!

05:26:12.050 --> 05:26:16.310
Charlie Sloane dared Artie Gillis to jump over it, and Artie did, because he wouldn't take a dare.

05:26:16.310 --> 05:26:19.910
Nobody would in school. It is very fashionable to dare.

05:26:20.770 --> 05:26:25.590
Mr. Phillips gave all the Mayflowers he found to Percy Andrews, and I heard him say, sweets to the sweet.

05:26:26.010 --> 05:26:29.230
He got that out of a book, I know, but it shows he has some imagination.

05:26:30.030 --> 05:26:33.030
I was offered some Mayflowers, too, but I rejected them with scorn.

05:26:33.470 --> 05:26:36.850
I can't tell you the person's name because I have vowed never to let it cross my lips.

05:26:37.570 --> 05:26:42.570
We made wreaths of the Mayflowers and put them on our hats, and when the time came to go home we marched in procession down the road,

05:26:42.570 --> 05:26:45.190
two by two, with our bouquets and wreaths, singing my home on the hill.

05:26:45.190 --> 05:26:48.410
Oh, it was so thrilling, Marilla.

05:26:49.450 --> 05:26:55.690
All of Mr. Silas Sloane's folks rushed out to see us, and everybody we met on the road stopped and stared after us.

05:26:56.010 --> 05:26:57.790
We made a real sensation.

05:26:58.730 --> 05:27:04.850
No such wonder, such silly doings, was Marilla's response.

05:27:06.170 --> 05:27:11.970
After the Mayflowers came the violets, and violet veil was unpurpled with them.

05:27:11.970 --> 05:27:20.450
Anne walked through it on her way to school, with reverent steps and worshipping eyes, as if she trod on holy ground.

05:27:21.570 --> 05:27:30.650
Somehow, she told Diana, when I'm going through here, I don't really care whether anybody gets ahead of me in class or not.

05:27:31.290 --> 05:27:34.890
But when I'm up in school it's all different, and I care as much as ever.

05:27:35.570 --> 05:27:38.130
There's such a lot of different Ans in me.

05:27:38.130 --> 05:27:41.630
I sometimes think that is why I'm such a troublesome person.

05:27:42.010 --> 05:27:45.470
If I was just the one Anne, it would be ever so much more comfortable.

05:27:45.910 --> 05:27:48.410
But then it wouldn't be half so interesting.

05:27:49.710 --> 05:27:54.590
One June evening, when the orchids were pink-blossoming again,

05:27:55.150 --> 05:28:01.190
when the frogs were singing silvery sweet in the marshes about the head of the lake of shining waters,

05:28:01.770 --> 05:28:06.930
and the air was full of the savour of clover fields and balsamic-fur woods,

05:28:06.930 --> 05:28:10.150
Anne was sitting by her gable window.

05:28:10.770 --> 05:28:15.530
She had been studying her lessons, but it had grown too dark to see the book,

05:28:16.090 --> 05:28:21.970
so she had fallen into wide-eyed reverie, looking out past the boughs of the Snow Queen,

05:28:22.650 --> 05:28:25.710
once more bestarred with its tufts of blossom.

05:28:26.870 --> 05:28:31.650
In all essential respects, the little gable chamber was unchanged.

05:28:32.290 --> 05:28:35.710
The walls were as white, the pincushion as hard,

05:28:35.710 --> 05:28:39.910
the chairs as stiffly and yellowly upright as ever,

05:28:40.210 --> 05:28:42.870
yet the whole character of the room was altered.

05:28:43.550 --> 05:28:49.310
It was full of a new vital pulsing personality that seemed to pervade it

05:28:49.310 --> 05:28:54.030
and to be quite independent of schoolgirl books and dresses and ribbons,

05:28:54.290 --> 05:28:58.610
and even of the cracked blue jug full of apple-blossoms on the table.

05:28:59.750 --> 05:29:05.050
It was as if all the dreams, sleeping and waking, of its vivid occupant,

05:29:05.050 --> 05:29:09.070
had taken a visible, although unmaterial form

05:29:09.070 --> 05:29:16.050
and had tapestried the bare room with splendid filmy tissues of rainbow and moonshine.

05:29:17.270 --> 05:29:22.750
Presently, Marilla came briskly in with some of Anne's freshly ironed school aprons.

05:29:23.590 --> 05:29:27.390
She hung them over a chair and sat down with a short sigh.

05:29:28.390 --> 05:29:30.990
She had had one of her headaches that afternoon,

05:29:30.990 --> 05:29:37.230
and although the pain had gone, she felt weak and tuckered out as she expressed it,

05:29:37.750 --> 05:29:41.010
and looked at her with eyes limpid with sympathy.

05:29:41.910 --> 05:29:45.950
I do truly wish I could have had the headache in your place, Marilla.

05:29:46.330 --> 05:29:49.310
I would have endured it joyfully for your sake.

05:29:50.390 --> 05:29:55.530
I guess you did your part in attending to the work and letting me rest, said Marilla.

05:29:55.910 --> 05:29:59.090
You seemed to get on fairly well and made fewer mistakes than usual.

05:29:59.090 --> 05:30:03.110
Of course, it wasn't exactly necessary to starch Matthew's handkerchiefs,

05:30:03.330 --> 05:30:06.390
and most people, when they put a pie in the oven to warm up for dinner,

05:30:06.750 --> 05:30:10.630
take it out and eat it when it gets hot, instead of leaving it to be burned to a crisp.

05:30:11.510 --> 05:30:14.050
But that doesn't seem to be your way, evidently.

05:30:15.290 --> 05:30:18.390
Headaches always left Marilla somewhat sarcastic.

05:30:19.690 --> 05:30:23.650
Oh, I'm so sorry, said Anne pentently.

05:30:24.070 --> 05:30:27.850
I never thought about the pie from the moment I put it in the oven till now,

05:30:27.850 --> 05:30:32.230
although I felt instinctively that there was something missing on the dinner table.

05:30:32.570 --> 05:30:37.910
I was firmly resolved when you left me in charge this morning not to imagine anything but keep my thoughts on the facts.

05:30:38.350 --> 05:30:43.010
I did pretty well until I put the pie in, and then an irresistible temptation came on me

05:30:43.010 --> 05:30:46.010
to imagine I was an enchanted princess shut up in a lonely tower

05:30:46.010 --> 05:30:49.150
with a handsome knight riding to my rescue on a coal-black steed.

05:30:49.610 --> 05:30:51.690
So that is how I came to forget the pie.

05:30:53.090 --> 05:30:55.610
I didn't know I starched the handkerchiefs.

05:30:55.610 --> 05:30:58.870
All the time I was ironing I was trying to think of a name for a new island

05:30:58.870 --> 05:31:01.190
Diana and I have discovered up by the brook.

05:31:01.330 --> 05:31:03.670
It's the most ravishing spot, Marilla.

05:31:04.150 --> 05:31:07.650
There are two maple trees on it and the brook froze right around it.

05:31:07.990 --> 05:31:10.830
At first it struck me that it'd be splendid to call it Victoria Island

05:31:10.830 --> 05:31:12.490
because we found it on the Queen's birthday.

05:31:12.850 --> 05:31:14.750
Both Diana and I are very loyal.

05:31:15.390 --> 05:31:18.110
But I'm sorry about that pie and the handkerchiefs.

05:31:18.210 --> 05:31:21.110
I want it to be extra good today because it's an anniversary.

05:31:21.110 --> 05:31:24.570
Do you remember what happened this day last year, Marilla?

05:31:25.690 --> 05:31:28.330
No, I can't think of anything special.

05:31:29.730 --> 05:31:32.670
Oh, Marilla, it was the day I came to Green Gables.

05:31:32.790 --> 05:31:34.310
I shall never forget it.

05:31:34.310 --> 05:31:36.070
It was the turning point in my life.

05:31:36.710 --> 05:31:39.530
Of course, it wouldn't seem so important to you.

05:31:40.350 --> 05:31:43.330
I've been here for a year and I've been so happy.

05:31:43.770 --> 05:31:47.770
Of course, I've had my troubles, but one can live down troubles.

05:31:47.770 --> 05:31:50.310
Are you sorry you kept me, Marilla?

05:31:51.930 --> 05:31:56.430
No, I can't say I'm sorry, said Marilla,

05:31:56.590 --> 05:32:00.630
who sometimes wondered how she could have lived before Anne came to Green Gables.

05:32:01.590 --> 05:32:03.670
No, not exactly sorry.

05:32:04.150 --> 05:32:06.850
If you finished your lessons, Anne, I want you to run over

05:32:06.850 --> 05:32:09.550
and ask Mrs. Barry if she'll lend me Diana's apron pattern.

05:32:10.630 --> 05:32:14.170
Oh, oh, it's too dark, cried Anne.

05:32:15.230 --> 05:32:17.910
Too dark? Why, it's only twilight,

05:32:18.210 --> 05:32:21.270
and goodness knows you've gone over often enough after dark.

05:32:22.090 --> 05:32:26.250
I'll go over early in the morning, said Anne eagerly.

05:32:26.470 --> 05:32:28.870
I'll get up at sunrise and go over, Marilla.

05:32:30.430 --> 05:32:33.170
What has gotten into your head now, Anne Shirley?

05:32:33.450 --> 05:32:36.450
I want that pattern to cut out your new apron this evening.

05:32:37.010 --> 05:32:38.950
Go at once and be smart, too.

05:32:39.750 --> 05:32:44.150
I have to go around by the road, then, said Anne,

05:32:44.470 --> 05:32:46.370
taking up her hat reluctantly.

05:32:46.830 --> 05:32:50.030
Go by the road and waste half an hour.

05:32:50.310 --> 05:32:52.010
I'd like to catch you.

05:32:52.630 --> 05:32:57.910
I can't go through the haunted wood, Marilla, cried Anne desperately.

05:32:58.990 --> 05:33:00.110
Marilla stared.

05:33:01.470 --> 05:33:04.250
The haunted wood? Are you crazy?

05:33:04.770 --> 05:33:07.150
What under the canopy is the haunted wood?

05:33:07.950 --> 05:33:13.050
The spruce wood, over the brook, said Anne in a whisper.

05:33:14.690 --> 05:33:18.170
Fiddlesticks! There's no such thing as a haunted wood anywhere.

05:33:18.690 --> 05:33:20.350
Who's been telling you such stuff?

05:33:22.130 --> 05:33:24.530
Nobody, confessed Anne.

05:33:25.590 --> 05:33:28.030
Diana and I just imagined the wood was haunted.

05:33:28.390 --> 05:33:33.070
All the places around here are so, so commonplace.

05:33:33.510 --> 05:33:35.630
We just got this up for our own amusement.

05:33:35.630 --> 05:33:37.490
We began it in April.

05:33:37.930 --> 05:33:40.930
A haunted wood is so very romantic, Marilla.

05:33:41.590 --> 05:33:44.210
We chose the spruce grove because it's so gloomy.

05:33:44.870 --> 05:33:47.530
Oh, we've imagined the most harrowing things.

05:33:48.170 --> 05:33:52.350
There's a white lady walks along the brook just about this time of the night

05:33:52.350 --> 05:33:55.750
and wrings her hands and utters wailing cries.

05:33:56.770 --> 05:33:59.370
She appears when there is to be a death in the family,

05:33:59.890 --> 05:34:04.070
and the ghost of a little murdered child haunts the corner up by the Idlewild.

05:34:04.070 --> 05:34:08.450
It creeps up behind you and lays its cold fingers on your hand.

05:34:09.890 --> 05:34:10.450
So...

05:34:10.450 --> 05:34:13.470
Oh, Marilla, it gives me a shudder to think of it.

05:34:13.770 --> 05:34:16.690
And there's a headless man stalks up and down the path,

05:34:17.110 --> 05:34:19.770
and skeletons glower at you between the boughs.

05:34:20.610 --> 05:34:24.850
Oh, Marilla, I wouldn't go through the haunted wood after dark now for anything.

05:34:25.590 --> 05:34:30.090
I'd be sure that white things would reach out from behind the trees and grab me.

05:34:30.950 --> 05:34:33.850
Did you ever, anyone hear the like?

05:34:34.590 --> 05:34:38.010
ejaculated Marilla, who had listened in dumb amazement.

05:34:38.650 --> 05:34:44.110
Anne Shirley, do you mean to tell me that you believe all that wicked nonsense of your own imagination?

05:34:45.830 --> 05:34:49.870
Not believe exactly, faltered Anne.

05:34:50.450 --> 05:34:52.650
At least, I don't believe it in daylight.

05:34:53.190 --> 05:34:55.810
But after dark, Marilla, it's different.

05:34:56.070 --> 05:34:57.630
This is when ghosts walk.

05:34:57.630 --> 05:35:00.730
There are no such things as ghosts, Anne.

05:35:02.610 --> 05:35:06.930
Oh, but there are, Marilla, cried Anne eagerly.

05:35:07.270 --> 05:35:11.290
I know people who have seen them, and they are respectable people.

05:35:12.070 --> 05:35:18.430
Charlie Sloan says that his grandmother saw his grandfather driving home the cows one night after he'd been buried for a year.

05:35:19.110 --> 05:35:22.530
You know Charlie Sloan's grandmother wouldn't tell a story for anything.

05:35:23.030 --> 05:35:25.030
She's a very religious woman.

05:35:25.030 --> 05:35:32.570
And Mrs. Thomas's father was pursued home one night by a lamb of fire with his head cut off hanging by a strip of skin.

05:35:33.130 --> 05:35:38.490
He said he knew it was the sight of his brother, and that it was a warning he would die within nine days.

05:35:39.310 --> 05:35:45.410
He didn't, but he died two years after, so you see it was really true, and Ruby Gillis says,

05:35:46.950 --> 05:35:50.630
Anne Shirley, interrupted Marilla firmly.

05:35:51.190 --> 05:35:53.950
I never want to hear you talking in this fashion again.

05:35:53.950 --> 05:36:02.270
I've had my doubts about that imagination of yours right along, and if this is going to be the outcome of it, I won't countenance any such doings.

05:36:02.650 --> 05:36:08.230
You'll go right over to Barry's, and you'll go through that spruce grove, just for a lesson and a warning to you,

05:36:08.450 --> 05:36:11.770
and never let me hear a word out of your head about Haunted Woods again.

05:36:12.910 --> 05:36:18.750
Anne might plead and cry as she liked, and did, for her terror was very real.

05:36:18.750 --> 05:36:27.650
Her imagination had run away with her, and she held the spruce grove in mortal dread after nightfall, but Marilla was inexorable.

05:36:28.670 --> 05:36:35.590
She marched the shrinking ghost seer down to the spring, and ordered her to proceed straight away over the bridge,

05:36:35.990 --> 05:36:40.810
and into the dusky retreats of wailing ladies and headless spectres beyond.

05:36:42.070 --> 05:36:47.050
Oh, Marilla, how can you be so cruel? sobbed Anne.

05:36:47.050 --> 05:36:52.050
What would you feel like if a white thing did snatch me up and carry me off?

05:36:52.990 --> 05:36:56.550
I'll risk it, said Marilla unfeelingly.

05:36:56.970 --> 05:37:02.850
You know I always mean what I say. I'll cure you of imagining ghosts into places. March, now.

05:37:03.890 --> 05:37:14.390
Anne marched. That is, she stumbled over the bridge and went shuddering up the horrible dim path beyond, and never forgot that walk.

05:37:15.430 --> 05:37:19.510
Bitterly did she repent the license she had given to her imagination.

05:37:20.370 --> 05:37:31.930
The goblins of her fancy lurked in every shadow about her, reaching out their cold, fleshless hands to grasp the terrified small girl who had called them into being.

05:37:32.770 --> 05:37:41.170
A white strip of birch bark blowing up from the hollow over the brown floor of the grove made her heart stand still.

05:37:41.970 --> 05:37:50.950
The long-drawn wail of two old boughs rubbing against each other brought out the perspiration in beads on her forehead.

05:37:51.770 --> 05:37:57.130
The swoop of bats in the darkness over her was as the wings of unearthly creatures.

05:37:58.050 --> 05:38:05.270
When she reached Mr. William Bell's field, she fled across it as if pursued by an army of white things,

05:38:05.270 --> 05:38:12.450
and arrived at the berry kitchen so out of breath that she could hardly gasp out her request for the apron pattern.

05:38:13.830 --> 05:38:17.270
Diana was away, so that she had no excuse to linger.

05:38:18.170 --> 05:38:21.410
The dreadful return journey had to be faced.

05:38:22.210 --> 05:38:31.230
Anne went back over it with shut eyes, preferring to take the risk of dashing her brains out among the boughs to that of seeing a white thing.

05:38:31.230 --> 05:38:38.710
When she finally stumbled over the log bridge, she drew one long, shivering breath of relief.

05:38:39.450 --> 05:38:45.510
Well, so nothing caught you? said Marilla, un-sympathetically.

05:38:47.870 --> 05:38:59.310
Oh, Marilla, chattered Anne. I'll be contented with commonplace places after this.

05:39:32.430 --> 05:39:44.010
21 A New Departure in Flavorings Dear me, there is nothing but meetings and

05:39:44.010 --> 05:39:52.810
this world, as Mrs. Lynde says, remarked Anne plainly, putting her slate and books down

05:39:52.810 --> 05:39:59.210
in the kitchen table on the last day of June, and wiping her red eyes with a very damp handkerchief.

05:40:00.630 --> 05:40:04.910
Wasn't it fortunate, Marilla, that I took an extra handkerchief to school today?

05:40:05.670 --> 05:40:08.210
I had a pre-sentiment that it would be needed.

05:40:09.310 --> 05:40:13.990
I never thought you were so fond of Mr. Phillips that you'd require two handkerchiefs that dry

05:40:13.990 --> 05:40:17.710
your tears just because he was going away, said Marilla.

05:40:19.090 --> 05:40:23.670
I don't think I was crying because I was really so very fond of him, reflected Anne.

05:40:24.210 --> 05:40:26.310
I just cried because all the others did.

05:40:26.770 --> 05:40:28.550
It was Ruby Gillis started it.

05:40:28.790 --> 05:40:32.850
Ruby Gillis had always declared that she hated Mr. Phillips, but as soon as he got up to

05:40:32.850 --> 05:40:35.170
make his farewell speech, she burst into tears.

05:40:35.630 --> 05:40:37.630
Then all the other girls began to cry.

05:40:38.410 --> 05:40:39.630
One after the other.

05:40:39.790 --> 05:40:41.590
I tried to hold out, Marilla.

05:40:41.590 --> 05:40:47.690
I tried to remember the time Mr. Phillips made me sit with a boy, and the time he spelled

05:40:47.690 --> 05:40:51.170
my name without her knee on the blackboard, and how he said I was the worst dance he ever

05:40:51.170 --> 05:40:54.390
saw at geometry, and laughed at my spelling, and all the times he'd been so horrid and

05:40:54.390 --> 05:40:57.730
sarcastic, but somehow I couldn't, Marilla, and I just had to cry, too.

05:40:58.630 --> 05:41:01.790
Jane Williams has been talking for her mother about how glad she'd be when Mr. Phillips

05:41:01.790 --> 05:41:04.930
went away, and she declared she'd never shed a tear while she was worse than any of us

05:41:04.930 --> 05:41:06.590
and had to borrow a handkerchief from her brother.

05:41:06.670 --> 05:41:09.910
Of course the boys didn't cry because she hadn't brought one of her own, not expecting

05:41:09.910 --> 05:41:10.830
to need it.

05:41:11.510 --> 05:41:14.230
Oh, Marilla, it was heart-rending.

05:41:14.470 --> 05:41:19.350
Mr. Phillips made such a beautiful farewell speech, beginning the time has come for us

05:41:19.350 --> 05:41:19.810
to part.

05:41:19.930 --> 05:41:21.670
It was very affecting.

05:41:22.090 --> 05:41:24.650
And he had tears in his eyes, too, Marilla.

05:41:25.210 --> 05:41:29.930
Oh, I felt dreadfully sorry and remorseful for all the times I'd talked in school and

05:41:29.930 --> 05:41:33.070
draw pictures of him on my slate and made fun of him and Prissy.

05:41:33.730 --> 05:41:38.190
I can tell you I wished I'd been a model pupil like Minnie Andrews.

05:41:38.850 --> 05:41:41.050
She hadn't anything on her conscience.

05:41:41.590 --> 05:41:43.910
The girls cried all the way home from school.

05:41:44.110 --> 05:41:48.050
Carrie Sloan kept saying every few minutes, the time has come for us to part, and that

05:41:48.050 --> 05:41:51.350
would start us off again whenever we were in any danger of cheering up.

05:41:51.850 --> 05:41:57.930
I do feel dreadfully sad, Marilla, but one can't quite feel in the depths of despair

05:41:57.930 --> 05:42:00.910
with two months' vacation before them, can they, Marilla?

05:42:01.590 --> 05:42:05.150
And besides, we met the new minister and his wife coming from the station.

05:42:05.710 --> 05:42:10.410
For all I was feeling so bad about Mr. Phillips going away, I couldn't help taking a little

05:42:10.410 --> 05:42:12.330
interest in the new minister, could I?

05:42:13.290 --> 05:42:15.150
His wife is very pretty.

05:42:16.390 --> 05:42:18.290
Not exactly wiggly-lovely, of course.

05:42:18.310 --> 05:42:21.570
It wouldn't do, I suppose, for a minister to have a wiggly-lovely wife because she might

05:42:21.570 --> 05:42:22.290
set a bad example.

05:42:22.390 --> 05:42:25.590
Mrs. Lynn says the minister's wife over at Newbridge sets a very bad example because

05:42:25.590 --> 05:42:26.970
she dresses so fashionably.

05:42:27.390 --> 05:42:30.550
Our new minister's wife was dressed in blue muslin with lovely puff sleeves and a hat

05:42:30.550 --> 05:42:31.070
shim with roses.

05:42:31.230 --> 05:42:33.870
Jane Andrews said she thought puff sleeves were too whirly for a minister's wife, but

05:42:33.870 --> 05:42:37.830
I didn't make any such uncharitable remark, Marilla, because I know what is too long for

05:42:37.830 --> 05:42:38.490
puff sleeves.

05:42:39.050 --> 05:42:42.890
Besides, she's only been a minister's wife for a little while, so one should make allowances,

05:42:43.090 --> 05:42:43.610
shouldn't they?

05:42:43.870 --> 05:42:46.690
They are going to bore with Mrs. Lynn until the manse is ready.

05:42:48.090 --> 05:42:54.930
If Marilla, in going down to Mrs. Lynn's that evening, was actuated by any motive save her

05:42:54.930 --> 05:43:00.430
avowed one of returning the quilting-frames she had borrowed the preceding winter, it

05:43:00.430 --> 05:43:04.150
was an amiable weakness shared by most of the Avonlea people.

05:43:04.850 --> 05:43:10.710
Many a thing Mrs. Lynn had lent, sometimes never expecting to see it again, came home

05:43:10.710 --> 05:43:13.590
that night in charge of the borrowers thereof.

05:43:14.270 --> 05:43:20.890
A new minister, and moreover a minister with a wife, was a lawful object of curiosity in

05:43:20.890 --> 05:43:25.790
a quiet little country settlement where sensations were few and far between.

05:43:27.210 --> 05:43:33.770
Old Mr. Bentley, the minister a woman had found lacking in imagination, had been pastor

05:43:33.770 --> 05:43:36.050
of Avonlea for eighteen years.

05:43:36.630 --> 05:43:42.230
He was a widower when he came, and a widower he remained, despite the fact that gossip

05:43:42.230 --> 05:43:47.830
regularly married him to this, that, or the other one every year of his sojourn.

05:43:48.690 --> 05:43:54.170
In the preceding February he had resigned his charge and departed amid the regrets of

05:43:54.170 --> 05:43:59.870
these people, most of whom had the affection borne of long intercourse for their good old

05:43:59.870 --> 05:44:03.290
minister in spite of his shortcomings as an orator.

05:44:04.130 --> 05:44:10.210
Since then the Avonlea church had enjoyed a variety of religious dissipation in listening

05:44:10.210 --> 05:44:16.190
to the many and various candidates and supplies who came Sunday after Sunday to preach on

05:44:16.190 --> 05:44:16.730
trial.

05:44:18.070 --> 05:44:24.410
These stood or fell by the judgment of the fathers and mothers in Israel, but a certain

05:44:24.410 --> 05:44:31.010
small red-haired girl who sat meekly in the corner of the old Cuthbert pew also had her

05:44:31.010 --> 05:44:37.590
opinions about them, and discussed the same in full with Matthew, Marilla always declining

05:44:37.590 --> 05:44:41.430
from principle to criticize ministers in any shape or form.

05:44:42.630 --> 05:44:48.770
I don't think Mr. Smith would have done, Matthew, was Anne's final summing up.

05:44:49.390 --> 05:44:55.510
Mrs. Linses's delivery was so poor, but I think his worst fault was just like Mr. Bentley's.

05:44:55.650 --> 05:45:00.310
He had no imagination, and Mr. Terry had too much.

05:45:00.430 --> 05:45:04.210
He let her run away with him just as I did mine in the manor of the Haunted Wood.

05:45:04.770 --> 05:45:07.650
Besides, Mrs. Linses's theology wasn't sound.

05:45:08.430 --> 05:45:12.490
Mr. Grassland was a very good man and a very religious man, but he told too many funny

05:45:12.490 --> 05:45:14.190
stories and made the people laugh in church.

05:45:14.310 --> 05:45:18.730
He was undignified, and you must have some dignity about a minister, mustn't you, Matthew?

05:45:19.150 --> 05:45:23.270
I thought Mr. Marshall was decidedly attractive, but Mrs. Linses, as he isn't married or even

05:45:23.270 --> 05:45:26.450
engaged because she made special inquiries about him and she says it would never do to

05:45:26.450 --> 05:45:30.010
have a young unmarried minister in Avonlea, because he might marry in the congregation

05:45:30.010 --> 05:45:31.050
and that would make trouble.

05:45:32.090 --> 05:45:34.670
Mrs. Linses is a very far-seeing woman, isn't she, Matthew?

05:45:34.670 --> 05:45:37.030
I am very glad they have called Mr. Allen.

05:45:37.170 --> 05:45:40.610
I like him because his sermon was interesting and he prayed as if he meant it, and not just

05:45:40.610 --> 05:45:42.470
if he did it because he was in the habit of it.

05:45:42.970 --> 05:45:46.470
Mrs. Linses, he isn't perfect, but she says she supposes we couldn't expect a perfect

05:45:46.470 --> 05:45:51.410
minister for $750 a year in any way, his theology is sound, because she questioned him thoroughly

05:45:51.410 --> 05:45:52.490
at all points of doctrine.

05:45:53.250 --> 05:45:56.190
And she knows his wife's people, and they are most respectable, and the women are all

05:45:56.190 --> 05:45:56.790
good housekeepers.

05:45:56.910 --> 05:46:00.230
Mrs. Linses, the sound doctrine in the man and the good housekeeping in the woman make

05:46:00.230 --> 05:46:02.370
an ideal combination for a minister's family.

05:46:03.250 --> 05:46:08.970
The new minister and his wife were a young, pleasant-faced couple, still on their honeymoon

05:46:08.970 --> 05:46:13.390
and full of all good and beautiful enthusiasms for their chosen life work.

05:46:14.230 --> 05:46:16.690
Avonlea opened its heart to them from the start.

05:46:17.110 --> 05:46:23.290
Old and young, like the frank, cheerful young man with his high ideals and the bright, gentle

05:46:23.290 --> 05:46:26.770
little lady who assumed the mistresship of the man's.

05:46:26.770 --> 05:46:31.110
With Mrs. Allen, Anne fell promptly and wholeheartedly in love.

05:46:31.550 --> 05:46:34.090
She had discovered another kindred spirit.

05:46:35.270 --> 05:46:41.210
Mrs. Allen is perfectly lovely, she announced one Sunday afternoon.

05:46:42.130 --> 05:46:45.210
She's taken her class, and she's a splendid teacher.

05:46:45.770 --> 05:46:49.770
She said right away she didn't think it was fair for the teacher to ask all the questions.

05:46:50.290 --> 05:46:53.870
And you know, Marilla, that is exactly what I've always thought.

05:46:53.870 --> 05:46:58.530
She said we could ask her any question we liked, and I asked ever so many.

05:46:58.750 --> 05:47:00.770
I'm good at asking questions, Marilla.

05:47:01.610 --> 05:47:05.690
I believe you, was Marilla's emphatic comment.

05:47:07.310 --> 05:47:12.210
Nobody else asked any except Ruby Gillis, and she asked if there was to be a Sunday

05:47:12.210 --> 05:47:13.730
school picnic this summer.

05:47:14.110 --> 05:47:18.230
I didn't think that was a very proper question to ask, because it hadn't any connection

05:47:18.230 --> 05:47:18.950
with the lesson.

05:47:19.390 --> 05:47:23.850
The lesson was about Daniel and the lion's den, but Mrs. Allen just smiled and said she

05:47:23.850 --> 05:47:25.030
thought there would be.

05:47:25.410 --> 05:47:30.390
Mrs. Allen has a lovely smile, she has such exquisite dimples in her cheeks.

05:47:30.610 --> 05:47:32.890
I wish I had dimples in my cheeks, Marilla.

05:47:33.130 --> 05:47:37.730
I'm not half as skinny as I was when I came here, but I have no dimples yet.

05:47:38.210 --> 05:47:40.810
If I had, perhaps I could influence people for good.

05:47:41.530 --> 05:47:44.650
Mrs. Allen said we ought to try to influence other people for good.

05:47:44.910 --> 05:47:46.830
She talks so nice about everything.

05:47:46.950 --> 05:47:49.810
I never knew before that religion was such a cheerful thing.

05:47:49.810 --> 05:47:54.570
I always thought it was kind of melancholy, but Mrs. Allen's isn't, and I'd like to be

05:47:54.570 --> 05:47:56.370
a Christian if I could be one like her.

05:47:56.590 --> 05:47:59.390
I wouldn't want to be one like Mr. Superintendent Bell.

05:48:01.390 --> 05:48:06.610
It's very naughty of you to speak so about Mr. Bell, said Marilla severely.

05:48:07.010 --> 05:48:08.890
Mr. Bell is a real good man.

05:48:11.250 --> 05:48:17.930
Oh, of course he's good, agreed Anne, but he doesn't seem to get any comfort out of

05:48:17.930 --> 05:48:18.170
it.

05:48:18.170 --> 05:48:22.770
If I could be good, I'd dance and sing all day because I was glad of it.

05:48:23.330 --> 05:48:27.770
I suppose Mrs. Allen is too old to dance and sing, and of course it wouldn't be dignified

05:48:27.770 --> 05:48:28.650
to administer his wife.

05:48:29.230 --> 05:48:33.830
I can just feel she's glad she's a Christian and that she'd be one even if she could get

05:48:33.830 --> 05:48:35.170
to heaven without it.

05:48:36.330 --> 05:48:42.550
I suppose he must have missed her Mrs. Allen up to tea some day soon, said Marilla reflectively.

05:48:42.970 --> 05:48:44.930
They've been most everywhere but here.

05:48:44.930 --> 05:48:46.190
Let me see.

05:48:46.630 --> 05:48:50.930
Next Wednesday'd be a good time to have them, but don't say a word to Matthew about it,

05:48:51.030 --> 05:48:54.310
for if he knew they were coming he'd find some excuse to be away that day.

05:48:55.030 --> 05:48:59.230
He got so used to Mr. Bentley he didn't mind him, but he's going to find it hard to get

05:48:59.230 --> 05:49:02.950
acquainted with a new minister, and a new minister's wife will frighten him to death.

05:49:04.450 --> 05:49:11.450
I'll be as secret as the dead, assured Anne, but oh, Marilla, will you let me make a cake

05:49:11.450 --> 05:49:12.210
for the occasion?

05:49:12.210 --> 05:49:16.510
I'd love to do something for Mrs. Allen, and you know I can make a pretty good cake by

05:49:16.510 --> 05:49:17.170
this time.

05:49:18.570 --> 05:49:22.030
You can make a lighter cake, promised Marilla.

05:49:23.430 --> 05:49:27.810
Monday and Tuesday great preparations went on at Green Gables.

05:49:28.670 --> 05:49:34.070
Having the minister and his wife to tea was a serious and important undertaking, and Marilla

05:49:34.070 --> 05:49:37.910
was determined not to be eclipsed by any of the Avonlea housekeepers.

05:49:38.430 --> 05:49:40.930
Anne was wild with excitement and delight.

05:49:41.270 --> 05:49:46.750
She talked it all over with Diana Tuesday night in the twilight, as they sat on the

05:49:46.750 --> 05:49:53.050
big red stones by the Dryad's Bubble, and made rainbows in the water with little twigs

05:49:53.050 --> 05:49:54.730
dipped in fir balsam.

05:49:56.330 --> 05:50:01.530
Everything is ready, Diana, except my cake, which I'm to make in the morning, and the

05:50:01.530 --> 05:50:04.630
baking-powder biscuits which Marilla will make just before tea-time.

05:50:04.950 --> 05:50:09.590
I assure you, Diana, that Marilla and I have had a busy two days of it.

05:50:09.590 --> 05:50:13.930
It's such a responsibility, having a minister's family to tea.

05:50:14.330 --> 05:50:16.970
I never went through such an experience before.

05:50:17.550 --> 05:50:19.310
You should just see our pantry.

05:50:19.550 --> 05:50:20.950
It's a sight to behold.

05:50:21.410 --> 05:50:24.030
We're going to have jelly chicken and cold tongue.

05:50:24.410 --> 05:50:29.850
We're to have two kinds of jelly—red and yellow and whipped cream and leaven pie and

05:50:29.850 --> 05:50:34.610
cherry pie and three kinds of cookies and fruit cake and Marilla's famous yellow plum

05:50:34.610 --> 05:50:39.970
that she keeps especially for ministers and pound cake and layer cake and biscuits, as

05:50:40.470 --> 05:50:45.970
aforesaid, and new bread and old both in case the minister is dyspeptic and can't eat new.

05:50:46.870 --> 05:50:50.450
Mrs. Lynn says ministers are dyspeptic, but I don't think Mr. Allen has been a minister

05:50:50.450 --> 05:50:52.370
long enough for it to have a bad effect on him.

05:50:52.690 --> 05:50:55.290
I just grow cold when I think of my layer cake.

05:50:55.850 --> 05:50:58.070
Oh, Diana, what if it shouldn't be good?

05:50:58.810 --> 05:51:03.650
I dreamed last night that I was chased all over by a fearful goblin with a big layer cake for a head.

05:51:04.890 --> 05:51:11.710
It'll be good, all right, assured Diana, who was a very comfortable sort of friend.

05:51:12.430 --> 05:51:17.010
I'm sure that piece of the one you made that we had for lunch a night a while two weeks ago

05:51:17.010 --> 05:51:18.810
was perfectly elegant.

05:51:20.250 --> 05:51:25.810
Yes, but cakes have such a terrible habit of turning out bad just when you especially

05:51:25.810 --> 05:51:32.210
want them to be good, side-and, setting a particularly well-balsam twig afloat.

05:51:33.250 --> 05:51:39.310
However, I suppose I shall just have to trust a providence and be careful to put in the flower.

05:51:40.410 --> 05:51:44.130
Oh, look, Diana, what a lovely rainbow.

05:51:44.950 --> 05:51:49.430
Do you suppose the dryad will come out after we go away and take it for a scarf?

05:51:50.550 --> 05:51:55.530
You know there is no such thing as a dryad, said Diana.

05:51:56.270 --> 05:52:01.630
Diana's mother had found out about the haunted wood and had been decidedly angry over it.

05:52:02.330 --> 05:52:07.970
As a result, Diana had abstained from any further imitative flights of imagination

05:52:07.970 --> 05:52:14.310
and did not think it prudent to cultivate a spirit of belief, even in harmless dryads.

05:52:15.390 --> 05:52:19.830
But it's so easy to imagine there is, said Anne.

05:52:20.730 --> 05:52:25.850
Every night before I go to bed I look out my window and wonder if the dryad is really sitting

05:52:25.850 --> 05:52:31.410
there, combing her locks with the spring for a mirror. Sometimes I look for her

05:52:31.410 --> 05:52:37.110
footprints in the dew in the morning. Oh, Diana, don't give up your faith in the dryad.

05:52:38.590 --> 05:52:44.170
Wednesday morning came. Anne got up at sunrise because she was too excited to sleep.

05:52:44.590 --> 05:52:49.330
She had caught a severe cold in the head by reason of her dabbling in the spring and the

05:52:49.330 --> 05:52:54.790
preceding evening, but nothing short of absolute pneumonia could have quenched her interest in

05:52:54.790 --> 05:53:01.730
culinary matters that morning. After breakfast she proceeded to make her cake. When she finally

05:53:01.730 --> 05:53:08.490
shut the oven door upon it, she drew a long breath. I'm sure I haven't forgotten anything

05:53:08.490 --> 05:53:14.530
this time, Marilla, but do you think it will rise? Just suppose perhaps the baking powder

05:53:14.530 --> 05:53:19.970
isn't good. I used it out of the new can, and Mrs. Lynde says you can never be sure of getting

05:53:19.970 --> 05:53:25.350
good baking powder nowadays when everything is so adulterated. Mrs. Lynde says the Government

05:53:25.350 --> 05:53:29.910
ought to take the matter up, but she says we'll never see the day when the Tory Government will

05:53:29.910 --> 05:53:38.130
do it. Marilla, what if the cake doesn't rise? We'll have plenty without it, was Marilla's

05:53:38.130 --> 05:53:45.050
unimpassioned way of looking at the subject. The cake did rise, however, and came out of the oven

05:53:45.430 --> 05:53:52.990
and feathery as golden foam. Anne, flushed with delight, clapped it together with layers of

05:53:52.990 --> 05:54:00.630
ruby jelly, and, in imagination, saw Mrs. Allen eating it and possibly asking for another piece.

05:54:00.950 --> 05:54:07.570
You'll be using the best tea set, of course, Marilla, she said. Can I fix the table with

05:54:07.570 --> 05:54:16.090
wild roses? I think that's all nonsense, sniffed Marilla, in my opinion it's the eatables that

05:54:16.090 --> 05:54:23.630
matter and not flummery decorations. Mrs. Barry had her table decorated, said Anne,

05:54:23.770 --> 05:54:29.750
who was not entirely guiltless of the wisdom of the serpent, and the minister paid her an

05:54:29.750 --> 05:54:34.350
elegant compliment. He said it was a feast for the eye as well as the palate.

05:54:35.230 --> 05:54:42.590
Well, do as you like, said Marilla, who was quite determined not to be surpassed by Mrs. Barry or

05:54:42.590 --> 05:54:50.490
anybody else. Only mind you need enough room for the dishes and food. Anne laid herself out to

05:54:50.490 --> 05:54:56.530
decorate in a manner and after a fashion that would leave Mrs. Barry's nowhere. Having abundance

05:54:56.530 --> 05:55:03.110
of roses and ferns and a very artistic taste of her own, she made that tea table such a thing of

05:55:03.110 --> 05:55:09.230
that when the minister and his wife sat down to it they exclaimed in chorus over its loveliness.

05:55:10.350 --> 05:55:18.170
It's Anne's doings, said Marilla, grimly just, and Anne felt that Mrs. Allen's approving smile

05:55:18.170 --> 05:55:25.470
was almost too much happiness for this world. Matthew was there, having been unveiled into the

05:55:25.470 --> 05:55:31.930
party only goodness and Anne knew how. He had been in such a state of shyness and nervousness that

05:55:31.930 --> 05:55:38.690
Marilla had given him up in despair, but Anne took him in hand so successfully that he now sat

05:55:38.690 --> 05:55:45.310
at the table in his best clothes and white collar and talked to the minister, not uninterestingly.

05:55:45.710 --> 05:55:51.170
He never said a word to Mrs. Allen, but that perhaps was not to be expected.

05:55:52.890 --> 05:56:00.110
All went merry as a marriage bell until Anne's layer cake was passed. Mrs. Allen, having already

05:56:00.110 --> 05:56:06.890
been held to a bewildering variety, declined it, but Marilla, seeing the disappointment on Anne's

05:56:06.890 --> 05:56:14.210
face, said smilingly, Oh, you must take a piece of this, Mrs. Allen. Anne made it on purpose for you.

05:56:14.930 --> 05:56:22.350
In that case I must sample it, laughed Mrs. Allen, helping herself to a plump triangle,

05:56:23.190 --> 05:56:29.130
as did also the minister and Marilla. Mrs. Allen took a mouthful of hers

05:56:29.130 --> 05:56:35.330
and a most peculiar expression crossed her face. Not a word did she say, however,

05:56:35.490 --> 05:56:41.590
but steadily ate away at it. Marilla saw the expression and hastened to taste the cake.

05:56:42.630 --> 05:56:47.670
Anne, surely, she exclaimed, what on earth did you put into that cake?

05:56:48.810 --> 05:56:56.630
Nothing but what the recipe said, Marilla, cried Anne with a look of anguish. Oh, isn't it all right?

05:56:57.790 --> 05:57:04.610
All right, it's simply horrible. Mr. Allen, don't try to eat it. Anne, taste it yourself.

05:57:04.850 --> 05:57:06.610
What flavoring did you use?

05:57:07.890 --> 05:57:13.770
Vanilla, said Anne, her face scarlet with mortification after tasting the cake.

05:57:14.730 --> 05:57:21.330
Holy vanilla! Oh, Marilla, it must have been the baking powder. I had my suspicions of that baking

05:57:21.330 --> 05:57:25.270
powder fiddlesticks. Go and bring me the bottle of vanilla you used.

05:57:26.410 --> 05:57:33.350
Anne fled to the pantry and returned with a small bottle, partially filled with a brown liquid,

05:57:33.770 --> 05:57:41.050
and labeled yellowly, best vanilla. Marilla took it, uncorked it, smelled it.

05:57:42.210 --> 05:57:48.430
Mercy on us, Anne! You flavored that cake with anodyne liniment. I broke the liniment bottle last

05:57:48.430 --> 05:57:53.530
week and poured what was left into an old empty vanilla bottle. I suppose it's partly my fault,

05:57:53.530 --> 05:57:58.090
I should have warned you. But for pity's sake, why couldn't you have smelled it?

05:57:59.010 --> 05:58:07.010
Anne dissolved into tears under this double disgrace. I couldn't. I had such a cold.

05:58:08.070 --> 05:58:11.910
And with this she fairly fled to the gabled chamber,

05:58:12.250 --> 05:58:16.970
where she cast herself on the bed and wept as one who refuses to be comforted.

05:58:18.990 --> 05:58:24.610
Presently a light step sounded on the stairs, and somebody entered the room.

05:58:26.150 --> 05:58:33.590
Oh, Marilla! sobbed Anne, without looking up. I'm disgraced forever. I shall never be able

05:58:33.590 --> 05:58:37.990
to live this down. It will get out. Things always do when Anne and Lee.

05:58:38.890 --> 05:58:42.610
Tana will ask me how my cake turned out, and I shall have to tell her the truth.

05:58:42.770 --> 05:58:46.950
I shall always be pointed at as the girl who flavored a cake with anodyne liniment.

05:58:46.970 --> 05:58:50.930
The boys in school will never get over laughing at it.

05:58:51.350 --> 05:58:54.230
Oh, Marilla, if you have a spark of Christian pity,

05:58:54.370 --> 05:58:57.450
don't tell me that I must go down and wash the dishes after this.

05:58:57.930 --> 05:59:02.250
I'll wash them when the minister and his wife are gone, but I cannot ever look at Mrs. Allen

05:59:02.250 --> 05:59:07.430
in the face again. Perhaps she'll think I tried to poison her. Mrs. Linz says she knows an orphan

05:59:07.430 --> 05:59:12.710
girl who tried to poison her, but the liniment isn't poisonous. It's meant to be taken eternally,

05:59:12.750 --> 05:59:16.630
although not in cakes. Won't you tell Mrs. Allen so, Marilla?

05:59:18.190 --> 05:59:23.190
Suppose you jump up and tell her so yourself, said a merry voice.

05:59:24.310 --> 05:59:31.690
Anne flew up to find Mrs. Allen standing by her bed, surveying her with laughing eyes.

05:59:32.890 --> 05:59:41.550
My dear little girl, you mustn't cry like this, she said, genuinely disturbed by Anne's tragic face.

05:59:42.230 --> 05:59:46.110
Why, it's all just a funny mistake that anybody might make.

05:59:47.070 --> 05:59:53.510
Oh, no, it takes me to make such a mistake, said Anne forlornly.

05:59:54.230 --> 05:59:58.010
And I wanted to have that cake so nice for you, Mrs. Allen.

05:59:59.230 --> 06:00:04.370
Yes, I know, dear, and I assure you I appreciate your kindness and thoughtfulness

06:00:04.370 --> 06:00:09.850
just as much as if it had turned out all right. Now, you mustn't cry any more,

06:00:10.050 --> 06:00:12.570
but come down with me and show me your flower garden.

06:00:12.570 --> 06:00:16.190
Miss Cuthbert tells me you have a little plot all your own.

06:00:16.370 --> 06:00:19.490
I want to see it, for I'm very much interested in flowers.

06:00:20.990 --> 06:00:24.090
Anne permitted herself to be let down and comforted,

06:00:24.970 --> 06:00:29.350
reflecting that it was really providential that Mrs. Allen was a kindred spirit.

06:00:30.330 --> 06:00:32.870
Nothing more was said about the liniment cake.

06:00:33.790 --> 06:00:38.530
And when the guests went away, Anne found that she'd enjoyed the evening more than she could

06:00:38.530 --> 06:00:45.170
have expected, considering that terrible incident. Nevertheless, she sighed deeply.

06:00:46.590 --> 06:00:52.590
Marilla, isn't it nice to think that tomorrow was a new day with no mistakes in it yet?

06:00:53.730 --> 06:00:56.950
I'll warrant you'll make plenty in it, said Marilla.

06:00:57.330 --> 06:01:00.170
I never saw your beat for making mistakes, Anne.

06:01:01.230 --> 06:01:05.650
Yes, and well I know it, admitted Anne mournfully.

06:01:07.250 --> 06:01:14.370
But have you ever noticed one encouraging thing about me, Marilla? I never make the same mistake twice.

06:01:16.450 --> 06:01:20.150
I don't know if that's much benefit when you're always making new ones.

06:01:22.030 --> 06:01:28.210
Oh, don't you see, Marilla? There must be a limit to the mistakes one person can make,

06:01:28.330 --> 06:01:31.590
and when I get to the end of them, then I'll be through with them.

06:01:31.850 --> 06:01:33.950
That's a very comforting thought.

06:01:35.030 --> 06:01:39.670
Well, you'd better go and give that cake to the pigs, said Marilla.

06:01:40.090 --> 06:01:43.970
It isn't fit for any human to eat, not even Jerry Boot.

06:02:03.950 --> 06:02:05.610
Prince Edward Island

06:02:26.710 --> 06:02:32.070
ForbiddenDragon.blogspot.com

06:02:32.610 --> 06:02:34.630
Anne of Green Gables

06:02:34.910 --> 06:02:37.770
by Lucy Maud Montgomery

06:02:41.070 --> 06:02:43.750
Anne is invited out to tea.

06:02:46.350 --> 06:02:49.750
And what are your eyes popping out of your head about now?

06:02:50.330 --> 06:02:54.630
asked Marilla, when Anne had just come in from a run to the post office.

06:02:55.270 --> 06:02:57.650
Have you discovered another kindred spirit?

06:02:59.750 --> 06:03:05.610
Excitement hung around Anne like a garment, shone in her eyes, kindled in every feature.

06:03:06.510 --> 06:03:10.510
She had come dancing up the lane like a windblown sprite

06:03:10.510 --> 06:03:15.030
through the mellow sunshine and lazy shadows of the August evening.

06:03:17.050 --> 06:03:20.730
No, Marilla, but oh, what do you think?

06:03:20.930 --> 06:03:23.950
I'm invited to tea at the man's tomorrow afternoon.

06:03:24.490 --> 06:03:27.130
Mrs. Allen left the letter for me at the post office.

06:03:27.570 --> 06:03:29.050
Just look at it, Marilla.

06:03:29.510 --> 06:03:32.450
Miss Anne Shirley, Green Gables.

06:03:32.910 --> 06:03:35.450
That is the first time I was ever called Miss.

06:03:36.090 --> 06:03:37.770
Such a thrill it gave me.

06:03:37.770 --> 06:03:41.730
I shall cherish it forever among my choicest treasures.

06:03:43.730 --> 06:03:48.530
Mrs. Allen told me she meant to have all the members of her Sunday school class to tea in turn,

06:03:49.310 --> 06:03:53.410
said Marilla, regarding the wonderful event very coolly.

06:03:54.090 --> 06:03:56.230
You needn't get in such a fever over it.

06:03:56.550 --> 06:03:58.670
Do learn to take things calmly, child.

06:04:00.730 --> 06:04:04.490
For Anne to take things calmly would have been to change her nature.

06:04:04.490 --> 06:04:10.670
All spirit and fire and dew as she was, the pleasures and pains of life

06:04:10.670 --> 06:04:12.850
came to her with trebled intensity.

06:04:13.910 --> 06:04:17.550
Marilla felt this and was vaguely troubled over it,

06:04:17.810 --> 06:04:23.930
realizing that the ups and downs of existence would probably bear hardly on this impulsive soul

06:04:23.930 --> 06:04:29.290
and not sufficiently understanding that the equally great capacity for delight

06:04:29.290 --> 06:04:31.090
might more than compensate.

06:04:32.650 --> 06:04:39.210
Therefore Marilla conceived it to be her duty to drill Anne into a tranquil uniformity of disposition

06:04:39.210 --> 06:04:45.170
as impossible and alien to her as to a dancing sunbeam in one of the brook shallows.

06:04:45.970 --> 06:04:50.610
She did not make much headway, as she sorrowfully admitted to herself.

06:04:51.370 --> 06:04:56.950
The downfall of some dear hope or plan plunged Anne into depths of affliction.

06:04:56.950 --> 06:05:02.630
The fulfillment thereof exalted her to dizzying realms of delight.

06:05:03.450 --> 06:05:07.990
Marilla had almost begun to despair of ever fashioning this waif of the world

06:05:07.990 --> 06:05:13.350
into her model little girl of demure manners and prim deportment.

06:05:13.790 --> 06:05:18.010
Neither would she believe that she really liked Anne much better as she was.

06:05:19.830 --> 06:05:22.990
Anne went to bed that night speechless with misery,

06:05:22.990 --> 06:05:29.450
because Matthew had said the wind was round northeast and he feared it would be a rainy day tomorrow.

06:05:30.330 --> 06:05:34.190
The rustle of the poplar leaves around the house worried her.

06:05:34.690 --> 06:05:40.750
It sounded so like pattering raindrops and the full faraway roar of the gulf,

06:05:41.110 --> 06:05:47.210
to which she listened delightly at other times, loving its strange, sonorous, haunting rhythm,

06:05:47.210 --> 06:05:55.830
now seemed like a prophecy of storm and disaster to a small maiden who particularly wanted a fine day.

06:05:56.890 --> 06:05:59.470
Anne thought that the morning would never come.

06:06:01.110 --> 06:06:08.190
But all things have an end, even nights before the day in which you were invited to take tea at the manse.

06:06:08.750 --> 06:06:15.630
The morning, in spite of Matthew's predictions, was fine, and Anne's spirits soared to their highest.

06:06:16.870 --> 06:06:23.010
Oh, Marilla, there is something in me today that makes me just love everybody I see,

06:06:23.490 --> 06:06:26.210
she exclaimed as she washed the breakfast dishes.

06:06:26.730 --> 06:06:31.210
You don't know how good I feel. Wouldn't it be nice if it could last?

06:06:31.730 --> 06:06:36.650
I believe I could be a model child if I were just invited out to tea every day.

06:06:37.050 --> 06:06:42.690
But, oh, Marilla, it's a solemn occasion, too. I feel so anxious.

06:06:42.690 --> 06:06:47.850
What if I shouldn't behave properly? You know I have never had tea at a manse before,

06:06:48.050 --> 06:06:50.790
and I'm not sure that I know all the rules of etiquette,

06:06:51.070 --> 06:06:55.850
although I've been studying the rules given in the etiquette department of the family herald ever since I came here.

06:06:56.290 --> 06:07:01.230
I'm so afraid I'll do something silly or forget to do something I should do.

06:07:01.870 --> 06:07:06.770
Would it be good manners to take a second helping of anything if you wanted it very much?

06:07:08.150 --> 06:07:11.1000
The trouble with you, Anne, is that you're thinking too much about yourself.

06:07:12.630 --> 06:07:16.530
You should just think of Mrs. Allen and what would be nice as the most agreeable to her,

06:07:17.190 --> 06:07:22.870
said Marilla, hitting for once in her life on a very sound and pithy piece of advice.

06:07:23.310 --> 06:07:25.810
Anne instantly recognized this.

06:07:27.270 --> 06:07:31.630
You are right, Marilla. I'll try not to think about myself at all.

06:07:32.870 --> 06:07:38.010
Anne evidently got through her visit without any serious breach of etiquette,

06:07:38.130 --> 06:07:42.930
for she came home through the twilight, under a great high-sprung sky,

06:07:43.850 --> 06:07:50.510
gloried over with trails of saffron and rosy cloud, in a beautified state of mind,

06:07:51.050 --> 06:07:57.930
and told Marilla all about it happily, sitting on the big red sandstone slab at the kitchen door,

06:07:57.930 --> 06:08:02.190
with her tired curly head in Marilla's gingham lap.

06:08:03.650 --> 06:08:07.770
A cool wind was blowing down over the long harvest fields,

06:08:08.090 --> 06:08:13.190
from the rims of furry western hills and whistling through the poplars.

06:08:14.110 --> 06:08:21.330
One clear star hung over the orchard, and the fireflies were flitting over in lovers' lane,

06:08:21.330 --> 06:08:25.590
in and out among the ferns and rustling boughs.

06:08:26.270 --> 06:08:32.250
Anne watched them as she talked, and somehow felt that wind and stars and fireflies

06:08:32.250 --> 06:08:38.710
were all tangled up together into something unutterably sweet and enchanting.

06:08:40.230 --> 06:08:44.410
Oh, Marilla, I've had a most fascinating time.

06:08:44.870 --> 06:08:49.610
I feel that I have not lived in vain, and I shall always feel like that,

06:08:49.610 --> 06:08:53.070
even if I should never be invited to tea at a manse again.

06:08:53.670 --> 06:08:57.010
When I got there, Mrs. Allen met me at the door.

06:08:57.370 --> 06:09:01.130
She was dressed in the sweetest dress of pale pink organdy,

06:09:01.430 --> 06:09:07.010
with dozens of frills and elbow sleeves, and she looked just like a seraph.

06:09:07.430 --> 06:09:11.110
I really think I'd like to be a minister's wife when I grow up, Marilla.

06:09:11.930 --> 06:09:17.270
A minister mightn't mind my red hair, because he wouldn't be thinking of such worldly things.

06:09:17.270 --> 06:09:22.630
But then, of course, one would have to be naturally good, and I'll never be that.

06:09:22.750 --> 06:09:25.510
So I suppose there's no use in thinking about it.

06:09:26.110 --> 06:09:29.530
Some people are naturally good, you know, and others are not.

06:09:29.830 --> 06:09:30.950
I'm one of the others.

06:09:31.630 --> 06:09:34.250
Mrs. Lynn says I'm full of original sin.

06:09:34.590 --> 06:09:40.450
No matter how hard I try to be good, I can never make such a success of it as those who are naturally good.

06:09:41.630 --> 06:09:44.330
It's a good deal like geometry, I expect.

06:09:44.970 --> 06:09:48.470
But don't you think that trying so hard ought to count for something?

06:09:49.850 --> 06:09:52.570
Mrs. Allen is one of the naturally good people.

06:09:53.010 --> 06:09:54.650
I love her passionately.

06:09:55.110 --> 06:10:01.110
You know there are some people, like Matthew and Mrs. Allen, that you can love right off without any trouble.

06:10:01.750 --> 06:10:06.870
And there are others, like Mrs. Lynn, that you have to try very hard to love.

06:10:07.590 --> 06:10:13.010
You know you ought to love them, because they know so much and are such active workers in the church,

06:10:13.010 --> 06:10:17.590
but you have to keep reminding yourself of it all the time, or else you forget.

06:10:18.410 --> 06:10:22.590
There was another little girl at the Man's to Tea from the White Sands Sunday School.

06:10:22.990 --> 06:10:26.150
Her name was Laurette Bradley, and she was a very nice little girl.

06:10:26.410 --> 06:10:28.550
Not exactly a kid in spirit, you know.

06:10:28.990 --> 06:10:30.770
But still, very nice.

06:10:31.210 --> 06:10:35.750
We had an elegant tea, and I think I kept all the rules of etiquette pretty well.

06:10:36.170 --> 06:10:40.470
After tea, Mrs. Allen played and sang, and she got Laurette and me to sing, too.

06:10:40.470 --> 06:10:45.410
Mrs. Allen says I have a good voice, and she says I must sing in the Sunday School Choir after this.

06:10:46.010 --> 06:10:48.290
You can't think how I was thrilled at the mere thought.

06:10:48.930 --> 06:10:55.610
I've longed so to sing in the Sunday School Choir as Dana does, but I feared it was an honor I could never aspire to.

06:10:56.110 --> 06:11:01.130
Laurette had to go home early, because there's a big concert in the White Sands Hotel tonight, and her sister is to recite it.

06:11:01.770 --> 06:11:07.270
Laurette says that the Americans at the hotel give a concert every fortnight in aid of the Charlottetown Hospital,

06:11:07.270 --> 06:11:10.230
and they ask lots of the White Sands people to recite.

06:11:11.170 --> 06:11:13.870
Laurette said she expected to be asked herself some day.

06:11:14.230 --> 06:11:16.110
I just gazed at her in awe.

06:11:16.610 --> 06:11:19.530
After she had gone, Mrs. Allen and I had a heart-to-heart talk.

06:11:19.770 --> 06:11:27.090
I told her everything about Mrs. Thomas and the twins and Katie Maurice and Violetta and coming to Green Gables and my troubles over geometry,

06:11:27.190 --> 06:11:28.530
and would you believe it, Marilla?

06:11:28.910 --> 06:11:31.730
Mrs. Allen told me she was adept at geometry, too.

06:11:32.050 --> 06:11:34.010
You don't know how that encouraged me.

06:11:34.010 --> 06:11:36.750
Mrs. Lynn came to the man's just before I left.

06:11:37.050 --> 06:11:38.550
And what do you think, Marilla?

06:11:38.770 --> 06:11:42.170
The trustees have hired a new teacher, and it's a lady.

06:11:42.590 --> 06:11:44.770
Her name is Miss Muriel Stacey.

06:11:45.250 --> 06:11:46.930
Isn't that a romantic name?

06:11:47.230 --> 06:11:52.530
Mrs. Lynn says they've never had a female teacher in Avonlea before, and she thinks it's a dangerous innovation,

06:11:52.970 --> 06:11:55.790
but I think it'll be splendid to have a lady teacher.

06:11:56.030 --> 06:11:59.890
And I really don't see how I'm going to live through the two weeks before school begins.

06:11:59.890 --> 06:12:03.030
I'm so impatient to see her.

06:12:25.070 --> 06:12:28.470
Anne Comes to Grief in an Affair of Honor

06:12:28.470 --> 06:12:33.630
Anne had to live through more than two weeks as it happened, almost a month having elapsed

06:12:33.630 --> 06:12:38.250
since the Liniment Cake episode, it was high time for her to get into fresh trouble of

06:12:38.250 --> 06:12:43.610
some sort, little mistakes, such as absentmindedly emptying a pan of skim milk into a basket

06:12:43.610 --> 06:12:48.290
of yarn balls in the pantry instead of into the pig's bucket, and walking clean over

06:12:48.290 --> 06:12:52.510
the edge of the log bridge into the brook while wrapped in imaginative reverie, not

06:12:52.510 --> 06:12:53.810
really being worth mentioning.

06:12:55.070 --> 06:12:58.210
A week after the tea at the manse, Diana Berry gave a party.

06:12:58.770 --> 06:13:02.410
Small and select, Anne assured Marilla, just the girls in our class.

06:13:02.410 --> 06:13:07.550
They had a very good time, and nothing untoward happened until after tea, when they found

06:13:07.550 --> 06:13:12.390
themselves in the berry garden, a little tired of all their games, and ripe for any enticing

06:13:12.390 --> 06:13:14.450
form of mischief which might present itself.

06:13:14.850 --> 06:13:16.670
This presently took the form of daring.

06:13:17.430 --> 06:13:21.010
Daring was the fashionable amusement among the Avonlea small fry just then.

06:13:21.310 --> 06:13:24.330
It had begun among the boys, but soon spread to the girls.

06:13:24.550 --> 06:13:28.410
And all the silly things that were done in Avonlea that summer, because the doers thereof

06:13:28.410 --> 06:13:30.690
were dared to do them, would fill a book by themselves.

06:13:30.690 --> 06:13:35.790
First of all, Carrie Sloane dared Ruby Gillis to climb to a certain point in the huge old

06:13:35.790 --> 06:13:40.210
willow tree before the front door, which Ruby Gillis, albeit in mortal dread of the fat

06:13:40.210 --> 06:13:44.030
green caterpillars with which said tree was infested, and with the fear of her mother

06:13:44.030 --> 06:13:48.550
before her eyes if she should tear her new muslin dress, nimbly did, to the discomfiture

06:13:48.550 --> 06:13:50.130
of the aphor said Carrie Sloane.

06:13:50.690 --> 06:13:55.070
Then Josie Pye dared Jane Andrews to hop on her left leg around the garden without stopping

06:13:55.070 --> 06:13:59.730
once or putting her right foot to the ground, which Jane Andrews gamely tried to do, but

06:13:59.730 --> 06:14:02.670
gave out at the third corner and had to confess herself defeated.

06:14:04.130 --> 06:14:08.970
Josie's triumph, being rather more pronounced than good taste permitted, and Shirley dared

06:14:08.970 --> 06:14:12.490
her to walk along the top of the board fence which bounded the garden to the east.

06:14:13.010 --> 06:14:17.650
Now to walk board fences requires more skill and steadiness of head and heel than one might

06:14:17.650 --> 06:14:19.130
suppose who has never tried it.

06:14:19.390 --> 06:14:24.730
But Josie Pye, if deficient in some qualities that make for popularity, had at least a natural

06:14:24.730 --> 06:14:28.230
and inborn gift duly cultivated for walking board fences.

06:14:29.030 --> 06:14:33.450
Josie walked the berry fence with an airy unconcern which seemed to imply that a little

06:14:33.450 --> 06:14:35.230
thing like that wasn't worth a dare.

06:14:35.990 --> 06:14:40.470
Reluctant admiration greeted her exploit, for most of the other girls could appreciate it,

06:14:40.530 --> 06:14:43.730
having suffered many things themselves in their efforts to walk fences.

06:14:44.470 --> 06:14:49.090
Josie descended from her perch, flushed with victory, and darted a defiant glance at Anne.

06:14:49.490 --> 06:14:50.990
Anne tossed her red braids.

06:14:51.230 --> 06:14:55.210
"'I don't think it's such a very wonderful thing to walk a little low board fence,' she

06:14:55.210 --> 06:14:55.490
said.

06:14:55.490 --> 06:14:58.850
"'I knew a girl in Marysville who could walk the ridge pole of a roof.'

06:14:59.550 --> 06:15:01.790
"'I don't believe it,' said Josie flatly.

06:15:01.790 --> 06:15:04.110
"'I don't believe anybody could walk a ridge pole.

06:15:04.230 --> 06:15:05.930
You couldn't, anyhow.'

06:15:05.930 --> 06:15:06.650
"'Couldn't I?'

06:15:06.650 --> 06:15:07.790
cried Anne rashly.

06:15:07.950 --> 06:15:10.150
"'Then I dare you to do it,' said Josie defiantly.

06:15:10.250 --> 06:15:14.790
"'I dare you to climb up there and walk the ridge pole of Mr. Barry's kitchen roof.'

06:15:14.790 --> 06:15:17.890
Anne turned pale, but there was clearly only one thing to be done.

06:15:18.130 --> 06:15:21.830
She walked toward the house, where a ladder was leaning against the kitchen roof.

06:15:21.830 --> 06:15:23.630
All the fifth-class girls said,

06:15:24.190 --> 06:15:24.670
"'Oh!'

06:15:24.670 --> 06:15:26.750
Partly in excitement, partly in dismay.

06:15:27.130 --> 06:15:29.050
"'Don't you do it, Anne,' entreated Diana.

06:15:29.110 --> 06:15:30.610
"'You'll fall off and be killed.

06:15:30.790 --> 06:15:32.050
Never mind, Josie Pie.

06:15:32.210 --> 06:15:35.390
It isn't fair to dare anybody to do anything so dangerous.'

06:15:35.390 --> 06:15:37.090
"'I must do it.

06:15:37.150 --> 06:15:39.710
My honour is at stake,' said Anne solemnly.

06:15:39.830 --> 06:15:43.170
"'I shall walk that ridge pole, Diana, or perish in the attempt.

06:15:43.290 --> 06:15:46.230
If I am killed, you are to have my pearl bead ring.'

06:15:46.670 --> 06:15:51.810
Anne climbed the ladder amid breathless silence, gained the ridge pole, balanced herself uprightly

06:15:51.810 --> 06:15:54.870
on that precarious footing, and started to walk along it,

06:15:55.110 --> 06:15:57.970
dizzily conscious that she was uncomfortably high up in the world,

06:15:58.110 --> 06:16:01.870
and that walking ridge poles was not a thing in which your imagination helped you out much.

06:16:02.670 --> 06:16:06.370
Nevertheless, she managed to take several steps before the catastrophe came.

06:16:06.770 --> 06:16:10.410
Then she swayed, lost her balance, stumbled, staggered, and fell,

06:16:10.870 --> 06:16:15.310
sliding down over the sun-baked roof and crashing off it through the tangle of Virginia creeper beneath,

06:16:15.730 --> 06:16:19.850
all before the dismayed circle below could give a simultaneous, terrified shriek.

06:16:19.850 --> 06:16:23.510
If Anne had tumbled off the roof on the side up which she had ascended,

06:16:23.850 --> 06:16:27.030
Diana would have probably fallen heir to the pearl bead ring then and there.

06:16:27.450 --> 06:16:31.330
Fortunately, she fell on the other side, where the roof extended down over the porch,

06:16:31.650 --> 06:16:35.270
so nearly to the ground that a fall therefrom was a much less serious thing.

06:16:36.130 --> 06:16:40.030
Nevertheless, when Diana and the other girls had rushed frantically around the house,

06:16:40.350 --> 06:16:43.930
except Ruby Gillis, who remained as if rooted to the ground and went into hysterics,

06:16:44.310 --> 06:16:48.590
they found Anne lying all white and limp among the wreck and ruin of the Virginia creeper.

06:16:48.590 --> 06:16:52.710
"'Anne, are you killed?' shrieked Diana, throwing herself on her knees beside her friend.

06:16:52.910 --> 06:16:56.710
"'Oh, Anne, dear Anne, speak just one word to me and tell me if you're killed.'

06:16:56.710 --> 06:17:00.570
To the immense relief of all the girls, and especially of Josie Pye, who,

06:17:00.810 --> 06:17:05.270
in spite of lack of imagination, had been seized with horrible visions of a future branded

06:17:05.270 --> 06:17:08.650
as the girl who was the cause of Anne Shirley's early and tragic death,

06:17:09.070 --> 06:17:11.530
Anne sat dizzily up and answered uncertainly.

06:17:11.730 --> 06:17:15.850
"'No, Diana, I am not killed, but I think I am rendered unconscious.'

06:17:15.850 --> 06:17:17.850
"'Where?' sobbed Carrie Sloane.

06:17:18.030 --> 06:17:19.390
"'Oh, where, Anne?'

06:17:19.390 --> 06:17:22.110
Before Anne could answer, Mrs. Barry appeared on the scene.

06:17:22.410 --> 06:17:24.690
At sight of her, Anne tried to scramble to her feet,

06:17:24.950 --> 06:17:27.330
but sank back again with a sharp little cry of pain.

06:17:27.690 --> 06:17:28.590
"'What's the matter?

06:17:28.710 --> 06:17:30.930
Where have you hurt yourself?' demanded Mrs. Barry.

06:17:31.510 --> 06:17:33.010
"'My ankle,' gasped Anne.

06:17:33.190 --> 06:17:36.210
"'Oh, Diana, please find your father and ask him to take me home.

06:17:36.410 --> 06:17:40.130
I know I can never walk there, and I'm sure I couldn't hop so far on one foot

06:17:40.130 --> 06:17:42.090
when Jane couldn't even hop around the garden.'

06:17:42.830 --> 06:17:45.870
Marilla was out in the orchard picking a panful of summer apples

06:17:45.870 --> 06:17:49.170
when she saw Mr. Barry coming over the log bridge and up the slope,

06:17:49.550 --> 06:17:53.770
with Mrs. Barry beside him and a whole procession of little girls trailing after him.

06:17:54.130 --> 06:17:57.650
In his arms he carried Anne, whose head lay limply against his shoulder.

06:17:58.330 --> 06:18:00.430
At that moment Marilla had a revelation.

06:18:00.890 --> 06:18:03.610
In the sudden stab of fear that pierced her very heart,

06:18:03.930 --> 06:18:05.990
she realized what Anne had come to mean to her.

06:18:06.310 --> 06:18:09.990
She would have admitted that she liked Anne, nay, that she was very fond of Anne,

06:18:09.990 --> 06:18:12.950
but now she knew, as she hurried wildly down the slope,

06:18:13.250 --> 06:18:15.850
that Anne was dearer to her than anything else on earth.

06:18:16.530 --> 06:18:18.930
"'Mr. Barry, what has happened to her?' she gasped,

06:18:19.090 --> 06:18:22.230
more white and shaken than the self-contained, sensible Marilla

06:18:22.230 --> 06:18:23.550
had been for many years.

06:18:24.050 --> 06:18:26.150
Anne herself answered, lifting her head.

06:18:26.410 --> 06:18:27.890
"'Don't be very frightened, Marilla.

06:18:28.130 --> 06:18:30.270
I was walking the ridge-pole and I fell off.

06:18:30.450 --> 06:18:32.050
I expect I have sprained my ankle.

06:18:32.290 --> 06:18:33.950
But, Marilla, I might have broken my neck.

06:18:34.190 --> 06:18:35.830
Let us look on the bright side of things.'

06:18:35.830 --> 06:18:38.290
"'I might have known you'd go and do something of the sort

06:18:38.290 --> 06:18:40.450
when I let you go to that party,' said Marilla,

06:18:40.810 --> 06:18:42.350
sharp and shrewish in her very relief.

06:18:42.810 --> 06:18:45.390
"'Bring her in here, Mr. Barry, and lay her on the sofa.

06:18:45.930 --> 06:18:46.670
Mercy me!

06:18:46.690 --> 06:18:48.630
The child has gone and fainted.'

06:18:48.630 --> 06:18:49.730
It was quite true.

06:18:50.310 --> 06:18:53.590
Overcome by the pain of her injury, Anne had one more of her wishes

06:18:53.590 --> 06:18:54.590
granted to her.

06:18:54.790 --> 06:18:56.150
She had fainted dead away.

06:18:57.050 --> 06:18:59.370
Matthew, hastily summoned from the harvest field,

06:18:59.670 --> 06:19:01.410
was straightway dispatched for the doctor,

06:19:01.710 --> 06:19:04.950
who in due time came to discover that the injury was more serious

06:19:04.950 --> 06:19:06.110
than they had supposed.

06:19:06.530 --> 06:19:07.890
Anne's ankle was broken.

06:19:08.870 --> 06:19:10.850
That night, when Marilla went up to the East Gable,

06:19:10.950 --> 06:19:12.570
where a white-faced girl was lying,

06:19:12.890 --> 06:19:14.810
a plaintive voice greeted her from the bed.

06:19:15.270 --> 06:19:17.650
"'Aren't you very sorry for me, Marilla?'

06:19:17.650 --> 06:19:19.890
"'It was your own fault,' said Marilla,

06:19:20.070 --> 06:19:21.830
twitching down the blind and lighting a lamp.

06:19:22.430 --> 06:19:24.970
"'And that is just why you should be sorry for me,'

06:19:24.970 --> 06:19:25.510
said Anne,

06:19:25.670 --> 06:19:27.530
"'because the thought that it is all my own fault

06:19:27.530 --> 06:19:28.970
is what makes it so hard.

06:19:29.270 --> 06:19:32.230
If I could blame it on anybody I would feel so much better.

06:19:32.570 --> 06:19:34.030
But what would you have done, Marilla,

06:19:34.050 --> 06:19:35.930
if you had been dared to walk a ridge-pole?'

06:19:36.770 --> 06:19:39.070
"'I'd have stayed on good, firm ground

06:19:39.070 --> 06:19:40.570
and let them dare away.

06:19:40.790 --> 06:19:42.670
Such absurdity,' said Marilla.'

06:19:43.750 --> 06:19:44.630
Anne sighed.

06:19:44.630 --> 06:19:46.890
"'But you have such strength of mind, Marilla.

06:19:47.090 --> 06:19:47.970
I haven't.

06:19:48.150 --> 06:19:50.870
I just felt that I couldn't bear Josie Pye's scorn.

06:19:51.110 --> 06:19:53.070
She would have crowed over me all my life.

06:19:53.290 --> 06:19:55.450
And I think I have been punished so much

06:19:55.450 --> 06:19:57.530
that you needn't be very cross with me, Marilla.

06:19:57.810 --> 06:19:59.970
It's not a bit nice to faint after all.

06:20:00.070 --> 06:20:01.570
And the doctor hurt me dreadfully

06:20:01.570 --> 06:20:02.810
when he was setting my ankle.

06:20:03.170 --> 06:20:05.810
I won't be able to go around for six or seven weeks

06:20:05.810 --> 06:20:07.450
and I'll miss the new lady teacher.

06:20:07.810 --> 06:20:09.370
She won't be new any more by the time

06:20:09.370 --> 06:20:10.510
I'm able to go to school.

06:20:11.050 --> 06:20:13.770
And everybody will get ahead of me in class.

06:20:14.250 --> 06:20:15.890
Oh, I am an afflicted mortal.

06:20:16.190 --> 06:20:17.750
But I'll try to bear it all bravely

06:20:17.750 --> 06:20:20.270
if only you won't be cross with me, Marilla.'

06:20:20.270 --> 06:20:22.650
"'There, there, I'm not cross,' said Marilla.

06:20:22.870 --> 06:20:24.150
You're an unlucky child.

06:20:24.250 --> 06:20:25.510
There's no doubt about that.

06:20:25.770 --> 06:20:27.990
But as you say, you'll have the suffering of it.

06:20:28.330 --> 06:20:30.410
Here now, try and eat some supper.'

06:20:30.410 --> 06:20:32.690
"'Isn't it fortunate I've got such an imagination,'

06:20:33.070 --> 06:20:33.530
said Anne.

06:20:33.530 --> 06:20:35.870
"'It will help me through splendidly, I expect.

06:20:36.090 --> 06:20:38.210
What do people who haven't any imagination

06:20:38.210 --> 06:20:41.310
do when they break their bones, do you suppose, Marilla?'

06:20:41.310 --> 06:20:42.510
Anne had good reason

06:20:42.510 --> 06:20:44.410
to bless her imagination many a time

06:20:44.410 --> 06:20:46.350
and oft during the tedious seven weeks

06:20:46.350 --> 06:20:46.970
that followed.

06:20:47.310 --> 06:20:49.610
But she was not solely dependent on it.

06:20:49.810 --> 06:20:52.290
She had many visitors and not a day passed

06:20:52.290 --> 06:20:53.730
without one or more of the school girls

06:20:53.730 --> 06:20:55.610
dropping in to bring her flowers and books

06:20:55.610 --> 06:20:58.270
and tell her all the happenings in the juvenile world

06:20:58.270 --> 06:20:59.430
of Avonlea.

06:21:00.350 --> 06:21:02.190
"'Everybody has been so good and kind,

06:21:02.190 --> 06:21:04.370
Marilla,' sighed Anne happily on the day

06:21:04.370 --> 06:21:06.070
when she could first limp across the floor.

06:21:06.370 --> 06:21:08.430
"'It isn't very pleasant to be laid up.

06:21:08.570 --> 06:21:10.210
But there is a bright side to it, Marilla.

06:21:10.490 --> 06:21:12.210
You find out how many friends you have.

06:21:12.470 --> 06:21:15.030
Why, even Superintendent Bell came to see me

06:21:15.030 --> 06:21:16.890
and he's really a very fine man.

06:21:17.130 --> 06:21:18.850
Not a kindred spirit, of course.

06:21:19.030 --> 06:21:21.250
But still I like him and I'm awfully sorry

06:21:21.250 --> 06:21:22.810
I ever criticised his prayers.

06:21:23.130 --> 06:21:25.090
I believe now he really does mean them

06:21:25.090 --> 06:21:27.070
only he has gotten to the habit of saying

06:21:27.070 --> 06:21:28.110
them as if he didn't.

06:21:28.370 --> 06:21:30.310
He could get over that if he'd take a little trouble.

06:21:30.310 --> 06:21:32.030
I gave him a good broad hint.

06:21:32.330 --> 06:21:34.110
I told him how hard I tried to make my own

06:21:34.110 --> 06:21:35.650
little private prayers interesting.

06:21:36.290 --> 06:21:38.210
He told me all about the time he broke his ankle

06:21:38.210 --> 06:21:39.050
when he was a boy.

06:21:39.430 --> 06:21:42.030
It does seem so strange to think of Superintendent Bell

06:21:42.030 --> 06:21:43.050
ever being a boy.

06:21:43.450 --> 06:21:45.370
Even my imagination has its limits,

06:21:45.530 --> 06:21:47.030
for I can't imagine that.

06:21:47.410 --> 06:21:49.090
When I try to imagine him as a boy,

06:21:49.290 --> 06:21:51.270
I see him with grey whiskers and spectacles,

06:21:51.550 --> 06:21:53.830
just as he looks in Sunday school, only small.

06:21:54.390 --> 06:21:56.710
Now, it's so easy to imagine Mrs. Allan

06:21:56.710 --> 06:21:57.590
as a little girl.

06:21:57.590 --> 06:22:00.410
Mrs. Allan has been to see me fourteen times.

06:22:00.630 --> 06:22:02.290
Isn't that something to be proud of, Marilla?

06:22:02.690 --> 06:22:04.490
When a minister's wife has so many claims

06:22:04.490 --> 06:22:05.250
on her time.

06:22:05.870 --> 06:22:08.210
She is such a cheerful person to have visit you, too.

06:22:08.430 --> 06:22:10.210
She never tells you it's your own fault

06:22:10.210 --> 06:22:11.850
and she hopes you'll be a better girl

06:22:11.850 --> 06:22:12.670
on account of it.

06:22:13.090 --> 06:22:15.730
Mrs. Lynde always told me that when she came to see me

06:22:15.730 --> 06:22:17.910
and she said it in a kind of way that made me feel

06:22:17.910 --> 06:22:19.450
she might hope I'd be a better girl,

06:22:19.450 --> 06:22:21.030
but didn't really believe I would.

06:22:21.990 --> 06:22:23.830
Even Josie Pye came to see me.

06:22:23.930 --> 06:22:25.750
I received her as politely as I could

06:22:25.750 --> 06:22:28.610
because I think she was sorry she dared me to walk a ridge pole.

06:22:29.010 --> 06:22:29.950
If I had been killed,

06:22:30.190 --> 06:22:32.590
she would have had to carry a dark burden of remorse

06:22:32.590 --> 06:22:33.450
all her life.

06:22:34.150 --> 06:22:35.530
Diana has been a faithful friend.

06:22:35.730 --> 06:22:38.070
She's been over every day to cheer my lonely pillow.

06:22:38.470 --> 06:22:40.990
But, oh, I shall be so glad when I can go to school

06:22:40.990 --> 06:22:42.530
for I've heard such exciting things

06:22:42.530 --> 06:22:43.450
about the new teacher.

06:22:43.850 --> 06:22:45.790
The girls all think she is perfectly sweet.

06:22:46.270 --> 06:22:48.650
Diana says she has the loveliest fair curly hair

06:22:48.650 --> 06:22:50.210
and such fascinating eyes.

06:22:50.430 --> 06:22:51.570
She dresses beautifully

06:22:51.570 --> 06:22:54.170
and her sleeve puffs are bigger than anybody else

06:22:54.170 --> 06:22:55.390
and she is as beautiful as an Avonlea.

06:22:55.610 --> 06:22:57.810
Every other Friday afternoon she has recitations

06:22:57.810 --> 06:22:59.530
and everybody has to say a piece

06:22:59.530 --> 06:23:00.730
or take part in a dialogue.

06:23:01.210 --> 06:23:03.110
Oh, it's just glorious to think of it.

06:23:03.450 --> 06:23:04.950
Josie Pye says she hates it,

06:23:04.970 --> 06:23:07.530
but that is just because Josie has so little imagination.

06:23:08.630 --> 06:23:10.430
Diana and Ruby Gillis and Jane Andrews

06:23:10.430 --> 06:23:12.070
are preparing a dialogue called

06:23:12.070 --> 06:23:14.190
A Morning Visit for next Friday.

06:23:14.570 --> 06:23:16.810
And the Friday afternoons they don't have recitations.

06:23:17.170 --> 06:23:19.550
Miss Stacy takes them all to the woods for a field day

06:23:19.550 --> 06:23:21.850
and they study ferns and flowers and birds

06:23:21.850 --> 06:23:23.870
and they have physical culture exercises

06:23:23.870 --> 06:23:25.090
every morning and evening.

06:23:25.550 --> 06:23:27.750
Mrs. Lynn says she had never heard of such goings on

06:23:27.750 --> 06:23:29.570
and it all comes from having a lady teacher.

06:23:30.190 --> 06:23:31.830
But I think it must be splendid

06:23:31.830 --> 06:23:33.950
and I believe I shall find that Miss Stacy

06:23:33.950 --> 06:23:35.010
is a kindred spirit.

06:23:36.110 --> 06:23:38.750
There is one thing plain to be seen, Anne,

06:23:38.890 --> 06:23:39.590
said Marilla,

06:23:39.830 --> 06:23:41.850
and that is that your fall off the berry roof

06:23:41.850 --> 06:23:44.350
hasn't injured your tongue at all.

06:23:48.630 --> 06:23:50.330
Anne comes to grief

06:23:50.330 --> 06:23:51.710
in an affair of honour.

06:23:52.850 --> 06:23:54.910
Recorded by Randy Warwick

06:24:22.850 --> 06:24:26.070
Miss Stacy and her pupils get up a concert.

06:24:27.550 --> 06:24:30.790
It was October again when Anne was ready to go back to school.

06:24:31.410 --> 06:24:36.950
A glorious October, all red and gold with mellow mornings, when the valleys were filled with

06:24:36.950 --> 06:24:41.510
delicate mists as if the spirit of autumn had poured them in for the sun to drain.

06:24:42.050 --> 06:24:45.170
Amethyst pearl, silver rose, and smoke blue.

06:24:46.370 --> 06:24:51.910
The dews were so heavy that the fields glistened like cloth of silver, and there were such heaps

06:24:51.910 --> 06:24:56.430
of rustling leaves in the hollows of many stemmed woods to run crisply through.

06:24:57.710 --> 06:25:03.190
The birch path was a canopy of yellow, and the ferns were sear and brown all along it.

06:25:03.890 --> 06:25:08.190
There was a tang in the very air that inspired the hearts of small maidens tripping,

06:25:08.330 --> 06:25:11.490
unlike snails, swiftly and willingly to school.

06:25:12.290 --> 06:25:16.570
And it was jolly to be back again at the little brown desk beside Diana,

06:25:16.570 --> 06:25:22.010
with Ruby Gillis nodding across the aisle, and Carrie Sloane sending up notes,

06:25:22.450 --> 06:25:25.710
and Julia Bell passing a chew of gum down from the back seat.

06:25:26.750 --> 06:25:29.590
Anne drew a long breath of happiness as she sharpened her pencil

06:25:29.590 --> 06:25:32.430
and arranged her picture cards in her desk.

06:25:32.890 --> 06:25:34.950
Life was certainly very interesting.

06:25:35.930 --> 06:25:39.010
In the new teacher she found another true and helpful friend.

06:25:39.710 --> 06:25:44.910
Miss Stacy was a bright, sympathetic young woman with the happy gift of winning and holding the

06:25:44.910 --> 06:25:49.330
affections of her pupils and bringing out the best that was in them mentally and morally.

06:25:50.450 --> 06:25:55.930
Anne expanded like a flower under this wholesome influence and carried home to the admiring Matthew

06:25:55.930 --> 06:25:59.750
and the critical Marilla, glowing accounts of schoolwork and aims.

06:26:00.570 --> 06:26:02.970
I love Miss Stacy with my whole heart, Marilla.

06:26:03.370 --> 06:26:06.190
She is so ladylike, and she has such a sweet voice.

06:26:06.670 --> 06:26:10.750
When she pronounces my name I feel instinctively that she's spelling it with an E.

06:26:11.230 --> 06:26:13.090
We had recitations this afternoon.

06:26:13.090 --> 06:26:17.130
I just wish you could have been there to hear me recite Mary, Queen of Scots.

06:26:17.450 --> 06:26:19.690
I just put my whole soul into it.

06:26:20.330 --> 06:26:23.150
Ruby Gillis told me coming home that the way I said the line,

06:26:23.570 --> 06:26:27.490
now for my father's arms, she said, my woman's heart farewell.

06:26:28.150 --> 06:26:30.090
Just made her blood run cold.

06:26:31.310 --> 06:26:35.690
Well now, you might recite it for me some of these days out in the barn,

06:26:36.070 --> 06:26:36.990
suggested Matthew.

06:26:38.110 --> 06:26:40.450
Of course I will, said Anne meditatively.

06:26:41.030 --> 06:26:43.730
But I won't be able to do it so well, I know.

06:26:44.410 --> 06:26:48.610
It won't be so exciting as it is when you have a whole schoolful before you,

06:26:48.630 --> 06:26:50.470
hanging breathlessly on your words.

06:26:51.290 --> 06:26:53.630
I know I won't be able to make your blood run cold.

06:26:54.910 --> 06:26:59.930
Mrs. Lynn says it made her blood run cold to see the boys climbing to the very tops of those big

06:26:59.930 --> 06:27:04.390
trees on Bell's Hill after crow's nest last Friday, said Marilla.

06:27:05.210 --> 06:27:07.850
I wonder at Miss Stacy for encouraging it.

06:27:08.490 --> 06:27:12.490
But we wanted a crow's nest for nature study, explained Anne.

06:27:12.990 --> 06:27:14.370
And that was on our field afternoon.

06:27:14.950 --> 06:27:17.150
Field afternoons are splendid, Marilla.

06:27:17.790 --> 06:27:20.410
And Miss Stacy explains everything so beautifully.

06:27:21.310 --> 06:27:25.550
We have to write compositions on our field afternoons, and I write the best ones.

06:27:26.750 --> 06:27:29.050
It's very vain of you to say so, then.

06:27:29.270 --> 06:27:31.370
You'd better let your teacher say it.

06:27:31.810 --> 06:27:33.710
But she did say it, Marilla.

06:27:34.130 --> 06:27:36.450
And indeed, I'm not vain about it.

06:27:36.450 --> 06:27:39.650
How can I be when I'm such a dunce at geometry?

06:27:40.750 --> 06:27:43.570
Although I'm really beginning to see through it a little, too.

06:27:44.090 --> 06:27:45.770
Miss Stacy makes it so clear.

06:27:46.570 --> 06:27:51.070
Still, I'll never be good at it, and I assure you it is a humbling reflection.

06:27:52.270 --> 06:27:54.070
But I love writing compositions.

06:27:54.830 --> 06:27:57.310
Mostly Miss Stacy lets us choose our own subjects.

06:27:57.910 --> 06:28:01.370
But next week we are to write a composition on some remarkable person.

06:28:02.250 --> 06:28:05.250
It is hard to choose among so many remarkable people who have lived.

06:28:05.950 --> 06:28:08.110
Mustn't it be splendid to be remarkable

06:28:08.110 --> 06:28:10.650
and have compositions written about you after you're dead?

06:28:11.490 --> 06:28:13.810
Oh, I would dearly love to be remarkable.

06:28:14.770 --> 06:28:17.550
I think when I'm grown up, I'll be a trained nurse

06:28:17.550 --> 06:28:21.130
and go with the Red Crosses to the field of battle as a messenger of mercy.

06:28:21.970 --> 06:28:24.750
That is, if I don't go out as a foreign missionary.

06:28:25.550 --> 06:28:27.230
That would be very romantic.

06:28:27.930 --> 06:28:30.350
But one would have to be very good to be a missionary.

06:28:30.790 --> 06:28:32.490
And that would be a stumbling block.

06:28:32.490 --> 06:28:36.450
We have physical culture exercises every day, too.

06:28:36.770 --> 06:28:38.890
They make you graceful and promote digestion.

06:28:40.490 --> 06:28:44.990
Promote fiddlesticks, said Marilla, who honestly thought it was all nonsense.

06:28:45.930 --> 06:28:48.530
But all the field afternoons and recitation Fridays

06:28:48.530 --> 06:28:50.350
and physical culture contortions

06:28:50.350 --> 06:28:53.750
paled before a project which Miss Stacy brought forward in November.

06:28:54.890 --> 06:28:58.590
This was that the scholars of Avonlea School should get up a concert

06:28:58.590 --> 06:29:00.810
and hold it in the hall on Christmas night.

06:29:00.810 --> 06:29:04.690
For the laudable purpose of helping to pay for a schoolhouse flag.

06:29:06.490 --> 06:29:09.350
The pupils, one and all, taking graciously to this plan,

06:29:09.790 --> 06:29:12.490
the preparations for a program were begun at once.

06:29:13.550 --> 06:29:18.130
And of all the excited performers elect, none was so excited as Anne Shirley,

06:29:18.830 --> 06:29:21.630
who threw herself into the undertaking heart and soul,

06:29:22.270 --> 06:29:24.630
hampered as she was by Marilla's disapproval.

06:29:25.510 --> 06:29:27.790
Marilla thought it all rank foolishness.

06:29:28.610 --> 06:29:30.930
It's just filling your heads up with nonsense

06:29:30.930 --> 06:29:34.030
and taking time that ought to be put on your lessons, she grumbled.

06:29:34.810 --> 06:29:38.630
I don't approve of children's getting up concerts and racing about to practices.

06:29:39.310 --> 06:29:42.610
It makes them vain and forward and fond of gadding.

06:29:43.330 --> 06:29:45.950
But think of the worthy object, pleaded Anne.

06:29:46.430 --> 06:29:49.610
A flag will cultivate a spirit of patriotism, Marilla.

06:29:50.630 --> 06:29:54.650
Fudge, there's precious little patriotism in the thoughts of any of you.

06:29:54.970 --> 06:29:56.830
All you want is a good time.

06:29:58.330 --> 06:30:02.530
Well, when you can combine patriotism and fun, isn't it all right?

06:30:03.410 --> 06:30:06.130
Of course, it's real nice to be getting up a concert.

06:30:06.710 --> 06:30:10.110
We're going to have six choruses and Diana is to sing a solo.

06:30:10.750 --> 06:30:15.710
I'm in two dialogues, the Society for the Suppression of Gossip and the Fairy Queen.

06:30:16.690 --> 06:30:18.730
The boys are going to have a dialogue too.

06:30:19.310 --> 06:30:21.410
And I'm to have two recitations, Marilla.

06:30:21.970 --> 06:30:24.070
I just tremble when I think of it.

06:30:24.370 --> 06:30:26.510
But it's a nice, thrilling kind of tremble.

06:30:27.150 --> 06:30:31.390
And we're to have a tableau at the end, faith, hope, and charity.

06:30:32.090 --> 06:30:36.890
Diana and Ruby and I are all to be in it, all draped in white with flowing hair.

06:30:37.550 --> 06:30:42.770
I'm to be hope with my hands clasped, so, and my eyes uplifted.

06:30:43.750 --> 06:30:46.090
I'm going to practice my recitations in the garret.

06:30:46.670 --> 06:30:48.630
Don't be alarmed if you hear me groaning.

06:30:48.970 --> 06:30:51.510
I have to groan heartrendingly in one of them.

06:30:51.930 --> 06:30:55.070
And it's really hard to get up a good artistic groan, Marilla.

06:30:56.010 --> 06:30:59.650
Josie Pye is sulky because she didn't get the part she wanted in the dialogue.

06:31:00.390 --> 06:31:01.950
She wanted to be the fairy queen.

06:31:02.670 --> 06:31:07.450
That would have been ridiculous, for who ever heard of a fairy queen as fat as Josie?

06:31:07.770 --> 06:31:09.530
Fairy queens must be slender.

06:31:10.610 --> 06:31:14.630
Jane Andrews is to be the queen, and I am to be one of her maids of honor.

06:31:15.510 --> 06:31:19.510
Josie says she thinks a red-haired fairy is just as ridiculous as a fat one.

06:31:19.830 --> 06:31:22.490
But I do not let myself mind what Josie says.

06:31:23.370 --> 06:31:25.970
I'm to have a wreath of white roses on my hair,

06:31:26.290 --> 06:31:29.990
and Ruby Gillis is going to lend me her slippers because I haven't any of my own.

06:31:30.830 --> 06:31:33.710
It's necessary for fairies to have slippers, you know.

06:31:34.090 --> 06:31:38.010
You couldn't imagine a fairy wearing boots, could you, especially with copper toes?

06:31:39.030 --> 06:31:42.570
We are going to decorate the hall with creeping spruce and fur mottos

06:31:42.570 --> 06:31:44.850
with pink tissue paper roses in them.

06:31:45.190 --> 06:31:48.570
And we are all to march in two by two after the audience is seated,

06:31:48.870 --> 06:31:50.990
while Emma White plays a march on the organ.

06:31:51.670 --> 06:31:55.630
Oh, Marilla, I know you are not so enthusiastic about it as I am,

06:31:55.890 --> 06:31:58.770
but don't you hope your little Anne will distinguish herself?

06:31:59.830 --> 06:32:02.290
All I hope is that you'll behave yourself.

06:32:02.730 --> 06:32:07.270
I'll be heartily glad when all this fuss is over, and you'll be able to settle down.

06:32:07.430 --> 06:32:09.270
And you are simply good for nothing just now,

06:32:09.310 --> 06:32:12.650
with your head stuffed full of dialogues and groans and tableaus.

06:32:13.430 --> 06:32:17.270
As for your tongue, it's a marvel, it's not clean worn out.

06:32:19.010 --> 06:32:24.110
Anne sighed and betook herself to the back yard, over which a young new moon was shining

06:32:24.110 --> 06:32:27.910
through the leafless poplar boughs from an apple green western sky,

06:32:28.230 --> 06:32:29.750
and where Matthew was splitting wood.

06:32:30.610 --> 06:32:34.130
Anne perched herself on a block and talked the concert over with him.

06:32:35.070 --> 06:32:38.810
Sure of an appreciative and sympathetic listener in this instance, at least.

06:32:39.770 --> 06:32:43.010
Well now, I reckon it's going to be a pretty good concert,

06:32:43.010 --> 06:32:46.630
and I expect you'll do your part fine, he said,

06:32:46.630 --> 06:32:49.570
smiling down into her eager vivacious little face.

06:32:50.350 --> 06:32:51.870
Anne smiled back at him.

06:32:52.050 --> 06:32:53.630
Those two were the best of friends,

06:32:53.890 --> 06:32:56.530
and Matthew thanked his stars many a time and oft

06:32:56.530 --> 06:32:59.130
that he had nothing to do with bringing her up.

06:32:59.590 --> 06:33:01.430
That was Marilla's exclusive duty.

06:33:02.070 --> 06:33:05.090
If it had been his, he would have been worried over frequent conflicts

06:33:05.090 --> 06:33:07.490
between inclination and said duty.

06:33:08.090 --> 06:33:13.410
As it was, he was free to spoil Anne, Marilla's phrasing, as much as he liked.

06:33:14.190 --> 06:33:16.610
But it was not such a bad arrangement, after all.

06:33:16.630 --> 06:33:20.230
A little appreciation sometimes does quite as much good

06:33:20.230 --> 06:33:23.010
as all the conscientious bringing up in the world.

06:33:45.590 --> 06:33:49.250
Anne of Green Gables by Lucy Maude Montgomery

06:33:50.830 --> 06:33:55.250
Matthew insists on puffed sleeves.

06:33:58.130 --> 06:34:05.350
Matthew was having a bad 10 minutes of it. He had come into the kitchen in the twilight of a cold,

06:34:05.450 --> 06:34:12.250
gray, December evening, and had sat down in the wood box corner to take off his heavy boots,

06:34:13.010 --> 06:34:18.470
unconscious of the fact that Anne and a bevy of her schoolmates were having a practice of

06:34:18.470 --> 06:34:25.370
fairy queen in the sitting room. Presently, they came trooping through the hall and out into the

06:34:25.370 --> 06:34:32.690
kitchen, laughing and chattering gaily. They did not see Matthew, who shrank bashfully back into

06:34:32.690 --> 06:34:40.150
the shadows beyond the wood box, with a boot in one hand and a bootjack in the other, and he watched

06:34:40.150 --> 06:34:46.530
them shyly for the aforesaid 10 minutes as they put on caps and jackets and talked about the

06:34:46.530 --> 06:34:53.570
dialogue in the concert. Anne stood among them, bright-eyed and animated as they,

06:34:54.730 --> 06:35:00.030
but Matthew suddenly became conscious that there was something about her different from her mates,

06:35:00.870 --> 06:35:06.130
and what worried Matthew was that the difference impressed him as being something that should not

06:35:06.130 --> 06:35:15.430
exist. Anne had a brighter face and bigger starrier eyes and more delicate features than the others,

06:35:16.090 --> 06:35:20.310
even shy and observant Matthew had learned to take note of these things,

06:35:21.490 --> 06:35:25.530
but the difference that disturbed him did not consist in any of these respects.

06:35:27.130 --> 06:35:28.670
Then in what did it consist?

06:35:30.870 --> 06:35:37.310
Matthew was haunted by this question long after the girls had gone, arm in arm, down the long,

06:35:37.470 --> 06:35:44.890
hard-frozen lane, and Anne had betaken herself to her books. He could not refer it to Marilla,

06:35:44.890 --> 06:35:50.630
who he felt would be quite sure to sniff scornfully and remark that the only difference

06:35:50.630 --> 06:35:56.230
she saw between Anne and the other girls was that they sometimes kept their tongues quiet,

06:35:56.270 --> 06:36:01.070
while Anne never did. This Matthew felt would be no great help.

06:36:03.250 --> 06:36:09.610
He had recourse to his pipe that evening to help him study it out, much to Marilla's disgust.

06:36:10.410 --> 06:36:16.370
After two hours of smoking and hard reflection, Matthew arrived at a solution of his problem.

06:36:17.730 --> 06:36:19.890
Anne was not dressed like the other girls.

06:36:22.390 --> 06:36:25.770
The more Matthew thought about the matter, the more he was convinced

06:36:25.770 --> 06:36:31.710
that Anne never had been dressed like the other girls, never since she had come to Green Gables.

06:36:33.150 --> 06:36:39.850
Marilla kept her clothed in plain dark dresses, all made after the same unvarying pattern.

06:36:42.030 --> 06:36:47.170
If Matthew knew there was such a thing as fashion and dress, it was as much as he did,

06:36:47.850 --> 06:36:53.590
but he was quite sure that Anne's sleeves did not look at all like the sleeves the other girls wore.

06:36:54.830 --> 06:36:58.430
He recalled the cluster of little girls he had seen around her that evening,

06:36:59.150 --> 06:37:02.990
all gay in waists of red and blue and pink and white,

06:37:03.330 --> 06:37:08.150
and he wondered why Marilla always kept her so plainly and soberly gowned.

06:37:09.710 --> 06:37:15.470
Of course, it must be all right. Marilla knew best, and Marilla was bringing her up.

06:37:16.150 --> 06:37:20.890
Probably some wise, inscrutable motive was to be served thereby.

06:37:21.850 --> 06:37:26.170
But surely it would do no harm to let the child have one pretty dress.

06:37:26.750 --> 06:37:29.350
Something like Diana Berry always wore.

06:37:30.950 --> 06:37:37.550
Matthew decided that he would give her one. That, surely, could not be objected to as an unwarranted

06:37:37.550 --> 06:37:43.770
putting in of his oar. Christmas was only a fortnight off. A nice new dress would be the

06:37:43.770 --> 06:37:51.010
very thing for a present. Matthew, with a sigh of satisfaction, put away his pipe and went to bed,

06:37:51.710 --> 06:37:54.750
while Marilla opened all the doors and aired the house.

06:37:57.430 --> 06:38:02.530
The very next evening, Matthew betook himself to Carmody to buy the dress,

06:38:03.350 --> 06:38:06.470
determined to get the worst over and have done with it.

06:38:07.670 --> 06:38:14.390
It would be, he felt assured, no trifling ordeal. There were some things Matthew could buy and prove

06:38:14.390 --> 06:38:20.590
himself no mean bargainer, but he knew he would be at the mercy of shopkeepers when it came to

06:38:20.590 --> 06:38:22.130
a girl's dress.

06:38:24.590 --> 06:38:31.390
After much cogitation, Matthew resolved to go to Samuel Lawson's store, instead of William Blair's.

06:38:32.690 --> 06:38:36.190
To be sure, the Cuthberts always had gone to William Blair's.

06:38:37.130 --> 06:38:41.810
It was almost as much a matter of conscience with them as to attend the Presbyterian Church

06:38:41.810 --> 06:38:47.630
and vote conservative. But William Blair's two daughters frequently waited on customers there,

06:38:47.630 --> 06:38:54.030
and Matthew held them in absolute dread. He could contrive to deal with them when he knew

06:38:54.030 --> 06:39:00.810
exactly what he wanted and could point it out, but in such a matter as this, requiring explanation

06:39:00.810 --> 06:39:06.110
and consultation, Matthew felt that he must be sure of a man behind the counter.

06:39:07.350 --> 06:39:11.330
So he would go to Lawson's, where Samuel or his son would wait on him.

06:39:13.250 --> 06:39:19.510
Alas, Matthew did not know that Samuel, in the recent expansion of his business, had set up a

06:39:19.510 --> 06:39:27.650
lady clerk also. She was a niece of his wife's, and a very dashing young person indeed, with a huge

06:39:27.650 --> 06:39:34.890
drooping pompadour, big rolling brown eyes, and a most extensive and bewildering smile.

06:39:36.430 --> 06:39:41.310
She was dressed with exceeding smartness and wore several bangle bracelets that glowed

06:39:41.310 --> 06:39:48.830
and rattled and tinkled with every movement of her hands. Matthew was covered with confusion

06:39:48.830 --> 06:39:55.390
at finding her there at all, and those bangles completely wrecked his wits at one fell swoop.

06:39:57.850 --> 06:40:03.070
What can I do for you this evening, Mr. Cuthbert? Miss Lucilla Harris inquired,

06:40:04.250 --> 06:40:08.310
briskly and ingratiatingly, tapping the counter with both hands.

06:40:09.470 --> 06:40:21.670
Have you any garden rakes? stammered Matthew. Miss Harris looked somewhat surprised,

06:40:22.750 --> 06:40:28.090
as well she might, to hear a man inquiring for garden rakes in the middle of December.

06:40:30.130 --> 06:40:36.530
I believe we have one or two left over, she said, but they're upstairs in the lumber room.

06:40:37.410 --> 06:40:44.470
I'll go and see. During her absence, Matthew collected his scattered senses for another effort.

06:40:46.890 --> 06:40:50.130
When Miss Harris returned with the rake and cheerfully inquired,

06:40:50.810 --> 06:40:56.430
anything else tonight, Mr. Cuthbert? Matthew took his courage in both hands and replied,

06:40:56.430 --> 06:41:09.230
Well now, since you suggest it, I might as well take, that is, look at, buy some hayseed.

06:41:11.070 --> 06:41:17.430
Miss Harris had heard Matthew Cuthbert called odd. She now concluded that he was entirely crazy.

06:41:19.350 --> 06:41:26.010
We only keep hayseed in the spring, she explained loftily. We've none on hand just now.

06:41:27.750 --> 06:41:33.770
Oh, certainly, certainly, just as you say, stammered unhappy Matthew,

06:41:34.390 --> 06:41:40.550
seizing the rake and making for the door. At the threshold, he recollected that he had not paid

06:41:40.550 --> 06:41:47.090
for it, and he turned miserably back. While Miss Harris was counting out his change,

06:41:47.690 --> 06:41:56.030
he rallied his powers for a final desperate attempt. Well now, if it isn't too much trouble,

06:41:56.430 --> 06:42:03.730
I might as well, that is, I'd like to look at, at some sugar.

06:42:05.970 --> 06:42:12.810
White or brown, queried Miss Harris patiently. Oh, well now, brown, said Matthew feebly.

06:42:14.690 --> 06:42:18.650
There's a barrel of it over there, said Miss Harris, shaking her bangles at it.

06:42:18.650 --> 06:42:20.870
It's the only kind we have.

06:42:22.890 --> 06:42:28.770
I'll, I'll take twenty pounds of it, said Matthew with beads of perspiration standing on his forehead.

06:42:30.630 --> 06:42:37.110
Matthew had driven halfway home before he was his own man again. It had been a gruesome experience,

06:42:37.490 --> 06:42:42.690
but it served him right, he thought, for committing the heresy of going to a strange store.

06:42:43.380 --> 06:42:49.650
When he reached home, he hid the rake in the tool house, but the sugar he carried in to Marilla.

06:42:51.150 --> 06:42:59.230
Brown sugar, exclaimed Marilla. Whatever possessed you to get so much? You know I never use it except

06:42:59.230 --> 06:43:06.850
for the hired man's porridge or black fruitcake. Cherry's gone, and I've made my cake long ago.

06:43:07.730 --> 06:43:14.910
It's not good sugar either. It's coarse and dark. William Blair doesn't usually keep sugar like that.

06:43:17.030 --> 06:43:22.390
I, I thought it might come in handy sometimes, said Matthew, making good his escape.

06:43:24.370 --> 06:43:27.830
When Matthew came to think the matter over, he decided that

06:43:27.830 --> 06:43:34.850
a woman was required to cope with the situation. Marilla was out of the question. Matthew felt

06:43:34.850 --> 06:43:42.310
sure she would throw cold water on his project at once. Remained only Mrs. Lind, for of no other

06:43:42.310 --> 06:43:48.330
woman in Avonlea would Matthew have dared to ask advice. To Mrs. Lind he went accordingly,

06:43:48.930 --> 06:43:53.250
and that good lady promptly took the matter out of the harassed man's hands.

06:43:55.390 --> 06:43:58.490
Pick out a dress for you to give Anne? To be sure I will.

06:43:58.990 --> 06:44:04.750
I'm going to Carmody tomorrow, and I'll attend to it. Have you something particular in mind?

06:44:04.850 --> 06:44:12.910
No. Well, I'll just go by my own judgment then. I believe a nice rich brown would just suit Anne,

06:44:13.190 --> 06:44:18.790
and William Blair has some new Gloria in that's real pretty. Perhaps he'd like me to make it up

06:44:18.790 --> 06:44:23.710
for her too, seeing that if Marilla was to make it Anne would probably get wind of it before the

06:44:23.710 --> 06:44:30.550
time and spoil the surprise. Well, I'll do it. No, it isn't a might of trouble. I like sewing.

06:44:31.150 --> 06:44:36.770
I'll make it to fit my niece Jenny Gillis, for she and Anne are as like as two peas as far as

06:44:36.770 --> 06:44:46.730
figure goes. Well, now I'm much obliged, said Matthew, and, and, I don't know, but I'd like...

06:44:46.730 --> 06:44:50.390
I think they make the sleeves different nowadays to what they used to be.

06:44:51.070 --> 06:44:55.690
If it wouldn't be asking too much, I'd like them made in the new way.

06:44:57.170 --> 06:45:02.750
Puffs? Of course. You needn't worry. Expect more about it, Matthew. I'll make it up in the very

06:45:02.750 --> 06:45:09.810
latest fashion, said Mrs. Lind. To herself she added when Matthew had gone. It'll be a real

06:45:09.810 --> 06:45:16.030
satisfaction to see that poor child wearing something decent for once. The way Marilla dresses her is

06:45:16.030 --> 06:45:20.970
positively ridiculous, that's what, and I've ached to tell her so plainly a dozen times.

06:45:21.730 --> 06:45:25.590
I've held my tongue, though, for I can see Marilla doesn't want advice,

06:45:25.950 --> 06:45:30.350
and she thinks she knows more about bringing children up than I do, for all she's an old maid.

06:45:31.310 --> 06:45:36.570
But that's always the way. Folks that has brought up children know there's no hard and fast method

06:45:36.570 --> 06:45:42.330
in the world that'll suit every child, but them as never have think it's all plain and easy as

06:45:42.330 --> 06:45:47.770
rule of three. Just set your three terms down so fashion and the sum will work out correct.

06:45:48.650 --> 06:45:51.510
But flesh and blood don't come under the head of arithmetic,

06:45:51.970 --> 06:45:57.210
and that's where Marilla Cuthbert makes her mistake. I suppose she's trying to cultivate

06:45:57.210 --> 06:46:01.950
a spirit of humility in Anne by dressing her as she does, but it's more likely to

06:46:01.950 --> 06:46:07.310
cultivate envy and discontent. I'm sure the child must feel the difference between her

06:46:07.310 --> 06:46:14.030
clothes and the other girls, but to think of Matthew taking notice of it, that man is waking up

06:46:14.030 --> 06:46:16.110
after being asleep for over 60 years.

06:46:19.650 --> 06:46:24.130
Marilla knew all the following fortnight that Matthew had something on his mind,

06:46:24.850 --> 06:46:30.130
but what it was she could not guess until Christmas Eve when Mrs. Lynde brought up the new dress.

06:46:31.870 --> 06:46:37.590
Marilla behaved pretty well on the whole, although it is very likely she distrusted Mrs. Lynde's

06:46:37.590 --> 06:46:42.770
diplomatic explanation that she had made the dress because Matthew was afraid Anne would

06:46:42.770 --> 06:46:45.230
find out about it too soon if Marilla made it.

06:46:47.550 --> 06:46:52.370
So this is what Matthew's been looking so mysterious over and grinning about to himself

06:46:52.370 --> 06:47:00.090
for two weeks, is it? She said a little stiffly, but tolerantly. I knew he was up to some foolishness.

06:47:00.610 --> 06:47:06.970
Well, I must say I don't think Anne needed any more dresses. I made her three good, warm,

06:47:06.970 --> 06:47:13.230
serviceable ones this fall, and anything more is sheer extravagance. There's enough material in

06:47:13.230 --> 06:47:18.870
those sleeves alone to make a waste, I declare there is. You'll just pamper Anne's vanity,

06:47:19.170 --> 06:47:25.030
Matthew, and she's as vain as a peacock now. Well, I hope she'll be satisfied at last,

06:47:25.490 --> 06:47:29.490
for I know she's been hankering after those silly sleeves ever since they came in,

06:47:30.250 --> 06:47:35.970
although she never said a word after the first. The puffs have been getting bigger and more

06:47:35.970 --> 06:47:41.670
ridiculous right along. They're as big as balloons now. Next year anybody who wears them will have to

06:47:41.670 --> 06:47:50.250
go through a door sideways. Christmas morning broke on a beautiful white world. It had been

06:47:50.250 --> 06:47:56.390
a very mild December, and people had looked forward to a green Christmas, but just enough

06:47:56.390 --> 06:48:03.370
snow fell softly in the night to transfigure Avonlea. Anne peeked out from her frosted gable

06:48:03.370 --> 06:48:09.690
window with delighted eyes. The firs in the haunted wood were all feathery and wonderful.

06:48:10.650 --> 06:48:16.610
The brooches and wild cherry trees were outlined in pearl. The plowed fields were stretches of

06:48:16.610 --> 06:48:24.110
snowy dimples, and there was a crisp tang in the air that was glorious. Anne ran downstairs

06:48:24.110 --> 06:48:31.410
singing until her voice re-echoed through green gables. Merry Christmas, Marilla. Merry Christmas,

06:48:31.410 --> 06:48:38.710
Matthew. Isn't it a lovely Christmas? I'm so glad it's white. Any other kind of Christmas doesn't

06:48:38.710 --> 06:48:46.190
seem real, does it? I don't like green Christmases. They're not green. They're just nasty faded browns

06:48:46.190 --> 06:48:55.090
and grays. What makes people call them green? Why, why Matthew? Is that for me? Oh, Matthew!

06:48:57.070 --> 06:49:03.590
Matthew had sheepishly unfolded the dress from its paper swavings and held it out with a deprecatory

06:49:03.590 --> 06:49:10.170
glance at Marilla, who famed to be contemptuously filling the teapot, but nevertheless watched the

06:49:10.170 --> 06:49:17.090
scene out of the corner of her eye with a rather interested air. Anne took the dress and looked at

06:49:17.090 --> 06:49:25.070
it in reverent silence. Oh, how pretty it was! A lovely soft brown gloria, with all the glossy

06:49:25.070 --> 06:49:33.390
silk, a skirt with dainty frills and shirrings, a waist elaborately pin-tucked in the most

06:49:33.390 --> 06:49:39.370
fashionable way, with a little ruffle of filmy lace at the neck. But the sleeves,

06:49:39.830 --> 06:49:46.410
they were the crowning glory, long elbow cuffs, and above them two beautiful puffs

06:49:46.410 --> 06:49:50.450
divided by rows of shirring and bows of brown silk ribbon.

06:49:52.210 --> 06:49:59.450
That's a Christmas present for you, Anne, said Matthew shyly. Why, why Anne, don't you like it?

06:49:59.830 --> 06:50:06.390
Well now, well now. For Anne's eyes had suddenly filled with tears.

06:50:07.950 --> 06:50:15.070
Like it? Oh, Matthew! Anne laid the dress over a chair and clasped her hands.

06:50:15.750 --> 06:50:22.910
Matthew, it's perfectly exquisite. Oh, I can never thank you enough. Look at those sleeves.

06:50:23.790 --> 06:50:26.090
Oh, it seems to me this must be a happy dream.

06:50:27.970 --> 06:50:33.750
Well, well, let us have breakfast, interrupted Marilla. I must say, Anne, I don't think you

06:50:33.750 --> 06:50:38.630
needed the dress. But since Matthew's got it for you, see that you take good care of it.

06:50:39.790 --> 06:50:44.410
There's a hair ribbon Mrs. Lent left for you. It's brown to match the dress.

06:50:45.070 --> 06:50:51.410
Come now, sit in. I don't see how I'm going to eat breakfast, said Anne rapturously.

06:50:52.610 --> 06:50:58.870
Breakfast seems so commonplace at such an exciting moment. I'd rather feast my eyes on that dress.

06:51:00.150 --> 06:51:04.810
I'm so glad that puffed sleeves are still fashionable. It did seem to me that I'd never

06:51:04.810 --> 06:51:10.090
get over it if they went out before I had a dress with them. I'd never have felt quite

06:51:10.090 --> 06:51:14.690
satisfied, you see. It was lovely of Mrs. Lent to give me the ribbon, too.

06:51:15.710 --> 06:51:21.510
I feel that I ought to be a very good girl indeed. It's at times like this I'm sorry I'm

06:51:21.510 --> 06:51:28.090
not a model little girl, and I always resolve that I will be in future. But somehow it's

06:51:28.090 --> 06:51:33.850
hard to carry out your resolutions when irresistible temptations come. Still,

06:51:34.270 --> 06:51:37.010
I really will make an extra effort after this.

06:51:39.190 --> 06:51:45.070
When the commonplace breakfast was over, Diana appeared, crossing the white log bridge in the

06:51:45.070 --> 06:51:51.470
hollow, a gay little figure in her crimson ulster. Anne flew down the slope to meet her.

06:51:52.810 --> 06:51:58.930
Merry Christmas, Diana. And oh, it's a wonderful Christmas. I've something splendid to show you.

06:51:59.290 --> 06:52:06.230
Matthew has given me the loveliest dress, with such sleeves. I couldn't even imagine any nicer.

06:52:07.610 --> 06:52:14.490
I've got something more for you, said Diana breathlessly. Here, this box. Anne Josephine

06:52:14.490 --> 06:52:20.450
sent us out a big box with ever so many things in it, and this is for you. I'd have brought it

06:52:20.450 --> 06:52:25.670
over last night, but it didn't come until after dark, and I never feel very comfortable coming

06:52:25.670 --> 06:52:31.890
through the haunted wood in the dark now. Anne opened the box and peeped in.

06:52:31.890 --> 06:52:39.130
First, a card with for the Anne girl and Merry Christmas written on it, and then a pair of the

06:52:39.130 --> 06:52:45.490
daintiest little kid slippers with beaded toes and satin bows and glistening buckles.

06:52:46.910 --> 06:52:52.130
Oh, said Anne, Diana, this is too much. I must be dreaming.

06:52:53.790 --> 06:52:58.950
I call it providential, said Diana. You won't have to borrow Ruby's slippers now,

06:52:58.950 --> 06:53:04.750
and that's a blessing, for they're two sizes too big for you, and it would be awful to hear a fairy

06:53:04.750 --> 06:53:11.610
shuffling. Josie Pye would be delighted. Mind you, Rob Wright went home with Gertie Pye from the

06:53:11.610 --> 06:53:19.810
practice night before last. Did you ever hear anything equal to that? All the Avonlea scholars

06:53:19.810 --> 06:53:25.850
were in a fever of excitement that day, for the hall had to be decorated and a last grand rehearsal

06:53:25.850 --> 06:53:33.510
held. The concert came off in the evening and was a pronounced success. The little hall was

06:53:33.510 --> 06:53:40.030
crowded. All the performers did excellently well, but Anne was the bright particular star of the

06:53:40.030 --> 06:53:48.770
occasion, as even envy in the shape of Josie Pye dared not deny. Oh, hasn't it been a brilliant

06:53:48.770 --> 06:53:54.670
evening, sighed Anne when it was all over and she and Diana were walking home together under a dark

06:53:54.670 --> 06:54:02.990
starry sky. Everything went off very well, said Diana practically. I guess we must have made as

06:54:02.990 --> 06:54:08.430
much as ten dollars. Mind you, Mr. Allen is going to send an account of it to the Charlottetown

06:54:08.430 --> 06:54:15.710
papers. Oh, Diana, will we really see our names in print? It makes me thrilled to think of it.

06:54:16.670 --> 06:54:22.670
Your solo was perfectly elegant, Diana. I felt prouder than you did when it was on chord.

06:54:22.670 --> 06:54:28.410
I just said to myself, it is my dear bosom friend who is so honored.

06:54:30.410 --> 06:54:35.790
Well, your recitations just brought down the house, Anne. That sad one was simply splendid.

06:54:37.390 --> 06:54:41.450
Oh, I was so nervous, Diana. When Mr. Allen called out my name,

06:54:41.730 --> 06:54:47.970
I really cannot tell how I ever got up on that platform. I felt as if a million eyes were looking

06:54:47.970 --> 06:54:53.310
at me and through me. And for one dreadful moment, I was sure I couldn't begin at all.

06:54:54.790 --> 06:55:00.430
Then I thought of my lovely puffed sleeves and took courage. I knew that I must live up to those

06:55:00.430 --> 06:55:06.110
sleeves, Diana. So I started in and my voice seemed to be coming from ever so far away.

06:55:06.330 --> 06:55:17.050
I just felt like a parrot. It's providential that I practiced those recitations so often in the

06:55:17.050 --> 06:55:21.650
right. Yes, indeed. You groaned lovely, assured Diana.

06:55:23.990 --> 06:55:29.630
I saw old Mrs. Sloan wiping away tears when I sat down. It was splendid to think I'd touched

06:55:29.630 --> 06:55:36.110
somebody's heart. It's so romantic to take part in a concert, isn't it? Oh, it's been a very

06:55:36.110 --> 06:55:44.230
memorable occasion indeed. Wasn't the boy's dialogue fine, said Diana. Gilbert Blythe was

06:55:44.230 --> 06:55:51.050
just splendid. Anne, I do think it's awful mean the way you treat Gil. Wait till I tell you.

06:55:51.330 --> 06:55:56.070
When you ran off the platform after the fairy dialogue, one of your roses fell out of your

06:55:56.070 --> 06:56:03.470
hair. I saw Gil pick it up and put it in his breast pocket. There now. You're so romantic

06:56:03.470 --> 06:56:10.070
that I'm sure you ought to be pleased at that. It's nothing to me what that person does,

06:56:10.070 --> 06:56:14.250
said Anne loftily. I simply never waste a thought on him, Diana.

06:56:16.470 --> 06:56:21.930
That night, Marilla and Matthew, who had been out to a concert for the first time in 20 years,

06:56:22.630 --> 06:56:26.010
sat for a while by the kitchen fire after Anne had gone to bed.

06:56:27.390 --> 06:56:35.950
Well now. I guess our Anne did as well as any of them, said Matthew proudly. Yes, she did,

06:56:35.950 --> 06:56:42.490
admitted Marilla. She's a bright child, Matthew, and she looked real nice too.

06:56:43.650 --> 06:56:48.450
I've been kind of opposed to this concert scheme, but I suppose there's no real harm

06:56:48.450 --> 06:56:54.790
in it after all. Anyhow, I was proud of Anne tonight, although I'm not going to tell her so.

06:56:56.570 --> 06:57:02.510
Well now, I was proud of her and I did tell her so, for she went upstairs, said Matthew.

06:57:03.570 --> 06:57:09.450
We must see what we can do for her some of these days, Marilla. I guess she'll need something more

06:57:09.450 --> 06:57:17.590
than Avonlea's school by and by. It's time enough to think of that, said Marilla. She's only 13 in

06:57:17.590 --> 06:57:25.190
March. Though tonight, it struck me that she was growing quite a big girl. Mrs. Lind made that dress

06:57:25.190 --> 06:57:31.970
a mite too long and it makes Anne look so tall. She's quick to learn and I guess the best thing

06:57:31.970 --> 06:57:38.690
we can do for her will be to send her to Queen's after a spell. But nothing need be said about that

06:57:38.690 --> 06:57:47.030
for a year or two yet. Well now, it'll do no harm to be thinking it over off and on, said Matthew.

06:57:48.170 --> 06:57:51.890
Things like that are all the better for lots of thinking over.

06:57:57.030 --> 06:58:02.450
Recorded by Diana Keisners in Toronto on December 14, 2005.

06:58:26.870 --> 06:58:31.130
Junior Avonlea found it hard to settle down to humdrum existence again.

06:58:31.710 --> 06:58:37.750
To Anne in particular, things seemed fearfully flat, stale, and unprofitable

06:58:37.750 --> 06:58:41.210
after the goblet of excitement she had been sipping for weeks.

06:58:41.870 --> 06:58:46.070
Could she go back to the former quiet pleasures of those faraway days before the concert?

06:58:46.990 --> 06:58:51.130
At first, as she told Diana, she did not really think she could.

06:58:52.510 --> 06:58:58.470
I'm positively certain, Diana, that life can never be quite the same as it was in those olden days,

06:58:58.470 --> 06:59:03.690
she said mournfully, as if referring to a period of at least fifty years back.

06:59:04.330 --> 06:59:10.470
Perhaps after a while I'll get used to it, but I'm afraid concerts spoil people for everyday life.

06:59:11.310 --> 06:59:16.430
I suppose that is why Marilla disapproves of them. Marilla is such a sensible woman.

06:59:17.310 --> 06:59:20.790
It must be a great deal better to be sensible, but still,

06:59:21.230 --> 06:59:26.030
I don't believe I'd really want to be a sensible person because they are so unromantic.

06:59:26.770 --> 06:59:31.490
Mrs. Lynde says there is no danger of my ever being one, but you can never tell.

06:59:32.330 --> 06:59:35.250
I feel just now that I may grow up to be sensible yet.

06:59:36.110 --> 06:59:41.530
But perhaps that is only because I'm tired. I simply couldn't sleep last night for ever so long.

06:59:41.990 --> 06:59:45.310
I just lay awake and imagine the concert over and over again.

06:59:45.830 --> 06:59:50.510
That's one splendid thing about such affairs. It's so lovely to look back at them.

06:59:52.230 --> 06:59:58.370
Eventually, however, Avonlea School slipped back into its old groove and took up its old interests.

06:59:59.310 --> 07:00:04.070
To be sure, the concert left traces. Ruby Gillis and Emma White,

07:00:04.190 --> 07:00:07.670
who had quarelled over a point of precedence in their platform seats,

07:00:08.090 --> 07:00:13.390
no longer sat at the same desk, and a promising friendship of three years was broken up.

07:00:14.370 --> 07:00:20.810
Josie Pye and Julia Bell did not speak for three months because Josie Pye had told Bessie Wright

07:00:20.810 --> 07:00:25.990
that Julia Bell's bow, when she got up to recite, made her think of a chicken jerking its head,

07:00:26.090 --> 07:00:31.450
and Bessie told Julia. None of the Sloanes would have any dealings with the Bells

07:00:31.930 --> 07:00:35.670
because the Bells had declared that the Sloanes had too much to do in the program,

07:00:36.050 --> 07:00:40.390
and the Sloanes had retorted that the Bells were not capable of doing the little they had to do

07:00:40.390 --> 07:00:47.590
properly. Finally, Charlie Sloane fought Moody Spurgeon McPherson because Moody Spurgeon had said

07:00:47.590 --> 07:00:53.850
that Anne Shirley put on airs about her recitations, and Moody Spurgeon was licked. Consequently,

07:00:54.310 --> 07:00:59.590
Moody Spurgeon's sister, Ella May, would not speak to Anne Shirley all the rest of the winter.

07:01:00.910 --> 07:01:06.050
With the exception of these trifling frictions, work in Miss Stacy's Little Kingdom went on with

07:01:06.050 --> 07:01:13.550
regularity and smoothness. The winter weeks slipped by. It was an unusually mild winter,

07:01:14.010 --> 07:01:19.950
with so little snow that Anne and Diana could go to a school nearly every day by way of the Birch

07:01:19.950 --> 07:01:26.450
Path. On Anne's birthday, they were tripping lightly down it, keeping eyes and ears alert amid

07:01:26.450 --> 07:01:31.230
all the chatter, for Miss Stacy had told them that they must soon write a composition on

07:01:31.230 --> 07:01:35.890
a winter's walk in the woods, and it behooved them to be observant.

07:01:36.850 --> 07:01:44.250
Just think, Diana, I'm thirteen years old today, remarked Anne in an odd voice. I can scarcely

07:01:44.250 --> 07:01:49.470
realize that I'm in my teens. When I woke up this morning, it seemed to me that everything must be

07:01:49.470 --> 07:01:55.090
different. You've been thirteen for a month, so I suppose it doesn't seem such a novelty to you as

07:01:55.090 --> 07:02:00.830
it does to me. It makes life seem so much more interesting. In two more years, I'll be really

07:02:00.830 --> 07:02:06.350
grown up. It's a great comfort to think that I'll be able to use big words then without being laughed

07:02:06.350 --> 07:02:12.230
at. Ruby Gillis says she means to have a bow as soon as she's fifteen, said Diana.

07:02:13.430 --> 07:02:18.870
Ruby Gillis thinks of nothing but bows, said Anne disdainfully. She's actually delighted when

07:02:18.870 --> 07:02:25.010
anyone writes her name up in a take notice for all she pretends to be so mad. But I'm afraid that is

07:02:25.010 --> 07:02:30.730
an uncharitable speech. Miss Allen says we should never make uncharitable speeches, but they do

07:02:30.730 --> 07:02:36.790
slip out so often before you think, don't they? I simply can't talk about Josie Pye without making

07:02:36.790 --> 07:02:43.330
an uncharitable speech, so I never mention her at all. You may have noticed that. I'm trying to be

07:02:43.330 --> 07:02:50.470
as much like Mrs. Allen as I possibly can, for I think she's perfect. Mr. Allen thinks so, too.

07:02:51.390 --> 07:02:56.170
Mrs. Lin says he just worships the ground she treads on, and she doesn't really think it right

07:02:56.170 --> 07:03:00.790
for a minister to set his affections so much on a mortal being. But then, Diana,

07:03:01.390 --> 07:03:05.450
even ministers are human and have their besetting sins just like everyone else.

07:03:06.330 --> 07:03:10.970
I had such an interesting talk with Mrs. Allen about besetting sins last Sunday afternoon.

07:03:11.750 --> 07:03:16.030
There are just a few things it's proper to talk about on Sundays, and that is one of them.

07:03:16.730 --> 07:03:22.450
My besetting sin is imagining too much and forgetting my duties. I'm striving very hard

07:03:22.450 --> 07:03:26.610
to overcome it, and now I'm really 13, perhaps. I'll get on better.

07:03:28.050 --> 07:03:33.490
In four more years, we'll be able to put our hair up, said Diana. Alice Belle is only 16,

07:03:33.550 --> 07:03:38.030
and she's wearing hers up, but I think that's ridiculous. I shall wait until I'm 17.

07:03:39.190 --> 07:03:45.370
If I had Alice Belle's crooked nose, said Anne decidedly, I wouldn't, but there. I won't say

07:03:45.370 --> 07:03:50.670
what I was going to, because it was extremely uncharitable. Besides, I was comparing it with

07:03:50.670 --> 07:03:55.810
my own nose, and that's vanity. I'm afraid I think too much about my nose ever since I heard

07:03:55.810 --> 07:04:02.230
that compliment about it long ago. It really is a great comfort to me. Oh, Diana, look,

07:04:02.370 --> 07:04:07.930
there's a rabbit. That's something to remember for our woods composition. I really think the woods

07:04:07.930 --> 07:04:13.670
are just as lovely in winter as in summer. They're so white and still, as if they were asleep and

07:04:13.670 --> 07:04:20.110
dreaming pretty dreams. I won't mind writing that composition when its time comes, said Diana.

07:04:20.670 --> 07:04:25.430
I can manage to write about the woods, but the one we're to hand in on Monday is terrible.

07:04:26.290 --> 07:04:30.590
The idea of Miss Stacy telling us to write a story out of our own heads?

07:04:31.490 --> 07:04:37.190
Why, it's easy as a wink, said Anne. It's easy for you because you have an imagination,

07:04:37.530 --> 07:04:42.550
retorted Diana, but what would you do if you had been born without one? I suppose you have

07:04:42.550 --> 07:04:49.110
your composition all done? Anne nodded, trying hard not to look virtuously complacent and failing

07:04:49.110 --> 07:04:56.930
miserably. I wrote it last Monday evening. It's called The Jealous Rival, or In Death Not Divided.

07:04:57.130 --> 07:05:01.970
I read it to Marilla, and she said it was stuff and nonsense. Then I read it to Matthew,

07:05:02.050 --> 07:05:08.750
and he said it was fine. That's the kind of critic I like. It's a sad, sweet story. I cried

07:05:08.750 --> 07:05:14.370
just like a child when I was writing it. It's about two beautiful maidens called Cordelia

07:05:15.330 --> 07:05:21.100
and Geraldine Seymour, who lived in the same village and were devotedly attached to each other.

07:05:22.030 --> 07:05:27.550
Cordelia was a regal brunette with a cornet of midnight hair and duskly flashing eyes.

07:05:27.990 --> 07:05:32.750
Geraldine was a queenly blonde with hair like spun gold and velvety purple eyes.

07:05:33.610 --> 07:05:40.210
I never saw anybody with purple eyes, said Diana dubiously. Neither did I. I just imagined them.

07:05:40.210 --> 07:05:45.610
I wanted something out of the common. Geraldine had an alabaster brow, too.

07:05:46.490 --> 07:05:51.090
I found out what an alabaster brow is. That's one of the advantages of being 13.

07:05:51.650 --> 07:05:54.450
You know so much more than you did when you were only 12.

07:05:55.710 --> 07:05:59.010
Well, what became of Cordelia and Geraldine, asked Diana,

07:05:59.530 --> 07:06:05.090
who was beginning to feel rather interested in their fate. They grew in beauty side by side

07:06:05.090 --> 07:06:11.850
until they were 16. Then, Bertrand de Vere came to their native village and fell in love with

07:06:11.850 --> 07:06:16.570
the fair Geraldine. He saved her life when a horse ran away with her in a carriage,

07:06:17.190 --> 07:06:22.210
and she fainted in his arms, and he carried her home three miles because, you understand,

07:06:22.410 --> 07:06:26.750
the carriage was all smashed up. I found it rather hard to imagine the proposal because I

07:06:26.750 --> 07:06:32.230
had no experience to go by. I asked Ruby Gillis if she knew anything about how men propose

07:06:32.230 --> 07:06:36.890
because I thought she'd likely be an authority on the subject, having so many sisters married.

07:06:37.990 --> 07:06:43.550
Ruby told me that she was hid in the hall pantry when Malcolm Andreas proposed to his sister Susan.

07:06:44.430 --> 07:06:49.430
She said Malcolm told Susan that his dad had given him the farm in his own name and then said,

07:06:50.070 --> 07:06:53.910
What do you say, darling pet, if we get hitched this fall? And Susan said,

07:06:54.250 --> 07:07:00.510
Yes, no, I don't know. Let me see. And they were engaged quick as that.

07:07:01.190 --> 07:07:05.090
But I don't think that sort of proposal was a very romantic one,

07:07:05.570 --> 07:07:12.290
so in the end I had to imagine it out as well as I could. I made it very flowery and poetical,

07:07:12.710 --> 07:07:17.010
and Bertrand went down on his knees, although Ruby Gillis says it isn't done nowadays.

07:07:18.210 --> 07:07:23.490
Geraldine accepted him in a speech a page long. I can tell you I took a lot of trouble with that

07:07:23.490 --> 07:07:27.970
speech. I rewrote it five times, and I took it up as my masterpiece.

07:07:29.830 --> 07:07:34.010
Bertrand gave her a diamond ring with a ruby necklace and told her they would go to Europe

07:07:34.010 --> 07:07:39.370
for a wedding tour, for he was immensely wealthy. Cordelia was secretly in love with Bertrand

07:07:39.370 --> 07:07:45.490
herself, and when Geraldine told her about the necklace, she was simply furious, especially when

07:07:45.490 --> 07:07:51.750
she saw the necklace and the diamond ring. All her affection for Geraldine turned to bitter hate,

07:07:51.750 --> 07:07:57.250
and she vowed she should never marry Bertrand, but she pretended to be Geraldine's friend the

07:07:57.250 --> 07:08:02.730
same as ever. One evening they were standing on the bridge over a rushing turbulent stream,

07:08:03.190 --> 07:08:09.010
and Cordelia, thinking that they were alone, pushed Geraldine over the brink with a wild mocking,

07:08:09.350 --> 07:08:14.650
ha ha ha. But Bertrand saw it all, and once he plunged into the current, exclaiming,

07:08:14.870 --> 07:08:20.610
I will save thee, my peerless Geraldine. But alas, he'd forgotten he couldn't swim,

07:08:20.610 --> 07:08:26.410
and they were both drowned, clasped in each other's arms. Their bodies were washed ashore

07:08:26.410 --> 07:08:32.170
soon afterwards. They were buried in the one grave, and their funeral was most imposing Diana.

07:08:32.690 --> 07:08:35.830
It's so much more romantic to end a story with a funeral than a wedding.

07:08:37.010 --> 07:08:42.210
As for Cordelia, she went insane with remorse and was shut up in a lunatic asylum.

07:08:42.930 --> 07:08:45.450
I thought that was poetical retribution for her crime.

07:08:47.370 --> 07:08:52.410
How perfectly lovely, sighed Diana, who belonged to Matthew's School of Critics.

07:08:53.150 --> 07:08:57.210
I don't see how you can make up such thrilling things out of your own head, Anne. I wish my

07:08:57.210 --> 07:09:02.410
imagination was as good as yours. It would be if you'd only cultivate it, said Anne cheeringly.

07:09:02.690 --> 07:09:07.550
I've just thought of a plan, Diana. Let's you and me have a story club all our own and write stories

07:09:07.550 --> 07:09:12.970
for practice. I'll help you along until you can do them by yourself. You ought to cultivate your

07:09:12.970 --> 07:09:19.390
imagination, you know. Miss Stacey says so. Only we must take the right way. I told her about the

07:09:19.390 --> 07:09:25.570
haunted wood, but she said we went the wrong way about that. This was how the story club came into

07:09:25.570 --> 07:09:32.390
existence. It was limited to Diana and Anne at first, but soon it was extended to include Jane

07:09:32.390 --> 07:09:37.610
Andrews and Ruby Gillis and one or two others who felt that their imaginations need cultivating.

07:09:38.270 --> 07:09:42.870
No boys were allowed in it, although Ruby Gillis opined that their admission would make it more

07:09:42.870 --> 07:09:49.810
exciting, and each member had to produce one story a week. It's extremely interesting, Anne

07:09:49.810 --> 07:09:55.550
told Marilla. Each girl has to read her story out loud and then we talk it over. We are going to

07:09:55.550 --> 07:10:01.510
keep them all sacredly and I have to read it to their descendants. Each will write under a

07:10:01.510 --> 07:10:09.710
nom de plume. Mine is Rosamond Montemorci. All the girls do pretty well. Ruby Gillis is rather

07:10:09.710 --> 07:10:14.470
sentimental. She puts too much love making into her stories and you know too much is worse than

07:10:14.470 --> 07:10:20.050
too little. Jane never puts any because she says it makes her feel so silly when she has to read it

07:10:20.050 --> 07:10:26.830
out loud. Jane's stories are extremely sensible. Then Diana puts too many murders into hers. She

07:10:26.830 --> 07:10:30.730
says most of the time she doesn't know what to do with people so she kills them off to get rid of

07:10:30.730 --> 07:10:35.870
them. I mostly always have to tell them what to write about, but that isn't hard for I have millions

07:10:35.870 --> 07:10:43.770
of ideas. I think this story writing business is the foolishest yet, scoff Marilla. You'll get a

07:10:43.770 --> 07:10:49.470
pack of nonsense into your head and waste time that should be put on your lessons. Reading stories

07:10:49.470 --> 07:10:56.170
is bad enough, but writing them is worse. But we're so careful to put a moral into them all, Marilla,

07:10:56.330 --> 07:11:01.850
explained Anne. I insist upon that. All the good people are rewarded and all the bad ones are

07:11:01.850 --> 07:11:07.930
punished. I'm sure that must have a wholesome effect. The moral is the great thing, Mr. Allen

07:11:07.930 --> 07:11:12.950
says so. I read one of my stories to him and Mrs. Allen and they both agree that the moral was

07:11:12.950 --> 07:11:18.070
excellent. Only they laughed in all the wrong places. I like it better when people cry.

07:11:19.330 --> 07:11:22.390
Jane and Ruby almost always cry when I come to the pathetic parts.

07:11:23.770 --> 07:11:28.710
Diana wrote her Aunt Josephine about her club and her Aunt Josephine wrote back that we were to send

07:11:28.710 --> 07:11:35.830
her some of our stories. So we copied out four of our very best and sent them. Miss Josephine

07:11:35.830 --> 07:11:41.550
Berry wrote back that she had never read anything so amusing in her life. That kind of puzzled us

07:11:41.550 --> 07:11:46.210
because the stories were all very pathetic and almost everyone died. But I'm glad Miss Berry

07:11:46.210 --> 07:11:52.150
liked them. It shows our club is doing some good in the world. Mrs. Allen says that ought to be

07:11:52.150 --> 07:11:58.290
our object in everything. I do really try to make it my object, but I forget so often when I'm having

07:11:58.290 --> 07:12:04.090
fun. I hope I shall be a little like Mrs. Allen when I grow up. Do you think there's any prospect

07:12:04.090 --> 07:12:09.970
of it, Marilla? I shouldn't say there was a great deal, Ms. Marilla's encouraging answer.

07:12:10.490 --> 07:12:14.930
I'm sure Mrs. Allen was never such a silly, forgetful little girl as you are.

07:12:16.130 --> 07:12:21.830
No, but she wasn't always so good as she is now either, said Anne seriously. She told me so

07:12:21.830 --> 07:12:27.830
herself, that is. And she said she was a dreadful mischief when she was a girl and was always getting

07:12:28.330 --> 07:12:34.550
scrapes. I felt so encouraged when I heard that. Is it very wicked of me, Marilla, to feel encouraged

07:12:34.550 --> 07:12:40.770
when I hear that other people have been bad and mischievous? Mrs. Lynn says it is. Mrs. Lynn says

07:12:40.770 --> 07:12:45.710
she always feels shocked when she hears of anyone ever having been naughty, no matter how small they

07:12:45.710 --> 07:12:52.270
were. Mrs. Lynn said that she once heard a minister confess that when he was a boy he stole a raspberry

07:12:52.270 --> 07:12:58.010
tart out of his aunt's pantry, and she never had any respect for that minister again. Now,

07:12:58.330 --> 07:13:03.610
I wouldn't have felt that way. I would have thought that it was real noble of him to confess it,

07:13:03.610 --> 07:13:08.230
and I'd have thought what an encouraging thing it would be for small boys nowadays who do naughty

07:13:08.230 --> 07:13:12.990
things and who are sorry for them to know perhaps they may grow up to be ministers in spite of it.

07:13:13.170 --> 07:13:20.290
That's how I feel, Marilla. The way I feel at present, Anne, said Marilla, is it's high time

07:13:20.290 --> 07:13:24.770
you had those dishes washed. You take half an hour longer than you should with all your

07:13:24.770 --> 07:13:37.690
chattering. Learn to work first and talk afterwards.

07:13:54.330 --> 07:13:57.030
End of Green Gables by Lucy Maud Montgomery.

07:14:00.570 --> 07:14:02.550
Vanity and vexation of spirit.

07:14:04.430 --> 07:14:09.110
Marilla, walking home one late April afternoon from an aid meeting, realized that the winter

07:14:09.110 --> 07:14:13.910
was over and gone with the thrill of delight that spring never fails to bring to the oldest

07:14:13.910 --> 07:14:17.070
and saddest as well as the youngest and merriest.

07:14:18.050 --> 07:14:21.550
Marilla was not given to subjective analysis of her thoughts and feelings.

07:14:22.510 --> 07:14:27.650
She probably imagined that she was thinking about the aides and their missionary box and

07:14:27.650 --> 07:14:29.290
the new carpet for their vestry room.

07:14:30.090 --> 07:14:35.670
But under these reflections was a harmonious consciousness of red fields smoking into pale

07:14:35.670 --> 07:14:42.030
purpley mists in the declining sun, of long sharp pointed fur shadows following over the

07:14:42.030 --> 07:14:49.270
meadow beyond the brook, of still crimson-butted maples around a mirror-like wood pool, of

07:14:49.270 --> 07:14:53.190
awakening in a world and the stir of hidden pulses under the gray sod.

07:14:55.070 --> 07:15:00.590
The spring was abroad in the land and Marilla's sober, middle-aged step was lighter and swifter

07:15:00.590 --> 07:15:02.990
because of its deep primal gladness.

07:15:04.310 --> 07:15:10.350
Her eyes swelled affectionately on Green Gables, peering through its network of trees and reflecting

07:15:10.350 --> 07:15:14.750
the sunlight back from its windows in several little coruscations of glory.

07:15:15.550 --> 07:15:21.110
Marilla, as she picked her steps along the damp lane, thought that it was really a satisfaction

07:15:21.110 --> 07:15:26.610
to know that she was going home to a briskly snapping wood fire and a table nicely spread

07:15:26.610 --> 07:15:32.610
for tea instead of to the cold comfort of old aid meetings before Anne had come to Green

07:15:32.610 --> 07:15:32.990
Gables.

07:15:36.270 --> 07:15:41.710
Consequently, when Marilla entered her kitchen and found the fire black out, with no sign

07:15:41.710 --> 07:15:45.610
of Anne anywhere, she felt justly disappointed and irritated.

07:15:46.630 --> 07:15:51.530
She had told Anne to be sure and have tea ready at five o'clock, but now she must hurry

07:15:51.530 --> 07:15:56.270
to take off her second-best dress and prepare the meal herself against Matthew's returning

07:15:56.270 --> 07:15:56.930
from plowing.

07:15:59.790 --> 07:16:04.950
I'll settle Miss Anne when she comes home, said Marilla grimly, as she shaved up kindlings

07:16:04.950 --> 07:16:08.610
with a carving knife and with more vim than was strictly necessary.

07:16:10.370 --> 07:16:13.510
Matthew had come in and was waiting patiently for his tea in the corner.

07:16:14.730 --> 07:16:19.290
She's off gadding somewhere with Diana, writing stories or practicing dialogues or some such

07:16:19.290 --> 07:16:22.850
tomfoolery and never thinking once about the time or her duties.

07:16:23.810 --> 07:16:26.870
She's just got to be pulled up short and sudden on this sort of thing.

07:16:27.490 --> 07:16:31.630
I don't care if Mrs. Allen does say she's the brightest and sweetest child she ever knew.

07:16:32.270 --> 07:16:36.570
She may be bright and sweet enough, but her head is full of nonsense, and there's never

07:16:36.570 --> 07:16:38.870
any knowing what shape it'll break out in next.

07:16:39.770 --> 07:16:44.870
Just as soon as she grows out of one freak, she takes up another, but there, here I am

07:16:44.870 --> 07:16:48.550
saying the very thing I was so riled with Rachel Lynn for saying at the aid today.

07:16:48.550 --> 07:16:54.310
I was really glad when Mrs. Allen spoke up for Anne, for if she hadn't, I know I'd have

07:16:54.310 --> 07:16:56.950
had said something too sharp to Rachel before everybody.

07:16:58.010 --> 07:17:03.250
Anne's got plenty of faults, goodness knows, and far be it for me to deny it, but I'm bringing

07:17:03.250 --> 07:17:08.610
her up, and not Rachel Lynn, who'd pick faults in the angel Gabriel himself if he lived in

07:17:08.610 --> 07:17:09.310
Avonlea.

07:17:09.970 --> 07:17:13.970
Just the same, Anne has no business to leave the house like this when I told her she must

07:17:13.970 --> 07:17:16.430
stay home this afternoon and look after things.

07:17:17.070 --> 07:17:22.570
I must say, with all her faults, I never found her disobedient or untrustworthy before, and

07:17:22.570 --> 07:17:24.430
I'm real sorry to find her so now.

07:17:26.330 --> 07:17:33.670
Well now, I don't know, said Matthew, who, being patient and wise and, above all, hungry,

07:17:34.390 --> 07:17:39.070
had deemed it best to let Marilla talk her wrath out unhindered, having learned by experience

07:17:39.070 --> 07:17:43.550
that she got through with whatever work was on hand much quicker, if not delayed by untimely

07:17:43.550 --> 07:17:44.070
argument.

07:17:45.250 --> 07:17:47.970
Perhaps you're judging her too hastily, Marilla.

07:17:48.890 --> 07:17:52.690
Don't call her untrustworthy until you're sure she's disobeyed you.

07:17:53.290 --> 07:17:56.610
Maybe it can be all explained, Anne's a great hand at explaining.

07:17:58.350 --> 07:18:01.270
She's not here when I told her to stay, retorted Marilla.

07:18:01.810 --> 07:18:05.090
I reckon she'll find it hard to explain that to my satisfaction.

07:18:06.230 --> 07:18:10.130
Of course I knew you'd take her part, Matthew, but I'm bringing her up, not you.

07:18:12.370 --> 07:18:17.690
It was dark when supper was ready, and still no sign of Anne, coming hurriedly over the

07:18:17.690 --> 07:18:22.130
log bridge or up Lovers Lane, breathless and repentant with a sense of neglected duties.

07:18:23.410 --> 07:18:25.490
Marilla washed and put away the dishes grimly.

07:18:25.950 --> 07:18:30.830
Then, wanting a candle to light her way down the cellar, she went up to the east gable

07:18:30.830 --> 07:18:33.110
for the one that generally stood on Anne's table.

07:18:34.010 --> 07:18:38.710
Lighting it, she turned around to see Anne herself lying on the bed, face downward among

07:18:38.710 --> 07:18:39.250
the pillows.

07:18:40.930 --> 07:18:43.290
Mercy on us, said astonished Marilla.

07:18:43.810 --> 07:18:44.990
Have you been asleep, Anne?

07:18:46.070 --> 07:18:48.350
No, was a muffled reply.

07:18:49.210 --> 07:18:50.330
Are you sick then?

07:18:50.950 --> 07:18:53.910
Dermended Marilla anxiously, going over to the bed.

07:18:54.990 --> 07:18:59.870
Anne cowered deeper into her pillows as if desirous of hiding herself forever from mortal

07:18:59.870 --> 07:19:00.370
eyes.

07:19:01.390 --> 07:19:06.330
No, but please, Marilla, go away and don't look at me.

07:19:06.330 --> 07:19:11.350
I'm in the depths of despair, and I don't care who gets ahead in class or writes the

07:19:11.350 --> 07:19:14.630
best compositions or sings in the Sunday school choir anymore.

07:19:15.490 --> 07:19:19.570
Little things like that are of no importance now, because I don't suppose I'll ever be

07:19:19.570 --> 07:19:20.890
able to go anywhere again.

07:19:21.510 --> 07:19:22.690
My career is closed.

07:19:23.310 --> 07:19:25.890
Please, Marilla, go away and don't look at me.

07:19:27.170 --> 07:19:31.230
Did anyone ever hear the like the mystified Marilla wanted to know?

07:19:31.790 --> 07:19:34.270
And Shirley, whatever is the matter with you?

07:19:34.430 --> 07:19:35.210
What have you done?

07:19:36.030 --> 07:19:37.870
Get right up this minute and tell me.

07:19:38.090 --> 07:19:39.310
This minute, I say.

07:19:39.750 --> 07:19:40.390
There now.

07:19:40.590 --> 07:19:41.670
What is it?

07:19:42.910 --> 07:19:45.510
Anne had slid to the floor in despairing obedience.

07:19:46.470 --> 07:19:50.150
Look at my hair, Marilla, she whispered.

07:19:52.310 --> 07:19:57.730
Accordingly, Marilla lifted her candle and looked scrutinizingly at Anne's hair, flowing

07:19:57.730 --> 07:19:59.270
in heavy masses down her back.

07:20:00.050 --> 07:20:02.370
It certainly had a very strange appearance.

07:20:03.730 --> 07:20:07.170
Anne Shirley, what have you done to your hair?

07:20:07.710 --> 07:20:09.810
Why, it's green.

07:20:11.430 --> 07:20:19.150
Green it might be called, if it were any earthly color, a queer, dull, bronzy green with streaks

07:20:19.150 --> 07:20:22.870
here and there of the original red to highlight the ghastly effect.

07:20:23.870 --> 07:20:29.410
Never in all her life had Marilla seen anything so grotesque as Anne's hair at that moment.

07:20:30.470 --> 07:20:32.790
Yes, it's green, moaned Anne.

07:20:33.550 --> 07:20:38.870
I thought nothing could be as bad as red hair, but now I know it's ten times worse to have

07:20:38.870 --> 07:20:39.570
green hair.

07:20:40.310 --> 07:20:44.290
Oh, Marilla, you little know how utterly wretched I am.

07:20:45.850 --> 07:20:49.630
I little know how you got into this fix, but I mean to find out, said Marilla.

07:20:50.210 --> 07:20:54.050
Come right down to the kitchen, it's too cold up here, and tell me just what you've done.

07:20:54.530 --> 07:20:57.190
I've been expecting something queer for some time now.

07:20:57.190 --> 07:21:01.530
You haven't gotten into any scrape for over two months, and I was sure another one was due.

07:21:02.010 --> 07:21:04.270
Now then, what did you do to your hair?

07:21:05.770 --> 07:21:06.650
I dyed it.

07:21:08.010 --> 07:21:08.790
Died it?

07:21:09.130 --> 07:21:10.030
Died your hair?

07:21:10.650 --> 07:21:14.270
And Shirley, didn't you know it was a wicked thing to do?

07:21:15.530 --> 07:21:21.070
Yes, I knew it was a little wicked, admitted Anne, but I thought it was worthwhile to be

07:21:21.070 --> 07:21:22.930
a little wicked to get rid of red hair.

07:21:23.710 --> 07:21:25.150
I counted the cost, Marilla.

07:21:25.810 --> 07:21:29.090
Besides, I meant to be extra good in other ways to make up for it.

07:21:30.150 --> 07:21:35.150
Well, said Marilla sarcastically, if I had decided it was worthwhile to dye my hair,

07:21:35.250 --> 07:21:36.890
I'd have dyed it a decent color at least.

07:21:36.990 --> 07:21:38.130
I wouldn't have dyed it green.

07:21:39.530 --> 07:21:43.550
But I didn't mean to dye it green, Marilla, protested Anne dejectedly.

07:21:44.450 --> 07:21:47.170
If I was wicked, I meant to be wicked to some purpose.

07:21:47.890 --> 07:21:50.370
He said it would turn my hair a beautiful raven black.

07:21:50.770 --> 07:21:52.830
He positively assured me that it would.

07:21:53.470 --> 07:21:54.990
How could I doubt his word, Marilla?

07:21:55.670 --> 07:21:58.330
I know what it feels like to have your word doubted.

07:21:58.550 --> 07:22:03.190
And Mrs. Allen says we should never suspect anyone of not telling us the truth unless

07:22:03.190 --> 07:22:04.610
we have proof that they're not.

07:22:05.750 --> 07:22:06.990
I have proof now.

07:22:07.530 --> 07:22:09.130
Green hair is proof enough for anybody.

07:22:09.990 --> 07:22:14.190
But I hadn't then, and I believed every word he said implicitly.

07:22:16.090 --> 07:22:16.750
Who said?

07:22:17.350 --> 07:22:18.390
Who are you talking about?

07:22:19.290 --> 07:22:21.190
The peddler that was here this afternoon.

07:22:21.190 --> 07:22:22.810
I bought the dye from him.

07:22:24.010 --> 07:22:24.830
And Shirley.

07:22:25.710 --> 07:22:29.370
How often have I told you never to let one of those Italians in the house?

07:22:29.690 --> 07:22:32.350
I don't believe in encouraging them to come around at all.

07:22:33.570 --> 07:22:35.390
Oh, I didn't let him in the house.

07:22:35.830 --> 07:22:40.330
I remember what you told me, and I went out, carefully shut the door, and looked at his

07:22:40.330 --> 07:22:41.090
things on the step.

07:22:41.730 --> 07:22:43.690
Besides, he wasn't an Italian.

07:22:43.870 --> 07:22:44.990
He was a German Jew.

07:22:45.530 --> 07:22:50.450
He had a big box full of very interesting things, and told me he was working hard to

07:22:50.450 --> 07:22:53.450
make enough money to bring his wife and children out from Germany.

07:22:54.230 --> 07:22:57.650
He spoke so feelingly about them that it touched my heart.

07:22:58.170 --> 07:23:01.730
I wanted to buy something from him to help him in such a worthy object.

07:23:02.470 --> 07:23:04.410
Then all at once I saw the bottle of hair dye.

07:23:05.070 --> 07:23:10.150
The peddler said it was warranted to dye any hair a beautiful raven black and wouldn't

07:23:10.150 --> 07:23:10.970
wash off.

07:23:11.970 --> 07:23:17.930
In a trice, I saw myself with beautiful raven black hair, and the temptation was irresistible.

07:23:18.390 --> 07:23:22.550
But the price of the bottle was seventy-five cents, and I only had fifty cents left out

07:23:22.550 --> 07:23:23.310
of my chicken money.

07:23:24.330 --> 07:23:29.730
I think the peddler had a very kind heart, for he said that, seeing it was me, he'd

07:23:29.730 --> 07:23:32.370
sell it for fifty cents, and that was just giving it away.

07:23:33.310 --> 07:23:37.490
So I bought it, and as soon as I had gone up here and applied it with an old hairbrush,

07:23:37.590 --> 07:23:43.630
as the direction said, I used up the whole bottle, and oh, Marilla, when I saw the dreadful

07:23:43.630 --> 07:23:47.530
color that had turned my hair, I repented of being wicked, I can tell you, and I've

07:23:47.530 --> 07:23:48.850
been repenting ever since.

07:23:51.290 --> 07:23:55.670
Well, I hope you'll repent to good purpose, said Marilla severely, and that you've got

07:23:55.670 --> 07:23:58.290
your eyes open to where your vanity has led you, Anne.

07:23:58.750 --> 07:24:00.350
Goodness knows what's to be done.

07:24:00.690 --> 07:24:03.850
I suppose the first thing to do is give your hair a good washing and see if it will do

07:24:03.850 --> 07:24:04.410
any good.

07:24:05.850 --> 07:24:10.810
Accordingly, Anne washed her hair, scrubbing it vigorously with soap and water, but for

07:24:10.810 --> 07:24:13.990
all the difference it made, she might as well have been scouring its original red.

07:24:13.990 --> 07:24:18.470
The peddler had certainly spoken the truth when he declared the dye wouldn't wash off.

07:24:18.830 --> 07:24:21.530
However, his veracity might be impeached in other respects.

07:24:22.970 --> 07:24:25.170
Oh, Marilla, what shall I do?

07:24:25.530 --> 07:24:26.810
questioned Anne in tears.

07:24:27.390 --> 07:24:28.930
I can never live this down.

07:24:29.590 --> 07:24:34.410
People have pretty well forgotten my other mistakes, the liniment kink and setting Diana

07:24:34.410 --> 07:24:39.130
drunk and flying into a temper with Mrs. Linde, but they'll never forget this.

07:24:39.730 --> 07:24:41.310
They will think I'm not respectable.

07:24:41.310 --> 07:24:47.430
Oh, Marilla, what a tangled web we weave when first we practice to deceive.

07:24:48.150 --> 07:24:49.970
That is poetry, but it is true.

07:24:50.430 --> 07:24:53.350
And oh, how Josie Pye will laugh.

07:24:53.910 --> 07:24:56.910
Marilla, I cannot face Josie Pye.

07:24:57.470 --> 07:25:00.230
I'm the unhappiest girl in Prince Edward Island.

07:25:02.330 --> 07:25:04.410
Anne's unhappiness continued for a week.

07:25:05.130 --> 07:25:08.230
During that time, she went nowhere and shampooed her hair every day.

07:25:09.030 --> 07:25:14.390
Diana alone of outsiders knew the fatal secret, but she promised solemnly never to tell,

07:25:14.910 --> 07:25:17.510
and it may be stated here now that she kept her word.

07:25:18.650 --> 07:25:20.950
At the end of the week, Marilla said decidedly,

07:25:21.550 --> 07:25:22.650
It's no use, Anne.

07:25:23.310 --> 07:25:25.230
This is fast dye if there ever was any.

07:25:25.510 --> 07:25:26.510
Your hair must be cut off.

07:25:26.650 --> 07:25:27.570
There is no other way.

07:25:27.910 --> 07:25:29.730
You can't go out with it looking like that.

07:25:30.950 --> 07:25:34.910
Anne's lips quivered, but she realized the bitter truth of Marilla's remarks.

07:25:35.490 --> 07:25:37.910
With a dismal sigh, she went for the scissors.

07:25:39.570 --> 07:25:42.150
Please cut it off at once, Marilla, and have it over.

07:25:42.730 --> 07:25:44.710
Oh, I feel that my heart is broken.

07:25:45.410 --> 07:25:47.170
This is such an unromantic affliction.

07:25:47.930 --> 07:25:51.850
The girls in books lose their hair in fevers or sell it to get money for some good dean,

07:25:52.250 --> 07:25:55.710
and I'm sure I wouldn't mind losing my hair in such a fashion half so much.

07:25:56.510 --> 07:26:01.550
But there is nothing comforting in having your hair cut off because you've dyed it a dreadful color, is there?

07:26:02.170 --> 07:26:05.810
I'm going to weep all the time you're cutting it off, if it won't interfere.

07:26:06.750 --> 07:26:08.490
It seems such a tragic thing.

07:26:10.610 --> 07:26:15.810
Anne wept then, but later on, when she went upstairs and looked in the glass, she was calm with despair.

07:26:16.770 --> 07:26:21.890
Marilla had done her work thoroughly, and it had been necessary to shingle the hair as closely as possible.

07:26:22.750 --> 07:26:26.510
The result was not becoming, to state the case as mildly as may be.

07:26:27.210 --> 07:26:29.290
Anne promptly turned her glass to the wall.

07:26:30.090 --> 07:26:34.550
I'll never, never look at myself again until my hair grows, she exclaimed passionately.

07:26:35.770 --> 07:26:37.450
Then suddenly she righted the glass.

07:26:38.530 --> 07:26:42.090
Yes, I will, too. I'll do penance for being wicked that way.

07:26:42.410 --> 07:26:46.170
I'll look at myself every time I come into my room and see how ugly I am.

07:26:46.530 --> 07:26:48.690
And I won't try to imagine it away, either.

07:26:49.250 --> 07:26:54.970
I never thought I was vain about my hair, of all things, but now I know I was, in spite of its being red,

07:26:55.430 --> 07:26:57.430
because it was so long and thick and curly.

07:26:58.070 --> 07:27:01.970
I expect something will happen to my nose next.

07:27:03.510 --> 07:27:06.390
Anne's clipped head made a sensation in school on the following Monday,

07:27:06.950 --> 07:27:10.770
but to her relief nobody guessed the real reason for it, not even Josie Pye,

07:27:11.310 --> 07:27:15.850
who, however, did not fail to inform Anne that she looked like a perfect scarecrow.

07:27:17.390 --> 07:27:19.930
I didn't say anything when Josie said that to me.

07:27:20.130 --> 07:27:24.410
Anne confided that evening to Marilla, who was lying on the sofa after one of her headaches,

07:27:24.410 --> 07:27:28.250
because I thought it was part of my punishment, and I ought to bear it patiently.

07:27:29.310 --> 07:27:35.370
It's hard to be told you look like a scarecrow, and I wanted to say something back, but I didn't.

07:27:35.690 --> 07:27:39.290
I just swept her one of my scornful looks, and then I forgave her.

07:27:39.650 --> 07:27:43.230
It makes you feel very virtuous when you forgive people, doesn't it?

07:27:44.170 --> 07:27:49.790
I mean to devote all my energies to being good after this, and I shall never try to be beautiful again.

07:27:50.410 --> 07:27:52.450
Of course, it's better to be good.

07:27:52.450 --> 07:27:57.250
I know it is, but sometimes it's so hard to believe a thing even when you know it.

07:27:57.770 --> 07:28:04.430
I do really want to be good, Marilla, like you and Mrs. Allen and Miss Stacy, and grow up to be a credit to you.

07:28:05.050 --> 07:28:10.710
Diana says, when my hair begins to grow, to tie a black velvet ribbon around my head with a bow at one side.

07:28:11.570 --> 07:28:13.210
She says she thinks it will be very becoming.

07:28:14.010 --> 07:28:16.890
I will call it a snood. That sounds so romantic.

07:28:17.790 --> 07:28:20.690
But am I talking too much, Marilla? Does it hurt your head?

07:28:22.570 --> 07:28:24.110
My head is better now.

07:28:24.530 --> 07:28:26.570
It was terrible by this afternoon, though.

07:28:26.910 --> 07:28:28.790
These headaches of mine are getting worse and worse.

07:28:29.310 --> 07:28:31.090
I'll have to see a doctor about them.

07:28:31.530 --> 07:28:34.370
As for your chatter, I don't know that I mind it.

07:28:34.590 --> 07:28:36.110
I've got so used to it.

07:28:37.470 --> 07:28:41.630
Which was Marilla's way of saying that she liked to hear it.

07:28:50.690 --> 07:28:54.690
Recorded by Susan Hooks, Tokyo, Japan

07:29:20.470 --> 07:29:25.230
Of course you must be Elaine Anne, said Diana. I could never have the courage to float down there.

07:29:25.750 --> 07:29:31.070
Nor I, said Ruby Gillis with a shiver. I don't mind floating down when there's two or three of us in

07:29:31.070 --> 07:29:36.790
the flat and we can sit up. It's fun then. But to lie down and pretend I was dead? I just couldn't.

07:29:36.970 --> 07:29:44.850
I'd really die of fright. Of course it would be romantic, conceded Jane Andrews, but I know that

07:29:44.850 --> 07:29:49.830
I couldn't keep still. I'd be popping up every minute or so to see where I was and if I wasn't

07:29:49.830 --> 07:29:56.070
drifting too far out. And you know Anne, that would spoil the effect. But it's so ridiculous

07:29:56.070 --> 07:30:02.010
to have a redheaded Elaine, mourned Anne. I'm not afraid to float down and I'd love to be Elaine,

07:30:02.390 --> 07:30:08.250
but it's ridiculous just the same. Ruby ought to be Elaine because she is so fair and has such

07:30:08.250 --> 07:30:19.810
lovely long golden hair. Elaine had all her bright hair streaming down, you know. And Elaine was a

07:30:19.810 --> 07:30:26.650
haired person, cannot be a lilymaid. Your complexion is just as fair as Ruby's, said Diana

07:30:26.650 --> 07:30:33.030
earnestly, and your hair is ever so much darker than it used to be before you cut it. Oh, do you

07:30:33.030 --> 07:30:40.070
really think so? exclaimed Anne, flushing sensitively with delight. I've sometimes thought it was myself,

07:30:40.230 --> 07:30:45.190
but I never dared to ask anyone, for fear she would tell me it wasn't. Do you think it could

07:30:45.190 --> 07:30:52.710
be called Auburn now, Diana? Yes, and I think it is real pretty, said Diana, looking admirably

07:30:52.710 --> 07:30:57.690
at the short silky curls that clustered over Anne's head and were held in place by a very jaunty

07:30:57.690 --> 07:31:03.830
black velvet ribbon and bow. They were sitting on the bank of the pond below Orchard Slope,

07:31:05.050 --> 07:31:10.790
where a little headland fringed with birches ran out from the bank. At its tip was a small wooden

07:31:10.790 --> 07:31:15.790
platform built out into the water for the convenience of fishermen and duck hunters.

07:31:17.450 --> 07:31:21.770
Ruby and Jane were spending the mid-summer afternoon with Diana, and Anne had come over

07:31:21.770 --> 07:31:29.050
to play with them. Anne and Diana had spent most of their play time that summer on and about the

07:31:29.050 --> 07:31:36.250
pond. Idlewild was a thing of the past, Mr. Bell having ruthlessly cut down the little circle of

07:31:36.250 --> 07:31:42.830
his back pasture in the spring. Anne had sat among the stumps and wept, not without an eye

07:31:42.830 --> 07:31:48.270
for the romance of it, but she was speedily consoled for, after all, as she and Diana,

07:31:48.830 --> 07:31:54.610
big girls of thirteen going on fourteen, were too old for such childish amusements as playhouses,

07:31:54.930 --> 07:32:00.370
and there were more fascinating sports to be found about the pond. It was splendid to fish

07:32:00.370 --> 07:32:04.890
for trout over the bridge, and the two girls learned to row themselves about in the little

07:32:04.890 --> 07:32:11.530
bottom dory Mr. Berry kept for duck shooting. It was Anne's idea that they dramatize a lane.

07:32:12.270 --> 07:32:17.310
They had studied Tennyson's poems in school the preceding winter, the superintendent of

07:32:17.310 --> 07:32:21.290
education having prescribed it in the English course for the Prince Edward Island schools.

07:32:22.170 --> 07:32:26.610
They had analyzed and parsed it and torn it to pieces in general, until it was a wonder there

07:32:26.610 --> 07:32:31.450
was any meaning at all left in it for them. But at least the fair lily maid and Lancelot and

07:32:31.450 --> 07:32:37.010
King Arthur had become very real people to them, and Anne was devoured by secret regret

07:32:37.010 --> 07:32:42.310
that she had not been born in Camelot. Those days, she said, were so much more romantic than the

07:32:42.310 --> 07:32:50.810
present. Anne's plan was hailed with enthusiasm. The girls had discovered that if the flat were

07:32:50.810 --> 07:32:55.190
pushed off from the landing place, it would drift down with the current under the bridge

07:32:55.190 --> 07:33:00.410
and finally strand itself in another headland lower down which ran a curve of the pond.

07:33:01.450 --> 07:33:05.670
They had often gone down like this, and nothing could be more convenient for playing Elaine.

07:33:07.370 --> 07:33:13.310
Well, I'll be Elaine, said Anne, yielding reluctantly, for although she would have been

07:33:13.310 --> 07:33:18.230
delighted to play the principal character, yet her artistic sense demanded fitness for it,

07:33:18.530 --> 07:33:31.430
and thus she felt her limitations made impossible. Ruby, you must be King Arthur, and Jane will be

07:33:31.430 --> 07:33:36.330
We can't have the old dumb servitor because there isn't room for two in the flat when one

07:33:36.330 --> 07:33:41.310
is lying down. We must pawl the barge all its length in the blackest semi.

07:33:42.630 --> 07:33:45.890
That old black shell of your mother's will do, just the thing, Diana.

07:33:47.570 --> 07:33:53.070
The black shell having been procured, Anne sped it over the flat and then lay down on the bottom

07:33:53.070 --> 07:33:56.290
with closed eyes and hands folded over her breast.

07:33:57.670 --> 07:34:04.170
Oh, she really does look dead, whispered Ruby Gillis nervously, watching the still white little

07:34:04.170 --> 07:34:10.010
face under the flickering shadows of the birches. It makes me feel frightened, girls. Do you suppose

07:34:10.010 --> 07:34:15.610
it's really right to act like this? Mrs. Lynde says that all play acting is abominably wicked.

07:34:18.290 --> 07:34:23.970
Ruby, you shouldn't talk about Mrs. Lynde, said Anne severely. It spoils the effect because this

07:34:23.970 --> 07:34:29.470
hundreds of years before Mrs. Lynde was born. Jane, you arrange this. It's silly for Elaine

07:34:29.470 --> 07:34:36.930
to be talking when she's dead. Jane rose to the occasion. Cloths of gold for coverlet, there was

07:34:36.930 --> 07:34:44.750
none, but an old piano scarf of yellow Japanese crepe was an excellent substitute. A white lily

07:34:44.750 --> 07:34:51.550
was not obtainable just then, but the effect of a tall blue iris placed in one of Anne's folded hands

07:34:51.550 --> 07:34:58.810
was all that could be desired. Now she's all ready, said Jane. We must kiss her quiet brows.

07:34:59.330 --> 07:35:07.190
And Diana, you say, Sister, farewell forever. And Ruby, you say, Farewell, sweet sister.

07:35:08.090 --> 07:35:15.230
Both of you as sorrowfully as you possibly can. And for goodness sake, smile a little. You know,

07:35:15.430 --> 07:35:20.570
Elaine, lay as though she smiled. That's better. Now push the flat off.

07:35:21.990 --> 07:35:27.630
The flat was accordingly pushed off, scraping roughly over an old embedded stake in the process.

07:35:30.150 --> 07:35:34.690
Diana and Jane and Ruby only waited long enough to see it caught in the current and headed for the

07:35:34.690 --> 07:35:39.770
bridge before scampering up through the woods, across the road, and down to the lower headland

07:35:39.770 --> 07:35:45.950
where, as L'Antillante and Guinevere and the King, they were to be in readiness to receive the lily

07:35:45.950 --> 07:35:53.330
and Jane. For a few minutes, Anne, drifting slowly down, enjoyed the romance of her situation in

07:35:53.330 --> 07:36:01.570
full. Then something happened not at all romantic. The flat began to leak. In a very few moments,

07:36:01.650 --> 07:36:06.830
it was necessary for Elaine to scramble to her feet, pick up her cloth of gold coverlet

07:36:06.830 --> 07:36:12.130
and pall of the blackest semite, and glaze blankly at the big crack in the bottom of her barge,

07:36:12.130 --> 07:36:14.190
through which the water was literally pouring.

07:36:16.570 --> 07:36:23.530
That sharp shake at the landing had torn off the strip of batting nailed on the flat. Anne did not

07:36:23.530 --> 07:36:28.230
know this, but it did not take her long to realize that she was in a dangerous plight.

07:36:28.950 --> 07:36:33.090
At this rate, the flat would fill and sink long before it could drift to the lower headland.

07:36:33.970 --> 07:36:36.670
Where were the oars? Left behind at the landing.

07:36:39.390 --> 07:36:44.510
Anne gave one gasping little scream, which nobody ever heard. She was white to the lips,

07:36:44.950 --> 07:36:49.290
but she did not lose her self-possession. There was one chance, just one.

07:36:50.410 --> 07:36:56.010
I was horribly frightened, she told Mrs. Allen the next day. And it seemed like years while the

07:36:56.010 --> 07:37:01.230
flat was drifting down to the bridge and the water was rising at every moment. I prayed, Mrs. Allen,

07:37:01.610 --> 07:37:06.650
most earnestly, but I didn't shut my eyes to pray, for I knew the only way God could save me was to

07:37:07.310 --> 07:37:11.790
let the flat float close enough to one of the bridge piles for me to climb up on it.

07:37:12.490 --> 07:37:17.050
You know, the piles are just old tree trunks and there are lots of knots and old branch dubs on

07:37:17.050 --> 07:37:22.850
them. It was proper to pray, but I had to do my part by watching out and right while I knew it.

07:37:23.330 --> 07:37:28.230
I just said, Dear God, please take the flat close to the pile and I'll do the rest,

07:37:28.590 --> 07:37:34.930
over and over again. Under such circumstances, you don't think much about making a flowery prayer,

07:37:34.930 --> 07:37:40.810
but mine was answered, for the flat bumped right into the pile for a minute and I flung the scarf

07:37:40.810 --> 07:37:46.830
and the shawl over my shoulder and scrambled up on a big providential stub. And there I was,

07:37:46.890 --> 07:37:51.330
Mrs. Allen, clinging to that slippery old pile with no way of getting up or down.

07:37:52.010 --> 07:37:56.190
It was a very unromantic position, but I didn't think about it at the time.

07:37:56.870 --> 07:38:00.410
You don't think much about romance when you have just escaped from a watery grave.

07:38:00.970 --> 07:38:05.830
I said a grateful prayer at once and then I gave all my attention to holding on tight,

07:38:06.330 --> 07:38:09.830
for I knew I should probably have to depend on human aid to get back to dry land.

07:38:12.790 --> 07:38:15.970
The flat drifted under the bridge and then promptly sank in midstream.

07:38:16.770 --> 07:38:23.270
Ruby, Jane, and Diana, already awaiting it on the lower headland, saw it disappear before their very

07:38:23.270 --> 07:38:28.470
eyes and had no doubt but that Anne had gone down with it. For the moment they stood still,

07:38:28.470 --> 07:38:34.630
white as sheets, frozen with a horror at the tragedy. Then, shrieking at the top of their

07:38:34.630 --> 07:38:39.850
voices, they started on a frantic run up through the woods, never pausing as they crossed the main

07:38:39.850 --> 07:38:44.730
road to glance the way of the bridge. Anne, clinging desperately to her precarious foothold,

07:38:45.130 --> 07:38:50.230
saw their flying forms and heard their shrieks. Help would soon come, but meanwhile her position

07:38:50.230 --> 07:38:57.210
was a very uncomfortable one. The minutes passed by, a seeming like an hour to the unfortunate

07:38:57.210 --> 07:39:03.190
Lily made. Why didn't somebody come? Where had the girls gone? Suppose they had fainted,

07:39:03.290 --> 07:39:08.070
one and all. Suppose nobody ever came. Suppose she grew so tired and cramped that she could

07:39:08.070 --> 07:39:14.550
hold on no longer. Anne looked at the wicked green depths below her, wavering with long oily

07:39:14.550 --> 07:39:20.190
shadows and shivered. Her imagination began to suggest all manner of gruesome possibilities to

07:39:20.190 --> 07:39:26.590
her. Then, just as she thought she could really not endure the ache in her arms and wrists another

07:39:26.590 --> 07:39:34.130
moment, Gilbert Blythe came rowing under the bridge and harming Andrew's dory. Gilbert glanced

07:39:34.130 --> 07:39:39.890
up and, much to his amazement, beheld a little white scornful face looking down on him with big,

07:39:40.030 --> 07:39:46.270
frightened but also scornful gray eyes. Anne, surely, how on earth did you get up there?

07:39:46.490 --> 07:39:52.030
he exclaimed. Without waiting for an answer, he pulled close to the pile and extended his hand.

07:39:52.030 --> 07:39:57.570
There was no help for it. Anne, clinging to Gilbert Blythe's hand, scrambled down into the

07:39:57.570 --> 07:40:03.150
dory where she sat, drabbled and furious, in the stern with her arms full of draping shawl

07:40:03.150 --> 07:40:08.910
and wet crepe. It was certainly extremely difficult to be dignified under the circumstances.

07:40:10.190 --> 07:40:13.790
What has happened, Anne? asked Gilbert, taking up his oars.

07:40:14.610 --> 07:40:18.990
We were playing Elaine, explained Anne frantically without even looking at her

07:40:18.990 --> 07:40:25.330
rescue. And I had to drift down to Camelot and the barge, I mean the flat. The flat began to

07:40:25.330 --> 07:40:30.650
leak and I climbed onto the pile. The girls went for help. Would you be kind enough to row me to

07:40:30.650 --> 07:40:37.810
the landing? Gilbert obligingly rowed to the landing and Anne, disdaining assistance, sprang

07:40:37.810 --> 07:40:43.310
nimbly on the shore. I'm very much obliged to you, she said haughtily as she turned away.

07:40:43.310 --> 07:40:47.830
But Gilbert also sprung from the boat and gnawed a detaining hand on her arm.

07:40:49.450 --> 07:40:54.630
Anne, he said hurriedly, look here. Can't we be good friends? I'm awfully sorry I made fun of your

07:40:54.630 --> 07:40:59.570
hair that time. I didn't mean to vex you and I only meant it for a joke. Besides, it's so long ago.

07:40:59.910 --> 07:41:03.710
I think your hair is awful pretty now. Honest I do. Let's be friends.

07:41:05.110 --> 07:41:10.530
For a moment Anne hesitated. She had an odd, newly awakened consciousness

07:41:11.090 --> 07:41:17.590
under all her outraged dignity that the half shy, half eager expression in Gilbert's hazel eyes

07:41:17.590 --> 07:41:23.310
was something that was very good to see. Her heart gave a quick, queer little beat.

07:41:24.490 --> 07:41:29.210
But the bitterness of her old grievance promptly stiffened up her wavering determination.

07:41:30.110 --> 07:41:35.650
That scene of two years before flushed back into her recollection as vividly as if it had taken

07:41:35.650 --> 07:41:42.250
place yesterday. Gilbert had called her carrots and had brought about her disgrace before the whole

07:41:42.250 --> 07:41:48.010
school. Her resentment, which to other and older people might be as laughable as its cause,

07:41:48.810 --> 07:41:54.310
was a no wit allayed and softened by time seemingly. She hated Gilbert Blythe. She would

07:41:54.310 --> 07:42:01.790
never forgive him. No, she said coldly, I shall never be friends with you Gilbert Blythe and I

07:42:01.790 --> 07:42:07.990
don't want to be. All right, Gilbert sprang into his skiff with angry colour in his cheeks.

07:42:08.410 --> 07:42:12.050
I'll never ask you to be friends again Anne Shirley and I don't care either.

07:42:14.330 --> 07:42:18.550
He pulled away with swift, defiant strokes and Anne went up to the steep,

07:42:18.750 --> 07:42:25.250
forny little path under the maples. She held her head very high but she was conscious of an odd

07:42:25.250 --> 07:42:31.370
feeling of regret. She almost wished she had answered Gilbert differently. Of course,

07:42:31.890 --> 07:42:38.470
he had insulted her terribly but still. Altogether Anne rather thought it would be quite a relief

07:42:38.470 --> 07:42:44.650
to sit down and have a good cry. She was really quite unstrung for the reaction from her fright

07:42:44.650 --> 07:42:52.490
and cramped clinging was making itself felt. Halfway up the path she met Jane and Diana rushing back

07:42:52.490 --> 07:42:58.490
the pond and the state narrowly removed from the positive friendly. They had found nobody at

07:42:58.490 --> 07:43:04.950
Orchard Slope, both Mr. and Mrs. Berry being away. He and Ruby Gillis had succumbed to hysterics

07:43:04.950 --> 07:43:10.050
and was left to recover from them as best she might. While Jane and Diana flew through the

07:43:10.050 --> 07:43:15.390
haunted wood and across the brook to Green Gables. There they had found nobody either

07:43:15.390 --> 07:43:19.910
for Marilla had gone back to Carmody and Matthew was making hay in the back field.

07:43:20.850 --> 07:43:26.530
Oh Anne, gasped Diana, fairly falling on the former's neck and weeping with relief and

07:43:26.530 --> 07:43:35.450
delight. Oh Anne, we thought you were drowned and we felt like murderers because we had made you

07:43:35.450 --> 07:43:40.430
made you be Elaine and Ruby's in hysterics. Oh Anne, how did you escape?

07:43:42.070 --> 07:43:47.710
I climbed up on one of the piles, explained Anne wearily and Gilbert Blythe came along

07:43:47.710 --> 07:43:55.250
Andrew's story and brought me to land. Oh Anne, how splendid of him. Why it's so romantic said

07:43:55.250 --> 07:44:00.510
Jane finding breath enough for this utterance at last. Of course she'll speak to him after this.

07:44:02.190 --> 07:44:08.770
Of course I won't flashed Anne with a momentary return of her old spirit and I don't want to ever

07:44:08.770 --> 07:44:14.030
hear the word romantic again Jane Andrews. I'm awfully sorry you're so frightened girls.

07:44:14.030 --> 07:44:21.290
It is all my fault. I feel I'm sure I was born under an unlucky star. Everything I do gets me

07:44:21.290 --> 07:44:26.790
or my dearest friends into escape. We've gone and lost your father's flat Diana and I have a

07:44:26.790 --> 07:44:32.990
presentiment that will not be allowed to row in the pond anymore. Anne's presentiment proved more

07:44:32.990 --> 07:44:38.810
trustworthy than presentiments are apt to do. Great was the consternation in the Barry and Cuthbert

07:44:38.810 --> 07:44:44.910
households when the events of the afternoon became known. Will you ever have any sense Anne

07:44:44.910 --> 07:44:52.410
grown Marilla? Oh yes I think I will Marilla returned Anne optimistically. A good cry indulged

07:44:52.410 --> 07:44:57.250
in the grateful solitude of the East Gable had soothed her nerves and restored her to her wilted

07:44:57.250 --> 07:45:04.270
cheerfulness. I think my prospects are becoming sensible are brighter than ever now. I don't say

07:45:04.880 --> 07:45:11.570
said Marilla. Well explained Anne I've learned a new and viable lesson today.

07:45:12.310 --> 07:45:18.050
Ever since I came to Green Gables I've been making mistakes and each mistake has helped to cure me of

07:45:18.050 --> 07:45:23.510
some great shortcoming. The affair of the amethyst brooch cured me of meddling with things that

07:45:23.510 --> 07:45:29.550
didn't belong to me. The haunted wood mistake cured me of letting my imagination run away with me.

07:45:29.550 --> 07:45:35.970
The liniment mistake cured me of carelessness and cooking. Dying my hair cured me of vanity.

07:45:37.030 --> 07:45:43.510
I never think about my hair and nose now at least very seldom and today's mistake is going to cure

07:45:43.510 --> 07:45:49.390
me of being too romantic. I have come to the conclusion that it is no use trying to be romantic

07:45:49.390 --> 07:45:57.010
and avidly. It was probably easy enough in towered Camelot of hundreds of years ago but romance is

07:45:57.010 --> 07:46:03.050
appreciated now. I feel quite sure that you will soon see a great improvement in me in this respect

07:46:03.050 --> 07:46:11.750
Marilla. I surely hope so said Marilla skeptically but Matthew who had been seated mutely in the

07:46:11.750 --> 07:46:19.550
corner laid a hand on Anne's shoulder when Marilla had gone out. Don't give up all your romance Anne

07:46:19.550 --> 07:46:26.730
he whispered shyly. A little of it is a good thing not too much of course but keep a little

07:46:26.730 --> 07:46:37.930
of it Anne. Keep a little of it.

07:47:00.350 --> 07:47:04.270
XXIX. An Epoch in Anne's Life.

07:47:06.050 --> 07:47:34.250
Anne was bringing the cows home from the back pasture by way of Lover's Lane. It was a September evening, and all the gaps and clearings in the woods were brimmed up with ruby sunset light. Here and there the lane was splashed with it, but for the most part it was already quite shadowy beneath the maples, and the spaces under the firs were filled with a clear violet dusk like airy wine. The winds were out in their tops, and there is no sweeter music on earth than that which the wind makes in the fir trees.

07:47:35.690 --> 07:47:52.970
The cows swung placidly down the lane, and Anne followed them dreamily, repeating aloud the battle canto from Marmion, which had also been part of their English course the preceding winter, and which Miss Stacy had made them learn off by heart, and exulting in its rushing lines and the clash of spears in its imagery.

07:47:52.970 --> 07:48:17.770
When she came to the lines, the stubborn spearsmen still made good their dark, impenetrable wood. She stopped in ecstasy to shut her eyes, that she might better fancy herself one of that heroic ring. When she opened them again it was to behold Diana coming through the gate that led into the berry field, and looking so important that Anne instantly divined that there was news to be told, but betray too eager curiosity she would not.

07:48:18.890 --> 07:48:28.850
Isn't this evening just like a purple dream, Diana? It makes me so glad to be alive. In the mornings I always think the mornings are best, but when evening comes I think it's lovelier still.

07:48:30.010 --> 07:48:35.750
It's a very fine evening, said Diana, but oh, I have such news, Anne. Guess. You can have three guesses.

07:48:36.910 --> 07:48:42.330
Charlotte Gillis is going to be married in the church after all, and Mrs. Allen wants us to decorate it, cried Anne.

07:48:43.550 --> 07:48:53.370
No, Charlotte's beau won't agree to that, because nobody ever has been married in the church yet, and he thinks it would seem too much like a funeral. It's too mean, because it would be such fun. Guess again.

07:48:54.230 --> 07:48:59.810
Jean's mother is going to let her have a birthday party? Diana shook her head, her black eyes dancing with merriment.

07:49:00.770 --> 07:49:08.090
I can't think what it can be, said Anne in despair, unless it's that moody Spurgeon MacPherson saw you home from prayer meeting last night, did he?

07:49:08.090 --> 07:49:16.970
I should think not, exclaimed Diana indignantly. I wouldn't be likely to boast of it if he did, the horrid creature. I knew you couldn't guess it.

07:49:17.270 --> 07:49:24.890
Mother had a letter from Aunt Josephine today, and Aunt Josephine wants you and me to go to town next Tuesday and stop with her for the exhibition. There.

07:49:25.730 --> 07:49:32.810
Oh, Diana, whispered Anne, finding it necessary to lean up against a maple tree for support. Do you really mean it?

07:49:32.810 --> 07:49:45.070
But I'm afraid Marilla won't let me go. She will say that she can't encourage gadding about. That was what she said last week when Jane invited me to go with them in their double-seated buggy to the American concert at the White Sands Hotel.

07:49:45.590 --> 07:49:59.250
I wanted to go, but Marilla said I'd be better at home learning my lessons, and so would Jane. I was bitterly disappointed, Diana. I felt so heartbroken that I wouldn't say my prayers when I went to bed, but I repented of that and got up in the middle of the night and said them.

07:49:59.990 --> 07:50:16.610
I'll tell you, said Diana, we'll get Mother to ask Marilla. She'll be more likely to let you go then, and if she does, we'll have the time of our lives, Anne. I've never been to an exhibition, and it's so aggravating to hear the other girls talking about their trips. Jane and Ruby have been twice, and they're going this year again.

07:50:17.230 --> 07:50:30.190
I'm not going to think about it at all until I know whether I can go or not, said Anne resolutely. If I did and then was disappointed, it would be more than I could bear. But in case I do go, I'm very glad my new coat will be ready by that time.

07:50:30.650 --> 07:50:55.010
Marilla didn't think I needed a new coat. She said my old one would do very well for another winter, and that I ought to be satisfied with having a new dress. The dress is very pretty, Diana, navy blue, and made so fashionably. Marilla always makes my dresses fashionably now, because she says she doesn't intend to have Matthew going to Mrs. Lynde to make them. I'm so glad. It is ever so much easier to be good if your clothes are fashionable. At least, it is easier for me.

07:50:55.010 --> 07:51:18.050
I suppose it doesn't make such a difference to naturally good people, but Matthew said I must have a new coat, so Marilla bought a lovely piece of blue broadcloth, and it's being made by a real dressmaker over at Carmody. It's to be done Saturday night, and I'm trying not to imagine myself walking up the church aisle on Sunday in my new suit and cap, because I'm afraid it isn't right to imagine such things, but it just slips into my mind in spite of me.

07:51:18.770 --> 07:51:47.430
It was a long drive, but Anne and Diana enjoyed every minute of it. It was delightful to rattle along over the moist roads and the early red sunlight that was creeping across the shore and harvest fields. The air was fresh and crisp, and little smoke-blue mists curled through the valleys and floated off from the hills. Sometimes the road went through woods where maples were beginning to hang out scarlet banners. Sometimes it crossed rivers on bridges that made Anne's flesh cringe with the old half-delightful fear.

07:51:48.470 --> 07:52:17.090
Sometimes it wound along a harbor shore and passed by a little cluster of weather-gray fishing huts. Again it mounted to hills whence a far sweep of curving upland or misty blue sky could be seen. But wherever it went, there was much of interest to discuss. It was almost noon when they reached town and found their way to Beechwood. It was quite a fine old mansion, set back from the street in a seclusion of green elms and branching beaches. Miss Barry met them at the door with a twinkle in her sharp black eyes.

07:52:18.050 --> 07:52:30.470
"'So you've come to see me at last, you Anne girl,' she said. "'Mercy, child, how you have grown! You're taller than I am, I declare, and you're ever so much better looking than you used to be, too. But I dare say you know that without being told.'"

07:52:31.270 --> 07:52:43.410
"'Indeed I didn't,' said Anne radiantly. "'I know I'm not so freckled as I used to be, so I've much to be thankful for. But I really hadn't dared to hope there was any other improvement. I'm so glad you think there is, Miss Barry.'"

07:52:43.410 --> 07:52:54.930
Miss Barry's house was furnished with great magnificence, as Anne told Marilla afterward. The two little country girls were rather abashed by the splendour of the parlour, where Miss Barry left them when she went to see about dinner.

07:52:55.750 --> 07:53:08.530
"'Isn't it just like a palace?' whispered Diana. "'I never was in Aunt Josephine's house before, and I'd no idea it was so grand. I just wish Julia Bell could see this. She puts on such airs about her mother's parlour.'"

07:53:08.530 --> 07:53:28.490
"'Velvet carpet,' sighed Anne luxuriously, "'and silk curtains. I've dreamed of such things, Diana. But do you know, I don't believe I feel very comfortable with them after all. There are so many things in this room, and all so splendid, that there is no scope for imagination. That is one consolation when you are poor. There are so many more things you can imagine about.'

07:53:29.330 --> 07:53:40.770
Their sojourn in town was something that Anne and Diana dated from for years. From first to last, it was crowded with delights. On Wednesday, Miss Barry took them to the exhibition grounds and kept them there all day.

07:53:41.370 --> 07:54:10.190
"'It was splendid,' Anne related to Marilla later on. "'I never imagined anything so interesting. I don't really know which department was the most interesting. I think I like the horses and the flowers and the fancy work best. Josie Pye took first prize for knitted lace. I was real glad she did, and I was glad that I felt glad, for it shows I'm improving, don't you think, Marilla, when I can rejoice in Josie's success?' Mr. Harmon Andrews took second prize for gravenstein apples, and Mr. Bell took first prize for a pig.

07:54:10.730 --> 07:54:29.730
Diana said she thought it was ridiculous for a Sunday school superintendent to take a prize in pigs, but I don't see why, do you? She said she would always think of it after this when he was praying so solemnly. Clara Louise McPherson took a prize for painting, and Mrs. Lynde got first prize for homemade butter and cheese. So Avonlea was pretty well represented, wasn't it?

07:54:29.730 --> 07:54:59.710
Mrs. Lynde was there that day, and I never knew how much I really liked her until I saw her familiar face among all those strangers. There were thousands of people there, Marilla. It made me feel dreadfully insignificant, and Miss Barry took us up to the grandstand to see the horse races. Mrs. Lynde wouldn't go. She said horse racing was an abomination, and, she being a church member, thought it her bounden duty to set a good example by staying away. But there were so many there, I don't believe Mrs. Lynde's absence would ever be noticed. I don't think, though, that I ought to go very far.

07:54:59.710 --> 07:55:27.950
I go very often to horse races, because they are awfully fascinating. Diana got so excited that she offered to bet me ten cents that the red horse would win. I didn't believe he would, but I refused to bet, because I wanted to tell Mrs. Allen all about everything, and I felt sure it wouldn't do to tell her that. It's always wrong to do anything you can't tell the minister's wife. It's as good as an extra conscience to have a minister's wife for your friend. And I was very glad I didn't bet, because the red horse did win, and I would have lost ten cents.

07:55:27.950 --> 07:55:57.930
So you see that virtue was its own reward. We saw a man go up in a balloon. I'd love to go up in a balloon, Marilla. It would be simply thrilling, and we saw a man selling fortunes. You paid him ten cents, and a little bird picked out your fortune for you. Miss Barry gave Diana and me ten cents each to have our fortunes told. Mine was that I would marry a dark-complected man who was very wealthy, and I would go across water to live. I looked carefully at all the dark men I saw after that, but I didn't care much for any of them, and anyhow I suppose it's too early to be looking elsewhere.

07:55:58.410 --> 07:56:19.730
Oh, it was a never-to-be-forgotten day, Marilla. I was so tired I couldn't sleep at night. Miss Barry put us in the spare room, according to promise. It was an elegant room, Marilla, but somehow sleeping in a spare room isn't what I used to think it was. That's the worst of growing up, and I'm beginning to realize it. The things you wanted so much when you were a child don't seem half so wonderful to you when you get them.

07:56:20.750 --> 07:56:31.410
Thursday the girls had a drive in the park, and in the evening Miss Barry took them to a concert in the Academy of Music, where a noted prima donna was to sing. To Anne, the evening was a glittering vision of delight.

07:56:33.010 --> 07:56:49.530
Oh, Marilla, it was beyond description. I was so excited I couldn't even talk, so you may know what it was like. I just sat in enraptured silence. Madame Solitsky was perfectly beautiful and wore white satin and diamonds, but when she began to sing I never thought about anything else.

07:56:49.530 --> 07:57:05.750
Oh, I can't tell you how I felt, but it seemed to me that it could never be hard to be good any more. I felt like I do when I look up to the stars. Tears came into my eyes, but oh, they were such happy tears. I was so sorry when it was all over, and I told Miss Barry I didn't see how I was ever to return to common life again.

07:57:06.190 --> 07:57:20.710
She said she thought if we went over to the restaurant across the street and had an ice cream it might help me. That sounded so prosaic, but to my surprise I found it true. The ice cream was delicious, Marilla, and it was so lovely and dissipated to be sitting there eating at eleven o'clock at night.

07:57:21.230 --> 07:57:31.990
Diana said she believed she was born for city life. Miss Barry asked me what my opinion was, but I said I would have to think it over very seriously before I could tell her what I really thought, so I thought it over after I went to bed.

07:57:31.990 --> 07:57:54.950
That is the best time to think things out, and I came to the conclusion, Marilla, that I wasn't born for city life and that I was glad of it. It's nice to be eating ice cream at brilliant restaurants at eleven o'clock at night once in a while, but as a regular thing I'd rather be in the east gable at eleven, sound asleep, but kind of knowing even in my sleep that the stars were shining outside and that the wind was blowing in the furs across the brook.

07:57:54.950 --> 07:58:09.930
I told Miss Barry so at breakfast the next morning, and she laughed. Miss Barry generally laughed at anything I said, even when I said the most solemn things. I don't think I liked it, Marilla, because I wasn't trying to be funny, but she is a most hospitable lady and treated us royally.

07:58:10.530 --> 07:58:14.310
Friday brought going home time, and Mr. Barry drove in for the girls.

07:58:15.130 --> 07:58:19.210
Well, I hope you've enjoyed yourselves, said Miss Barry as she bade them good-bye.

07:58:19.690 --> 07:58:21.270
Indeed we have, said Diana.

07:58:21.770 --> 07:58:22.910
And you, Anne girl?

07:58:23.570 --> 07:58:29.990
I've enjoyed every minute of the time, said Anne, throwing her arms impulsively about the old woman's neck and kissing her wrinkled cheek.

07:58:30.570 --> 07:58:45.630
Diana would never have dared to do such a thing and felt rather aghast at Anne's freedom, but Miss Barry was pleased, and she stood on her veranda and watched the buggy out of sight. Then she went back into her big house with a sigh. It seemed very lonely, lacking those fresh young lives.

07:58:46.370 --> 07:58:56.290
Miss Barry was a rather selfish old lady, if the truth must be told, and had never cared much for anybody but herself. She valued people only as they were of service to her or amused her.

07:58:56.290 --> 07:59:11.510
Anne had amused her, and consequently stood high in the old lady's good graces. But Miss Barry found herself thinking less about Anne's quaint speeches than of her fresh enthusiasms, her transparent emotions, her little winning ways, and the sweetness of her eyes and lips.

07:59:12.510 --> 07:59:25.610
I thought Marilla Cuthbert was an old fool when I heard she'd adopted a girl out of an orphan asylum, she said to herself, but I guess she didn't make much of a mistake after all. If I had a child like Anne in the house all the time, I'd be a better and happier woman.

07:59:26.670 --> 07:59:38.490
Anne and Diana found the drive home as pleasant as the drive in, pleasanter indeed, since there was the delightful consciousness of home waiting at the end of it. It was sunset when they passed through white sands and turned into the shore road.

07:59:39.010 --> 07:59:48.190
Beyond, the Avonlea Hills came out darkly against the saffron sky. Behind them the moon was rising out of the sea, that grew all radiant and transfigured in her light.

07:59:48.770 --> 07:59:58.590
Every little cove along the curving road was a marvel of dancing ripples. The waves broke with a soft swish on the rocks below them, and the tang of the sea was in the strong, fresh air.

07:59:59.510 --> 08:00:03.110
Oh, but it's good to be alive and to be going home, breathed Anne.

08:00:03.970 --> 08:00:14.710
When she reached the log bridge over the brook, the kitchen light of green gables winked her a friendly welcome back, and through the open door shone the hearth fire, sending out its warm red glow a thwart the chilly autumn night.

08:00:15.230 --> 08:00:20.010
Anne ran blithely up the hill and into the kitchen, where a hot supper was waiting on the table.

08:00:20.530 --> 08:00:23.350
So you've got back? said Marilla, folding up her knitting.

08:00:23.950 --> 08:00:33.410
Yes, and oh, it's so good to be back, said Anne joyously. I could kiss everything, even to the clock. Marilla, a broiled chicken! You don't mean to say you cooked that for me.

08:00:34.430 --> 08:00:39.950
Yes, I did, said Marilla. I thought you'd be hungry after such a drive, and need something real appetizing.

08:00:40.570 --> 08:00:44.530
Hurry and take off your things, and we'll have supper as soon as Matthew comes in.

08:00:44.930 --> 08:00:50.890
I'm glad you've got back, I must say. It's been fearful lonesome here without you, and I never put in four longer days.

08:00:51.630 --> 08:00:57.350
After supper, Anne sat before the fire between Matthew and Marilla, and gave them a full account of her visit.

08:00:58.110 --> 08:01:05.450
I've had a splendid time, she concluded happily, and I feel that it marks an epoch in my life. But the best of it all was the coming home.

08:01:10.010 --> 08:01:14.390
An epoch in Anne's life. Recorded by Randy Warwick.

08:01:43.010 --> 08:01:45.290
The Queen's class is organized.

08:01:46.770 --> 08:01:50.730
Marilla laid her knitting on her lap and leaned back in her chair.

08:01:51.510 --> 08:01:58.670
Her eyes were tired and she thought vaguely that she must see about having her glasses changed the next time she went to town,

08:01:59.150 --> 08:02:02.230
for her eyes had grown tired very often of late.

08:02:03.170 --> 08:02:07.650
It was nearly dark for the full November twilight had fallen around Green Gables

08:02:07.650 --> 08:02:12.590
and the only light in the kitchen came from the dancing red flames in the stove.

08:02:13.710 --> 08:02:17.050
Anne was curled up, Turk fashion, on the hearth rug,

08:02:17.510 --> 08:02:24.190
gazing into that joyous glow where the sunshine of a hundred summers was being distilled from the maple cordwood.

08:02:24.970 --> 08:02:33.030
She had been reading, but her book had slipped to the floor and now she was dreaming with a smile on her parted lips.

08:02:33.030 --> 08:02:40.670
Glittering castles in Spain were shaping themselves out of the mists and rainbows of her lively fancy.

08:02:41.810 --> 08:02:46.250
Adventures wonderful and enthralling were happening to her in cloudland,

08:02:46.870 --> 08:02:53.550
adventures that always turned out triumphantly and never involved her in scrapes like those of actual life.

08:02:54.850 --> 08:02:59.330
Marilla looked at her with a tenderness that would never have been suffered to reveal itself

08:02:59.330 --> 08:03:04.770
in any clearer light than that soft mingling of fire shine and shadow.

08:03:05.730 --> 08:03:13.630
The lesson of a love that should display itself easily in spoken word and open look was one Marilla could never learn,

08:03:14.330 --> 08:03:23.510
but she had learned to love this slim, grey-eyed girl with an affection all the deeper and stronger from its very undemonstrativeness.

08:03:23.510 --> 08:03:28.730
Her love made her afraid of being unduly indulgent indeed.

08:03:29.330 --> 08:03:38.890
She had an uneasy feeling that it was rather sinful to set one's heart so intensely on any human creature as she had set hers on Anne,

08:03:39.470 --> 08:03:49.130
and perhaps she performed a sort of unconscious penance for this by being stricter and more critical than if the girl had been less dear to her.

08:03:49.130 --> 08:03:53.670
Clearly Anne herself had no idea how Marilla loved her.

08:03:54.270 --> 08:04:01.090
She sometimes thought wistfully that Marilla was very hard to please and distinctly lacking in sympathy and understanding,

08:04:01.470 --> 08:04:07.170
but she always checked the thought reproachfully, remembering what she owed to Marilla.

08:04:08.770 --> 08:04:14.530
Anne, said Marilla abruptly, Miss Stacy was here this afternoon while you were out with Diana.

08:04:15.290 --> 08:04:19.110
Anne came back from her other world with a start and a sigh.

08:04:20.090 --> 08:04:25.470
Was she? Oh, I'm so sorry I wasn't in. Why didn't you call me, Marilla?

08:04:26.030 --> 08:04:30.930
Diana and I were only over in the haunted wood. It's lovely in the woods now.

08:04:31.390 --> 08:04:37.090
All the little wood things, the ferns and the satin leaves and the cracker berries have gone to sleep,

08:04:37.430 --> 08:04:41.990
just as if somebody had tucked them away until spring under a blanket of leaves.

08:04:41.990 --> 08:04:50.990
I think it was a little gray fairy with a rainbow scarf that came tiptoeing along the last moonlit night and did it.

08:04:51.890 --> 08:04:53.830
Diana wouldn't say much about that, though.

08:04:54.230 --> 08:04:59.510
Diana has never forgotten the scolding her mother gave her about imagining ghosts in the haunted wood.

08:05:00.290 --> 08:05:04.590
It had a very bad effect on Diana's imagination. It blighted it.

08:05:05.190 --> 08:05:08.110
Mrs. Lind says Myrtle Bell is a blighted being.

08:05:08.110 --> 08:05:15.590
I asked Ruby Gillis why Myrtle was blighted, and Ruby said she guessed it was because her young man had gone back on her.

08:05:16.250 --> 08:05:20.670
Ruby Gillis thinks of nothing but young men, and the older she gets, the worse she is.

08:05:21.110 --> 08:05:26.250
Young men are all very well in their place, but it doesn't do to drag them into everything, does it?

08:05:26.850 --> 08:05:33.930
Diana and I are thinking seriously of promising each other that we will never marry, but be nice old maids and live together forever.

08:05:35.170 --> 08:05:43.870
Diana hasn't quite made up her mind, though, because she thinks perhaps it would be nobler to marry some wild, dashing, wicked young man and reform him.

08:05:44.630 --> 08:05:47.810
Diana and I talk a great deal about serious subjects now, you know.

08:05:48.230 --> 08:05:53.750
We feel that we are so much older than we used to be that it isn't becoming to talk of childish matters.

08:05:54.550 --> 08:05:57.530
It's such a solemn thing to be almost fourteen, Marilla.

08:05:57.530 --> 08:06:04.410
Miss Stacey took all us girls who are in our teens down to the brook last Wednesday and talked to us about it.

08:06:04.750 --> 08:06:10.590
She said we couldn't be too careful what habits we formed and what ideals we acquired in our teens,

08:06:11.030 --> 08:06:17.430
because by the time we were twenty our characters would be developed and the foundation laid for our whole future life,

08:06:17.470 --> 08:06:23.410
and she said if the foundation was shaky we could never build anything really worthwhile on it.

08:06:23.990 --> 08:06:26.870
Diana and I talked the matter over coming home from school.

08:06:26.870 --> 08:06:35.210
We felt extremely solemn, Marilla, and we decided that we would try to be very careful indeed and form respectable habits

08:06:35.210 --> 08:06:42.530
and learn all we could and be as sensible as possible, so that by the time we were twenty our characters would be properly developed.

08:06:43.210 --> 08:06:49.190
It's perfectly appalling to think of being twenty, Marilla. It sounds so fearfully old and grown up.

08:06:49.550 --> 08:06:51.730
But why was Miss Stacey here this afternoon?

08:06:52.870 --> 08:06:58.910
That is what I wanted to tell you, Anne. If you'll ever give me a chance to get a word in edgewise.

08:06:59.490 --> 08:07:01.410
She was talking about you.

08:07:02.350 --> 08:07:05.190
About me? Anne looked rather scared.

08:07:05.950 --> 08:07:08.150
Then she flushed and exclaimed,

08:07:08.850 --> 08:07:15.650
Oh, I know what she was saying. I meant to tell you, Marilla. Honestly I did, but I forgot.

08:07:16.210 --> 08:07:23.130
Miss Stacey caught me reading Ben Hur in school yesterday afternoon when I should have been studying my Canadian history.

08:07:23.690 --> 08:07:31.050
Jane Andrews lent it to me. I was reading it at dinner hour, and I had just got to the chariot race when school went in.

08:07:31.550 --> 08:07:40.070
I was simply wild to know how it turned out, although I felt sure Ben Hur must win, because it wouldn't be poetical justice if he didn't.

08:07:40.070 --> 08:07:46.390
So I spread the history open on my desk lid, and then tucked Ben Hur between the desk and my knee.

08:07:46.990 --> 08:07:53.610
I just looked as if I were studying Canadian history, you know, while all the while I was reveling in Ben Hur.

08:07:54.150 --> 08:08:04.310
I was so interested in it that I never noticed Miss Stacey coming down the aisle until all at once I just looked up, and there she was looking down at me, so reproachful-like.

08:08:04.310 --> 08:08:10.390
I can't tell you how ashamed I felt, Marilla, especially when I heard Josie Pye giggling.

08:08:11.170 --> 08:08:19.910
Miss Stacey took Ben Hur away, but she never said a word then. She kept me in at recess and talked to me. She said I had done very wrong in two respects.

08:08:20.690 --> 08:08:31.530
First, I was wasting the time I ought to have put on my studies, and secondly, I was deceiving my teacher in trying to make it appear I was reading a history when it was a storybook instead.

08:08:32.150 --> 08:08:36.740
I had never realized until that moment, Marilla, that what I was doing was deceitful.

08:08:37.610 --> 08:08:44.890
I was shocked. I cried bitterly and asked Miss Stacey to forgive me, and I'd never do such a thing again.

08:08:45.290 --> 08:08:53.890
And I offered to do penance by never so much as looking at Ben Hur for a whole week, not even to see how the chariot race turned out.

08:08:54.230 --> 08:08:58.230
But Miss Stacey said she wouldn't require that, and she forgave me freely.

08:08:58.730 --> 08:09:03.430
So I think it wasn't very kind of her to come up here to you about it after all.

08:09:04.810 --> 08:09:10.070
Miss Stacey never mentioned such a thing to me, Anne, and it's only your guilty conscience that's the matter with you.

08:09:10.550 --> 08:09:19.690
You have no business to be taking storybooks to school. You read too many novels, anyhow. When I was a girl, I wasn't so much as allowed to look at a novel.

08:09:20.650 --> 08:09:26.410
Oh, how can you call Ben Hur a novel when it's really a religious book, protested Anne?

08:09:27.190 --> 08:09:32.590
Of course, it's a little too exciting to be proper reading for Sunday, and I only read it on weekdays.

08:09:33.050 --> 08:09:41.410
And I never read any book now unless either Miss Stacey or Mrs. Allen thinks it is a proper book for a girl 13 ¾ to read.

08:09:42.330 --> 08:09:49.070
Miss Stacey made me promise that. She found me reading a book one day called The Lurid Mystery of the Haunted Hall.

08:09:49.070 --> 08:09:57.610
It was one Ruby Gillis had lent me, and oh, Marilla, it was so fascinating and creepy. It just curdled the blood in my veins.

08:09:58.210 --> 08:10:04.650
But Miss Stacey said it was a very silly, unwholesome book, and she asked me not to read any more of it, or any like it.

08:10:05.250 --> 08:10:12.530
I didn't mind promising not to read any more like it, but I was agonizing to give back that book without knowing how it turned out.

08:10:13.090 --> 08:10:16.370
But my love for Miss Stacey stood the test, and I did.

08:10:16.370 --> 08:10:22.010
It's really wonderful, Marilla, what you can do when you're truly anxious to please a certain person.

08:10:23.670 --> 08:10:30.890
Well, I guess I'll light the lamp and get to work, said Marilla. I see plainly that you don't want to hear what Miss Stacey had to say.

08:10:31.490 --> 08:10:35.330
You're more interested in the sound of your own tongue than in anything else.

08:10:36.210 --> 08:10:43.350
Oh, indeed, Marilla, I do want to hear it, cried Anne contritely. I won't say another word, not one.

08:10:43.350 --> 08:10:47.410
I know I talk too much, but I'm really trying to overcome it.

08:10:47.570 --> 08:10:55.350
And although I say far too much, yet if only you knew how many things I want to say and don't, you'd give me some credit for it.

08:10:55.770 --> 08:10:57.010
Please tell me, Marilla.

08:10:58.210 --> 08:11:06.690
Well, Miss Stacey wants to organize a class among her advanced students who mean to study for the entrance examination into Queens.

08:11:07.350 --> 08:11:11.530
She intends to give them extra lessons for an hour after school.

08:11:11.530 --> 08:11:16.750
And she came to ask Matthew and me if we would like to have you join it.

08:11:17.170 --> 08:11:21.530
What do you think about it yourself, Anne? Would you like to go to Queens and pass for a teacher?

08:11:23.230 --> 08:11:28.370
Oh, Marilla! Anne straightened to her knees and clasped her hands.

08:11:29.070 --> 08:11:36.850
It's been the dream of my life, that is, for the last six months, ever since Ruby and Jane began to talk of studying for the entrance.

08:11:36.850 --> 08:11:41.770
But I didn't say anything about it, because I supposed it would be perfectly useless.

08:11:42.370 --> 08:11:46.250
I'd love to be a teacher, but won't it be dreadfully expensive?

08:11:46.870 --> 08:11:54.330
Mr. Andrews says it cost him $150 to put Prissy through, and Prissy wasn't a dunce in geometry.

08:11:55.690 --> 08:11:58.350
I guess you needn't worry about that part of it.

08:11:58.690 --> 08:12:04.870
When Matthew and I took you to bring up, we resolved we would do the best we could for you and give you a good education.

08:12:05.450 --> 08:12:11.190
I believe in a girl being fitted to earn her own living, whether she ever has to or not.

08:12:11.870 --> 08:12:15.990
You'll always have a home at Green Gables, as long as Matthew and I are here.

08:12:16.490 --> 08:12:21.830
But nobody knows what is going to happen in this uncertain world, and it's just as well to be prepared.

08:12:22.430 --> 08:12:24.850
So you can join the Queen's class if you like, Anne.

08:12:25.970 --> 08:12:32.910
Oh, Marilla, thank you! Anne flung her arms around Marilla's waist and looked up earnestly into her face.

08:12:32.910 --> 08:12:41.450
I'm extremely grateful to you, Anne Matthew, and I'll study as hard as I can and do my very best to be a credit to you.

08:12:41.950 --> 08:12:48.490
I warn you not to expect much in geometry, but I think I can hold my own in anything else, if I work hard.

08:12:49.570 --> 08:12:54.550
I dare say you'll get along well enough. Miss Stacy says you are bright and diligent.

08:12:55.630 --> 08:13:00.650
Not for worlds would Marilla have told Anne just what Miss Stacy had said about her.

08:13:00.650 --> 08:13:02.890
That would have been to pamper vanity.

08:13:04.010 --> 08:13:08.450
You needn't rush to any extreme of killing yourself over your books. There is no hurry.

08:13:09.130 --> 08:13:12.050
You won't be ready to try the entrance for a year and a half yet.

08:13:12.710 --> 08:13:16.530
But it's well to begin in time and be thoroughly grounded, Miss Stacy says.

08:13:18.170 --> 08:13:24.190
I shall take more interest than ever in my studies now, said Anne blissfully, because I have a purpose in life.

08:13:24.910 --> 08:13:29.450
Mr. Allen says everybody should have a purpose in life and pursue it faithfully.

08:13:29.450 --> 08:13:33.610
Only, he says, we must first make sure that it is a worthy purpose.

08:13:34.270 --> 08:13:38.810
I would call it a worthy purpose to want to be a teacher like Miss Stacy, wouldn't you, Marilla?

08:13:39.330 --> 08:13:41.290
I think it's a very noble profession.

08:13:42.750 --> 08:13:45.690
The Queen's class was organized in due time.

08:13:46.150 --> 08:13:55.550
Gilbert Blythe, Anne Shirley, Ruby Gillis, Jane Andrews, Josie Pye, Charlie Sloan, and Moody Spurgeon McPherson joined it.

08:13:55.550 --> 08:14:00.670
Diana Berry did not, as her parents did not intend to send her to Queen's.

08:14:00.790 --> 08:14:03.650
This seemed nothing short of a calamity to Anne.

08:14:04.610 --> 08:14:10.310
Never, since the night on which Minnie May had had the croup, had she and Diana been separated in anything.

08:14:11.350 --> 08:14:15.590
On the evening when the Queen's class first remained in school for the extra hours,

08:14:16.050 --> 08:14:23.270
and Anne saw Diana go slowly out with the others to walk home alone through the birch path and violet veil,

08:14:23.270 --> 08:14:30.310
it was all the former could do to keep her seat and refrain from rushing impulsively after her chum.

08:14:30.730 --> 08:14:38.310
A lump came into her throat, and she hastily retired behind the pages of her uplifted grammar to hide the tears in her eyes.

08:14:38.990 --> 08:14:44.150
Not for the world would Anne have had Gilbert Blythe or Josie Pye see those tears.

08:14:44.890 --> 08:14:53.090
But oh, Marilla, I really felt that I had tasted the bitterness of death, as Mr. Allen said in his sermon last Sunday,

08:14:53.550 --> 08:14:57.510
when I saw Diana go out alone, she said mournfully that night.

08:14:57.950 --> 08:15:03.030
I thought how splendid it would have been if Diana had only been going to study for the entrance, too.

08:15:03.690 --> 08:15:07.990
But we can't have things perfect in this imperfect world, as Mrs. Lind says.

08:15:08.690 --> 08:15:13.230
Mrs. Lind isn't exactly a comforting person sometimes, but there's no doubt.

08:15:13.230 --> 08:15:15.790
She says a great many very true things.

08:15:16.250 --> 08:15:19.590
And I think the Queen's class is going to be extremely interesting.

08:15:20.230 --> 08:15:22.710
Jane and Ruby are just going to study to be teachers.

08:15:23.230 --> 08:15:24.870
That is the height of their ambition.

08:15:25.810 --> 08:15:30.970
Ruby says she will only teach for two years after she gets through, and then she intends to be married.

08:15:31.930 --> 08:15:38.750
Jane says she will devote her whole life to teaching, and never, never marry, because you are paid a salary for teaching.

08:15:38.750 --> 08:15:45.150
But a husband won't pay you anything, and growls if you ask for a share in the egg and butter money.

08:15:45.950 --> 08:15:54.730
I expect Jane speaks from a mournful experience, for Mrs. Lind says that her father is a perfect old crank, and meaner than second skimmings.

08:15:55.730 --> 08:16:01.190
Josie Pye says she is just going to college for education's sake, because she won't have to earn her own living.

08:16:01.870 --> 08:16:05.130
She says, of course, it is different with orphans who are living on charity.

08:16:05.550 --> 08:16:06.810
They have to hustle.

08:16:07.750 --> 08:16:10.010
Moody Spurgeon is going to be a minister.

08:16:10.650 --> 08:16:14.770
Mrs. Lind says he couldn't be anything else with a name like that to live up to.

08:16:15.450 --> 08:16:21.290
I hope it isn't wicked of me, Marilla, but really, the thought of Moody Spurgeon being a minister makes me laugh.

08:16:21.770 --> 08:16:28.810
He's such a funny looking boy, with that big fat face, and his little blue eyes, and his ears sticking out like flaps.

08:16:29.550 --> 08:16:32.870
But perhaps he will be more intellectual looking when he grows up.

08:16:33.430 --> 08:16:37.930
Charlie Sloan says he's going to go into politics, and be a member of parliament.

08:16:38.470 --> 08:16:46.490
But Mrs. Lind says he'll never succeed at that, because the Sloans are all honest people, and it's only rascals that get on in politics nowadays.

08:16:48.330 --> 08:16:53.590
What is Gilbert Blythe going to be? queried Marilla, seeing that Anne was opening her Caesar.

08:16:54.610 --> 08:17:00.910
I don't happen to know what Gilbert Blythe's ambition in life is, if he has any, said Anne scornfully.

08:17:00.910 --> 08:17:04.670
There was open rivalry between Gilbert and Anne now.

08:17:05.210 --> 08:17:13.930
Previously the rivalry had been rather one-sided, but there was no longer any doubt that Gilbert was as determined to be first in class as Anne was.

08:17:14.490 --> 08:17:16.830
He was a foeman worthy of her steel.

08:17:17.690 --> 08:17:24.730
The other members of the class tacitly acknowledged their superiority, and never dreamed of trying to compete with them.

08:17:24.730 --> 08:17:39.210
Since the day by the pond when she had refused to listen to his plea for forgiveness, Gilbert, save for the aforesaid determined rivalry, had evinced no recognition whatever of the existence of Anne Shirley.

08:17:40.150 --> 08:17:52.270
He talked and jested with the other girls, exchanged books and puzzles with them, discussed lessons and plans, sometimes walked home with one or the other of them from prayer meeting or debating club.

08:17:52.270 --> 08:17:59.210
But Anne Shirley he simply ignored, and Anne found out that it is not pleasant to be ignored.

08:18:00.130 --> 08:18:05.170
It was in vain that she told herself with a toss of her head that she did not care.

08:18:05.590 --> 08:18:17.230
Deep down in her wayward, feminine little heart, she knew that she did care, and that if she had the chance of the lake of shining waters again, she would answer very differently.

08:18:17.870 --> 08:18:29.450
All at once as it seemed, and to her secret dismay, she found that the old resentment she had cherished against him was gone, gone just when she most needed its sustaining power.

08:18:30.350 --> 08:18:38.510
It was in vain that she recalled every incident and emotion of that memorable occasion, and tried to feel the old satisfying anger.

08:18:38.510 --> 08:18:50.270
The day by the pond had witnessed its last spasmodic flicker. Anne realized that she had forgiven and forgotten without knowing it, but it was too late.

08:18:51.330 --> 08:19:01.530
And at least neither Gilbert nor anybody else, not even Diana, should ever suspect how sorry she was and how much she wished she hadn't been so proud and horrid.

08:19:01.530 --> 08:19:20.430
She determined to shroud her feelings in deepest oblivion, and it may be stated here and now that she did it so successfully that Gilbert, who possibly was not quite so indifferent as he seemed, could not console himself with any belief that Anne felt his retaliatory scorn.

08:19:21.210 --> 08:19:29.610
The only poor comfort he had was that she snubbed Charlie Sloan unmercifully, continually, and undeservedly.

08:19:31.130 --> 08:19:40.310
Otherwise, the winter passed away in a round of pleasant duties and studies. For Anne, the days slipped by like golden beads on the necklace of the year.

08:19:40.930 --> 08:19:56.770
She was happy, eager, interested. There were lessons to be learned and honor to be won, delightful books to read, new pieces to be practiced for the Sunday school choir, pleasant Saturday afternoons at the Mance with Mrs. Allen.

08:19:56.770 --> 08:20:05.950
And then, almost before Anne realized it, spring had come again to Green Gables, and all the world was a bloom once more.

08:20:06.810 --> 08:20:28.450
Studies pawled just a wee bit then. The Queen's class, left behind in school while the others scattered to green lanes and leafy woodcuts and meadow byways, looked wistfully out of the windows and discovered the Latin verbs and French exercises had somehow lost the tang and zest they had possessed in the crisp winter months.

08:20:28.450 --> 08:20:40.890
Even Anne and Gilbert lagged and grew indifferent. Teacher and taught were alike, glad when the term was ended, and the glad vacation days stretched rosily before them.

08:20:42.330 --> 08:21:03.250
But you've done good work this past year, Miss Stacy told them on the last evening, and you deserve a good, jolly vacation. Have the best time you can in the out-of-door world, and lay in a good stock of health and vitality and ambition to carry you through next year. It will be the tug of war, you know, the last year before the entrance.

08:21:04.150 --> 08:21:08.430
Are you going to be back next year, Miss Stacy? asked Josie Pie.

08:21:09.570 --> 08:21:28.570
Josie Pie never scrupled to ask questions. In this instance, the rest of the class felt grateful to her. None of them would have dared to ask it of Miss Stacy, but all wanted to, for there had been alarming rumors running at large through the school for some time that Miss Stacy was not coming back the next year.

08:21:28.570 --> 08:21:38.490
That she had been offered a position in the grade school of her own home district and meant to accept. The Queen's class listened in breathless suspense for her answer.

08:21:39.710 --> 08:21:55.470
Yes, I think I will, said Miss Stacy. I thought of taking another school, but I have decided to come back to Avonlea. To tell the truth, I've grown so interested in my pupils here that I found I couldn't leave them. So I'll stay and see you through.

08:21:56.790 --> 08:22:06.990
Hooray, said Moody Spurgeon. Moody Spurgeon had never been so carried away by his feelings before, and he blushed uncomfortably every time he thought about it for a week.

08:22:08.110 --> 08:22:21.790
Oh, I'm so glad, said Anne with shining eyes. Dear Miss Stacy, it would be perfectly dreadful if you didn't come back. I don't believe I could have the heart to go on with my studies at all if another teacher came here.

08:22:22.570 --> 08:22:31.650
When Anne got home that night, she stacked all her textbooks away in an old trunk in the attic, locked it, and threw the key into the blanket box.

08:22:32.490 --> 08:22:48.870
I'm not even going to look at a school book in vacation, she told Marilla. I've studied as hard all the term as I possibly could, and I've pored over that geometry until I know every proposition in the first book off by heart, even when the letters are changed.

08:22:48.870 --> 08:23:01.310
I just feel tired of everything sensible, and I'm going to let my imagination run riot for the summer. Oh, you needn't be alarmed, Marilla. I'll only let it run riot within reasonable limits.

08:23:01.950 --> 08:23:14.470
But I want to have a real good jolly time this summer, for maybe it's the last summer I'll be a little girl. Mrs. Lin says that if I keep stretching out next year as I've done this, I'll have to put on longer skirts.

08:23:14.470 --> 08:23:23.790
She says I'm all running to legs and eyes, and when I put on longer skirts, I shall feel that I have to live up to them and be very dignified.

08:23:24.410 --> 08:23:31.150
It won't even do to believe in fairies, then, I'm afraid, so I'm going to believe in them with all my whole heart this summer.

08:23:31.930 --> 08:23:41.430
I think we're going to have a very gay vacation. Ruby Gillis is going to have a birthday party soon, and there's the Sunday school picnic and the missionary concert next month.

08:23:41.430 --> 08:23:50.390
And Mr. Berry says that some evening he'll take Diana and me over to the White Sands Hotel and have dinner there. They have dinner there in the evening, you know.

08:23:51.130 --> 08:24:01.470
Jane Andrews was over once last summer, and she says it was a dazzling sight to see the electric lights and the flowers and all the lady guests in such beautiful dresses.

08:24:02.530 --> 08:24:08.290
Jane says it was her first glimpse into high life, and she'll never forget it to her dying day.

08:24:09.190 --> 08:24:15.410
Mrs. Lind came up the next afternoon to find out why Marilla had not been at the aid meeting on Thursday.

08:24:16.290 --> 08:24:21.210
When Marilla was not at aid meeting, people knew there was something wrong at Green Gables.

08:24:22.690 --> 08:24:29.570
Matthew had a bad spell with his heart Thursday, Marilla explained, and I didn't feel like leaving him.

08:24:30.310 --> 08:24:37.110
Oh yes, he's all right now, but he takes them spells oftener than he used to, and I'm anxious about him.

08:24:37.110 --> 08:24:40.710
The doctor says he must be careful to avoid excitement.

08:24:41.270 --> 08:24:47.110
That's easy enough, for Matthew doesn't go about looking for excitement by any means, and never did.

08:24:47.570 --> 08:24:53.530
But he's not to do any very heavy work either, and you might as well tell Matthew not to breathe as not to work.

08:24:54.470 --> 08:24:57.210
Come and lay off your things, Rachel. You'll stay to tea?

08:24:58.430 --> 08:25:06.530
Well, seeing you're so pressing, perhaps I might as well stay, said Mrs. Rachel, who had not the slightest intention of doing anything else.

08:25:07.510 --> 08:25:17.330
Mrs. Rachel and Marilla sat comfortably in the parlor while Anne got the tea and made hot biscuits that were light and white enough to defy even Mrs. Rachel's criticism.

08:25:18.150 --> 08:25:26.710
I must say Anne has turned out a real smart girl, admitted Mrs. Rachel, as Marilla accompanied her to the end of the lane at sunset.

08:25:27.350 --> 08:25:29.250
She must be a great help to you.

08:25:29.970 --> 08:25:34.430
She is, said Marilla, and she's real steady and reliable now.

08:25:35.070 --> 08:25:42.990
I used to be afraid she'd never get over her feather-brained ways, but she has, and I wouldn't be afraid to trust her in anything now.

08:25:44.010 --> 08:25:50.610
I never would have thought she'd have turned out so well that first day I was here three years ago, said Mrs. Rachel.

08:25:51.310 --> 08:25:54.390
Lawful heart shall I ever forget that tantrum of hers.

08:25:55.130 --> 08:26:03.030
When I went home that night, I says to Thomas, says I, mark my words Thomas, Marilla Cuthbert'll live to rue the steps she's took.

08:26:03.750 --> 08:26:06.510
But I was mistaken, and I'm real glad of it.

08:26:07.150 --> 08:26:12.150
I ain't one of those kind of people, Marilla, as can never be brought to own up that they've made a mistake.

08:26:12.810 --> 08:26:15.330
No, that never was my way, thank goodness.

08:26:15.970 --> 08:26:24.050
I did make a mistake in judging Anne, but it weren't no wonder, for an otter, unexpected, or witch of a child, there never was in this world, that's what.

08:26:24.710 --> 08:26:28.150
There was no ciphering her out by the rules that worked with other children.

08:26:29.070 --> 08:26:33.610
It's nothing short of wonderful how she's improved these three years, but especially in looks.

08:26:34.330 --> 08:26:40.970
She's a real pretty girl, got to be, though I can't say I'm overly partial to that pale, big-eyed style myself.

08:26:40.970 --> 08:26:45.910
I like more snappin' color, like Diana Berry has, or Ruby Gillis.

08:26:46.750 --> 08:26:57.970
Ruby Gillis's looks are real showy, but somehow, I don't know how it is, but when Anne and them are together, though she ain't half as handsome, she makes them look kind of common, and overdone.

08:26:58.850 --> 08:27:05.170
Something like the white June lilies she calls narcissists, alongside of the big red peonies, that's what.

08:27:17.130 --> 08:27:18.530
Thank you for watching!

08:27:43.570 --> 08:27:47.830
Anne of Green Gables by Lucy Maud Montgomery.

08:27:49.850 --> 08:27:53.920
Where the Brook and River Meet.

08:27:56.130 --> 08:27:59.750
Anne had her good summer and enjoyed it wholeheartedly.

08:28:00.470 --> 08:28:06.210
She and Diana fairly lived outdoors, reveling in all the delights that Lover's Lane

08:28:06.210 --> 08:28:11.010
and the Dryad's Bubble and Willowmere and Victoria Island afforded.

08:28:12.270 --> 08:28:15.170
Marilla offered no objections to Anne's gypsyings.

08:28:15.730 --> 08:28:19.230
The Spencervale doctor, who had come the night Mini May had the croup,

08:28:19.590 --> 08:28:25.290
met Anne at a house of a patient one afternoon early in vacation, looked her over sharply,

08:28:25.970 --> 08:28:31.950
screwed up his mouth, shook his head, and sent a message to Marilla Cuthbert by another person.

08:28:32.670 --> 08:28:37.390
It was, Keep that redheaded girl of yours in the open air all summer,

08:28:37.730 --> 08:28:41.030
and don't let her read books until she gets more spring into her step.

08:28:41.870 --> 08:28:44.690
This message frightened Marilla wholesomely.

08:28:45.290 --> 08:28:50.850
She read Anne's death warrant by consumption in it, unless it was scrupulously obeyed.

08:28:51.390 --> 08:28:56.950
As a result, Anne had the golden summer of her life as far as freedom and frolic went.

08:28:57.510 --> 08:29:04.410
She walked, rode, buried, and dreamed to her heart's content, and when September came,

08:29:04.770 --> 08:29:10.050
she was bright-eyed and alert, with a step that would have satisfied the Spencervale doctor,

08:29:10.530 --> 08:29:13.370
and a heart full of ambition and zest once more.

08:29:14.350 --> 08:29:19.310
I feel just like studying with might in Maine, she declared as she brought her books down from

08:29:19.310 --> 08:29:25.450
the attic. Oh, you good old friends, I'm glad to see your honest faces once more.

08:29:25.450 --> 08:29:32.970
Yes, even you, Geometry. I've had a perfectly beautiful summer, Marilla, and now I'm rejoicing

08:29:32.970 --> 08:29:38.950
as a strong man to run a race, as Mr. Allen said last Sunday. Doesn't Mr. Allen preach

08:29:38.950 --> 08:29:45.110
magnificent sermons? Mrs. Lynde says he is improving every day, and the first thing we know,

08:29:45.270 --> 08:29:50.690
some city church will gobble him up, and then we'll be left and have to turn to and break in

08:29:51.290 --> 08:29:56.750
preacher. But I don't see the use of meeting trouble halfway, do you, Marilla? I think it

08:29:56.750 --> 08:30:01.970
would be better just to enjoy Mr. Allen while we have him. If I were a man, I think I'd be a

08:30:01.970 --> 08:30:08.310
minister. They can have such an influence for good if their theology is sound, and it must be

08:30:08.310 --> 08:30:14.890
thrilling to preach splendid sermons and stir your hearer's hearts. Why can't women be ministers,

08:30:14.890 --> 08:30:21.010
Marilla? I asked Mrs. Lynde that, and she was shocked and said it would be a scandalous thing.

08:30:21.510 --> 08:30:26.170
She said there might be female ministers in the States, and she believed there was,

08:30:26.490 --> 08:30:31.310
but thank goodness we hadn't got to that stage in Canada yet, and she hoped we never would.

08:30:31.790 --> 08:30:37.450
But I don't see why. I think women would make splendid ministers. When there is a social to

08:30:37.450 --> 08:30:42.730
be got up, or a church tea, or anything else to raise money, the women have to turn to and do the

08:30:43.270 --> 08:30:47.210
I'm sure Mrs. Lynde can pray every bit as well as Superintendent Bell,

08:30:47.650 --> 08:30:50.530
and I've no doubt she could preach, too, with a little practice.

08:30:51.770 --> 08:30:59.030
Yes, I believe she could, said Marilla dryly. She does plenty of unofficial preaching as it is.

08:30:59.710 --> 08:31:04.350
Nobody has much of a chance to go wrong in Avonlea with Rachel to oversee them.

08:31:05.510 --> 08:31:10.750
Marilla, said Anne in a burst of confidence, I want to tell you something and ask you what

08:31:10.750 --> 08:31:16.390
think about it. It has worried me terribly. On Sunday afternoons, that is, when I think

08:31:16.390 --> 08:31:22.450
especially about such matters. I do really want to be good, and when I'm with you, or Mrs. Allen,

08:31:22.530 --> 08:31:27.470
or Miss Stacy, I want it more than ever, and I want to do just what would please you and what

08:31:27.470 --> 08:31:33.130
you would approve of. But mostly when I am with Mrs. Lynde, I feel desperately wicked,

08:31:33.530 --> 08:31:39.330
and as if I wanted to go and do the very thing she tells me I oughtn't to do. I feel irresistibly

08:31:39.330 --> 08:31:44.690
tempted to do it. Now what do you think is the reason I feel like that? Do you think

08:31:44.690 --> 08:31:51.810
it's because I'm really bad and unregenerate? Marilla looked dubious for a moment. Then she

08:31:51.810 --> 08:31:59.230
laughed. If you are, I guess I am, too, Anne, for Rachel often has that very effect on me.

08:31:59.670 --> 08:32:04.570
I sometimes think she'd have more of an influence for good, as you say yourself,

08:32:04.570 --> 08:32:09.550
if she didn't keep up nagging people to do right. There should have been a special

08:32:09.550 --> 08:32:16.390
commandment against nagging. But there I shouldn't talk so. Rachel is a good Christian woman,

08:32:16.390 --> 08:32:22.990
and she means well. There isn't a kinder soul in Avonlea, and she never shirks her share of work.

08:32:23.830 --> 08:32:30.410
I'm very glad you feel the same, said Anne decidedly. It's so encouraging. I shan't worry

08:32:30.410 --> 08:32:35.730
so much over that after this. But I dare say there'll be other things to worry me.

08:32:36.090 --> 08:32:41.670
They keep coming up new all the time, things to perplex you, you know. You settle one question,

08:32:41.810 --> 08:32:46.570
and there's another right after. There are so many things to be thought over and decided when

08:32:46.570 --> 08:32:51.750
you're beginning to grow up. It keeps me busy all the time thinking them over and deciding what is

08:32:51.750 --> 08:32:57.970
right. It's a serious thing to grow up, isn't it, Marilla? But when I have such good friends as you

08:32:57.970 --> 08:33:03.610
Matthew and Mrs. Allen and Miss Stacey, I ought to grow up successfully, and I'm sure it will be

08:33:03.610 --> 08:33:08.950
my own fault if I don't. I feel it's a great responsibility, because I have only the one

08:33:08.950 --> 08:33:15.510
chance. If I don't grow up right, I can't go back and begin over again. I've grown two inches this

08:33:15.510 --> 08:33:22.150
summer, Marilla. Mr. Gillis measured me at Ruby's party. I'm so glad you made my new dresses longer.

08:33:22.150 --> 08:33:28.310
That dark green one is so pretty, and it was sweet of you to put on the flounce. Of course,

08:33:28.310 --> 08:33:34.210
I know it wasn't really necessary, but flounces are so stylish this fall, and Josie Pye has

08:33:34.210 --> 08:33:39.930
flounces on all her dresses. I know I'll be able to study better because of mine. I shall have such

08:33:39.930 --> 08:33:46.390
a comfortable feeling deep down in my mind about that flounce. It's worth something to have that,

08:33:46.390 --> 08:33:53.490
admitted Marilla. Miss Stacey came back to Avonlea School and found all her pupils eager

08:33:53.490 --> 08:33:59.610
for work once more. Especially did the Queen's class gird up their loins for the fray,

08:33:59.810 --> 08:34:05.690
for at the end of the coming year, dimly shadowing their pathway already, loomed up that fateful

08:34:05.690 --> 08:34:11.470
thing known as the entrance, at the very thought of which one and all felt their hearts sink into

08:34:11.470 --> 08:34:18.790
their very shoes. Suppose they did not pass. That thought was doomed to haunt Anne through

08:34:18.790 --> 08:34:25.910
the waking hours of that winter, Sunday afternoons inclusive, to the almost entire exclusion of moral

08:34:25.910 --> 08:34:31.890
and theological problems. When Anne had bad dreams, she found herself staring miserably

08:34:31.890 --> 08:34:38.130
at pass lists of the entrance exams, where Gilbert Blythe's name was blazoned at the top,

08:34:38.130 --> 08:34:45.510
and in which hers did not appear at all. But it was a jolly, busy, happy, swift flying winter.

08:34:46.390 --> 08:34:53.390
Schoolwork was as interesting, class rivalry as absorbing as of yore. New worlds of thought,

08:34:53.610 --> 08:34:59.770
feeling, and ambition, fresh, fascinating fields of unexplored knowledge seemed to be opening out

08:34:59.770 --> 08:35:07.110
Anne's eager eyes. Hills peeped o'er hill, and alps on alps arose.

08:35:08.430 --> 08:35:15.430
Much of all this was due to Miss Stacy's tactful, careful, broad-minded guidance. She led her class

08:35:15.430 --> 08:35:22.090
to think and explore and discover for themselves, and encouraged straying from the old beaten paths

08:35:22.090 --> 08:35:28.670
to a degree that quite shocked Mrs. Linde and the school trustees, who viewed all innovations on

08:35:28.670 --> 08:35:36.390
established methods rather dubiously. Apart from her studies, Anne expanded socially. For Marilla,

08:35:36.790 --> 08:35:43.390
mindful of the Spencer Vale's doctor's dictum, no longer vetoed occasional outings. The debating

08:35:43.390 --> 08:35:49.190
club flourished and gave several concerts. There were one or two parties almost verging on grown-up

08:35:49.190 --> 08:35:56.930
affairs. There were sleigh drives and skating frolics galore. Between times Anne grew, shooting

08:35:56.930 --> 08:36:03.150
up so rapidly that Marilla was astonished one day when they were standing side by side to find the

08:36:03.150 --> 08:36:10.170
girl was taller than herself. Why, Anne, how you've grown, she said almost unbelievably.

08:36:11.250 --> 08:36:19.090
A sigh followed on the words. Marilla felt a queer regret over Anne's inches. The child she had learned

08:36:19.090 --> 08:36:26.090
to love had vanished somehow, and here was this tall, serious-eyed girl of fifteen, with the

08:36:26.090 --> 08:36:32.890
thoughtful brows and the proudly poised little head in her place. Marilla loved the girl as much

08:36:32.890 --> 08:36:39.890
as she had loved the child, but she was conscious of a queer, sorrowful sense of loss, and that night,

08:36:39.910 --> 08:36:45.910
when Anne had gone to prayer meeting with Diana, Marilla sat alone in the wintry twilight and

08:36:45.910 --> 08:36:52.710
indulged in the weakness of a cry. Matthew, coming in with a lantern, caught her at it and

08:36:52.710 --> 08:36:57.490
gazed at her in such consternation that Marilla had to laugh through her tears.

08:36:58.350 --> 08:37:04.630
I was thinking about Anne, she explained. She's got to be such a big girl, and she'll probably

08:37:04.630 --> 08:37:11.470
be away from us next winter. I'll miss her terrible. She'll be able to come home often,

08:37:11.830 --> 08:37:17.610
comforted Matthew, to whom Anne was as yet and always would be the little eager girl he had

08:37:18.290 --> 08:37:21.850
from Bright River on that June evening, four years before.

08:37:22.670 --> 08:37:25.930
The branch railroad will be built to Carmody by that time.

08:37:26.950 --> 08:37:31.490
It won't be the same thing as having her here all the time, said Marilla gloomily,

08:37:31.910 --> 08:37:38.870
determined to enjoy the luxury of grief uncomforted. But there, men can't understand these things.

08:37:40.770 --> 08:37:44.690
There were other changes in Anne, no less real than the physical change.

08:37:44.690 --> 08:37:51.110
For one thing, she became much quieter. Perhaps she thought all the more and dreamed as much as

08:37:51.110 --> 08:37:57.210
ever, but she certainly talked less. Marilla noticed and commented on this also.

08:37:58.230 --> 08:38:02.870
You don't chatter half as much as you used to, Anne, nor use half as many big words.

08:38:03.410 --> 08:38:09.150
What has come over you? Anne colored and laughed a little as she dropped her book and looked

08:38:09.150 --> 08:38:15.490
dreamily out of the window, where big, fat red buds were bursting out on the creeper in response

08:38:15.490 --> 08:38:22.090
to the lure of the spring sunshine. I don't know. I don't want to talk as much, she said,

08:38:22.230 --> 08:38:26.870
denting her chin thoughtfully with her forefinger. It's nicer to think dear,

08:38:26.970 --> 08:38:32.390
pretty thoughts and keep them in one's heart like treasures. I don't like to have them laughed at

08:38:32.390 --> 08:38:38.650
or wondered over. And somehow, I don't want to use big words any more. It's almost a pity,

08:38:38.650 --> 08:38:42.790
isn't it, now that I'm really growing big enough to say them if I did want to.

08:38:43.470 --> 08:38:48.570
It's fun to be almost grown up in some ways, but it's not the kind of fun I expected, Marilla.

08:38:49.210 --> 08:38:55.550
There's so much to learn and do and think that there isn't time for big words. Besides,

08:38:55.750 --> 08:39:01.170
Miss Stacy says the short ones are much stronger and better. She makes us write all our essays

08:39:01.170 --> 08:39:07.490
as simply as possible. It was hard at first. I was so used to crowding in all the fine,

08:39:07.490 --> 08:39:13.090
big words I could think of, and I thought of any number of them. But I've got used to it now,

08:39:13.250 --> 08:39:19.870
and I see it so much better. What has become of your story club? I haven't heard you speak of it

08:39:19.870 --> 08:39:27.630
for a long time. The story club isn't in existence any longer. We had in time for it. And anyhow,

08:39:27.850 --> 08:39:33.510
I think we had got tired of it. It was silly to be writing about love and murder and elopements and

08:39:33.510 --> 08:39:39.490
mysteries. Miss Stacy sometimes has us write a story for training in composition, but she won't

08:39:39.490 --> 08:39:45.730
let us write anything but what might happen in Avonlea in our own lives, and she criticizes it

08:39:45.730 --> 08:39:51.930
very sharply, and makes us criticize our own, too. I never thought my compositions had so many

08:39:51.930 --> 08:39:57.790
faults until I began to look for them myself. I felt so ashamed I wanted to give up altogether,

08:39:57.790 --> 08:40:03.470
but Miss Stacy said I could learn to write well, if I only trained myself to be my own

08:40:03.470 --> 08:40:09.830
severest critic. And so I am trying to. You've only two more months before the entrance,

08:40:10.130 --> 08:40:17.770
said Marilla. Do you think you'll be able to get through? Anne shivered. I don't know. Sometimes

08:40:17.770 --> 08:40:23.910
I think I'll be all right, and then I get horribly afraid. We've studied hard, and Miss Stacy has

08:40:23.910 --> 08:40:29.790
drilled us thoroughly, but we mayn't get through for all that. We've each got a stumbling block.

08:40:30.470 --> 08:40:35.670
Mine is geometry, of course, and Jane's is Latin, and Ruby and Charlie's is algebra,

08:40:35.950 --> 08:40:41.870
and Josie's is arithmetic. Moody Spurgeon says he feels it is in his bones that he is going to fail

08:40:41.870 --> 08:40:47.770
in English history. Miss Stacy is going to give us examinations in June just as hard as we'll have

08:40:47.770 --> 08:40:54.170
the entrance and mark us just as strictly so we'll have some idea. I wish it was all over,

08:40:54.330 --> 08:41:01.010
Marilla. It haunts me. Sometimes I wake up in the night and wonder what I'll do if I don't pass.

08:41:01.710 --> 08:41:09.570
Why, go to school next year and try again, said Marilla, unconcernedly. Oh, I don't believe I'd

08:41:09.570 --> 08:41:17.010
have the heart for it. It would be such a disgrace to fail, especially if the others passed,

08:41:17.010 --> 08:41:21.530
and I get so nervous in an examination that I'm likely to make a mess of it.

08:41:22.010 --> 08:41:26.010
I wish I had nerves like Jane Andrews. Nothing rattles her.

08:41:27.330 --> 08:41:33.290
Anne sighed, and, dragging her eyes from the witcheries of the spring world, the beckoning

08:41:33.290 --> 08:41:39.090
day of breeze and blue and the green things upspringing in the garden, buried herself

08:41:39.090 --> 08:41:44.750
resolutely in her book. There would be other springs, but if she did not succeed in passing

08:41:44.750 --> 08:41:50.740
the entrance, Anne felt convinced that she would never recover sufficiently to enjoy them.

08:42:20.960 --> 08:42:24.140
THE PASS LIST IS OUT.

08:42:25.560 --> 08:42:32.200
With the end of June came the close of the term and the close of Miss Stacy's rule in Avonlea School.

08:42:33.320 --> 08:42:37.560
Anne and Diana walked home that evening feeling very sober indeed.

08:42:38.580 --> 08:42:45.480
Red eyes and damp handkerchiefs bore convincing testimony to the fact that Miss Stacy's farewell words

08:42:45.480 --> 08:42:52.740
must have been quite as touching as Mr. Phillips's had been under similar circumstances three years before.

08:42:53.900 --> 08:42:58.680
Diana looked back at the schoolhouse from the foot of the Spruce Hill and sighed deeply.

08:42:59.740 --> 08:43:04.480
It does seem as if it was the end of everything, doesn't it? she said dismally.

08:43:05.480 --> 08:43:12.340
You oughtn't to feel half as badly as I do, said Anne hunting vainly for a dry spot on her handkerchief.

08:43:12.340 --> 08:43:20.060
You'll be back again next winter, but I suppose I've left the dear old school forever, if I have good luck that is.

08:43:21.020 --> 08:43:27.340
It won't be a bit the same. Miss Stacy won't be there, nor you nor Jane nor Ruby probably.

08:43:28.120 --> 08:43:33.180
I shall have to sit all alone, for I couldn't bear to have another deskmate after you.

08:43:34.120 --> 08:43:40.100
Oh, we have had jolly times, haven't we Anne? It's dreadful to think they're all over.

08:43:40.860 --> 08:43:44.500
Two big tears rolled down by Diana's nose.

08:43:45.660 --> 08:43:49.500
If you would stop crying, I could, said Anne imploringly.

08:43:49.900 --> 08:43:54.600
Just as soon as I put away my hanky, I see you brimming up, and that starts me off again.

08:43:55.480 --> 08:44:00.100
As Mrs. Lind says, if you can't be cheerful, be as cheerful as you can.

08:44:01.280 --> 08:44:07.360
After all, I dare say I'll be back next year. This is one of the times I know I'm not going to pass.

08:44:07.760 --> 08:44:09.460
They're getting alarmingly frequent.

08:44:10.400 --> 08:44:14.060
Why, you came out splendidly in the exams Miss Stacy gave.

08:44:14.880 --> 08:44:17.340
Yes, but those exams didn't make me nervous.

08:44:17.820 --> 08:44:23.500
When I think of the real thing, you can't imagine what a horrid, cold, fluttery feeling comes round my heart.

08:44:23.980 --> 08:44:28.160
And then my number is 13, and Josie Pye says it's so unlucky.

08:44:28.720 --> 08:44:32.340
I am not superstitious, and I know it can make no difference.

08:44:32.820 --> 08:44:35.240
But still, I wish it wasn't 13.

08:44:36.320 --> 08:44:39.440
I do wish I was going in with you, said Diana.

08:44:39.440 --> 08:44:42.260
Wouldn't we have a perfectly elegant time?

08:44:42.840 --> 08:44:45.220
But I suppose you'll have to cram in the evenings.

08:44:46.480 --> 08:44:50.240
No, Miss Stacy has made us promise not to open a book at all.

08:44:50.840 --> 08:44:58.460
She says it would only tire and confuse us, and we are to go out walking, and not think about the exams at all, and go to bed early.

08:44:59.220 --> 08:45:01.940
It's good advice, but I expect it will be hard to follow.

08:45:02.540 --> 08:45:04.680
Good advice is apt to be, I think.

08:45:05.500 --> 08:45:11.660
Prissy Andrews told me that she sat up half the night every night of her entrance week, and crammed for dear life.

08:45:12.180 --> 08:45:15.700
And I had determined to sit up at least as long as she did.

08:45:16.560 --> 08:45:20.500
It was so kind of your Aunt Josephine to ask me to stay at Beechwood while I'm in town.

08:45:21.280 --> 08:45:23.440
You'll write to me while you're in, won't you?

08:45:24.320 --> 08:45:28.280
I'll write Tuesday night, and tell you how the first day goes, promised Anne.

08:45:29.080 --> 08:45:32.300
I'll be haunting the post office Wednesday, vowed Diana.

08:45:33.160 --> 08:45:41.460
Anne went to town the following Monday, and on Wednesday Diana haunted the post office, as agreed, and got her letter.

08:45:42.720 --> 08:45:49.780
Dearest Diana, wrote Anne, here it is Tuesday night, and I'm writing this in the library at Beechwood.

08:45:50.540 --> 08:45:56.300
Last night I was horribly lonesome all alone in my room, and wished so much you were with me.

08:45:56.540 --> 08:45:59.940
I couldn't cram, because I'd promised Miss Stacy not to.

08:45:59.940 --> 08:46:06.720
But it was as hard to keep from opening my history as it used to be to keep from reading a story before my lessons were learned.

08:46:07.760 --> 08:46:14.300
This morning Miss Stacy came for me, and we went to the Academy, calling for Jane and Ruby and Josie on our way.

08:46:15.100 --> 08:46:18.640
Ruby asked me to feel her hands, and they were as cold as ice.

08:46:19.440 --> 08:46:27.340
Josie said I looked as if I hadn't slept a wink, and she didn't believe I was strong enough to stand the grind of the teacher's course, even if I did get through.

08:46:28.080 --> 08:46:34.680
There are times and seasons even yet when I don't feel that I've made any great headway in learning to like Josie Pie.

08:46:35.860 --> 08:46:40.580
When we reached the Academy, there were scores of students there from all over the island.

08:46:41.160 --> 08:46:46.760
The first person we saw was Moody Spurgeon, sitting on the steps and muttering away to himself.

08:46:47.820 --> 08:46:55.200
Jane asked him what on earth he was doing, and he said he was repeating the multiplication table over and over to steady his nerves,

08:46:55.200 --> 08:47:02.560
and for pity's sake not to interrupt him, because if he stopped for a moment he got frightened and forgot everything he ever knew,

08:47:03.020 --> 08:47:07.260
but the multiplication table kept all his facts firmly in their proper place.

08:47:08.260 --> 08:47:12.440
When we were assigned to our rooms, Miss Stacy had to leave us.

08:47:13.080 --> 08:47:17.220
Jane and I sat together, and Jane was so composed that I envied her.

08:47:17.740 --> 08:47:22.440
No need of the multiplication table for good, steady, sensible Jane.

08:47:22.440 --> 08:47:28.980
I wondered if I looked as I felt, and if they could hear my heart thumping clear across the room.

08:47:29.700 --> 08:47:34.420
Then a man came in and began distributing the English examination sheets.

08:47:35.140 --> 08:47:40.340
My hands grew cold then, and my head fairly whirled around as I picked it up.

08:47:40.780 --> 08:47:48.960
Just one awful moment, Diana, I felt exactly as I did four years ago when I asked Marilla if I might stay at Green Gables.

08:47:48.960 --> 08:47:54.120
And then everything cleared up in my mind, and my heart began beating again.

08:47:54.720 --> 08:48:00.620
I forgot to say that it had stopped altogether, for I knew I could do something with that paper anyhow.

08:48:01.780 --> 08:48:06.520
At noon we went home for dinner, and then back again for history in the afternoon.

08:48:07.520 --> 08:48:12.060
The history was a pretty hard paper, and I got dreadfully mixed up in the dates.

08:48:12.700 --> 08:48:14.920
Still, I think I did fairly well today.

08:48:14.920 --> 08:48:26.100
But oh, Diana, tomorrow the geometry exam comes off, and when I think of it, it takes every bit of determination I possess to keep from opening my Euclid.

08:48:26.580 --> 08:48:32.140
If I thought the multiplication table would help me any, I would recite it from now till tomorrow morning.

08:48:33.020 --> 08:48:39.940
I went down to see the other girls this evening. On my way I met Moody Spurgeon wandering distractedly around.

08:48:39.940 --> 08:48:51.320
He said he knew he had failed in history, and he was born to be a disappointment to his parents, and he was going home on the morning train, and it would be easier to be a carpenter than a minister anyhow.

08:48:52.040 --> 08:48:57.600
I cheered him up and persuaded him to stay to the end, because it would be unfair to Miss Stacy if he didn't.

08:48:58.700 --> 08:49:05.560
Sometimes I have wished I was born a boy, but when I see Moody Spurgeon, I'm always glad I'm a girl and not his sister.

08:49:06.620 --> 08:49:14.320
Ruby was in hysterics when I reached their boarding-house. She had just discovered a fearful mistake she had made in her English paper.

08:49:15.180 --> 08:49:21.120
When she recovered, we went uptown and had an ice-cream. How we wished you had been with us!

08:49:22.020 --> 08:49:33.940
Oh, Diana, if only the geometry examination were over! But there, as Mrs. Lind would say, the sun will go on rising and setting, whether I fail in geometry or not.

08:49:33.940 --> 08:49:40.480
That is true, but not especially comforting. I think I'd rather it didn't go on if I failed.

08:49:41.660 --> 08:49:43.740
Yours, devotedly, Anne

08:49:44.800 --> 08:49:56.820
The geometry examination and all the others were over in due time, and Anne arrived home on Friday evening, rather tired, but with an air of chastened triumph about her.

08:49:57.440 --> 08:50:02.1000
Diana was over at Green Gables when she arrived, and they met as if they had been parted for years.

08:50:02.1000 --> 08:50:13.160
You old darling, it's perfectly splendid to see you back again. It seems like an age since you went to town, and oh, Anne, how did you get along?

08:50:14.220 --> 08:50:23.700
Pretty well, I think, and everything but the geometry. I don't know whether I passed in it or not, and I have a creepy-crawly pre-sentiment that I didn't.

08:50:24.540 --> 08:50:30.360
Oh, how good it is to be back! Green Gables is the dearest, loveliest spot in the world.

08:50:31.120 --> 08:50:32.720
How did the others do?

08:50:33.560 --> 08:50:41.680
The girls say they know they didn't pass, but I think they did pretty well. Josie says the geometry was so easy a child of ten could do it.

08:50:41.980 --> 08:50:51.100
Moody Spurgeon still thinks he failed in history, and Charlie says he failed in algebra. But we don't really know anything about it, and won't until the pass list is out.

08:50:51.760 --> 08:51:00.340
That won't be for a fortnight. Fancy living a fortnight in such suspense! I wish I could go to sleep and never wake up until it is over.

08:51:01.460 --> 08:51:10.100
Diana knew it would be useless to ask how Gilbert Blythe had fared, so she merely said, Oh, you'll pass all right. Don't worry.

08:51:11.100 --> 08:51:25.780
I'd rather not pass at all than not come up pretty well on the list, flashed Anne, by which she meant, and Diana knew she meant, that success would be incomplete and bitter if she did not come out ahead of Gilbert Blythe.

08:51:26.600 --> 08:51:39.480
With this end in view Anne had strained every nerve during the examinations. So had Gilbert. They had met and passed each other on the street a dozen times without any sign of recognition,

08:51:39.1000 --> 08:51:53.680
and every time Anne had held her head a little higher and wished a little more earnestly that she had made friends with Gilbert when he asked her, and vowed a little more determinedly to surpass him in the examination.

08:51:54.420 --> 08:52:13.960
She knew that all Avonlea, Jr. was wondering which would come out first. She even knew that Jimmy Glover and Ned Wright had a bet on the question, and that Josie Pye had said there was no doubt in the world that Gilbert would be first, and she felt that her humiliation would be unbearable if she failed.

08:52:13.960 --> 08:52:30.440
But she had another and nobler motive for wishing to do well. She wanted to pass high for the sake of Matthew and Marilla, especially Matthew. Matthew had declared to her his conviction that she would beat the whole island.

08:52:31.080 --> 08:52:48.120
That, Anne felt, was something it would be foolish to hope for, even in the wildest dreams. But she did hope fervently that she would be amongst the first ten at least, so that she might see Matthew's kindly brown eyes gleam with pride in her achievement.

08:52:49.020 --> 08:52:58.900
That, she felt, would be a sweet reward indeed for all her hard work and patient grubbing among unimaginative equations and conjugations.

08:52:59.700 --> 08:53:17.840
At the end of the fortnight, Anne took to haunting the post office also, in the distracted company of Jane, Ruby, and Josie, opening the Charlottetown dailies with shaking hands and cold, sink-way feelings as bad as any experienced during the entrance week.

08:53:18.680 --> 08:53:24.580
Charlie and Gilbert were not above doing this too, but Moody Spurgeon stayed resolutely away.

08:53:25.700 --> 08:53:35.460
I haven't got the grit to go there and look at a paper in cold blood, he told Anne. I'm just going to wait until somebody comes and tells me suddenly whether I've passed or not.

08:53:35.460 --> 08:53:48.780
When three weeks had gone by without the pass list appearing, Anne began to feel that she really couldn't stand in the strain much longer. Her appetite failed and her interest in avidly doings languished.

08:53:48.780 --> 08:54:08.720
Mrs. Lind wanted to know what else you could expect with a Tory Superintendent of Education at the Head of Affairs, and Matthew, noting Anne's paleness and indifference and the lagging steps that bore her home from the post office every afternoon, began seriously to wonder if he hadn't better vote grit at the next election.

08:54:09.580 --> 08:54:31.100
But one evening the news came. Anne was sitting at her open window, for the time forgetful of the woes of examinations and the cares of the world, as she drank in the beauty of the summer dusk, sweet scented with flower breaths from the garden below and sibilant and rustling from the stir of poplars.

08:54:31.100 --> 08:54:51.120
The eastern sky above the firs was flushed faintly pink from the reflection of the west, and Anne was wondering dreamily if the spirit of color looked like that, when she saw Diana come flying down through the firs, over the log bridge and up the slope with a fluttering newspaper in her hand.

08:54:51.840 --> 08:55:13.260
Anne sprang to her feet, knowing at once what that paper contained. The pass list was out. Her head whirled and her heart beat until it hurt her. She could not move a step. It seemed an hour to her before Diana came rushing along the hall and burst into the room without even knocking. So great was her excitement.

08:55:14.020 --> 08:55:24.280
Anne, you've passed! she cried. Passed the very first! You and Gilbert both, your ties! But your name is first! Oh, I'm so proud!

08:55:25.260 --> 08:55:41.520
Diana flung the paper on the table and herself on Anne's bed, utterly breathless and incapable of further speech. Anne lighted the lamp, over setting the match safe and using up half a dozen matches before her shaking hands could accomplish the task.

08:55:41.520 --> 08:55:53.420
Then she snatched up the paper. Yes, she had passed. There was her name at the very top of a list of two hundred. That moment was worth living for.

08:55:54.020 --> 08:56:05.140
You did just splendidly, Anne! puffed Diana, recovering sufficiently to sit up and speak. For Anne, starry-eyed and rapt, had not uttered a word.

08:56:05.860 --> 08:56:17.400
Father brought the paper home from Bright River not ten minutes ago. It came out on the afternoon train, you know, and won't be here till tomorrow by mail. And when I saw the pass list, I just rushed over like a wild thing.

08:56:17.400 --> 08:56:27.460
You've all passed, every one of you, Moody Spurgeon and all, although he's conditioned in history. Jane and Ruby did pretty well. They're halfway up, and so did Charlie.

08:56:28.360 --> 08:56:34.340
Josie just scraped through with three marks to spare, but you'll see she'll put on as many airs as if she'd led.

08:56:35.120 --> 08:56:50.020
Won't Miss Stacy be delighted? Oh, Anne, what does it feel like to see your name at the head of a pass list like that? If it were me, I'd know I'd go crazy with joy. I am pretty near crazy as it is, but you're as calm and cool as a spring evening.

08:56:51.060 --> 08:57:00.900
I'm just dazzled inside, said Anne. I want to say a hundred things, and I can't find words to say them in. I never dreamed of this.

08:57:01.440 --> 08:57:12.780
Yes, I did too, just once. I let myself think once. What if I should come out first? Quakingly, you know, for it seemed so vain and presumptuous to think I could lead the island.

08:57:13.380 --> 08:57:20.380
Excuse me a minute, Diana. I must run right out to the field to tell Matthew. Then we'll go up the road and tell the good news to the others.

08:57:21.220 --> 08:57:30.420
They hurried to the hayfield below the barn, where Matthew was coiling hay, and as luck would have it, Mrs. Lynde was talking to Marilla at the lane fence.

08:57:31.360 --> 08:57:39.360
Oh, Matthew! exclaimed Anne. I've passed, and I'm first, or one of the first. I'm not vain, but I'm thankful.

08:57:40.220 --> 08:57:48.920
Well now, I always said it, said Matthew, gazing at the pass list, delightedly. I knew you could beat them all easy.

08:57:49.920 --> 08:57:59.500
You've done pretty well, I must say, Anne, said Marilla, trying to hide her extreme pride in Anne from Mrs. Rachel's critical eye.

08:57:59.500 --> 08:58:11.460
But that good soul said heartedly, I just guess she has done well, and far be it for me to be backward in saying it. You're a credit to your friends, Anne, that's what, and we're all proud of you.

08:58:12.100 --> 08:58:30.180
That night Anne, who had wound up the delightful evening with a serious little talk with Mrs. Allen at the manse, knelt sweetly by her open window in a great sheen of moonlight, and murmured a prayer of gratitude and aspiration that came straight from her heart.

08:58:30.180 --> 08:58:44.440
There was in it thankfulness for the past and reverent petition for the future, and when she slept on her white pillow, her dreams were as fair and bright and beautiful as maidenhood might desire.

08:59:13.800 --> 08:59:19.160
The Hotel Concert

08:59:20.420 --> 08:59:26.880
Put on your white organdy, by all means, Anne, advised Diana decidedly.

08:59:27.280 --> 08:59:30.020
They were together in the east gable chamber.

08:59:30.860 --> 08:59:38.300
Outside it was only twilight, a lovely yellowish-green twilight, with a clear blue cloudless sky.

08:59:38.900 --> 08:59:47.440
A big round moon, slowly deepening from her pallid luster into burnished silver, hung over the haunted wood.

08:59:48.400 --> 08:59:58.060
The air was full of sweet summer sounds, sleepy birds twittering, freakish breezes, far-away voices and laughter.

08:59:58.900 --> 09:00:06.800
But in Anne's room the blind was drawn and the lamp lighted, for an important toilet was being made.

09:00:07.500 --> 09:00:13.460
The east gable was a very different place from what it had been on that night four years before,

09:00:13.960 --> 09:00:20.680
when Anne had felt its bareness penetrate to the marrow of her spirit with its inhospitable chill.

09:00:21.640 --> 09:00:31.400
Changes had crept in, Marilla conniving at them resignedly, until it was as sweet and dainty a nest as a young girl could desire.

09:00:32.040 --> 09:00:40.620
The velvet carpet with the pink roses and the pink silk curtains of Anne's early visions had certainly never materialized,

09:00:40.960 --> 09:00:46.600
but her dreams had kept pace with her growth, and it is not probable she lamented them.

09:00:47.440 --> 09:00:57.660
The floor was covered with a pretty matting, and the curtains that softened the high window and fluttered in the vagrant breezes were of pale green art muslin.

09:00:58.300 --> 09:01:10.280
The walls, hung not with gold and silver brocade tapestry, but with a dainty apple blossom paper, were adorned with a few good pictures given Anne by Mrs. Allen.

09:01:11.300 --> 09:01:20.580
Miss Stacy's photograph occupied the place of honor, and Anne made a sentimental point of keeping fresh flowers on the bracket under it.

09:01:21.220 --> 09:01:27.680
Tonight a spike of white lilies faintly perfumed the room like the dream of a fragrance.

09:01:28.440 --> 09:01:35.080
There was no mahogany furniture, but there was a white painted bookcase filled with books,

09:01:35.660 --> 09:01:40.880
a cushioned wicker rocker, a toilet table befrilled with white muslin,

09:01:41.420 --> 09:01:53.400
a quaint, gilt-framed mirror with chubby pink cupids and purple grapes painted over its archtop that used to hang in the spare room, and a low, white bed.

09:01:54.840 --> 09:01:58.220
Anne was dressing for a concert at the White Sands Hotel.

09:01:58.960 --> 09:02:09.200
The guests had got it up in aid of the Charlottetown Hospital, and had hunted out all the available amateur talent in the surrounding districts to help it along.

09:02:09.840 --> 09:02:17.080
Bertha Sampson and Pearl Clay of the White Sands Baptist Choir had been asked to sing a duet.

09:02:17.400 --> 09:02:20.900
Milton Clarke of Newbridge was to give a violin solo.

09:02:21.800 --> 09:02:26.080
Winnie Adella Blair of Carmody was to sing a Scotch ballad.

09:02:26.600 --> 09:02:32.700
And Laura Spencer of Spencervale and Anne Shirley of Avonlea were to recite.

09:02:33.740 --> 09:02:42.1000
As Anne would have said at one time, it was an epoch in her life, and she was deliciously a thrill with the excitement of it.

09:02:43.700 --> 09:02:49.820
Matthew was in the seventh heaven of gratified pride over the honor conferred on his Anne,

09:02:50.260 --> 09:02:55.780
and Marilla was not far behind, although she would have died rather than admit it,

09:02:55.780 --> 09:03:05.120
and said she didn't think it was very proper for a lot of young folks to be gadding over to the hotel without any responsible person with them.

09:03:06.180 --> 09:03:12.680
Anne and Diana were to drive over with Jane Andrews and her brother Billy in their double-seated buggy,

09:03:12.1000 --> 09:03:16.540
and several other Avonlea girls and boys were going too.

09:03:17.080 --> 09:03:24.920
There was a party of visitors expected out from town, and after the concert a supper was to be given to the performers.

09:03:25.860 --> 09:03:30.660
Do you really think the organdy will be best? queried Anne anxiously.

09:03:31.340 --> 09:03:36.500
I don't think it's as pretty as my blue-flowered muslin, and it certainly isn't so fashionable.

09:03:37.560 --> 09:03:40.980
But it suits you ever so much better, said Diana.

09:03:41.520 --> 09:03:44.040
It's so soft and frilly and clinging.

09:03:44.680 --> 09:03:50.900
The muslin is stiff and makes you look too dressed up, but the organdy seems as if it grew on you.

09:03:52.080 --> 09:03:54.140
Anne sighed and yielded.

09:03:54.600 --> 09:04:03.580
Diana was beginning to have a reputation for notable taste in dressing, and her advice on such subjects was much sought after.

09:04:04.440 --> 09:04:11.160
She was looking very pretty herself on this particular night in a dress of the lovely wild rose pink,

09:04:11.620 --> 09:04:19.880
from which Anne was forever debarred, but she was not to take any part in the concert, so her appearance was of minor importance.

09:04:20.460 --> 09:04:31.160
All her pains were bestowed upon Anne, who, she vowed, must, for the credit of Avonlea, be dressed and combed and adorned to the Queen's taste.

09:04:32.440 --> 09:04:34.040
Pull out that frill a little more.

09:04:34.380 --> 09:04:37.140
So, here, let me tie your sash.

09:04:37.600 --> 09:04:38.720
Now for your slippers.

09:04:39.280 --> 09:04:44.520
I'm going to braid your hair in two thick braids, and tie them halfway up with big white bows.

09:04:45.100 --> 09:04:47.920
No, don't pull out a single curl over your forehead.

09:04:48.380 --> 09:04:49.820
Just have the soft part.

09:04:50.640 --> 09:04:57.880
There is no way you'd do your hair suits you so well, Anne, and Mrs. Allen says you look like a Madonna when you part it so.

09:04:58.760 --> 09:05:02.260
I shall fasten this little white house rose just behind your ear.

09:05:02.780 --> 09:05:05.860
There was just one on my bush, and I saved it for you.

09:05:06.1000 --> 09:05:09.120
Shall I put my pearl beads on?

09:05:09.320 --> 09:05:09.960
asked Anne.

09:05:10.560 --> 09:05:15.700
Matthew brought me a string from town last week, and I know he'd like to see them on me.

09:05:16.600 --> 09:05:28.1000
Diana pursed up her lips, put her black head on one side critically, and finally pronounced in favor of the beads, which were thereupon tied around Anne's slim, milk-white throat.

09:05:29.840 --> 09:05:36.080
There's something so stylish about you, Anne, said Diana, with unenvious admiration.

09:05:36.780 --> 09:05:38.860
You hold your head with such an air.

09:05:39.500 --> 09:05:41.140
I suppose it's your figure.

09:05:41.500 --> 09:05:42.840
I am just a dumpling.

09:05:43.460 --> 09:05:46.220
I've always been afraid of it, and now I know it is so.

09:05:47.140 --> 09:05:50.820
Well, I suppose I shall just have to resign myself to it.

09:05:51.520 --> 09:05:58.700
But you have such dimples, said Anne, smiling affectionately into the pretty vivacious face so near her own.

09:05:59.280 --> 09:06:01.920
Lovely dimples, like little dents and cream.

09:06:02.460 --> 09:06:04.600
I have given up all hope of dimples.

09:06:05.100 --> 09:06:07.180
My dimple dream will never come true.

09:06:07.180 --> 09:06:10.660
But so many of my dreams have that I mustn't complain.

09:06:11.400 --> 09:06:12.880
Am I all ready now?

09:06:13.640 --> 09:06:25.040
All ready, assured Diana, as Marilla appeared in the doorway, a gaunt figure with grayer hair than of your, and no fewer angles, but with a much softer face.

09:06:25.1000 --> 09:06:28.780
Come right in and look at our elocutionist, Marilla.

09:06:29.320 --> 09:06:30.560
Doesn't she look lovely?

09:06:31.460 --> 09:06:35.360
Marilla emitted a sound between a sniff and a grunt.

09:06:35.940 --> 09:06:37.740
She looks neat and proper.

09:06:38.120 --> 09:06:40.160
I like that way of fixing her hair.

09:06:40.680 --> 09:06:45.040
But I expect she'll ruin that dress driving over there in the dust and do with it.

09:06:45.380 --> 09:06:48.360
And it looks most too thin for these damp nights.

09:06:49.020 --> 09:06:54.820
Organdy's the most unserviceable stuff in the world anyhow, and I told Matthew so when he got it.

09:06:55.060 --> 09:06:57.1000
But there is no use in saying anything to Matthew nowadays.

09:06:58.580 --> 09:07:07.300
Time was when he would take my advice, but now he just buys things for Anne regardless, and the clerks at Carmody know they can palm anything off on him.

09:07:07.820 --> 09:07:13.320
Just let them tell him a thing is pretty and fashionable, and Matthew plunks his money down for it.

09:07:13.840 --> 09:07:18.040
Mind you, keep your skirt clear of the wheel, Anne, and put your warm jacket on.

09:07:18.940 --> 09:07:27.860
Then Marilla stalked downstairs, thinking proudly how sweet Anne looked with that one moonbeam from the forehead to the crown,

09:07:28.440 --> 09:07:33.280
and regretting that she could not go to the concert herself to hear her girl recite.

09:07:34.300 --> 09:07:38.380
I wonder if it is too damp for my dress, said Anne anxiously.

09:07:38.960 --> 09:07:42.540
Not a bit of it, said Diana, pulling up the window blind.

09:07:42.1000 --> 09:07:45.820
It's a perfect night, and there won't be any dew.

09:07:46.340 --> 09:07:47.300
Look at the moonlight.

09:07:48.140 --> 09:07:53.960
I'm so glad my window looks east into the sun rising, said Anne going over to Diana.

09:07:54.720 --> 09:08:01.820
It's so splendid to see the morning coming up over those long hills and glowing through those sharp fur tops.

09:08:02.240 --> 09:08:09.060
It's new every morning, and I feel as if I washed my very soul in that bath of earliest sunshine.

09:08:10.240 --> 09:08:13.860
Oh, Diana, I love this little room so dearly.

09:08:13.860 --> 09:08:17.780
I don't know how I'll get along without it when I go to town next month.

09:08:18.920 --> 09:08:22.140
Don't speak of your going away tonight, begged Diana.

09:08:22.740 --> 09:08:25.300
I don't want to think of it. It makes me so miserable.

09:08:25.880 --> 09:08:28.060
And I do want to have a good time this evening.

09:08:28.720 --> 09:08:31.380
What are you going to recite, Anne? And are you nervous?

09:08:32.440 --> 09:08:36.480
Not a bit. I've recited so often in public I don't mind at all now.

09:08:36.1000 --> 09:08:39.440
I've decided to give the maidens vow.

09:08:39.1000 --> 09:08:41.400
It's so pathetic.

09:08:42.040 --> 09:08:47.920
Lara Spencer's going to give a comic recitation, but I'd rather make people cry than laugh.

09:08:48.860 --> 09:08:50.880
Will you recite if they encore you?

09:08:51.520 --> 09:08:57.840
They won't dream of encoring me, scoffed Anne, who is not without her own secret hopes that they would,

09:08:58.320 --> 09:09:03.160
and already visioned herself telling Matthew all about it at the next morning's breakfast table.

09:09:04.140 --> 09:09:07.420
There are Billy and Jane now. I hear the wheels. Come on.

09:09:08.620 --> 09:09:14.840
Billy Andrews insisted that Anne should ride on the front seat with him, so she unwillingly climbed up.

09:09:15.400 --> 09:09:21.500
She would have much preferred to sit back with the girls, or she could have laughed and chattered to her heart's content.

09:09:22.300 --> 09:09:25.220
There is not much of either laughter or chatter in Billy.

09:09:25.880 --> 09:09:34.020
He was a big, fat, stolid youth of twenty, with a round, expressionless face and a painful lack of conversational gifts.

09:09:34.580 --> 09:09:43.960
But he admired Anne immensely, and was puffed up with pride over the prospect of driving to White Sands with that slim, upright figure beside him.

09:09:44.400 --> 09:09:51.280
Anne, by dint of talking over her shoulder to the girls, and occasionally passing a sop of civility to Billy,

09:09:51.800 --> 09:09:59.280
who grinned and chuckled and never could think of any reply until it was too late, contrived to enjoy the drive in spite of all.

09:09:59.780 --> 09:10:10.320
It was a night for enjoyment. The road was full of buggies, all bound for the hotel, and laughter, silver clear, echoed and re-echoed along it.

09:10:10.700 --> 09:10:14.740
When they reached the hotel, it was a blaze of light from top to bottom.

09:10:15.560 --> 09:10:21.780
They were met by the ladies of the concert committee, one of whom took Anne off to the performers dressing room,

09:10:21.780 --> 09:10:30.860
which was filled with the members of a Charlottetown symphony club, among whom Anne felt suddenly shy and frightened and contrived.

09:10:31.620 --> 09:10:41.120
Her dress, which, in the East Gable, had seemed so dainty and pretty, now seemed simple and plain, too simple and plain, she thought,

09:10:41.640 --> 09:10:45.760
among all the silks and laces that glistened and rustled around her.

09:10:46.270 --> 09:10:51.060
What were her pearl beads compared to the diamonds of the big, handsome lady near her?

09:10:51.600 --> 09:10:58.200
And how poor her one wee white rose must look beside all the hothouse flowers the others wore!

09:10:59.220 --> 09:11:07.880
Anne laid her hat and jacket away and shrank miserably into a corner. She wished herself back in the white room at Green Gables.

09:11:08.840 --> 09:11:15.160
It was still worse on the platform of the big concert hall of the hotel, where she presently found herself.

09:11:15.680 --> 09:11:21.060
The electric lights dazzled her eyes. The perfume and home bewildered her.

09:11:21.760 --> 09:11:28.980
She wished she were sitting down in the audience with Diana and Jane, who seemed to be having a splendid time away at the back.

09:11:29.600 --> 09:11:37.220
She was wedged in between a stout lady in pink silk and a tall, scornful-looking girl in a white lace dress.

09:11:37.720 --> 09:11:43.800
The stout lady occasionally turned her head squarely around and surveyed Anne through her eyeglasses,

09:11:44.240 --> 09:11:50.380
until Anne, acutely sensitive of being so scrutinized, felt that she must scream aloud.

09:11:50.980 --> 09:12:00.080
And the white lace girl kept talking audibly to her next-door neighbor about the country bumpkins and rustic bells in the audience,

09:12:00.1000 --> 09:12:06.420
languidly anticipating such fun from the displays of local talent on the program.

09:12:07.060 --> 09:12:12.140
Anne believed that she would hate that white lace girl to the end of life.

09:12:12.800 --> 09:12:19.740
Unfortunately for Anne, a professional elocutionist was staying at the hotel and had consented to recite.

09:12:20.480 --> 09:12:31.400
She was a lithe, dark-eyed woman in a wonderful gown of shimmering gray stuff like woven moonbeams with gems on her neck and in her dark hair.

09:12:32.020 --> 09:12:36.220
She had a marvelously flexible voice and wonderful power of expression.

09:12:36.980 --> 09:12:39.420
The audience went wild over her selection.

09:12:40.700 --> 09:12:47.240
Anne, forgetting all about herself and her troubles for the time, listened with rapt and shining eyes.

09:12:47.620 --> 09:12:51.980
But when the recitation ended, she suddenly put her hands over her face.

09:12:52.520 --> 09:12:55.520
She could never get up and recite after that, never!

09:12:56.120 --> 09:12:57.780
Had she ever thought she could recite?

09:12:58.420 --> 09:13:01.040
Oh, if she were only back at Green Gables!

09:13:01.800 --> 09:13:05.180
At this un-propitious moment, her name was called.

09:13:06.060 --> 09:13:12.860
Somehow Anne, who did not notice the rather guilty little start of surprise the white lace girl gave

09:13:12.860 --> 09:13:17.620
and would not have understood the subtle compliment implied therein if she had,

09:13:17.980 --> 09:13:21.420
got on her feet and moved, dizzily, out to the front.

09:13:22.060 --> 09:13:29.700
She was so pale that Diana and Jane, down in the audience, clasped each other's hands in nervous sympathy.

09:13:31.220 --> 09:13:34.960
Anne was the victim of an overwhelming attack of stage fright.

09:13:35.880 --> 09:13:41.420
Often as she had recited in public, she had never before faced such an audience as this,

09:13:41.920 --> 09:13:45.280
and the sight of it paralyzed her energies completely.

09:13:46.180 --> 09:13:50.760
Everything was so strange, so brilliant, so bewildering.

09:13:51.160 --> 09:13:59.440
The rows of ladies in evening dress, the critical faces, the whole atmosphere of wealth and culture about her.

09:14:00.200 --> 09:14:04.200
Very different was this from the plain benches at the debating club,

09:14:04.720 --> 09:14:08.240
filled with the homely, sympathetic faces of friends and neighbors.

09:14:08.900 --> 09:14:12.440
These people, she thought, would be merciless critics.

09:14:13.220 --> 09:14:19.480
Perhaps, like the white lace girl, they anticipated amusement from her rustic efforts.

09:14:20.030 --> 09:14:23.700
She felt hopelessly, helplessly ashamed and miserable.

09:14:24.520 --> 09:14:29.1000
Her knees trembled, her heart fluttered, a horrible faintness came over her.

09:14:30.520 --> 09:14:35.980
Not a word could she utter, and the next moment she would have fled from the platform,

09:14:36.460 --> 09:14:42.560
despite the humiliation which, she felt, must ever after be her portion if she did so.

09:14:43.180 --> 09:14:48.500
But suddenly, as her dilated, frightened eyes gazed out over the audience,

09:14:48.810 --> 09:14:56.200
she saw Gilbert Blythe away at the back of the room, bending forward with a smile on his face,

09:14:56.660 --> 09:15:01.700
a smile which seemed to Anne at once triumphant and taunting.

09:15:02.600 --> 09:15:05.140
In reality, it was nothing of the kind.

09:15:05.700 --> 09:15:10.140
Gilbert was merely smiling with appreciation of the whole affair in general,

09:15:10.640 --> 09:15:16.280
and of the effect produced by Anne's slender white form and spiritual face

09:15:16.620 --> 09:15:19.460
against a background of palms in particular.

09:15:20.600 --> 09:15:24.480
Josie Pye, whom he had driven over, sat beside him,

09:15:24.880 --> 09:15:27.860
and her face certainly was both triumphant and taunting.

09:15:28.580 --> 09:15:32.400
But Anne did not see Josie. I would not have cared if she had.

09:15:33.160 --> 09:15:36.600
She drew a long breath and flung her head up proudly,

09:15:37.300 --> 09:15:41.220
courage and determination tingling over her like an electric shock.

09:15:41.720 --> 09:15:44.680
She would not fail before Gilbert Blythe.

09:15:45.280 --> 09:15:48.940
He should never be able to laugh at her, never, never.

09:15:49.600 --> 09:15:54.100
Her fright and nervousness vanished, and she began her recitation,

09:15:54.560 --> 09:15:59.160
her clear, sweet voice reaching to the farthest corner of the room,

09:15:59.420 --> 09:16:01.460
without a tremor or a break.

09:16:02.300 --> 09:16:04.820
Self-possession was fully restored to her,

09:16:05.160 --> 09:16:08.600
and in the reaction from that horrible moment of powerlessness,

09:16:09.220 --> 09:16:12.080
she recited as she had never done before.

09:16:12.720 --> 09:16:16.760
When she finished, there were bursts of honest applause.

09:16:17.620 --> 09:16:22.160
Anne, stepping back to her seat, blushing with shyness and delight,

09:16:22.800 --> 09:16:28.440
found her hand vigorously clasped and shaken by the stout lady in pink silk.

09:16:29.360 --> 09:16:32.320
My dear, you did splendidly, she puffed.

09:16:32.540 --> 09:16:35.560
I've been crying like a baby. Actually, I have.

09:16:36.080 --> 09:16:38.960
There, they're encoring you. They're bound to have you back.

09:16:39.560 --> 09:16:42.740
Oh, I can't go, said Anne confusedly.

09:16:42.980 --> 09:16:45.660
But yet I must, or Matthew will be disappointed.

09:16:46.160 --> 09:16:47.760
He said they would encore me.

09:16:48.580 --> 09:16:52.440
Then don't disappoint Matthew, said the pink lady, laughing.

09:16:53.660 --> 09:16:58.440
Smiling, blushing, limpid-eyed, Anne tripped back

09:16:58.440 --> 09:17:00.900
and gave a quaint, funny little selection

09:17:00.900 --> 09:17:03.960
that captivated her audience still further.

09:17:05.040 --> 09:17:08.120
The rest of the evening was quite a little triumph for her.

09:17:09.120 --> 09:17:12.440
When the concert was over, the stout pink lady,

09:17:12.720 --> 09:17:15.100
who was the wife of an American millionaire,

09:17:15.640 --> 09:17:18.640
took her under her wing and introduced her to everybody,

09:17:19.200 --> 09:17:21.260
and everybody was very nice to her.

09:17:22.080 --> 09:17:24.960
The professional elocutionist, Mrs. Evans,

09:17:25.440 --> 09:17:29.600
came and chatted with her, telling her that she had a charming voice

09:17:29.600 --> 09:17:32.420
and interpreted her selections beautifully.

09:17:33.260 --> 09:17:36.820
Even the white lace girl paid her a languid little compliment.

09:17:37.460 --> 09:17:41.820
They had supper in the big, beautifully decorated dining room.

09:17:42.420 --> 09:17:45.340
Diana and Jane were invited to partake of this,

09:17:45.520 --> 09:17:47.760
also, since they had come with Anne.

09:17:48.240 --> 09:17:50.400
But Billy was nowhere to be found,

09:17:50.820 --> 09:17:54.380
having decamped in mortal fear of some such invitation.

09:17:55.320 --> 09:17:58.040
He was in waiting for them, with the team, however,

09:17:58.300 --> 09:18:01.060
when it was all over, and the three girls

09:18:01.060 --> 09:18:05.880
came merrily out into the calm, white, moonshine radiance.

09:18:06.520 --> 09:18:10.520
Anne breathed deeply and looked into the clear sky

09:18:10.520 --> 09:18:13.300
beyond the dark boughs of the firs.

09:18:13.840 --> 09:18:18.540
Oh, it was good to be out again in the purity and silence of the night.

09:18:19.200 --> 09:18:22.780
How great and still and wonderful everything was,

09:18:23.160 --> 09:18:25.820
with the murmur of the sea sounding through it

09:18:25.820 --> 09:18:29.520
and the darkling cliffs beyond, like grim giants

09:18:29.520 --> 09:18:32.560
guarding enchanted coasts.

09:18:32.900 --> 09:18:35.440
Hasn't it been a perfectly splendid time?

09:18:36.080 --> 09:18:37.820
sighed Jane as they drove away.

09:18:38.300 --> 09:18:40.660
I just wish I was a rich American

09:18:40.660 --> 09:18:43.240
and could spend my summer at a hotel

09:18:43.240 --> 09:18:46.160
and wear jewels and low-necked dresses

09:18:46.160 --> 09:18:49.900
and have ice cream and chicken salad every blessed day.

09:18:50.560 --> 09:18:53.900
I'm sure it would be ever so much more fun than teaching school.

09:18:54.820 --> 09:18:57.400
Anne, your recitation was simply great,

09:18:57.740 --> 09:19:00.260
although I thought at first you were never going to begin.

09:19:00.820 --> 09:19:03.140
I think it was better than Mrs. Evans's.

09:19:03.780 --> 09:19:06.320
Oh, no, don't say things like that, Jane,

09:19:06.620 --> 09:19:09.580
said Anne quickly, because it sounds silly.

09:19:09.1000 --> 09:19:12.560
It couldn't be better than Mrs. Evans's, you know,

09:19:12.820 --> 09:19:16.120
for she is a professional and I am only a schoolgirl

09:19:16.120 --> 09:19:18.120
with a little knack of reciting.

09:19:18.700 --> 09:19:22.220
I'm quite satisfied if the people just liked mine pretty well.

09:19:23.280 --> 09:19:26.300
I have a compliment for you, Anne, said Diana.

09:19:26.700 --> 09:19:28.620
At least I think it must be a compliment

09:19:28.620 --> 09:19:30.900
because of the tone he said it in.

09:19:31.460 --> 09:19:32.820
Part of it was, anyhow.

09:19:33.340 --> 09:19:36.180
There was an American sitting behind Jane and me,

09:19:36.380 --> 09:19:40.480
such a romantic-looking man with cold black hair and eyes.

09:19:41.100 --> 09:19:43.700
Josie Pye says he is a distinguished artist

09:19:43.700 --> 09:19:46.540
and that her mother's cousin in Boston is married

09:19:46.540 --> 09:19:48.680
to a man that used to go to school with him.

09:19:49.600 --> 09:19:52.060
Well, we heard him say, didn't we, Jane?

09:19:52.660 --> 09:19:57.080
Who is that girl on the platform with the splendid Titian hair?

09:19:57.560 --> 09:19:59.960
She has a face I should like to paint.

09:20:00.600 --> 09:20:04.040
There now, Anne, but what does Titian hair mean?

09:20:04.780 --> 09:20:09.280
Being interpreted, it means plain red, I guess, laughed Anne.

09:20:09.820 --> 09:20:11.680
Titian was a very famous artist

09:20:11.680 --> 09:20:13.600
who liked to paint red-haired women.

09:20:14.780 --> 09:20:18.240
Did you see all the diamonds those ladies wore, side Jane?

09:20:18.740 --> 09:20:20.240
They were simply dazzling.

09:20:20.780 --> 09:20:22.840
Wouldn't you just love to be rich, girls?

09:20:23.460 --> 09:20:26.340
We are rich, said Anne staunchly.

09:20:26.880 --> 09:20:29.400
Why, we have sixteen years to our credit

09:20:29.400 --> 09:20:30.880
and we're happy as queens,

09:20:31.360 --> 09:20:34.260
and we've all got imaginations, more or less.

09:20:34.840 --> 09:20:36.360
Look at that sea, girls.

09:20:36.820 --> 09:20:40.1000
All silver and shadow and vision of things not seen.

09:20:41.700 --> 09:20:44.480
We couldn't enjoy its loveliness any more

09:20:44.480 --> 09:20:48.220
if we had millions of dollars and ropes of diamonds.

09:20:48.800 --> 09:20:52.620
You wouldn't change into any of those women if you could.

09:20:53.340 --> 09:20:55.520
Would you want to be that white-laced girl

09:20:55.520 --> 09:20:57.840
and wear a sour look all your life

09:20:57.840 --> 09:21:00.780
as if you'd been born turning up your nose at the world?

09:21:01.300 --> 09:21:04.560
Or the pink lady, kind and nice as she is,

09:21:04.860 --> 09:21:08.080
so stout and short that you'd really know figure at all?

09:21:08.400 --> 09:21:12.760
Or even Mrs. Evans, with that sad, sad look in her eyes.

09:21:13.260 --> 09:21:15.900
She must have been dreadfully unhappy sometime

09:21:15.900 --> 09:21:17.360
to have such a look.

09:21:17.960 --> 09:21:20.560
You know you wouldn't, Jane Andrews.

09:21:20.940 --> 09:21:25.200
I don't know exactly, said Jane unconvinced.

09:21:25.200 --> 09:21:28.680
I think diamonds would comfort a person for a good deal.

09:21:29.780 --> 09:21:32.760
Well, I don't want to be anyone but myself

09:21:32.760 --> 09:21:36.600
even if I go uncomforted by diamonds all my life,

09:21:36.940 --> 09:21:37.720
declared Anne.

09:21:38.420 --> 09:21:41.360
I'm quite content to be Anne of Green Gables

09:21:41.360 --> 09:21:43.760
with my string of pearl beads.

09:21:44.520 --> 09:21:47.760
I know Matthew gave me as much love with them as ever

09:21:47.760 --> 09:21:50.320
went into Madame the Pink Lady's jewels.

09:22:20.500 --> 09:22:22.400
A Queen's Girl.

09:22:24.200 --> 09:22:33.740
The next three weeks were busy ones at Green Gables, for Anne was getting ready to go to Queen's, and there was much sewing to be done, and many things to be talked over and arranged.

09:22:34.520 --> 09:22:43.600
Anne's outfit was ample and pretty, for Matthew saw to that, and Marilla for once made no objections whatever to any thing he purchased or suggested.

09:22:43.600 --> 09:22:50.680
More, one evening she went up to the East Gable with her arms full of a delicate pale green material.

09:23:15.640 --> 09:23:25.760
I got Mrs. Allan to help me pick it in town last week, and we'll get Emily Gillis to make it for you. Emily has got taste, and her fits aren't to be equaled.

09:23:25.760 --> 09:23:36.400
Oh, Marilla, it's just lovely, said Anne. Thank you so much. I don't believe you ought to be so kind to me. It's making it harder every day for me to go away.

09:23:38.020 --> 09:23:51.520
The green dress was made up with as many tucks and frills and shirrings as Emily's taste permitted. Anne put it on one evening for Matthew's and Marilla's benefit, and recited the maiden's vow for them in the kitchen.

09:23:52.800 --> 09:24:16.140
As Marilla watched the bright animated face and graceful motions, her thoughts went back to the evening Anne had arrived at Green Gables, and memory recalled a vivid picture of the odd frightened child in her preposterous yellowish-brown wincey dress, the heartbreak looking out of her tearful eyes. Something in the memory brought tears to Marilla's own eyes.

09:24:17.120 --> 09:24:28.700
I declare my recitation has made you cry, Marilla," said Anne, gaily stooping over Marilla's chair to drop a butterfly kiss on that lady's cheek. Now I call that a positive triumph.

09:24:30.080 --> 09:24:38.240
No, I wasn't crying over your peace, said Marilla, who would have scorned to be betrayed into such weakness by any poetry stuff.

09:24:38.860 --> 09:24:47.180
I just couldn't help thinking of the little girl you used to be, Anne, and I was wishing you could have stayed a little girl, even with all your queer ways.

09:24:47.180 --> 09:25:02.180
You're so grown up now, and you're going away, and you look so tall and stylish and so, so different altogether in that dress, as if you didn't belong in Avonlea at all, and I just got lonesome thinking it all over.

09:25:03.640 --> 09:25:04.240
Marilla!

09:25:05.320 --> 09:25:14.520
Anne sat down on Marilla's gingham lap, took Marilla's lined face between her hands, and looked gravely and tenderly into Marilla's eyes.

09:25:15.580 --> 09:25:30.260
I'm not a bit changed, not really. I'm only just pruned down and branched out. The real me, back here, is just the same. It won't make a bit of difference where I go or how much I change outwardly.

09:25:30.720 --> 09:25:40.120
At heart I shall always be your little Anne, who will love you and Matthew and dear Green Gables more and better every day of her life.

09:25:41.060 --> 09:25:47.800
Anne laid her fresh young cheek against Marilla's faded one, and reached out a hand to pat Matthew's shoulder.

09:25:49.040 --> 09:26:06.300
Marilla would have given much just then to have possessed Anne's power of putting her feelings into words, but nature and habit had willed it otherwise, and she could only put her arms close about her girl and hold her tenderly to her heart, wishing that she need never let her go.

09:26:07.540 --> 09:26:20.280
Matthew, with a suspicious moisture in his eyes, got up and went out of doors. Under the stars of the blue summer night he walked agitatedly across the yard to the gate under the poplars.

09:26:21.540 --> 09:26:36.380
Well, now I guess she ain't been much spoiled, he muttered proudly. I guess my putting in my oar occasional never did much harm after all. She's smart and pretty and loving too, which is better than all the rest.

09:26:37.020 --> 09:26:50.400
She's been a blessing to us, and there never was a luckier mistake than what Mrs. Spencer made, if it was luck. I don't believe it was any such thing. It was Providence, because the Almighty saw we needed her, I reckon.

09:27:07.720 --> 09:27:32.440
But when Anne had gone, Diana dried her tears and went to a beach picnic at White Sands, with some of her Carmody cousins, where she contrived to enjoy herself tolerably well, while Marilla plunged fiercely into unnecessary work and kept at it all day long with the bitterest kind of heartache, the ache that burns and gnaws, and cannot wash itself away in ready tears.

09:27:33.460 --> 09:27:59.180
But that night, when Marilla went to bed, acutely and miserably conscious that the little gable-room at the end of the hall was untenanted by any vivid young life, and unstirred by any soft breathing, she buried her face in her pillow and wept for her girl in a passion of sobs that appalled her, when she grew calm enough to reflect how very wicked it must be to take on so about a sinful fellow-creature.

09:28:00.860 --> 09:28:18.720
Anne and the rest of the Avonlea scholars reached town just in time to hurry off to the Academy. That first day passed pleasantly enough in a whirl of excitement, meeting all the new students, learning to know the professors by sight, and being assorted and organized into classes.

09:28:19.900 --> 09:28:37.440
Anne intended taking up the second-year work being advised to do so by Miss Stacy. Gilbert Blythe elected to do the same. This meant getting a first-class teacher's licence in one year, instead of two, if they were successful. But it also meant much more and harder work.

09:28:38.660 --> 09:29:05.840
Jane, Ruby, Josie, Charlie, and Moody Spurgeon, not being troubled with the stirrings of ambition, were content to take up the second-class work. Anne was conscious of a pang of loneliness when she found herself in a room with fifty other students, not one of whom she knew, except the tall brown-haired boy across the room, and knowing him in the fashion she did did not help her much, as she reflected pessimistically.

09:29:06.640 --> 09:29:16.980
Yet she was undeniably glad that they were in the same class. The old rivalry could still be carried on, and Anne would hardly have known what to do if it had been lacking.

09:29:18.080 --> 09:29:41.260
I wouldn't feel comfortable without it, she thought. Gilbert looks awfully determined. I suppose he's making up his mind, here and now, to win the medal. What a splendid chin he has! I never noticed it before. I do wish Jane and Ruby had gone in for first class, too. I suppose I won't feel so much like a cat in a strange garret when I get acquainted, though.

09:29:41.260 --> 09:29:47.440
I wonder which of the girls here are going to be my friends. It's really an interesting speculation.

09:29:48.800 --> 09:29:58.760
Of course I promised Diana that no queen's girl, no matter how much I liked her, should ever be as dear to me as she is, but I've lots of second-best affections to bestow.

09:29:59.320 --> 09:30:13.360
I like the look of that girl with the brown eyes and the crimson waist. She looks vivid and red-rosy. There's that pale, fair one gazing out of the window. She has lovely hair, and looks as if she knew a thing or two about dreams.

09:30:14.640 --> 09:30:29.580
I'd like to know them both, know them well, well enough to walk with my arm about their waists and call them nicknames. But just now I don't know them, and they don't know me, and probably don't want to know me particularly. Oh, it's lonesome.

09:30:31.360 --> 09:30:56.320
It was lonesomer still when Anne found herself alone in her hall-bedroom that night at twilight. She was not to board with the other girls, who all had relatives in town to take pity on them. Miss Josephine Barry would have liked to board her, but Beechwood was so far from the Academy that it was out of the question. So Miss Barry hunted up a boarding-house, assuring Matthew and Marilla that it was the very place for Anne.

09:30:56.940 --> 09:31:16.520
The lady who keeps it is a reduced gentlewoman," explained Miss Barry. Her husband was a British officer, and she is very careful what sort of boarders she takes. Anne will not meet with any objectionable persons under her roof. The table is good, and the house is near the Academy, in a quiet neighbourhood.

09:31:18.100 --> 09:31:46.500
All this might be quite true, and, indeed, proved to be so, but it did not materially help Anne in the first agony of homesickness that seized upon her. She looked dismally about her narrow little room, with its dull-papered, pictureless walls, its small iron bedstead and empty bookcase, and a horrible choke came into her throat as she thought of her own white room at Green Gables, where she would have the pleasant consciousness of a great

09:31:46.500 --> 09:32:05.400
green still outdoors, of sweet peas growing in the garden and moonlight falling on the orchard, of the brook below the slope and the spruce boughs tossing in the night wind beyond it, of a vast starry sky, and the light from Diana's window shining out through the gap in the trees.

09:32:06.120 --> 09:32:24.760
Here there was nothing of this. Anne knew that outside of her window was a hard street, with a network of telephone wires shutting out the sky, the tramp of alien feet, and a thousand lights gleaming on stranger faces. She knew that she was going to cry, and fought against it.

09:32:25.600 --> 09:32:47.720
I won't cry. It's silly and weak. There's the third tear splashing down by my nose. There are more coming. I must think of something funny to stop them. But there's nothing funny except what is connected with Avonlea, and that only makes things worse—four, five. I'm going home next Friday, but that seems a hundred years away.

09:32:48.240 --> 09:33:04.760
Oh, Matthew is nearly home by now, and Marilla is at the gate, looking down the lane for him. Six, seven, eight. Oh, there's no use in counting them. They're coming in a flood presently. I can't cheer up. I don't want to cheer up. It's nicer to be miserable.

09:33:06.940 --> 09:33:24.860
The flood of tears would have come, no doubt, had not Josie Pye appeared at that moment. In the joy of seeing a familiar face, Anne forgot that there had never been much love lost between her and Josie. As a part of Avonlea life, even a pie was welcome.

09:33:26.160 --> 09:33:29.960
I'm so glad you came up," Anne said sincerely.

09:33:29.960 --> 09:33:36.160
You've been crying, remarked Josie, with aggravating pity.

09:34:06.260 --> 09:34:11.060
Have you anything eatable around, Anne? I'm literally starving.

09:34:30.300 --> 09:34:33.620
And nobody knew very much about what you'd been before that.

09:35:00.660 --> 09:35:14.060
I feel as if I'd lived many moons since the morning. I ought to be home studying my Virgil. That horrid old professor gave us twenty lines to start in on tomorrow. But I simply couldn't settle down to study tonight.

09:35:14.860 --> 09:35:28.280
Anne, methinks I see the traces of tears. If you've been crying duo and up, it will restore my self-respect, for I was shedding tears freely before Ruby came along. I don't mind being a goose so much if somebody else is goosey, too.

09:35:28.860 --> 09:35:35.160
Cake? You'll give me a teeny piece, won't you? Thank you. It has the real Avonlea flavour.

09:35:37.060 --> 09:35:47.260
Ruby, perceiving the Queen's calendar lying on the table, wanted to know if Anne meant to try for the gold medal. Anne blushed, and admitted she was thinking of it.

09:35:47.1000 --> 09:36:01.720
Oh, that reminds me, said Josie, Queen's is to get one of the Avery scholarships after all. The word came to-day. Frank Stockley told me. His uncle is one of the board governors, you know. It will be announced in the Academy to-morrow.

09:36:03.420 --> 09:36:12.300
An Avery scholarship! Anne felt her heart beat more quickly, and the horizons of her ambition shifted and broadened as if by magic.

09:36:13.140 --> 09:36:22.700
Before Josie had told the news, Anne's highest pinnacle of aspiration had been a teacher's provincial licence, first class, at the end of the year, and perhaps the medal.

09:36:23.540 --> 09:36:36.180
But now in one moment Anne saw herself winning the Avery scholarship, taking an arts course at Redmond College, and graduating in a gown and mortar board, before the echo of Josie's words had died away.

09:36:36.840 --> 09:36:42.900
For the Avery scholarship was in English, and Anne felt that here her foot was on native heath.

09:36:44.380 --> 09:36:59.180
A wealthy manufacturer of New Brunswick had died and left part of his fortune to endow a large number of scholarships to be distributed among the various high-schools and academies of the maritime provinces, according to their respective standings.

09:37:00.400 --> 09:37:12.120
There had been much doubt whether one would be allotted to Queen's, but the matter was settled at last, and at the end of the year the graduate who made the highest mark in English and English literature would win the scholarship.

09:37:12.960 --> 09:37:21.420
Two hundred and fifty dollars a year for four years at Redmond College! No wonder that Anne went to bed that night with tingling cheeks.

09:37:22.600 --> 09:37:29.800
I'll win that scholarship if hard work can do it, she resolved. Wouldn't Matthew be proud if I got to be a B.A.

09:37:30.240 --> 09:37:39.040
Oh, it's delightful to have ambitions. I'm so glad I have such a lot. And there never seems to be any end to them. That's the best of it.

09:37:39.360 --> 09:37:46.700
Just as soon as you attain one ambition you see another one glittering higher up still. It does make life so interesting.

09:38:10.700 --> 09:38:15.960
Anne's homesickness wore off, greatly helped in the wearing by her weekend visits home.

09:38:15.960 --> 09:38:23.420
As long as the open weather lasted, the Avonlea students went out to Carmody on the New Branch Railway every Friday night.

09:38:24.100 --> 09:38:31.200
Diana and several other Avonlea young folks were generally on hand to meet them, and they all walked over to Avonlea in a merry party.

09:38:32.020 --> 09:38:43.740
Anne thought those Friday evening gypsyings over the autumnal hills in the crisp golden air, with the home lights of Avonlea twinkling beyond, were the best and dearest hours in the whole week.

09:38:44.440 --> 09:38:49.860
Gilbert Blythe nearly always walked with Ruby Gillis, and carried her satchel for her.

09:38:50.180 --> 09:38:55.500
Ruby was a very handsome young lady, now thinking herself quite as grown up as she really was.

09:38:55.920 --> 09:39:02.960
She wore her skirts as long as her mother would let her, and did her hair up in town, though she had to take it down when she went home.

09:39:03.600 --> 09:39:08.760
She had large, bright blue eyes, a brilliant complexion and a plump, showy figure.

09:39:08.760 --> 09:39:14.760
She laughed a great deal, was cheerful and good-tempered, and enjoyed the pleasant things of life, frankly.

09:39:16.340 --> 09:39:21.080
But I shouldn't think she was the sort of girl Gilbert would like, whispered Jane to Anne.

09:39:21.460 --> 09:39:25.900
Anne did not think so either, but she would not have said so for the Avery Scholarship.

09:39:26.100 --> 09:39:35.780
She could not help thinking, too, that it would be very pleasant to have such a friend as Gilbert to jest and chatter with, and exchange ideas about books and studies and ambitions.

09:39:35.780 --> 09:39:44.680
Gilbert had ambitions, she knew, and Ruby Gillis did not seem the sort of person with whom such could be profitably discussed.

09:39:45.640 --> 09:39:48.960
There was no silly sentiment in Anne's ideas concerning Gilbert.

09:39:49.640 --> 09:39:54.380
Boys were, to her, when she thought about them at all, merely possible good comrades.

09:39:54.800 --> 09:40:00.520
If she and Gilbert had been friends, she would not have cared how many other friends he had, nor with whom he walked.

09:40:00.520 --> 09:40:09.940
She had a genius for friendship, girlfriends she had in plenty, but she had a vague consciousness that masculine friendship might also be a good thing,

09:40:10.300 --> 09:40:16.020
to round out one's conceptions of companionship and furnish broader standpoints of judgment and comparison.

09:40:16.840 --> 09:40:21.180
Not that Anne could have put her feelings on the matter into just such clear definition,

09:40:21.460 --> 09:40:28.680
but she thought that if Gilbert had ever walked home with her from the train, over the crisp fields and along the ferny byways,

09:40:28.680 --> 09:40:36.680
they might have had many and merry and interesting conversations about the new world that was opening around them and their hopes and ambitions therein.

09:40:37.660 --> 09:40:45.500
Gilbert was a clever young fellow, with his own thoughts about things and a determination to get the best out of life and put the best into it.

09:40:46.540 --> 09:40:51.440
Ruby Gillis told Jane Andrews that she didn't understand half the things Gilbert Blythe said.

09:40:51.440 --> 09:41:01.160
He talked just like Anne Shirley did when she had a thoughtful fit on, and for her part she didn't think it any fun to be bothering about books and that sort of thing when you didn't have to.

09:41:01.540 --> 09:41:09.480
Frank Stockley had lots more dash and go, but then he wasn't half as good looking as Gilbert, and she really couldn't decide which she liked best.

09:41:10.720 --> 09:41:18.520
In the academy, Anne gradually drew a little circle of friends about her, thoughtful, imaginative, ambitious students like herself.

09:41:19.300 --> 09:41:32.160
With the rose-red girl, Stella Maynard, and the dream girl, Priscilla Grant, she soon became intimate, finding the latter pale, spiritual-looking maiden to be full to the brim of mischief and pranks and fun,

09:41:32.420 --> 09:41:39.240
while the vivid black-eyed Stella had a heart full of wistful dreams and fancies, as aerial and rainbow-like as Anne's own.

09:41:42.040 --> 09:41:47.580
After the Christmas holidays, the Avonlea students gave up going home on Fridays and settled down to hard work.

09:41:47.580 --> 09:41:58.620
By this time, all the Queen's scholars had gravitated into their own places in the ranks, and the various classes had assumed distinct and settled shadings of individuality.

09:41:58.880 --> 09:42:08.880
Certain facts had become generally accepted. It was admitted that the medal contestants had practically narrowed down to three, Gilbert Blythe, Anne Shirley, and Lewis Wilson.

09:42:09.460 --> 09:42:14.160
The Avery Scholarship was more doubtful, any one of a certain six being a possible winner.

09:42:14.660 --> 09:42:22.260
The bronze medal for mathematics was considered as good as won by a fat, funny little upcountry boy with a bumpy forehead and a patched coat.

09:42:23.440 --> 09:42:34.160
Ruby Gillis was the handsomest girl of the year at the Academy. In the second-year classes, Stella Maynard carried off the palm for beauty, with small but critical minority in favor of Anne Shirley.

09:42:34.760 --> 09:42:46.760
Ethel Marr was admitted by all competent judges to have the most stylish modes of hairdressing, and Jane Andrews, plain, plodding, conscientious Jane, carried off the honors in the domestic science course.

09:42:47.340 --> 09:43:00.660
Even Josie Pye attained a certain preeminence as the sharpest-tongued young lady in attendance at Queen's, so it may be fairly stated that Miss Stacy's old pupils held their own in the wider arena of the academic course.

09:43:01.660 --> 09:43:12.880
Anne worked hard and steadily. Her rivalry with Gilbert was as intense as it had ever been in Avonlea School, although it was not known in the class at large, but somehow the bitterness had gone out of it.

09:43:13.100 --> 09:43:21.720
Anne no longer wished to win for the sake of defeating Gilbert, rather for the proud consciousness of a well-won victory over a worthy foeman.

09:43:22.640 --> 09:43:28.260
It would be worthwhile to win, but she no longer thought life would be insupportable if she did not.

09:43:29.140 --> 09:43:39.700
In spite of lessons, the students found opportunities for pleasant times. Anne spent many of her spare hours at Beachwood and generally ate her Sunday dinners there and went to church with Miss Barry.

09:43:40.420 --> 09:43:47.480
The latter was, as she admitted, growing old, but her black eyes were not dim nor the vigor of her tongue in the least abated.

09:43:47.920 --> 09:43:53.640
But she never sharpened the latter on Anne, who continued to be a prime favorite with the critical old lady.

09:43:53.640 --> 09:43:57.260
That Anne girl improves all the time, she said.

09:43:57.260 --> 09:44:07.280
I get tired of other girls. There is such a provoking and eternal sameness about them. Anne has as many shades as a rainbow, and every shade is the prettiest while it lasts.

09:44:07.760 --> 09:44:19.080
I don't know that she is as amusing as she was when she was a child, but she makes me love her and I like people who make me love them. It saves me so much trouble in making myself love them.

09:44:20.100 --> 09:44:30.280
Then, almost before anybody realized it, spring had come. Out in Avonlea, the Mayflowers were peeping pinkly out on the seer barrens where snow wreaths lingered.

09:44:30.840 --> 09:44:39.240
And the mist of green was on the woods and in the valleys. But in Charlottetown, harassed Queen's students thought and talked only of examinations.

09:44:39.820 --> 09:44:49.080
It doesn't seem possible that the term is nearly over, said Anne, while last fall it seemed so long to look forward to. A whole winter of studies and classes.

09:44:49.500 --> 09:44:55.920
And here we are with the exams looming up next week. Girls, sometimes I feel as if those exams meant everything.

09:44:56.320 --> 09:45:04.200
But when I look at the big buds swelling on those chestnut trees and the misty blue air at the end of the streets, they don't seem half so important.

09:45:05.140 --> 09:45:08.660
Jane and Ruby and Josie, who had dropped in, did not take this view of it.

09:45:08.660 --> 09:45:17.660
To them, the coming examinations were constantly very important indeed. Far more important than chestnut buds or Maytime hazes.

09:45:18.120 --> 09:45:24.040
It was all very well for Anne, who was sure of passing at least, to have her moments of belittling them.

09:45:24.440 --> 09:45:31.460
But when your whole future depended on them, as the girls truly thought theirs did, you could not regard them philosophically.

09:45:32.060 --> 09:45:39.260
I've lost seven pounds in the last two weeks, sighed Jane. It's no use to say don't worry. Worrying helps you some.

09:45:39.560 --> 09:45:47.960
It seems as if you were doing something when you're worrying. It would be dreadful if I failed to get my license after going to Queen's all winter and spending so much money.

09:45:48.860 --> 09:45:56.040
I don't care, said Josie Pye. If I don't pass this year, I'm coming back next. My father can't afford to send me.

09:45:56.040 --> 09:46:04.900
And Frank Stockley says that Professor Tremaine said Gilbert Blythe was sure to get the medal, and that Emily Clay would likely win the Avery Scholarship.

09:46:05.740 --> 09:46:16.100
That may make me feel badly tomorrow, Josie, laughed Anne, but just now I honestly feel that as long as I know the violets are coming out all purple down in the hollow below Green Gables,

09:46:16.540 --> 09:46:23.660
and that little ferns are poking their heads up in Lover's Lane, it's not a great deal of difference whether I win the Avery or not.

09:46:23.660 --> 09:46:31.800
I've done my best, and I begin to understand what is meant by the joy of the strife. Next to trying and winning, the best thing is trying and failing.

09:46:32.400 --> 09:46:43.320
Girls, don't talk about exams. Look at that arch of pale green sky over those houses, and picture to yourself what it must look like over the purpley dark beech woods back of Avonlea.

09:46:44.180 --> 09:46:47.880
What are you going to wear for commencement, Jane? asked Ruby practically.

09:46:48.600 --> 09:47:00.280
Jane and Josie both answered at once, and the chatter drifted into a side eddy of fashions, but Anne, with her elbows on the windowsill, her soft cheek laid against her clasped hands,

09:47:00.280 --> 09:47:14.700
and her eyes filled with visions looked out unheatingly across city roof and spire to that glorious dome of sunset sky, and wove her dreams of a possible future from the golden tissue of youth's own optimism.

09:47:15.800 --> 09:47:26.440
All the beyond was hers, with its possibilities lurking rosily in the oncoming years, each year a rose of promise to be woven into an immortal chaplet.

09:47:26.440 --> 09:47:31.640
And that's the

09:47:57.840 --> 09:47:59.300
THE GLORY AND THE DREAM

09:48:02.160 --> 09:48:10.020
On the morning when the final results of all the examinations were to be posted on the bulletin board at Queen's, Anne and Jane walked down the street together.

09:48:10.780 --> 09:48:19.640
Jane was smiling and happy. Examinations were over, and she was comfortably sure she had made a pass at least. Further considerations troubled Jane not at all.

09:48:19.840 --> 09:48:25.120
She had no soaring ambitions, and consequently was not affected with the unrest attendant thereon.

09:48:25.120 --> 09:48:37.600
For we pay a price for everything we get or take in this world, and although ambitions are well worth having, they are not to be cheaply won, but exact their dues of work and self-denial, anxiety and discouragement.

09:48:38.160 --> 09:48:49.380
Anne was pale and quiet. In ten more minutes she would know who had won the medal and who the Avery. Beyond those ten minutes there did not seem, just then, to be anything worth being called time.

09:48:50.660 --> 09:48:57.820
Of course you'll win one of them anyhow, said Jane, who couldn't understand how the faculty could be so unfair as to order it otherwise.

09:48:59.260 --> 09:49:08.840
I have not hope of the Avery, said Anne. Everybody says Emily Clay will win it, and I'm not going to march up to that bulletin board and look at it before everybody. I haven't the moral courage.

09:49:08.840 --> 09:49:26.320
I'm going straight to the girls' dressing room. You must read the announcements and then come and tell me, Jane, and I implore you, in the name of our old friendship, to do it as quickly as possible. If I have failed, just say so, without trying to break it gently, and whatever you do, don't sympathize with me. Promise me this, Jane.

09:49:27.520 --> 09:49:41.680
Jane promised solemnly, but as it happened, there was no necessity for such a promise. When they went up to the entrance steps of Queen's, they found the hall full of boys who were carrying Gilbert Blythe around on their shoulders, and yelling at the tops of their voices,

09:49:41.680 --> 09:50:00.360
Hurrah for Blythe, medalist! For a moment, Anne felt one sickening pang of defeat and disappointment, so she had failed, and Gilbert had won. Well, Matthew would be sorry. He had been so sure she would win. And then somebody called out, Three cheers for Miss Shirley, winner of the Avery!

09:50:00.880 --> 09:50:26.960
Oh, Anne, gasped Jane, as they fled to the girls' dressing room amid hearty cheers. Oh, Anne, I'm so proud. Isn't it splendid? And then the girls were around them, and Anne was the centre of a laughing, congratulating group. Her shoulders were thumped, and her hands were shaken vigorously. She was pushed and pulled and hugged, and among it all she managed to whisper to Jane, Oh, won't Matthew and Marilla be pleased? I must write the news home right away.

09:50:27.900 --> 09:50:56.940
Commencement was the next important happening. The exercises were held in the big assembly hall of the Academy. Addresses were given, essays read, songs sung, the public award of diplomas, prizes, and medals made. Matthew and Marilla were there, with eyes and ears for only one student on the platform, a tall girl in pale green, with faintly flushed cheeks and starry eyes, who read the best essay, and was pointed out and whispered about as the Avery winner. Reckon you're glad we kept her.

09:50:56.960 --> 09:51:02.760
Are you glad you kept her, Marilla? whispered Matthew, speaking for the first time since he had entered the hall, when Anne had finished her essay.

09:51:03.740 --> 09:51:18.340
It's not the first time I've been glad, retorted Marilla. You do like to rub things in, Matthew Cuthbert. Miss Barry, who was sitting behind them, leaned forward and poked Marilla in the back with her parasol. Aren't you proud of that, Anne girl? I am, she said.

09:51:19.980 --> 09:51:41.280
Anne went home to Avonlea with Matthew and Marilla that evening. She had not been home since April, and she felt that she could not wait another day. The apple blossoms were out, and the world was fresh and young. Diana was at Green Gables to meet her. In her own white room, where Marilla had set a flowering house rose on the windowsill, Anne looked about her and drew a long breath of happiness.

09:51:41.920 --> 09:51:59.220
Oh, Diana, it's so good to be back again. It's so good to see those pointed furs coming out against the pink sky, and that white orchard and the old snow queen. Isn't the breath of the mint delicious? And that tea rose. Why, it's a song and a hope and a prayer all in one. And it's good to see you again, Diana.

09:51:59.780 --> 09:52:13.400
I thought you liked that Stella Maynard better than me, said Diana reproachfully. Josie Pye told me you did. Josie Pye said you were infatuated with her. Anne laughed and pelted Diana with the faded June lilies of her bouquet.

09:52:14.080 --> 09:52:34.1000
Stella Maynard is the dearest girl in the world except one, and you are that one, Diana, she said. I love you more than ever, and I've so many things to tell you. But just now I feel as if it were joy enough to sit here and look at you. I'm tired, I think. Tired of being studious and ambitious. I mean to spend at least two hours tomorrow lying out in the orchard grass, thinking of absolutely nothing.

09:52:35.740 --> 09:52:56.140
You've done splendidly, Anne. I suppose you won't be teaching now that you've won the Avery? No, I'm going to Redmond in September. Doesn't it seem wonderful? I'll have a brand new stock of ambition laid in by that time after three glorious golden months of vacation. Jane and Ruby are going to teach. Isn't it splendid to think we all got through even to Moody Spurgeon and Josie Pye?

09:52:56.740 --> 09:53:12.820
The Newbridge trustees have offered Jane their school already, said Diana. Gilbert Blythe is going to teach too. He has to. His father can't afford to send him to college next year after all, so he means to earn his own way through. I expect he'll get the school here if Miss Ames decides to leave.

09:53:13.340 --> 09:53:31.060
Anne felt a queer little sensation of dismayed surprise. She had not known this. She had expected that Gilbert would be going to Redmond also. What would she do without their inspiring rivalry? Would not work, even at a co-educational college with a real degree in prospect, be rather flat without her friend the enemy?

09:53:31.720 --> 09:53:39.240
The next morning at breakfast, it suddenly struck Anne that Matthew was not looking well. Surely he was much greyer than he had been a year before.

09:53:40.200 --> 09:53:44.540
Marilla, she said hesitatingly when he had gone out, is Matthew quite well?

09:53:45.380 --> 09:54:03.380
No, he isn't, said Marilla in a troubled tone. He's had some real bad spells with his heart this spring, and he won't spare himself a mite. I've been real worried about him, but he's some better this while back, and we've got a good hired man, so I'm hoping he'll kind of rest and pick up. Maybe he will now you're home. You always cheer him up.

09:54:04.060 --> 09:54:07.580
Anne leaned across the table and took Marilla's face in her hands.

09:54:08.640 --> 09:54:24.1000
You are not looking as well yourself as I'd like to see you, Marilla. You look tired. I'm afraid you've been working too hard. You must take a rest now that I'm home. I'm just going to take this one day off to visit all the dear old spots and hunt up my old dreams, and then it will be your turn to be lazy while I do the work.

09:54:25.780 --> 09:54:27.760
Marilla smiled affectionately at her girl.

09:54:28.420 --> 09:54:45.920
It's not the work. It's my head. I've got a pain so often now, behind my eyes. Dr. Spencer's been fussing with glasses, but they don't do me any good. There is a distinguished oculist coming to the island the last of June, and the doctor says I must see him. I guess I'll have to. I can't read or sew with any comfort now.

09:54:46.700 --> 09:55:09.080
Well, Anne, you've done real well at Queen's, I must say, to take first-class license in one year and win the Avery Scholarship. Well, Mrs. Lynde says pride goes before a fall, and she doesn't believe in the higher education of women at all. She says it unfits them for a woman's true sphere. I don't believe a word of it. Speaking of Rachel reminds me, did you hear anything about the Abbey Bank lately, Anne?

09:55:09.080 --> 09:55:11.800
I heard it was shaky, answered Anne. Why?

09:55:12.600 --> 09:55:32.180
That is what Rachel said. She was up here one day last week, and said there was some talk about it. Matthew felt real worried. All we have saved is in that bank, every penny. I wanted Matthew to put it in the savings bank in the first place, but old Mr. Abbey was a great friend of father's, and he'd always banked with him. Matthew said any bank with him at the head of it was good enough for anybody.

09:55:32.700 --> 09:55:49.120
I think he has only been its nominal head for many years, said Anne. He is a very old man. His nephews are really at the head of the institution. Well, when Rachel told us that, I wanted Matthew to draw our money right out, and he said he'd think of it. But Mr. Russell told him yesterday that the bank was all right.

09:55:50.480 --> 09:56:16.900
Anne had her good day in the companionship of the outdoor world. She never forgot that day. It was so bright and golden and fair, so free from shadow, and so lavish of blossom. Anne spent some of its rich hours in the orchard. She went to the Dryad's Bubble in Willowmere in Violet Vale. She called at the manse and had a satisfying talk with Mrs. Allen, and finally in the evening she went with Matthew for the cows, through Lover's Lane to the back pasture.

09:56:16.900 --> 09:56:29.680
The woods were all gloried through a sunset, and the warm splendour of it streamed down through the hill gaps in the west. Matthew walked slowly with bent head. Anne, tall and erect, suited her springing step to his.

09:56:30.640 --> 09:56:36.360
You've been working too hard today, Matthew, she said reproachfully. Why won't you take things easier?

09:56:37.400 --> 09:56:49.1000
Well, now I can't seem to, said Matthew, as he opened the yard gate to let the cows through. It's only that I'm getting old, Anne, and keep forgetting it. Oh, well, I've always worked pretty hard, and I'd rather drop in harness.

09:56:50.700 --> 09:57:00.940
If I had been the boy you sent for, said Anne wistfully, I'd be able to help you so much now, and spare you in a hundred ways. I could find it in my heart to wish I had been, just for that.

09:57:01.960 --> 09:57:17.720
Well, now, I'd rather have you than a dozen boys, Anne, said Matthew, patting her hand. Just mind you that, rather than a dozen boys. Well, now, I guess it wasn't a boy that took the Avery Scholarship, was it? It was a girl, my girl, my girl that I'm proud of.

09:57:18.280 --> 09:57:30.140
He smiled his shy smile at her as he went into the yard. Anne took the memory of it with her when she went to her room that night, and sat for a long while at her open window, thinking of the past and dreaming of the future.

09:57:30.900 --> 09:57:41.860
Outside, the Snow Queen was mistily white in the moonshine, the frogs were singing in the marsh beyond Orchard Slope. Anne always remembered the silvery, peaceful beauty and fragrant calm of that night.

09:57:41.860 --> 09:57:50.1000
It was the last night before sorrow touched her life, and no life is ever quite the same again when once that cold, sanctifying touch has been laid upon it.

09:58:17.180 --> 09:58:19.480
Matthew, Matthew, what is the matter?

09:58:20.140 --> 09:58:21.160
Matthew, are you sick?

09:58:21.160 --> 09:58:27.240
It was Marilla who spoke, alarm in every jerky word. Anne came through the hall,

09:58:27.480 --> 09:58:32.720
her hands full of white narcissus. It was long before Anne could love the sight or order of

09:58:32.720 --> 09:58:38.200
white narcissus again. In time to hear her, Anne to see Matthew standing in the porch doorway,

09:58:38.920 --> 09:58:44.1000
a folded paper in his hand, and his face strangely drawn and grey. Anne dropped her

09:58:44.1000 --> 09:58:50.760
flowers and sprang across the kitchen to him at the same moment as Marilla. They were both too late,

09:58:50.760 --> 09:58:54.420
before they could reach him. Matthew had fallen across the threshold.

09:58:55.860 --> 09:59:01.120
He's fainted, gasped Marilla. Anne, run for Martin. Quick, quick, he's at the barn.

09:59:01.1000 --> 09:59:07.900
Martin, the hired hand, who had just driven home from the post office, started at once for the

09:59:07.900 --> 09:59:14.720
doctor, calling at Orchard Slope on his way to send Mr. and Mrs. Barry over. Mrs. Lind, who was

09:59:14.720 --> 09:59:19.860
there on an errand, came too. They found Anne and Marilla distractedly trying to restore

09:59:19.860 --> 09:59:26.560
Matthew to consciousness. Mrs. Lind pushed them gently aside, tried his pulse, and then laid her

09:59:26.560 --> 09:59:32.540
ear over his heart. She looked at their anxious faces sorrowfully, and the tears came into her

09:59:32.540 --> 09:59:41.600
eyes. Oh, Marilla, she said gravely, I don't think we can do anything for him. Mrs. Lind,

09:59:41.600 --> 09:59:49.180
you don't think, you can't think Matthew is, is. Anne could not say the dreadful word. She turned

09:59:49.180 --> 09:59:57.020
sick and pallid. Child, yes, I'm afraid of it. Look at his face. When you've seen that look as

09:59:57.020 --> 10:00:02.980
often as I have, you'll know what it means. Anne looked at the still face and there beheld the seal

10:00:02.980 --> 10:00:09.420
of the great presence. When the doctor came, he said that death had been instantaneous and probably

10:00:09.420 --> 10:00:16.500
painless, caused in all likelihood by some sudden shock. The secret of the shock was discovered to

10:00:16.500 --> 10:00:22.600
be in the paper Matthew had held and which Martin had brought from the office that morning. It

10:00:22.600 --> 10:00:29.080
contained an account of the failure of the Abbey Bank. The news spread quickly through Avonlea,

10:00:29.220 --> 10:00:34.300
and all day friends and neighbours thronged green gables and came and went on errands of kindness

10:00:34.300 --> 10:00:41.160
for the dead and living. For the first time, shy, quiet, Matthew Cuthbert was a person of

10:00:41.160 --> 10:00:46.910
central importance. The white majesty of death had fallen on him and set him apart as one crowned.

10:00:47.900 --> 10:00:54.080
When the calm night came softly down over green gables, the old house was hushed and tranquil.

10:00:54.860 --> 10:01:01.520
In the parlour lay Matthew Cuthbert, in his coffin, his long grey hair framing his placid face,

10:01:01.520 --> 10:01:09.440
on which there was a little kindly smile, as if he but slept, dreaming pleasant dreams.

10:01:10.280 --> 10:01:15.600
There were flowers about him, sweet old-fashioned flowers which his mother had planted in the

10:01:15.600 --> 10:01:22.520
homestead garden in her bridal days and for which Matthew had always had a secret, wordless love.

10:01:23.500 --> 10:01:29.560
Anne had gathered them and brought them to him, her anguished, tearless eyes burning in her white

10:01:29.560 --> 10:01:36.720
face. It was the last thing she could do for him. The berries and Mrs. Lynn stayed with them that

10:01:36.720 --> 10:01:44.580
night. Diana, going to the east gable, where Anne was standing at her window, said gently,

10:01:45.520 --> 10:01:52.780
Anne dear, would you like to have me sleep with you tonight? Thank you, Diana. Anne looked earnestly

10:01:52.780 --> 10:01:58.720
into her friend's face. I think you wouldn't misunderstand me when I say I want to be alone.

10:01:59.560 --> 10:02:07.200
I'm not afraid. I haven't been alone one minute since it happened. And I want to be. I want to be

10:02:07.200 --> 10:02:15.740
quite silent and quiet and try to realize it. I can't realize it. Half the time it seems to me

10:02:15.740 --> 10:02:21.940
that Matthew can't be dead, and the other half it seems as if he must have been dead for a long time

10:02:21.940 --> 10:02:27.660
and I've had this horrible, dull ache ever since. Diana did not quite understand.

10:02:28.740 --> 10:02:35.180
Marilla's impassioned grief, breaking all the bounds of national reserve, and lifelong habit

10:02:35.180 --> 10:02:42.260
in its stormy rush. She could comprehend better than Anne's tearless agony, but she went away

10:02:42.260 --> 10:02:48.860
kindly, leaving Anne alone to keep her first vigil with sorrow. Anne hoped that the tears

10:02:48.860 --> 10:02:53.980
would come in solitude. It seemed to her a terrible thing that she could not shed a tear for Matthew,

10:02:53.980 --> 10:02:59.080
whom she had loved so much and who had been so kind to her. Matthew, who had walked with

10:02:59.080 --> 10:03:04.960
her last evening at sunset and was now lying in the dim room below, with that awful piece on his

10:03:04.960 --> 10:03:11.140
brow. But no tears came at first, even when she knelt by her window in the darkness and prayed,

10:03:11.580 --> 10:03:17.460
looking up to the stars beyond the hills. No tears, only the same horrible dull ache of misery

10:03:17.460 --> 10:03:23.260
that kept on aching until she fell asleep, worn out with the day's pain and excitement.

10:03:23.980 --> 10:03:29.300
In the night she awakened, with the stillness and the darkness about her, and the recollection of

10:03:29.300 --> 10:03:34.600
the day came over her like a wave of sorrow. She could see Matthew's face smiling at her,

10:03:34.760 --> 10:03:40.080
as he had smiled when they parted at the gate that last evening. She could hear his voice saying,

10:03:40.560 --> 10:03:46.400
My girl, my girl that I'm proud of. Then the tears came and Anne wept her heart out.

10:03:46.840 --> 10:03:48.1000
Marilla heard her and crept in to comfort her.

10:03:50.260 --> 10:03:59.920
There, there. Don't cry so, dearie. It can't bring him back. It isn't right to cry so. I knew that

10:03:59.920 --> 10:04:05.520
today, but I couldn't help it then. He'd always been such a good kind brother to me. But God knows

10:04:05.520 --> 10:04:12.700
best. Oh, just let me cry, Marilla, sobbed Anne. The tears don't hurt me like that ache did. Stay

10:04:12.700 --> 10:04:20.020
for a while with me and keep your arms around me. So. I couldn't have Diana's day. She's good and

10:04:20.020 --> 10:04:25.340
kind and sweet, but it's not her sorrow. She's outside of it and she couldn't come close enough

10:04:25.340 --> 10:04:31.600
to my heart to help me. It's our sorrow, yours and mine. Oh, Marilla, what will we do without him?

10:04:32.600 --> 10:04:37.700
We've got each other, Anne. I don't know what I'd do if you weren't here, if you'd never come.

10:04:37.700 --> 10:04:41.760
Oh, Anne, I know I've been kind of strict and harsh with you maybe,

10:04:42.120 --> 10:04:48.060
but you mustn't think I didn't love you as well as Matthew did, for all that. I want to tell you

10:04:48.060 --> 10:04:53.920
now when I can. It's never been easy for me to say things out of my heart, but at times like this

10:04:53.920 --> 10:04:59.860
it's easier. I love you as dear as if you were my own flesh and blood, and you've been my joy and

10:04:59.860 --> 10:05:06.720
comfort ever since you came to Green Gables. Two days afterwards they carried Matthew Cuthbert over

10:05:06.720 --> 10:05:12.600
his homestead threshold and away from the fields he had tilled and the orchards he had loved and

10:05:12.600 --> 10:05:19.260
the trees he had planted. And then Avonlea settled back to its usual placidity, and even at Green

10:05:19.260 --> 10:05:25.260
Gables affairs slipped into their old groove and work was done and duties fulfilled with regularity

10:05:25.260 --> 10:05:33.080
as before, although always with the aching sense of loss in all familiar things. Anne, new to grief,

10:05:33.080 --> 10:05:39.040
thought it almost sad that it could be so, that they could go on in the old way without Matthew.

10:05:39.660 --> 10:05:44.900
She felt something like shame and remorse when she discovered that the sunrises behind the firs

10:05:45.440 --> 10:05:51.740
and the pale pink buds opening in the garden gave her the old inrush of gladness when she saw them,

10:05:52.180 --> 10:05:56.640
that Diana's visits were pleasant to her and that Diana's merry words and ways

10:05:56.640 --> 10:06:03.440
moved her to laughter and smiles, that, in brief, the beautiful world of blossom and love and

10:06:03.440 --> 10:06:07.880
friendship had lost none of its power to please her fancy and thrill her heart,

10:06:08.480 --> 10:06:11.560
that life still called to her with many insistent voices.

10:06:12.260 --> 10:06:17.900
It seems like disloyalty to Matthew somehow to find pleasure in these things now that he has gone,

10:06:18.240 --> 10:06:22.900
she said wistfully to Mrs. Allen one evening when they were together in the man's garden.

10:06:23.460 --> 10:06:29.620
I miss him so much, all the time, and yet Mrs. Allen, the world and life seem very beautiful

10:06:29.620 --> 10:06:35.260
and interesting to me for all. Today Diana said something funny and I found myself laughing,

10:06:35.940 --> 10:06:42.380
I thought when it happened I could never laugh again, and somehow it seems as if I oughtn't to.

10:06:43.460 --> 10:06:52.140
When Matthew was here he liked to hear you laugh, he liked to know you had found pleasure in the

10:06:52.140 --> 10:06:58.660
world, and he likes to know it just the same. I am sure we should not shut our hearts against

10:06:58.660 --> 10:07:04.680
the healing influences that nature offers us, but I can understand your feeling. I think we all

10:07:04.680 --> 10:07:09.860
experience the same thing, we resent the thought that anything can please us when someone we love

10:07:09.860 --> 10:07:15.200
is no longer here to share the pleasure with us, and we almost feel as if we were unfaithful to

10:07:15.200 --> 10:07:21.440
our sorrow when we find our interest in life returning to us. I was down to the graveyard

10:07:21.440 --> 10:07:26.980
to plant a rose bush on Matthew's grave this afternoon, said Anne dreamily. I took a slip

10:07:26.980 --> 10:07:32.900
of the little white scotch rose bush his mother brought out from Scotland long ago. Matthew always

10:07:32.900 --> 10:07:38.700
liked those roses the best, they were so small and sweet on their thorny stems. It made me feel glad

10:07:38.700 --> 10:07:43.720
that I could plant it by his grave, as if I were doing something that must please him in taking it

10:07:43.720 --> 10:07:49.460
there to be near him. I hope he has roses like them in heaven. Perhaps the souls of all those

10:07:49.460 --> 10:07:55.880
white roses that he has loved for so many years were all there to meet him. I must go home now,

10:07:56.120 --> 10:07:58.620
Marilla is all alone and she gets lonely at twilight.

10:07:59.580 --> 10:08:04.300
She will be lonelier still, I fear, when you go away again to college, said Mrs. Allen.

10:08:05.300 --> 10:08:09.040
Anne did not reply. She said good night and went slowly back to Green Gables.

10:08:09.800 --> 10:08:15.280
Marilla was sitting on the front doorsteps and Anne sat down beside her. The door was open behind

10:08:15.280 --> 10:08:22.100
them, held back by a big pink conch shell with hints of sea sunsets in its smooth inner convolutions.

10:08:22.680 --> 10:08:27.580
Anne gathered some sprays of pale yellow honeysuckle and put them in her hair. She

10:08:27.580 --> 10:08:33.360
liked the delicious hint of fragrance as some aerial benediction above her every time she moved.

10:08:34.120 --> 10:08:39.1000
Dr. Spencer was here while you were away, Marilla said. He says that the specialist will be in town

10:08:39.1000 --> 10:08:46.660
tomorrow and he insists that I must go in and have my eyes examined. I suppose I'd better go and have

10:08:46.660 --> 10:08:52.100
it over. I'll be more than thankful if the man can give me the right kind of glasses to suit my eyes.

10:08:52.760 --> 10:08:57.540
You won't mind staying here alone while I'm away, will you? Martin will have to drive me in and

10:08:57.540 --> 10:09:03.900
there's ironing and baking to do. I shall be all right. Diana will come over for company for me.

10:09:04.020 --> 10:09:08.380
I shall attend to the ironing and baking beautifully. You needn't fear that I'll

10:09:08.380 --> 10:09:14.400
torch the handkerchiefs or flavor the cake with liniment. Marilla laughed. What a girl you were

10:09:14.400 --> 10:09:19.660
for making mistakes in them days, Anne. You were always getting into scrapes. I did used to think

10:09:19.660 --> 10:09:25.900
you were possessed. Do you mind the time you dyed your hair? Yes, indeed, I shall never forget it,

10:09:26.080 --> 10:09:31.280
smiled Anne, touching the heavy braid of her hair that was wound about her shapely head.

10:09:31.940 --> 10:09:36.720
I laugh a little now sometimes when I think what a worry my hair used to be to me,

10:09:36.720 --> 10:09:42.880
but I don't laugh much because it was a very real trouble then. I did suffer terribly over my hair

10:09:42.880 --> 10:09:47.620
and my freckles. My freckles are really gone and people are nice enough to tell me my hair is

10:09:47.620 --> 10:09:53.620
open now. But old Josie Pie, she informed me yesterday that she really thought it was redder

10:09:53.620 --> 10:09:58.940
than ever, or at least my black dress made it look redder, and she asked me if people who had

10:09:58.940 --> 10:10:04.800
red hair ever got used to having it. Marilla, I've almost decided to give up trying to like Josie Pie.

10:10:05.360 --> 10:10:11.140
I've made what I would once have called a heroic effort to like her, but Josie Pie won't be liked.

10:10:11.960 --> 10:10:17.700
Josie is a pious, said Marilla sharply. So she can't help being disagreeable. I suppose people

10:10:17.700 --> 10:10:23.980
of that kind serve some useful purpose in society, but I must say I don't know what it is anymore than

10:10:23.980 --> 10:10:30.180
I know the use of thistles. Is Josie going to teach? No, she is going back to Queen's next year.

10:10:30.660 --> 10:10:36.500
So are Moody Spurgeon and Charlie Sloan. Jane and Ruby are going to teach and they have both

10:10:36.500 --> 10:10:42.580
got schools. Jane at New Bridge and Ruby at some place up west. Gilbert Blythe is going to teach

10:10:42.580 --> 10:10:50.640
too, isn't he? Yes, briefly. What a nice looking fellow he is, said Marilla absently. I saw him

10:10:50.640 --> 10:10:56.160
in church last Sunday and he seemed so tall and manly. He looks a lot like his father did at the

10:10:56.160 --> 10:11:02.220
same age. John Blythe was a nice boy. We used to be real good friends, he and I. People called him

10:11:02.220 --> 10:11:09.040
my beau. Anne looked up with swift interest. Oh Marilla, and what happened? Why didn't you?

10:11:09.680 --> 10:11:15.520
We had a quarrel. I wouldn't forgive him when he asked me to. I meant to, but after a while,

10:11:15.960 --> 10:11:22.580
but I was sulky and angry and I wanted to punish him first. He never came back. The Blythes were

10:11:22.580 --> 10:11:29.080
mighty independent. But I always felt rather sorry. I've always kind of wished I'd forgiven

10:11:29.080 --> 10:11:34.160
him when I had the chance. So you've had a bit of romance in your life too, said Anne softly.

10:11:34.1000 --> 10:11:39.220
Yes, I suppose you might call it that. You wouldn't think so to look at me, would you?

10:11:39.620 --> 10:11:44.360
But you could never tell about people from their outsides. Everybody has forgot about me and John.

10:11:44.800 --> 10:11:49.040
I'd forgotten myself, but it all came back to me when I saw Gilbert last Sunday.

10:12:16.580 --> 10:12:18.480
THE BEND IN THE ROAD.

10:12:18.480 --> 10:12:23.940
Marilla went to town the next day and returned in the evening. Anne had gone over to Orchard Slope

10:12:23.940 --> 10:12:28.920
with Diana and came back to find Marilla in the kitchen, sitting by the table with her head

10:12:28.920 --> 10:12:34.040
leaning on her hand. Something in her dejected attitude struck a chill to Anne's heart.

10:12:34.640 --> 10:12:37.880
She had never seen Marilla sit limply inert like that.

10:12:38.320 --> 10:12:39.800
Are you very tired, Marilla?

10:12:40.580 --> 10:12:45.760
Yes, no, oh, I don't know, said Marilla wearily, looking up.

10:12:46.380 --> 10:12:50.920
I suppose I am tired, but I haven't thought about it. It's not that.

10:12:51.880 --> 10:12:53.080
Did you see the oculist?

10:12:53.360 --> 10:12:55.840
What did he say? asked Anne anxiously.

10:12:57.080 --> 10:13:03.620
Yes, I saw him. He examined my eyes. He says that if I give up all reading and sewing entirely,

10:13:04.460 --> 10:13:08.800
and any kind of work that strains the eyes, and if I'm careful not to cry,

10:13:09.400 --> 10:13:13.900
and if I wear the glasses he's given me, he thinks my eyes may not get any worse,

10:13:13.900 --> 10:13:15.800
and my headaches will be cured.

10:13:16.920 --> 10:13:20.740
But if I don't, he says I'll certainly be stone blind in six months.

10:13:21.580 --> 10:13:24.040
Blind? Anne, just think of it.

10:13:25.140 --> 10:13:29.640
For a minute Anne, after her first quick exclamation of dismay, was silent.

10:13:30.740 --> 10:13:36.500
It seemed to her that she could not speak. Then she said bravely, but with a catch in her voice.

10:13:37.720 --> 10:13:41.320
Marilla, don't think of it. You know he has given you hope.

10:13:41.320 --> 10:13:44.440
If you are careful, you won't lose your sight altogether.

10:13:45.060 --> 10:13:48.300
And if his glasses cure your headaches, it will be a great thing.

10:13:49.320 --> 10:13:52.500
I don't call it much hope, said Marilla bitterly.

10:13:52.780 --> 10:13:56.240
What am I to live for if I can't read or sew, or do anything like that?

10:13:56.600 --> 10:14:02.520
I might as well be blind, or dead. And as for crying, I can't help that when I get lonesome.

10:14:02.920 --> 10:14:07.920
But there, it's no good talking about it. If you'll give me a cup of tea, I'll be thankful.

10:14:07.920 --> 10:14:13.380
I'm about done out. Don't say anything about this to anyone for a spell yet, anyway.

10:14:13.780 --> 10:14:17.500
I can't bear that folks should come here to question and sympathize and talk about it.

10:14:18.940 --> 10:14:22.480
When Marilla had eaten her lunch, Anne persuaded her to go to bed.

10:14:23.020 --> 10:14:27.260
Then Anne went herself to the east gable and sat down by her window in the darkness,

10:14:27.440 --> 10:14:30.220
alone with her tears and her heaviness of heart.

10:14:31.020 --> 10:14:35.140
How sadly things had changed since she had sat there the night after coming home.

10:14:35.580 --> 10:14:40.040
Then she had been full of hope and joy and the future had looked rosy with promise.

10:14:41.200 --> 10:14:46.280
Anne felt as if she had lived years since then, but before she went to bed there was a smile on

10:14:46.280 --> 10:14:51.260
her lips and peace in her heart. She had looked her duty courageously in the face and found it

10:14:51.260 --> 10:14:57.500
a friend, as duty ever is when we meet it frankly. One afternoon, a few days later,

10:14:57.880 --> 10:15:01.480
Marilla came slowly in from the front yard where she had been talking to a caller,

10:15:01.480 --> 10:15:07.800
a man whom Anne knew by sight as Sadler from Carmody. Anne wondered what he could have been

10:15:07.800 --> 10:15:12.800
saying to bring that look to Marilla's face. What did Mr. Sadler want, Marilla?

10:15:13.580 --> 10:15:17.720
Marilla sat down by the window and looked at Anne. There were tears in her eyes in

10:15:17.720 --> 10:15:21.720
defiance of the oculus prohibition and her voice broke as she said,

10:15:22.940 --> 10:15:27.080
He heard that I was going to sell Green Gables and he wants to buy it.

10:15:28.240 --> 10:15:33.120
Buy it? Buy Green Gables? Anne wondered if she had heard her right.

10:15:33.900 --> 10:15:36.680
Oh, Marilla, you don't mean to sell Green Gables.

10:15:37.820 --> 10:15:44.740
Anne, I don't know what else is to be done. I've thought it all over. If my eyes were strong,

10:15:44.840 --> 10:15:49.220
I could stay here and make out to look after things and manage with a good hired man,

10:15:49.220 --> 10:15:56.920
but as it is, I can't. I may lose my sight altogether and anyway I'll not be fit to

10:15:56.920 --> 10:16:01.840
run things. Oh, I never thought I'd live to see the day when I'd have to sell my home,

10:16:02.500 --> 10:16:06.880
but things would only go behind worse and worse all the time till nobody would want to buy it.

10:16:07.560 --> 10:16:12.700
Every cent of our money went in that bank and there's some notes Matthew gave last fall to pay.

10:16:13.420 --> 10:16:18.240
Mrs. Lynde advises me to sell the farm and board somewhere, with her I suppose.

10:16:18.1000 --> 10:16:24.620
It won't bring much. It's small and the buildings are old, but it'll be enough for me to live on,

10:16:24.620 --> 10:16:31.280
I reckon. I'm thankful you're provided for with that scholarship, Anne. I'm sorry you won't have

10:16:31.280 --> 10:16:36.160
a home to come to in your vacations, that's all, but I suppose you'll manage somehow.

10:16:37.300 --> 10:16:39.560
Marilla broke down and wept bitterly.

10:16:40.980 --> 10:16:44.660
You mustn't sell Green Gables, said Anne resolutely.

10:16:46.180 --> 10:16:52.400
Oh, Anne, I wish I didn't have to, but you can see for yourself. I can't stay here alone.

10:16:52.780 --> 10:16:57.860
I'd go crazy with trouble and loneliness, and my sight would go. I know it would.

10:16:59.640 --> 10:17:04.960
You won't have to stay here alone, Marilla. I'll be with you. I'm not going to Redmond.

10:17:07.400 --> 10:17:12.560
Not going to Redmond? Marilla lifted her worn face from her hands and looked at Anne.

10:17:13.280 --> 10:17:14.660
Why, what do you mean?

10:17:15.820 --> 10:17:21.020
Just what I say. I'm not going to take the scholarship. I decided so the night after

10:17:21.020 --> 10:17:25.840
you came home from town. You surely don't think I could leave you alone in your trouble, Marilla,

10:17:26.180 --> 10:17:33.120
after all you've done for me? I've been thinking and planning. Let me tell you my plans. Mr. Barry

10:17:33.120 --> 10:17:38.460
wants to rent the farm for next year, so you won't have any bother over that, and I'm going

10:17:38.460 --> 10:17:44.260
to teach. I've applied for the school here, but I don't expect to get it, for I understand

10:17:44.260 --> 10:17:50.420
the trustees have promised it to Gilbert Blythe, but I can have the Carmody School. Mr. Blair told

10:17:50.420 --> 10:17:55.100
me so last night at the store. Of course, that won't be quite as nice or convenient as if I had

10:17:55.100 --> 10:18:00.780
the Avonlea School, but I can board home and drive myself over to Carmody and back, in the warm

10:18:00.780 --> 10:18:07.420
weather at least, and even in winter I can come home Fridays. We'll keep a horse for that. Oh,

10:18:07.420 --> 10:18:13.120
I have it all planned out, Marilla, and I'll read to you and keep you cheered up. You shan't be dull

10:18:13.120 --> 10:18:19.900
or lonesome, and we'll be real cosy and happy here together, you and I. Marilla had listened like a

10:18:19.900 --> 10:18:26.760
woman in a dream. Oh, Anne, I could get on real well if you were here, I know, but I can't let

10:18:26.760 --> 10:18:33.700
you sacrifice yourself so for me. It would be terrible. Nonsense, Anne laughed merrily. There is

10:18:33.700 --> 10:18:39.300
no sacrifice. Nothing would be worse than giving up Green Gables. Nothing could hurt me more.

10:18:39.820 --> 10:18:45.360
We must keep the dear old place. My mind is quite made up, Marilla. I'm not going to Redmond,

10:18:45.600 --> 10:18:49.820
and I am going to stay here and teach. Don't you worry about me a bit.

10:18:50.820 --> 10:18:52.620
But your ambitions and...

10:18:53.820 --> 10:18:59.800
I'm just as ambitious as ever, only I've changed the object of my ambitions. I'm going to be a good

10:18:59.800 --> 10:19:05.820
teacher, and I'm going to save your eyesight. Besides, I mean to study at home here and take a

10:19:05.820 --> 10:19:11.340
little college course all by myself. Oh, I've dozens of plans, Marilla, and I've been thinking

10:19:11.340 --> 10:19:16.820
them over for a week. I shall give life here my best, and I believe it will give its best to me

10:19:16.820 --> 10:19:22.100
in return. When I left Queens, my future seemed to stretch out before me like a straight road.

10:19:22.580 --> 10:19:28.720
I thought I could see along it for many a milestone. Now there is a bend in it. I don't

10:19:28.720 --> 10:19:34.580
know what lies around the bend, but I'm going to believe that the best does. It has a fascination

10:19:34.580 --> 10:19:41.120
of its own, that bend, Marilla. I wonder how the road beyond it goes, what there is of green,

10:19:41.120 --> 10:19:46.760
glory and soft checkered light and shadows, what new landscapes, what new beauties,

10:19:47.100 --> 10:19:53.460
what curves and hills and valleys further on. I don't feel as if I ought to let you give it up,

10:19:53.740 --> 10:19:59.960
said Marilla, referring to the scholarship. But you can't prevent me. I'm sixteen and a half,

10:20:00.360 --> 10:20:06.860
obstinate as a mule, as Mrs. Lynde once told me, laughed Anne. Oh, Marilla, don't you go

10:20:06.860 --> 10:20:12.860
I don't like to be pitied, and there's no need for it. I'm heart-glad over the very thought

10:20:12.860 --> 10:20:18.860
of staying at Dear Green Gables. Nobody could love it as you and I do, so we must keep it.

10:20:20.380 --> 10:20:25.120
You blessed girl, said Marilla, yielding, I feel as if you'd given me new life.

10:20:25.520 --> 10:20:31.220
I guess I ought to stick out and make you go to college. But I know I can't, so I ain't going to

10:20:31.220 --> 10:20:38.180
cry. I'll make it up to you, though, Anne. When it became noised abroad in Avonlea that Anne

10:20:38.180 --> 10:20:42.580
Shirley had given up the idea of going to college and intended to stay home and teach,

10:20:42.840 --> 10:20:48.460
there was a good deal of discussion over it. Most of the good folks, not knowing about Marilla's

10:20:48.460 --> 10:20:55.120
eyes, thought she was foolish. Mrs. Allen did not. She told Anne so in approving words that

10:20:55.120 --> 10:21:01.200
brought tears of pleasure to the girl's eyes. Neither did good Mrs. Lynde. She came up

10:21:01.200 --> 10:21:05.660
one evening and found Anne and Marilla sitting at the front door in the warm scented summer dusk.

10:21:05.1000 --> 10:21:10.800
They liked to sit there when the twilight came down and the white moths flew about in the garden

10:21:10.800 --> 10:21:17.160
and the odor of mint filled the dewy air. Mrs. Rachel deposited her substantial person upon the

10:21:17.160 --> 10:21:21.720
stone bench by the door, behind which grew a row of tall pink and yellow hollyhocks,

10:21:21.1000 --> 10:21:28.200
with a long breath of mingled weariness and relief. I declare, I'm getting glad to sit down.

10:21:28.200 --> 10:21:33.480
I've been on my feet all day, and two hundred pounds is a good bit for two feet to carry around.

10:21:34.460 --> 10:21:38.040
It's a good blessing not to be fat, Marilla. I hope you appreciate it.

10:21:39.060 --> 10:21:44.780
Well, Anne, I hear you've given up your notion of going to college. I was real glad to hear it.

10:21:45.040 --> 10:21:50.020
You've got as much education now as a woman can be comfortable with. I don't believe in

10:21:50.020 --> 10:21:54.280
girls going to college with the men and cramming their heads full of Latin and Greek and all that

10:21:54.280 --> 10:22:00.800
nonsense. But I'm going to study Latin and Greek just the same, Mrs. Lynde, said Anne, laughing.

10:22:01.220 --> 10:22:06.420
I'm going to take my arts courses right here at Green Gables and study everything that I would

10:22:06.420 --> 10:22:13.180
at college. Mrs. Lynde lifted her hands in holy horror. Anne, surely you'll kill yourself.

10:22:14.160 --> 10:22:22.480
Not a bit of it. I shall thrive on it. Oh, I'm not going to overdo things. As Josiah Allen's wife

10:22:22.480 --> 10:22:28.620
says, I shall be medium. But I'll have lots of spare time in the long winter evenings,

10:22:28.840 --> 10:22:33.200
and I've no vocation for fancy work. I'm going to teach over at Carmody, you know.

10:22:33.940 --> 10:22:37.760
I don't know it. I guess you're going to teach right here in Avonlea.

10:22:37.900 --> 10:22:40.160
The trustees have decided to give you the school.

10:22:41.140 --> 10:22:45.180
Mrs. Lynde, cried Anne, springing to her feet in her surprise.

10:22:45.660 --> 10:22:48.300
Why, I thought they had promised it to Gilbert Blythe.

10:22:48.880 --> 10:22:54.200
So they did. But as soon as Gilbert heard that you had applied for it, he went to them—they

10:22:54.200 --> 10:22:58.300
had a business meeting at the school last night, you know—and told them that he withdrew his

10:22:58.300 --> 10:23:04.080
application and suggested that they accept yours. He said he was going to teach at White Sands.

10:23:04.460 --> 10:23:09.560
Of course, he knew how much you wanted to stay with Marilla, and I must say I think it was real

10:23:09.560 --> 10:23:15.800
kind and thoughtful in him, that's what. Real self-sacrificing, too, for he'll have his board

10:23:15.800 --> 10:23:20.480
pay at White Sands, and everybody knows he's got to earn his own way through college.

10:23:21.160 --> 10:23:26.460
So the trustees decided to take you. I was tickled to death when Thomas came home and told me.

10:23:27.400 --> 10:23:30.360
I don't feel like I ought to take it, murmured Anne. I mean,

10:23:30.820 --> 10:23:34.940
I don't think I ought to let Gilbert make such a sacrifice for—for me.

10:23:36.100 --> 10:23:40.740
I guess you can prevent it now. He signed papers with the White Sands trustees,

10:23:41.200 --> 10:23:43.980
so it wouldn't do him any good now if you were to refuse.

10:23:44.380 --> 10:23:49.780
Of course you'll take the school. You'll get along all right now that there are no pies going.

10:23:50.220 --> 10:23:53.940
Josie was the last of them, and a good thing she was, that's what.

10:23:54.740 --> 10:23:58.780
There's been some pie or other going to Avonlea School for the last twenty years,

10:23:58.880 --> 10:24:03.460
and I guess their mission in life was to keep schoolteachers reminded that earth isn't their

10:24:03.460 --> 10:24:09.100
home. Bless my heart! What does all that winking and blinking at the Berry Gable mean?

10:24:09.880 --> 10:24:12.800
Diana is signaling for me to go over, laughed Anne.

10:24:13.480 --> 10:24:18.080
You know we keep up the old custom. Excuse me while I run over and see what she wants.

10:24:18.780 --> 10:24:23.080
Anne ran down the clover slope like a deer and disappeared in the furry shadows of the haunted

10:24:23.080 --> 10:24:28.580
wood. Mrs. Lynde looked after her indulgently. There's a good deal of the child about her yet,

10:24:28.640 --> 10:24:35.140
in some ways. There's a good deal more of the woman about her in others, retorted Marilla with

10:24:35.140 --> 10:24:40.520
momentary return of her old crispness. But crispness was no longer Marilla's distinguishing

10:24:40.520 --> 10:24:45.920
characteristic, as Mrs. Lynde told her Thomas that night. Marilla Cuthbert has gotten mellow,

10:24:46.040 --> 10:24:51.1000
that's what. Anne went to the little Avonlea graveyard the next evening to put fresh flowers

10:24:51.1000 --> 10:24:58.320
on Matthew's grave and water the Scotch rose bush. She lingered there until dusk, liking the

10:24:58.320 --> 10:25:03.940
peace and calm of the little place with its poplars whose rustle was like low friendly speech and its

10:25:03.940 --> 10:25:09.580
whispering grasses growing at will among the graves. When she finally left it and walked down

10:25:09.580 --> 10:25:15.200
the long hill that sloped to the lake of shining waters, it was past sunset and all Avonlea lay

10:25:15.200 --> 10:25:20.880
before her in a dreamlike afterlight, a haunt of ancient peace. There was a freshness in the air

10:25:20.880 --> 10:25:26.420
as of a wind that had blown over honey-sweet fields of clover. Home lights twinkled here and there

10:25:26.420 --> 10:25:32.300
among the homestead trees. Beyond lay the sea, misty and purple, with its haunting unceasing

10:25:32.300 --> 10:25:37.880
murmur. The west was a glowing of soft mingled hues and the pond reflected them all in still

10:25:37.880 --> 10:25:43.460
softer shadings. The beauty of it all thrilled Anne's heart and she gratefully opened the gates

10:25:43.460 --> 10:25:50.460
of her soul to it. Dear old world, she murmured, you are very lovely and I'm glad to be alive in

10:25:50.460 --> 10:25:56.380
you. Halfway down the hill a tall lad came whistling out of a gate before the Blythe homestead.

10:25:56.380 --> 10:26:03.020
It was Gilbert and the whistle died on his lips as he recognized Anne. He lifted his cap courteously

10:26:03.020 --> 10:26:07.480
but he would have passed on in silence if Anne had not stopped and held out her hand.

10:26:08.460 --> 10:26:13.300
Gilbert, she said with scarlet cheeks, I want to thank you for giving up the school for me.

10:26:13.580 --> 10:26:18.880
It was very good of you and I want you to know that I appreciate it. Gilbert took her offered

10:26:18.880 --> 10:26:24.320
hand eagerly. It wasn't particularly good of me at all, Anne. I was pleased to be able to do you

10:26:24.320 --> 10:26:29.200
some small service. Are we going to be friends after this? Have you really forgiven me my old

10:26:29.200 --> 10:26:35.260
fault? Anne laughed and tried unsuccessfully to withdraw her hand. I forgave you that day by the

10:26:35.260 --> 10:26:41.480
pond landing, although I didn't know it. What a stubborn little goose I was. I've been. I may as

10:26:41.480 --> 10:26:47.260
well make a complete confession. I've been sorry ever since. We're going to be the best of friends,

10:26:47.400 --> 10:26:52.500
said Gilbert jubilantly. We were born to be good friends, Anne. You've thwarted destiny enough.

10:26:52.500 --> 10:26:57.660
I know we can help each other in many ways. You're going to keep up your studies, aren't you?

10:26:57.860 --> 10:27:00.700
So am I. Come, I'm going to walk home with you.

10:27:01.580 --> 10:27:04.760
Marilla looked curiously at Anne when the latter entered the kitchen.

10:27:04.960 --> 10:27:07.020
Who was that that came up the lane with you, Anne?

10:27:07.500 --> 10:27:12.400
Gilbert Blythe, answered Anne, vexed to find herself blushing. I met him at Berry's Hill.

10:27:13.080 --> 10:27:17.160
I didn't think you and Gilbert Blythe were such good friends that you'd stand for half an hour

10:27:17.160 --> 10:27:20.320
the gate talking to him, said Marilla with a dry smile.

10:27:20.1000 --> 10:27:26.260
We haven't been. We've been good enemies. But we have decided that it will be much more sensible

10:27:26.260 --> 10:27:32.060
to be good friends in the future. Were we really there half an hour? It seemed just a few minutes.

10:27:32.580 --> 10:27:36.220
But you see, we have five years lost conversations to catch up with, Marilla.

10:27:37.320 --> 10:27:41.020
Anne sat long at her window that night, companioned by a glad content.

10:27:41.860 --> 10:27:46.080
The wind purred softly in the cherry boughs, and the mint breaths came up to her.

10:27:46.080 --> 10:27:49.600
The stars twinkled over the pointed firs in the hollow,

10:27:50.120 --> 10:27:52.440
and Diana's light gleamed through the old gap.

10:27:53.260 --> 10:27:57.560
Anne's horizons had closed in since the night she had sat there after coming home from Queen's.

10:27:58.380 --> 10:28:01.340
But if the path set before her feet was to be narrow,

10:28:01.580 --> 10:28:04.760
she knew that flowers of quiet happiness would bloom along it.

10:28:04.1000 --> 10:28:09.820
The joy of sincere work and worthy aspiration and congenial friendship were to be hers.

10:28:10.380 --> 10:28:14.520
Nothing could rob her of her birthright of fancy or her ideal world of dreams.

10:28:14.520 --> 10:28:17.020
And there was always the bend in the road.

10:28:17.720 --> 10:28:22.580
God's in his heaven. All's right with the world, whispered Anne softly.
